<HEADER>
A1531 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     08-01 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT GOLF, SO IT MUST BE ENTERTAINMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You don't go to Raging Waters just because the
Russian River is a mite far to drive. Similarly, you don't tune
into the ABC's prime-time ``Sports Night'' _ assuming you watch it
at all _ to get caught up on the day's scores.
</P>
<P>
   The show exists to entertain. Occasionally, it even succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   This being summer, a slow time for sports and sitcoms, the
network that cast actors Peter Krause and Josh Charles as co-stars
and foils once more went rummaging through society's toybox,
searching for inspired programming.
</P>
<P>
   What they dug up were two more fresh faces to play off athletics
and each other for laughs, for tension and, above all else, for
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Premiering on Monday is ``Golf Night,'' er, ``Showdown at
Sherwood,'' a match-play event featuring Tiger Woods and David
Duval, who are either the two best golfers on the planet or the
'90s version of ``The Odd Couple,'' take your pick.
</P>
<P>
   No word yet on whether Oscar Madison will show up at Sherwood
Country Club in Thousand Oaks with a manual typewriter in one hand
and a cigar in the other. There's definitely a place, if not a
credential, for Jack Klugman's '70s sportswriter alter-ego at the
event, which ABC will air live to a prime-time East Coast audience.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever confused Klugman's character with the real thing.
Just as no one's confusing Monday's confrontation with real
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the UCLA football team's game this past December at Miami
or Pete Sampras' tennis semifinal Saturday at the ATP Tour stop at
UCLA, there is no No.1 ranking riding on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The results will have no bearing on either player's world
rankings, just their wallets.
</P>
<P>
   Though Duval and Woods are not really Friends, the winner will
pocket more than Monica or Chandler for one night's taping _ a cool
$1.1 million, with $200,000 earmarked for charity.
</P>
<P>
   The loser won't go home empty-handed or, heaven forbid, in hock.
Far from it; he will pocket a $400,000 consolation prize, less his
$200,000 contribution to charity, which would be as good as a
winning lottery ticket to most of us.
</P>
<P>
   If the match were all about the golf, Duval and Woods wouldn't
be teeing off at 4:30. With sports and television in bed together,
cozier than Rob and Laura Petrie were ever allowed to get, it
hardly fazes you anymore to ask, ``Is that a.m. or p.m.?''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it's p.m. _ as in prime marketability or paper
money. The late starting time means premium advertising dollars. It
also puts the golfers in direct competition not only with each
other, but with daylight.
</P>
<P>
   A hazard to be sure, but organizers smoothed it over as they
might smooth sand in a bunker by installing temporary lights on the
17th and 18th holes.
</P>
<P>
   Today, night golf; tomorrow, dawn middleweight fights?
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the golf, if it were just about entertainment then
surely Duval and Woods could have been persuaded to make themselves
available for 30 minutes last week to talk up their rivalry _ or
lack thereof, if that's how they really see it.
</P>
<P>
   A conference call was indeed arranged for reporters _ with ABC
announcers Mike Tirico and Curtis Strange. Tirico and Strange
earnestly went about selling the canned features that will go
hand-in-glove with the golf. Sure, they're meant to stave off
boredom between shots, but Tirico and Strange said they will also
pave the way for a deeper understanding of what makes Duval and
Woods tick.
</P>
<P>
   You know, besides the money.
</P>
<P>
   You hope it comes up somewhere in ABC's taped conversations with
the players why exactly both Woods and Duval are amenable to this
sort of exhibition but balk at the history-steeped Ryder Cup
matches.
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't be that representing your country for a $5,000
stipend on top of expenses is less palatable than representing
yourself for a guaranteed payoff of at least $200,000. Could it?
</P>
<P>
   Time was when you could get a bead on pro athletes by
approaching them for autographs or asking them a few questions
(This was before clubhouse badges went for $550, back in the days
when you didn't have to choose between seeing your favorite
athletes up close or paying your rent).
</P>
<P>
   Pro athletes used to be as close as your fingertips. Now,
increasingly, they never get closer than your television remote.
</P>
<P>
   Your favorite athletes appear as themselves on television shows,
Woods and Duval appear in prime time for lots and lots of dough and
the line between characters and competitors grows ever more
blurred.
</P>
<P>
   Everything looks so familiar, but it never has been less real. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 0054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
