<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1533 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GIANTS-WILLIAMS-A     08-01 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-WILLIAMS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS' TURNED CORNER BY DEALING WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seldom will one transaction figure in the complete restructuring
of a major league franchise. But that's exactly what happened to
the San Francisco Giants three years ago when they dealt one of
their cornerstone players away.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Williams, now considered the rock of the Diamondbacks
franchise, was the key player the Giants parted with in order to
remake themselves into their current perennial contending version.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, the Nov. 13, 1996, deal that sent Williams to the
Cleveland Indians for second baseman Jeff Kent, shortstop Jose
Vizcaino and reliever Julian Tavarez has made all the sense in the
world to the Giants, who open a key three-game series at Bank One
Ballpark on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But in the days, weeks and months following the
then-controversial trade, it was viewed as little more than a front
office losing its mind. The public backlash became so bad that
General Manager Brian Sabean called a press conference several days
after the deal with the sole intent of defending the move and
insisting he was no idiot, that the ballclub had a master plan.
</P>
<P>
   The headline in one of the San Francisco papers the next day
read: ``Sabean declares he's no idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were brutally savaged,'' Giants President Larry Baer said.
``We didn't expect it to be a popular move. But it was a necessary
requirement. There was no way we could develop and win at the same
time with Matt and Barry Bonds taking up so much salary. We had to
do it. The Williams trade was a defining moment for this franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't easy for anybody because of the kind of person Matt
is. We all felt that ultimately it was something we had to do. I'm
not going to sit here and BS you; everybody cringed about it at the
time we made the deal. Ultimately, what prevailed is, `This is the
best thing for the organization.' Obviously, it's turned out
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, whose 1997 opening-day payroll was $33 million,
would have seen nearly half of that swallowed up by Williams ($7.05
million) and Bonds ($8.67 million), leaving virtually nothing for
the remaining 23 players.
</P>
<P>
   Sabean, a three-year member of the front office who had been
elevated to general manager two weeks before the Williams trade,
had floated the idea that either Bonds or Williams had to be traded
if the franchise was going to take serious steps forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying this in a cavalier way, but when you're faced
with reality, it's sobering,'' Sabean said. ``We had to pick one
guy. We opted to keep Barry for obvious reasons of what the club
could be with him. If we wanted to get the hell out of last place,
we had to do something. I remember I smoked a lot of cigarettes
that weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate impact of the deal was quickly realized as the
Giants had a phenomenal 1997 season, capturing the National League
West Division title on the next to last day of the season and
reaching the playoffs for the first time in eight years. In
Williams' case, he became Cleveland's everyday third baseman and
helped the Indians reach the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was win-win,'' Sabean said. ``We all got what we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Williams deal brought the Giants stability in Kent, who has
emerged as one of the top-hitting middle infielders in the game,
and Vizcaino, whose one season with the Giants was above average,
and Tavarez, a dependable middle reliever.
</P>
<P>
   The three former Indians were under contract in 1997 for a
combined $6.03 million. Coupled with the $1 million the Indians
included in the trade, the Giants had an additional $2 million to
play with.
</P>
<P>
   Using that extra cash as a base, the front office then signed
free-agent center fielder Darryl Hamilton and traded for first
baseman J.T. Snow. In addition, Williams' departure opened up third
base for a young Bill Mueller, who has emerged into a solid
everyday player.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are so happy with these moves that on Friday they
gave Snow a $24 million, four-year contract extension and exercised
options on Bonds and Kent. Snow is now under contract through 2003,
Bonds through 2001 and Kent through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   In short, in trading away one player, Williams, the Giants were
able to land six integral pieces _ three of which (Kent, Tavarez
and Snow) are still with the club _ and one, Hamilton, who was
traded for Ellis Burks, who is now a starting outfielder when
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, every club needs to shake things up a bit,'' San
Diego General Manager Kevin Towers said. ``Everything was built
around two guys for them. If one of those guys went down, they were
stuck. They freed up salary and were able to go out and spend some
money on some role players. They added depth to their bullpen and
have been off and running ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants reached the postseason in 1997 and tied with the
Chicago Cubs for the wild-card spot last season, losing a one-game
playoff. San Francisco entered its weekend series in Cincinnati
with a 234-193 record (.548) since pulling the trigger on the
Williams deal. In the two previous seasons, the Giants were 135-171
(.441).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one hell of a move and a bold move for a guy's first
move as a GM,'' said Giants Manager Dusty Baker, one of Williams'
closest friends. ``I'm glad for Matty. It's worked out fine for
everyone. There are certain things you don't want to face
sometimes, and I'm glad I wasn't the GM for this one. A trade is
supposed to help both clubs, and this one did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were faced with reality because they had just
finished in last place for the second consecutive year, only the
second time this storied franchise had gone through such a two-year
stretch in its 116-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The '96 season was especially disastrous for the Giants, who
were decimated by injuries near the All-Star break and lost 17 of
19 at one point in late June and early July. San Francisco used 49
players, just two short of the all-time franchise record. They
managed to avoid losing 100 games mostly because of a late spurt in
which they won eight of their final 12 games. Attendance plummeted
as the Giants averaged just 17,671 fans per home game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We literally ran out of guys with big league experience and
guys who deserved to be there or should have been there,'' Sabean
said. ``There were guys we handed a major league uniform to who
were ill-equipped to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Giants had just won voter approval to build a
new privately financed stadium and needed to give fans a reason to
start buying ticket licenses for their new home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at a huge crossroads as an organization,'' Baer said.
``With Candlestick Park, if you don't win you're going to suffer a
tremendous hit at the gate. It was (a move) to stay competitive
while we won. We would have gotten the ballpark built anyway, but
it would have been a much tougher go if all these ingredients had
not happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants already have sold 25,500 season tickets for next
year's inaugural season at Pacific Bell Park, nearly double their
highest season ticket base in 42 years in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were not fooling ourselves into thinking Matt was
going to lose productivity,'' Baer said. ``We knew we were trading
a guy with good years ahead of him. I also can't say we sat there
and thought it was going to work out this well.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you ask anyone here, `Would we do the Matt deal again?'
Yes would be the answer.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
