<DOCNO> NYT19990801.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1534 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ASU-FINANCES-AZR &LR;      08-01 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-FINANCES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCES HAVE TURNED SCHOOL INTO ASU INC. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Welcome to Arizona State Inc., where
administrators believe treating your athletic department like a big
business is the only approach that make cents.
</P>
<P>
   In three years, ASU athletic department's operating budget has
jumped from $17 million to $26 million. A $2.9 million deficit is
now a $600,000 surplus. Eighteen capital projects, including new
softball and soccer stadiums and an overhauling of the
Intercollegiate Athletics Complex, are under way or will be soon.
</P>
<P>
   The driving force has been Athletic Director Kevin White, whose
corporate approach, while making some bristle, has pumped life into
a sedentary budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to continue to build our _ and I know saying this
makes people edgy _ core business,'' White said. ``If we don't do
that, at the end of the day we're not going to be able to be as
competitive as we like.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils' financial strides, which began taking shape with
White's arrival in June 1996, are significant considering ASU's
three major sports _ football, baseball and men's basketball _ all
failed to qualify for postseason play last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not have a good year,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   White is driven by the goals he announced when he arrived: to
create and develop programs that finish annually in the NCAA's top
10 and the Pac-10's top three; to be clean and compliant; and to be
academically responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Of ASU's 21 sports, only five finished among the Pac-10's top
three teams in 1998-99. White believes by pumping more money into
his programs, providing coaches with better opportunities to win
and finding ways to keep them around, the Sun Devils' success will
change. Two of ASU's more successful women's programs _ golf and
gymnastics _ are led by coaches approaching their 20th seasons. &QL; 
Arena by any other name &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White has improved the athletic department's financial status by
reorganizing ASU's fund-raising arm, securing better broadcast
deals, embracing corporate partnership and permitting facility
naming in exchange for sizable contributions. The latter alone
already has brought in approximately $14 million, led by Wells
Fargo Bank's $5 million gift to rename the University Activity
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The approach has not been without a price. Some fans have
complained about the audio and video marketing onslaught that
occurs during football games at Sun Devil Stadium, an effort that
appears excessive compared to the rest of the Pac-10. Others find
the naming rights offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, I don't really think fans care that much,'' said
Rick Burton, director of the Warsaw Sports Marketing Center at
Oregon. ``A lot bemoan the good old days, but then the good old
days were not that good. People would rather see a winning team,
and that helps them overcome their commercial sensitivities.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ASU's corporate approach is ahead of the game, it is by
no means the only university willing to trade naming rights for a
hefty gift. Ohio State, whose 1999-2000 budget of $64 million is
one of the biggest in the country, has renamed its basketball arena
the Jerome Schottenstein Center, thanks to a $12.5 million
contribution from a local businessman. Because of strong booster
support, the football team's Ohio Stadium is undergoing $150
million in renovations.
</P>
<P>
   One of college sports' first facilities to be named because of a
donation was Syracuse's Carrier Dome in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's budget ranks sixth in the Pac-10, according to a survey by
``The'' ``Arizona Republic,'' $13 million behind Stanford, a
private institution. &QL; 
An oversaturated market &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Arizona State announced a university-wide Capital
Campaign goal to raise $300 million (later increased to $400
million) by 2002. The athletic department quickly met its $20
million commitment and upped its goal to $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   With approximately 110,000 alumni living in the Valley, White
sees numerous resources to tap. But he also is aware his university
is situated in an area that was recently named ``the most
oversaturated sports market in the country'' by one publication.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils' challenges are different from those programs
that regularly see themselves in the Top 10. Schools such as
Tennessee and Nebraska sit in markets with little or no competition
from professional sports teams. For the most part, those schools
own the state's sports fans, who not only embrace dear old State U
but contribute to the program. Football sellouts are common.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils must compete for the marketing dollar against six
professional sports franchises, several of which are owned by one
of the best marketers in the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Jerry) Colangelo has raised the bar, and that's a challenge
for us,'' said Vic Cegles, ASU's lead associate athletic director
for external affairs. ``I think we have our own niche. Maybe we
can't attract the type of dollars they do, but we're getting
closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Said White:``When we look at what others are doing, I'm not sure
it really matters what happens in West Lafayette, Fayetteville,
Iowa City, Eugene, and maybe even Tucson. The tone of our market is
clearly being dictated by those professional franchises. We're
having to adjust to that.'' &QL; 
Signs of the times &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ASU has taken a Colangelo-like ``bundle'' approach to marketing.
For X amount of dollars, get radio time, a sign in Sun Devil
Stadium and tickets to a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``By controlling all the inventory, it enables you to create the
value for it,'' Cegles said. ``By combining everything, you
increase the sponsorship value, and in some respects you can create
the value. I think this is the wave of the future, and we're on the
cutting edge of doing this. We'll be the model for a lot of schools
down the road in terms of doing business.''
</P>
<P>
   More than $2.2 million of ASU's 1990-2000 budget comes from
sponsorship and signage, and the administration expects the numbers
to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, the stadium has been fairly bare,'' Cegles
said. ``Without overdoing it and over-commercializing, which we
don't want to do, we can add some signage we can sell. Not just in
the stadium proper, but the concourse, in the loge. Or the entrance
way into the tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils' latest broadcasting deal also has a corporate
feel. Last spring, ASU agreed on a five-year contract with Outdoor
Systems Sports Marketing for multimedia rights. OSSM, or The Sun
Devils Sports Network, will maintain ASU's radio and television
rights and sell its advertising, marketing and sponsorship
properties. Deals were negotiated with KGME-AM (550) and Fox Sports
Net Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ASU will net nearly $4.8 million from broadcasting this season,
nearly a million more than last year's $3.9 million. &QL; 
The man behind it all &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most observers think ASU has made significant inroads with
corporations and major-gift contributors because of White, who is
at ease mingling with the public, a task predecessor Charles Harris
never embraced.
</P>
<P>
   Although White has some concerns about his perception of
businessman first, athletic director second, he thinks that is
what's necessary to make ASU successful. During the past three
years, gift and corporate support has tripled. The Sun Devils have
received 11 donations of at least $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our supporters have been great, terrific,'' White said. ``But
we have 9,000 donors, and I'd like 20,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils, who have budgeted about $6 million from gifts,
donations and sponsors, aspire to be like Florida, which
anticipates raising $15 million in its annual fund this year.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question a successful football season would help
ASU's cause. A winning season means better TV/radio deals,
increased tickets sales and bowl revenue. Although the 1996 Rose
Bowl payout of $8.25 million was shared equally among Pac-10
conference members, it was still a nice chunk of change. The Sun
Devils made another $800,000 on Rose Bowl ticket surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   White jokingly referred to that period as the ``Jake Plummer
deficit-reduction program.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 survey by the NCAA revealed that football provided 66
percent of the revenue brought in by all Division I sports.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils also hope to benefit from a five-year, $7 million
deal with adidas that is expected to be signed soon.
</P>
<P>
   Where does ASU's money go? Much of it is targeted for facility
upgrades and additions. With state-of-the-art complexes popping up
around the country, the Sun Devils don't want to play catch-up.
Several decades ago, many of ASU's athletic facilities were
considered among the best, but that's no longer the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to give our coaches the best opportunities
available,'' White said. ``And that's ultimately what we're trying
to do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
