<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE HAVE (NOT) HEARD THIS BEFORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF - Eric, have a minute?
</P>
<P>
   Some days, he wags his head.
</P>
<P>
   Other days, he says, ``No,'' or if he's in an expansive mood,
``Hell, no.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, a sportscaster for a Valley TV station tried again
as Eric Swann walked by on his way to the dining hall at lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   Eric, is ``today'' the day?
</P>
<P>
   ``Never,'' Swann replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never''?``''
</P>
<P>
   ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   If No. 98 is serious, this is a big story. The Cardinals
defensive tackle hasn't spoken publicly for months. Now he seems to
be suggesting he will maintain his silence throughout this season
and into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   We assumed Swann would mature, end this little game and address
questions that Cardinals fans have been asking since the defensive
star had season-ending knee surgery in December.
</P>
<P>
   Eric, how's the knee?
</P>
<P>
   Are you still experiencing pain? If so, to what degree?
</P>
<P>
   Do you expect to be ready to start when the season opens Sept.
12?
</P>
<P>
   Some questioned or criticized your choosing to have surgery when
your teammates were battling for the playoffs. How difficult was
that controversial decision?
</P>
<P>
   What are your expectations?
</P>
<P>
   Swann isn't saying. The Silent Question Mark who failed his
pre-camp physical rides his exercise bike. He walks through drills.
We turn to the trainer and coaches for daily status reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric's knee is stable,'' Cardinals trainer John Omohundro
said. ``What we have to find out is whether it can accept the
pounding. Hopefully, (once Swann begins contact drills) there will
be no swelling and minimal pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave McGinnis, the defensive coordinator, keeps his fingers
crossed. He knows better than anyone Swann's value to the defense,
what a powerful and dominating player he can be. Swann anchors the
line. He draws double teams. Without him last year, Cardinals
opponents pounded the ball on the ground successfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no doctor, but we're counting on Eric,'' McGinnis said.
``He realizes he missed something special last year.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice to hear Swann say that. Or say anything that
would shed light on his physical condition and mental outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Swann, however, has been only slightly more communicative than
those monks who eat broccoli and other gassy foods in the TV
commercial but faithfully maintain their vow of silence, thanks to
Beano.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals hope Swann will speak. The PR department has done
everything but prompt him, in the manner of a pet store owner
trying to get a balky parrot to talk.
</P>
<P>
   This being America, the land of the free and home of the brave,
Swann is under no obligation to say boo. Many widely known athletes
have fallen mute for periods of time during their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Duane Thomas is the most celebrated of pro football's
non-talkers. On the advice of Jim Brown, his financial adviser and
confidant, Thomas vowed to speak to no one during the 1971 season.
The Cowboys halfback kept his word, too. He didn't end his silence
until after the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Carlton, the former pitcher, didn't talk to the media for
a decade or more, although yours truly did manage to get an
exclusive with Lefty when he appeared at one of those trading card
shows and signed autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve, ready for spring training?'' I asked after working my
way to the front of the line where Carlton sat, head bowed, eyes
downcast, scribbling his name for $5 a pop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Carlton replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``NEXT!'' barked Lefty's agent, whose job was to keep the line
moving.
</P>
<P>
   The Silent Question Mark is hardly breaking new ground.``
Anybody'' in sports can refuse to talk. Before the start of the LA
Games, two American Olympians _ Joe Fargis and Conrad Holmfeld were
their names _ announced they would not speak to the media.
Absolutely no interviews, they said. No exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Fargis and Holmfeld weren't gymnasts. They didn't swim or run
track or play basketball. They were members of the U.S. equestrian
team, riders in the show-jumping competition. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 0104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
