<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1540 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-TOBIN-AZR &LR;      08-01 1434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-TOBIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE DOES IT HIS WAY  
 TOBIN MOLDS WINNER, DOESN'T ROCK BOAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF - In the Cardinals media guide, the list of head
coaches occupies twice as much space as the list of postseason
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   And playoff wins? Well, that was a one-liner. Literally.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen men _ guys named Buddy, Curly, Pop, Bud and Buddy again
_ tried for more than a half-century to coach the Cardinals to a
playoff win. None could crack the code to doing it within the
stringent _ some say unusual or even archaic _ framework
established by team owner Bill Bidwill.
</P>
<P>
   Until Vince Tobin did it.
</P>
<P>
   It had become an annual rite for the Cardinals after
mid-November to play out another losing season and then wait to see
whether the latest coach would be fired.
</P>
<P>
   But there they were, beating the mighty NFC East champion Dallas
Cowboys, their greatest nemesis, on the road, in the playoffs, on
Jan. 2. Their 20-7 victory was the Cardinals' first playoff win
since they captured the NFL championship in 1947, when the team was
owned by Bidwill's father.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin's reward for taking his place in team history was a polite
thank you. He would have preferred a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Live with it and don't make a ruckus. That's the way the owner
likes it.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin is under contract for this season and next. If the
Cardinals come up lame in the wake of their 9-7 record and
excitement generated by going two games into the playoffs, the
remaining year easily could be bought out and Tobin could be sent
packing. That would be the Cardinal way, too.
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill, along with Cardinals fans, is waiting to see whether
Tobin is the man to lead them to a higher level and keep them
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around for a long time, around a lot of winning
football teams,'' Tobin said. ``You do things a certain way. And
you've got to believe that if you do them that way, eventually you
get over the top. That's where we are headed.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin would enjoy having more security, given where the team is
today compared with where it was when he signed in 1996. His 20-28
mark in three seasons doesn't reflect the job that has been done,
the progress made in nearly every facet of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said all along we were a better team the second year (4-12)
than the first (7-9), even though the record wasn't as good,''
Tobin said. ``Last season, we were 6-7 with three games left. We
won all three by kicking field goals as time expired. A lot of
people came together and we got over the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a team getting better. We're not where we need to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Not many big names were interested in coming to work for Bill
Bidwill, a very nice man, a wonderful corporate citizen whose
charitable giving goes far beyond what the general public can
imagine, but a tough football owner to work for. He is set in his
ways, and his ways go back a ways.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, 55, a man not totally comfortable with the '90s himself,
believed he could make it work.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin is not the sort who needs to gauge in which direction the
parade is moving in order to run out in front of it. That's good
because the owner isn't big on his coach being a star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always believed that as long as you get things going in
the direction you want them going, you don't necessarily have to be
the one thumping your chest saying, `I was the one who did it,' ''
Tobin said. `` `I, I, I,' that's all you hear from some guys. The
bottom line is a lot of people have to be working in the same
direction, doing the same thing. That's kind of what I believe,
kind of the way I coach. I give an awful lot of authority to my
assistant coaches. I let them coach. I'm very, very involved to
make sure things are going the way I think they should be going,
but beyond that, who gets the credit is kind of irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin let his accomplishments do the talking. In 1986, for
example, his Chicago Bears defense set a league record for fewest
points allowed. While successful as a defensive coordinator, he
never had been an NFL head coach.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of work for a first-timer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly when I got here, there was a vacuum here,'' Tobin
said. ``There was no general manager. There was no personnel
director. We kind of ruled by committee. It was a consensus thing.
The first thing you've got to do is have a vision and decide where
you're going. Then you've got to get going in that direction, and I
think that's the big thing that we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case three years ago. There was a lot of
infighting, a lot of bickering _ inside the locker room and outside
the locker room. That has changed, and Tobin's leadership is
responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ferguson, Cardinals general manager, has worked with Tom
Landry in Dallas, Mike Shanahan in Denver and Marv Levy in Buffalo,
all successful coaches who have taken teams to the Super Bowl. No
one is ready to place Tobin's name alongside those, but Ferguson
said he sees some of the qualities in Tobin that made the others
successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``His on-field demeanor, his sideline demeanor, how he handles
his staff and players, how he organizes his practices are very
similar,'' Ferguson said. ``He can hire quality people, can coach
quality players, coach underachievers, overachievers, veterans,
rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince has grown as a head coach, but we've all grown over the
past three years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had done nothing but lose horribly since moving to
Arizona in 1988. A decision was made to rebuild with young talent.
Tobin assembled a staff of strong teachers. Many have been longtime
friends and associates, either at the University of Missouri, where
Tobin played and was an assistant coach, or with the Bears, where
he was Mike Ditka's defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said the explanation is simple as to why Tobin could do
what so many before him could not.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understood the situation,'' Ferguson said. ``You can't
underestimate that. It's like running for the Senate or for
President. You've got to understand the political situation
wherever you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince doesn't have an ego like a lot of people do. He doesn't
have to be the main guy out front. In this organization, in our
building, you're not going to be. There's only one guy that's in
charge of everything. We understand that. Vince's personality is
perfect for this team and its ownership. He's perfect because he
doesn't want to rock the boat. All he wants to do is win, and he's
willing to take it and do it the hard way.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to erase 51 years of largely negative postseason
history. The remaining question is how far a first-time head coach
can take the team. To a conference championship? To the Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   Joe Greene, a Hall of Famer from his playing days with
Pittsburgh and Tobin's defensive line coach _ and among the few on
the staff who did not know Tobin before being hired _ has come to
believe that he can.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about going to the next level, he's done that
and he's doing that,'' Greene said. ``It's a work in progress. To
say he's growing as a head coach would be consistent with someone
who each and every year is striving to be a success. Time is going
to tell from here where he is going to be positioned. To me,
standing the test of time is the proof, and we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin is an excellent Xs and Os coach, a technician. He has
hired good assistants for the most part. He has the patience to
allow players to develop. He endears trust.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts _ front office personnel, his coaching staff,
the players _ Tobin is the same even-keeled man behind closed doors
that he is when the public sees him standing on the sideline clamly
clutching his clipboard to his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his demeanor, Tobin isn't perceived as a great
motivator.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my experience, you can do only so many pep talks,''
Greene said. ``Coach Tobin is not one to give you a
fire-and-brimstone, let's-go-get-'em-boys kind of speech.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tobin's messages are consistent. Players can spot a buffoon,
a phony. There's no faster way to erode respect than to be 95
percent bluster and 5 percent substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a straight shooter, and as a player, you can see that,''
said quarterback Jake Plummer. ``You can trust what he's saying.
You know he's not just blowing smoke trying to say the right thing
just to get us pumped up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good coach. I hope we can improve again this year and
keep him around.''
</P>
<P>
   That would define Tobin's first opportunity as an NFL head
coach. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
