<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-DODGERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON CHILLS DODGERS' BATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It isn't often when Diamondbacks left-hander Randy
Johnson needs to be motivated, told what to do during a crucial
point in the game. His icy stare rarely allows anyone to get within
shouting distance.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's 4-2 victory over the Los Angeles Dodgers included one
of those rare times when a few extra words were necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had a two-run lead entering the bottom of the ninth
inning at Dodger Stadium, but he walked leadoff man Gary Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   Damian Miller, who has been behind the plate during most of
Johnson's outings this season, called time and went to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I chewed him out,'' Miller said. ``He had lost his
concentration, so I told him to remove his cranium from . . . He
said, `` `Yeah, OK, OK.' He thanked me later for doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson loaded and locked in. He proceeded to throw eight
straight strikes and went on to strike out Eric Karros, Devon White
and Adrian Beltre to wrap up Arizona's 4-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fifth straight victory for the Diamondbacks (59-46),
their eighth straight road win and 10th triumph in their past 11
games and allowed them to maintain a 2{-game lead in the National
League West over San Francisco, which beat Cincinnati, 11-1.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson (11-8) pitched his ninth complete game of the season,
scattering six hits, walking just Sheffield and striking out 12. It
was the 16th time this season he has struck out 10 or more batters
and 118th time in his career. He also has a career strike out total
of 2,581, tying him with Cleveland Indians legend Bob Feller for
17th on the all-time list, and needs just two to tie Milwaukee
Braves left-hander Warren Spahn for No. 16.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-10 Johnson had thrown 138 and 143 pitches in his two
previous starts against the Mariners and the Dodgers. He got an
extra day of rest, ``but I still wasn't sure how effective I'd be.
I knew I was going to be limited in how many I threw today, 115,
maybe 120.''
</P>
<P>
   He admitted he had lost his focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damian came out and told me, ``Let's go,' '' Johnson said.
Miller laughed as he overheard Johnson's G-rated re-creation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart of the lineup was there, so I had to concentrate,''
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   He got revenge against Karros, who hit a two-run homer off him
in the fourth inning. Three straight sliders. Three straight
swings. Three straight misses. Former Diamondback Devon White, who
hit a homer here off Johnson in the season opener on April 5, went
down on three more pitches. He threw two strikes to Adrian Beltre
before a ball was called, then finished him off with his 125th
pitch of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson now will have the luxury of another five days' rest
before pitching again. After today's finale of the three-game
series, the Diamondbacks go home for three, have an off day on
Thursday and travel to Philadelphia for Johnson's next turn on
Friday night against the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy pitched a smart game. He was rarely in trouble,'' said
pitching coach Mark Connor. ``He made one mistake to Karros, and
then he had a 29-pitch inning in the eighth (including singles by
Jose Vizcaino and pinch-hitter Raul Mondesi), but pitched well.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said he has seen Johnson with better stuff, ``but he
still got it done when he needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson averaged 96-97 mph with a top reading of 99 and a low
reading of 92. He got help with solid defense, particularly a
diving grab of a drive in right-center by Steve Finley to lead off
the bottom of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter had Matt Mantei up briefly in the eighth
inning, but Johnson told him he was fine and was allowed to remain
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt had thrown about 30 pitches on Friday night (33 to get
the save), but could have gone. It was a matter of Randy knowing
himself and us knowing him better now. We trust him,'' Showalter
said.
</P>
<P>
   In several of his recent starts, Johnson had not been able to
trust his offense, but it gave him enough support to survive this
time.
</P>
<P>
   He got a first-inning run when Tony Womack and Jay Bell singled
off right-hander Ismael Valdes (8-9) and Luis Gonzalez grounded
into a double play. Womack singled with one out in the third, and
Gonzalez hit a two-out, two-run homer to make it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers pulled to within 3-2 on Karros' homer, and the
Diamondbacks picked up an important insurance run in the ninth when
Finley singled off left-hander Pedro Borbon to lead off the inning
and scored on a sacrifice fly by Womack.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, whose home run was his 16th of the season, said Valdes
was throwing him a lot of breaking pitches. ``He just hung one, and
I was able to stay with it,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great for us to be able to get Randy a couple of early
runs. When we (offense) had that bad stretch, Randy never
complained. He pitched a great game. Our whole pitching staff has
done a great job since the All-Star break.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
