<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DURAZO MAKES JUMP LOOK EASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ From El Paso to Hollywood,  &UR; Erubiel Durazo is
living a dream.
</P>
<P>
   Durazo, who began the season with Double-A El Paso, made his
third straight start at first base Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He got hits in his first three at-bats in his first start
against San Diego on Wednesday night, then followed with two hits
off Dodgers right-hander  &UR; Kevin Brown on Friday night and two
walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been a dream to play in the major leagues,'' he
said. ``They have better fielders, better hitters, better players.
Everything is better.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be difficult for someone to get off to a better start,
especially against a pitcher such as Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really thinking about anything (pitching pattern) _
I'm just reacting,'' Durazo said. ``I want to continue to hit the
best I can, but the main thing is to win.'' &QL; 
Benes ready &QL; 
Five days after taking a line drive off his pitching arm,
right-hander  &UR; Andy Benes will start today's finale against the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Benes threw on the side Friday without problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have a bit of a knot and it gets a little tight when I
completely extend the arm, but I don't think it will affect me,''
he said. &QL; 
Holmes progressing &QL; 
Right-handed reliever  &UR; Darren Holmes continues to work the
stiffness out of his lower back under the watch of the
organization's rehabilitation staff in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes, in the middle of his second stint on the disabled list,
likely will pitch in a game for the Arizona Rookie League affiliate
on Tuesday or Wednesday and could rejoin the Diamondbacks by the
end of the week. &QL; 
More practice &QL; 
Because of the Hollywood Stars game that preceded Saturday's game,
batting practice was optional.
</P>
<P>
   The message board in the clubhouse read, ``Optional batting
practice (in indoor cage), 11:40 a.m. Anderson bunting practice, 10
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander  &UR; Brian Anderson put that up after short-circuiting
on a two bunt attempts on Friday night and catching a bit of grief
from teammates.
</P>
<P>
   He accepted his share of the blame but said part of his problem
was that Brown was on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if you throw it 96 (mph), just throw it
straight,'' Anderson said. ``That thing had a turbo drop on it. It
was, `tick, foul,' `tick, foul,' `miss.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can bunt that stuff, my hat's off to you.'' &QL; 
Stars out &QL; 
Many of the Diamondbacks mingled with some of the entertainment
stars before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Among the notables were action stars  &UR; Jean Claude Van Damme and
 &UR; Lou
 &UR; Ferrigno, comics  &UR; Norm MacDonald, Ray Romano and  &UR; Elayne Boosler,
director  &UR; Garry Marshall and  &UR; Kevin Eubanks, the musical director
for ``The Tonight Show with Jay Leno''.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Robert Wuhl, who plays the fictitious sports agent on the HBO
show ``Arli$$,'' also participated. No word on whether any
Diamondbacks or Dodgers tried to sign him as their agent. &QL; 
Fashion statement &QL; 
Most of the teams around the majors have worn or will wear a ``turn
the clock forward'' uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter isn't exactly thrilled by the idea, but
he will comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'll be wearing my futuristic jacket,'' he said,
referring to his habit of wearing a jacket in the dugout. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
