<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS NOT IN HEAVEN  
 DISSENSION, POOR PLAY HAVE TEAM IN FREE FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The suits at Disney, the ones who signed off on raising the
payroll for the Anaheim Angels to $52 million this season and
agreed on  &UR; Mo
 &UR; Vaughn's six-year, $80 million contract, appear headed toward a
corporate write-off.
</P>
<P>
   It's very doubtful  &UR; Mickey Mouse and  &UR; Donald Duck will be
receiving their usual Christmas bonuses this year.
</P>
<P>
   If  &UR; Captain Hook ran the Angels ship, he would be abandoning by
now, alligators or not. This is a franchise taking on more water
than it can handle, and no end is in sight for a club many believed
(including me) would win the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had lost 12 of 13 entering their weekend series
against Minnesota. The trip that ended Wednesday saw Anaheim go
1-7, and normally soft-spoken outfielder  &UR; Darin Erstad labeled his
teammates as soft while accusing many of not caring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning would cure everything, but it's a very divided
clubhouse,'' Erstad said. ``It's a very cliquey team. There's not a
feeling that everyone is in the same corner. . . . We have a soft
team.''
</P>
<P>
   To further pour salt in the club's wounds, Vaughn has decided to
boycott the front office after what he perceived a slap in the face
from General Manager  &UR; Bill Bavasi, who had requested the opinion of
several leaders on the recent rift between Manager  &UR; Terry Collins
and the players and then declared it took him all of 15 minutes to
dismiss the players' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to get it done right here in Anaheim,'' Vaughn
said. ``I'm not going anywhere. ``This is how things were in
Boston. We went from 24 players/24 cabs to one unit. But it takes
time. I've done it before under more stressful situations, and I
can do it here. I don't think anything drastic needs to be done,
just a few things to restore order.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the free-falling Angels continue to implode from
within, with one member of the coaching staff wondering whether a
complete makeover is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe some of them aren't capable of being big league hitters,
I don't know,'' hitting coach  &UR; Rod Carew said after Monday's 7-0
loss at Tampa Bay. ``Maybe we need to clean house. . . . I live and
die with them on every pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, shortstop  &UR; Gary DiSarcina, a teammate's teammate, may
have put it best.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unprofessionalism I've seen in the organization this year,
from players to the front office, I'm really disappointed with
that,'' DiSarcina said. ``It's not how I grew up with the game, to
have everyone's laundry aired. It makes you want to take a gut
check and say, `What's happened to the team? Do I want to be here?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been involved in as unprofessional a situation in
my career. My head's spinning. It's not the team I remember. I've
been confused and disappointed by it all. If we're all in this
together, it sure as heck doesn't look like it. I'm not going to
get involved in any mudslinging. Let's all look in the mirror
together.''
</P>
<P>
   That's usually the first place to look anyway. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
 &UR; George Brett and  &UR; Robin Yount, both inducted into the Hall of Fame
last weekend, were praised for having played with the same
franchises for 21 and 20 years, respectively _ Brett with Kansas
City and Yount with Milwaukee. What is the major league record for
most years with the same club? &QL; 
Going Gonzo? &QL; 
There is absolutely no denying the talents of Texas outfielder
 &UR; Juan &UR; Gonzalez. But just when it might seem he is finally headed in
the same direction as his teammates, Gonzalez pulls a stunt like
the one last week, making even his most staunch defenders scratch
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez refused to play in Monday's Hall of Fame exhibition
game in Cooperstown because _ get this _ his 1993 pants were too
baggy. The Rangers had agreed to play in the game to honor their
first Hall of Famer,  &UR; Nolan Ryan, a former teammate of Gonzalez's.
They decided to honor Ryan by wearing their 1993 uniforms, the last
big league uniform Ryan ever wore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't help his image,'' Manager  &UR; Johnny Oates said. ``I
think the way his teammates look at him, Juan needs to do
everything he can to be a part of the club.''
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of sorts, teammate  &UR; Rafael Palmeiro instead wore
Gonzalez's baggy pants. The next day, Gonzalez again stepped in a
bucket of goo when he failed to tell Oates he could not play
because of his sore wrist. He had told all his teammates he could
not play.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few rules Oates has is that all players must inform
him directly if they cannot play for whatever reason. The Rangers
were forced to change their lineup card only 15 minutes before the
first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan can make it difficult at times,'' Texas second baseman
 &UR; Mark
 &UR; McLemore said. ``At times, it becomes harder for some of us to keep
focused on what we're out there to do every day. Every day. Not
five out of of every seven or six out of every seven, but every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the two-time MVP is fully aware of what he brings to
the Rangers. His bat in the middle of their lineup is one of the
most potent in the game. The problem is that the Rangers are never
quite sure which Gonzalez will show up at the ballpark, the
superstar player or the temperamental one.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez's seven-year, $45.45 million contract runs out after
the 2000 season. Over the winter, Gonzalez told a Puerto Rican
newspaper that he is worth more than the $105 million that  &UR; Kevin
Brown is paid. The question that soon will face the Rangers is
whether he is worth the headaches that come along with his talent? &QL; 
The return of Tricky Dick &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We've all heard how kids say the darndest things. Well,
sometimes parents, while holding their kids, also come up with some
doozies of their own.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Manager  &UR; Dusty Baker, among our all-time favorite
managers here at the ``Baseball Insider,'' was recently sitting
outside his Bay Area home, bonding with his toddler while looking
up at the moon. Suddenly,  &UR; Richard Nixon popped into his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a kid, I couldn't understand why this guy ran for president
_ he kept coming in second,'' Baker said. ``As a kid, I thought,
`Why didn't this guy stop running for office?' But he ended up
winning, though he ended up being messed up. I'm not saying I agree
or disagree with with his politics _ well, I believe in completely
different politics _ but I believe in determination and
perseverance. If you keep running, you'll eventually come in first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how that came about. Must've been a full moon.'' &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
 &UR; Brooks Robinson (Baltimore) and  &UR; Carl Yastrzemski (Boston) played
for their respective clubs 23 consecutive seasons for the major
league record. The National League record is 22 years, shared by
 &UR; Cap Anson (Chicago Cubs) and  &UR; Mel Ott (New York Giants).  &UR; Stan
Musial would have played 23 years for the St. Louis Cardinals if
not for taking 1945 off to serve in World War II. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at (602) 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; Now really, was there ever any doubt?: Yankees ace  &UR; David Cone, the
epitome of class throughout his major league career, could earn up
to $1 million by selling off autographed items and pictures from
his recent perfect game. Instead, he will give all the proceeds to
charity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In San Francisco, they're hoping for a giant
 &UR; turnaround: Since being named MVP of the 1997 World Series, newly
acquired Giants starter  &UR; Livan Hernandez has won only 15 of the 59
games he has started.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Scipio Spinks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback II: Richie Phillips (OK, we're jumping the gun a bit,
but this guy is a flashback waiting to happen).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The resemblance was almost spooky: It was eerie the way that
photo of Diamondbacks minor league pitcher  &UR; John Patterson that ran
in Tuesday's ``Republic'' resembled a young  &UR; Jim Palmer in terms of
delivery.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; You want to talk about a bad week?: Cleveland's  &UR; Tom
 &UR; Candiotti threw 38 pitches in his final start (July 23), then threw
another 38 pitches in relief the next day, during the Indians' 21-1
loss to the Yankees. Two days later, he was designated for
assignment. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
Pitcher  &UR; Rick Reed of the New York Mets once again filed a formal
petition to join the players association last week. Reed, who
pitched in replacement games during the strike in 1995, insists it
has nothing to do with the licensing money each player receives,
somewhere around $80,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia has had four pitchers _  &UR; Joel Bennett,
 &UR; Steve Schrenk,  &UR; Anthony Shumaker and  &UR; Randy Wolf _ make their first
major league starts this season. In those four games, the pitchers
have combined for a 1.46 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   With  &UR; Mark McGwire providing the loudest and largest obstacle,
the St. Louis Cardinals will not play the first regular season
games ever in Japan next year. The New York Mets remain interested
in the venture, which may have to be shelved for another year.
</P>
<P>
   To point out exactly how much Pittsburgh has been decimated by
injuries, consider the Pirates have had 17 players on the DL,
including 12 right now. All told, the players have missed a
combined 767 games entering today's game. ``We have a lot of guys
hurt, but all we can do is put our best foot forward and try not to
sprain it,'' first baseman  &UR; Kevin Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati reliever  &UR; Scott Sullivan, whose Rookie of the Year
campaign is losing steam after appearing in 48 of the club's first
99 games, recently had this to say: ``My arm is so heavy, I feel
like I can touch my ankles without bending over.''
</P>
<P>
   Montreal's  &UR; Felipe Alou, the 1994 NL Manager of the Year, passed
 &UR; Gene Mauch last week to take over the franchise lead for games
managed with 1,127. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
It now appears that Atlanta pitcher  &UR; Odalis Perez's injured elbow
is much worse than initially believed. A magnetic resonance imaging
test showed Perez has a partial ligament tear. A second opinion is
awaited, but it looks as if Perez may be headed toward &UR; ``Tommy
John'' surgery, which likely will keep him out until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Tigers, pleasantly surprised by outfielder  &UR; Luis
Polonia's production, are talking about making a contract offer for
the 2000 season to the left-handed hitter. Polonia, mostly a
leadoff hitter, was batting .355 entering the weekend series since
being acquired.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's  &UR; Steve Avery, placed on the disabled list last
week, threw only one pitch faster than 81 mph in his final start.
More amazing, Avery was earning $50,000 for every start, which
easily could be the reason he never mentioned a sore shoulder. Reds
Manager  &UR; Jack McKeon and pitching coach  &UR; Don Gullett were unaware
of the incentive.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado and Milwaukee were on the verge of a blockbuster deal
that would have sent  &UR; Marquis Grissom and  &UR; Scott Karl to the
Rockies for  &UR; Darryl Kile and  &UR; Darryl Hamilton. The deal fell
through, though, when the Brewers balked at paying Kile's $8
million salary in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   With time running out, it's looking more likely that Los Angeles
will return to its spring home in Vero Beach next season. The
decision could come within the next week. The Dodgers still are
working on moving to Arizona for the 2001 spring, with the Texas
Rangers possibly coming along for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego third base prospect  &UR; George Arias, upset that he no
longer is an everyday player, is apparently receptive to the
possibility of a trade. Detroit still covets Arias, the
Diamondbacks' third pick in the 1997 expansion draft. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. NY YankeesBack on top, but still no signs of swagger from this
workmanlike bunch.  &QL; 
2. HoustonCould superstar first baseman  &UR; Jeff Bagwell be the NL
MVP?  &QL; 
3. TexasSkipping over the Tribe, the Rangers set their sights on
the Yankees.  &QL; 
4. NY MetsBad news:  &UR; John Franco won't be back for at least three
weeks.  &QL; 
5. ClevelandThe usual post-All-Star Game swoon is in high gear.  &QL; 
6. AtlantaFor once, Braves were looking to add key parts for the
September run.  &QL; 
7. CincinnatiIf pitcher  &UR; Steve Parris is seriously hurt, so are the
Reds' chances.  &QL; 
8. BostonSweeping two at Toronto was a confidence boost for this
sagging bunch.  &QL; 
9. TorontoAdding 1B  &UR; David Segui is the type of move a contender
makes. &UR; BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. MontrealPitcher Javier Vazquez has made himself look like a
keeper of late.  &QL; 
29. FloridaStarting pitching has been surprisingly bright in the
past three weeks.  &QL; 
28. DetroitUh, oh, owner  &UR; Mike Ilitch wants to get involved in the
daily operations.  &QL; 
27. Anaheim &UR; Mickey Mouse must be blushing over this failed project.
 &QL; 
26. Tampa BayLook out below; the anvil is firmly attached to the
feet now.  &QL; 
25. ColoradoIn 14 of the past 20 games, a starter has failed to
reach the seventh.  &QL; 
24. Los AngelesThe latest rift belongs to  &UR; Davey Johnson and
2B &UR; Eric Young.  &QL; 
23. MinnesotaThe kids are in need of another truckload of acne
medicine.  &QL; 
22. Kansas CityThe  &UR; George Brett celebration is now over. Time to
face reality. ON THE RISE &QL; 
 &UR; Diamondbacks: The recent losing ways have all but been forgotten _
at least until the next bullpen failing. Even with  &UR; Travis
 &UR; Lee on the skids, the Diamondbacks have regained the form that help
catapult them into first place in the NL West through most of June.
Arizona is in the midst of a 12-game stretch against NL West
opponents, a stretch that began in a positive manner after a a
three-game sweep in San Diego. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL; 
 &UR; Seattle Mariners: The club's record isn't the only aspect heading
toward the gutter. When the Mariners dealt  &UR; David Segui for a pair
of minor league pitchers, it was hailed as the equivalent of
raising the proverbial white flag. ``These deals give you the sense
we are looking for next year,''  &UR; Edgar Martinez said. Outfielders
 &UR; Ken
 &UR; Griffey Jr. and  &UR; Jay Buhner each had a closed-door meeting with
Manager
 &UR; Lou Piniella, supposedly to wonder what direction the club is
headed. Management tried to spin the move as bringing in the need
for relievers and that offense is not the problem. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
Chicago White Sox General Manager  &UR; Ron Schueler when asked whether
he was interested in taking back enigmatic outfielder
 &UR; Albert &UR; Belle: ``No. No, I think obviously he had two great second
halves for us. I probably said it best this spring when I said that
I miss him about seven or eight minutes a day. That's four at-bats.
I liked that part of it. I think everything else was a
distraction.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL; 
At 35, he's not a young kid anymore, but Tampa Bay pitcher &UR; Bobby
Witt, who practically pleaded for a chance to go to spring training
with the Devil Rays, has made the most of his newfound opportunity
and baseball life. Witt leads the American League with two
shutouts, a fact made more amazing considering he hadn't had one
since 1994. Witt has made 20 starts this season and has a 6-6
record, respectable considering he plays for one of the worst clubs
in baseball. His 117 innings lead all Devil Rays pitchers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
