<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-SIDEBAR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCAIN BRINGS SIZE, POINTS OFF BENCH  
 3 FILL SHOES OF POINT GUARD PERROT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It has taken three players to fill the point guard
void in Houston left by Kim Perrot.
</P>
<P>
   Van Chancellor starts 5-foot-7 Sonja Henning but is not shy
about switching to 5-11 Janeth Arcain, normally a small forward who
brings more offense and size to the point, or 5-6 Jennifer
Rizzotti, who can be a spark plug off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, in a 77-70 win over the Mercury, Arcain made the
difference with a season-high 13 points, three steals and three
assists in 30 minutes. On Thursday, Arcain's defensive pressure
helped Houston turn a 13-point deficit into a 71-65 win over
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was so good for myself because we come back to home
and we like to play here in Houston,'' said Arcain, a two-time
Brazilian Olympian and 1996 silver medalist. ``I play hard every
minute, and that's what I will do the rest of the season, play
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Arcain, who weighs 147 pounds, said being at point is less
physically demanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when I play the post, the game is so physical, and I
am not so strong,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different when you come from the bench to help the team,
but she (Henning) is a great, great player, too, and she's helped
the team so much, too. I just try to do my job the best I can in
not my real position. To me, it's not so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercury point guard Michele Timms said Arcain, annually Most
Valuable Player and two-time leading scorer of the Brazilian pro
league, limits a team's ability to cheat off the point in helping
defend the Comets' Big Three of Cynthia Cooper, Sheryl Swoopes and
Tina Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere else in the league, she'd be a starter, and anywhere
else I think she'd possibly have a shot at winning MVP,'' Timms
said. ``We know what sort of player Arcain is.''
</P>
<P>
   Henning, a third-year pro out of Stanford, went into the game
averaging 25.7 minutes, 3.9 points and 2.4 assists. She had one
basket and three steals in 10 minutes Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Between college and her return to basketball when the American
Basketball League started in 1996, Henning graduated from Duke
University Law School and began a labor law career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that any of us can reach Coach Chancellor's mind
and know from day to day exactly what it is he wants or expects,''
Henning said. ``Obviously our Number 1 goal is for the team to do
well. So if Janeth is playing extremely well, I'm thrilled about
that, and I know Jen is as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all practice hard. We all compete against each other very
hard, knowing we're helping the team and helping each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot, the point on Houston's 1997 and '98 WNBA championship
teams, is back in Mexico for treatment of lung cancer. She had
surgery to remove a brain tumor in February. She last attended a
Comets home game July 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only be who I am,'' Henning said. ``Everyone on this
team knows and loves Kim and knows what a great player she is and
how she's contributed to the success of this team. By no means is
that ever forgotten, and by no means did I come in thinking that I
would somehow replace that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came in hoping I could contribute in whatever way to
the success of the team and just go from there.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
