<HEADER>
A1545 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-MERCURY-COMETS-AZ     08-01 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-COMETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMETS COMMAND 1ST HALF  
 TURNOVERS DELIVER BLOW TO MERCURY'S PLAYOFF HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In what might be as close as it gets this season to a
playoff game, the Mercury was valiant, resilient and at times as
good as the two-time WNBA champion Houston Comets on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   None of which means much when a 77-70 loss leaves Phoenix
(10-12) winless in seven games at the Compaq Center and probably
grasping at its last straw when it comes to making the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury is 3{ games behind Sacramento (14-9) for the third
and final playoff berth in the Western Conference. A loss in more
than one of its final 10 games, beginning Monday at Minnesota, and
any championship dreams almost certainly will be gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably was a playoff game to us because we can't afford
to drop any more,'' Mercury point guard Kristi Harrower said. ``But
I think every time we do play Houston, it's a playoff game. It's
always a great game between us, but the first half we gave them too
much of a lead. If we played like we did in the second half all
game, we could have come out with a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Phoenix was in a 16-point halftime hole, 45-29, because
of a pair of vintage, defense-driven runs by the Comets: 11-2 to
erase a four-point deficit and 15-2 to dramatically extend a
three-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Both runs were started by a Janeth Arcain three-pointer but were
powered by steals. In the latter outbreak, Sheryl Swoopes converted
a theft into a break layup, a steal by Arcain produced a Tina
Thompson layup, and a Lisa Harrison pass picked off by Cynthia
Cooper became a Swoopes three-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to press every time,'' said Arcain, who had 13 points,
three steals and three assists in 30 minutes off the bench, mostly
at point guard. ``The coach tells me to press the point guard and
not to let Jennifer Gillom get the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillom, the Mercury's leading scorer, was limited to 11 points
in what Houston Coach Van Chancellor said was the best pro defense
he has seen against his former University of Mississippi
All-American.
</P>
<P>
   But Houston (19-4), within three points at halftime of the
franchise low it managed in a 60-48 loss in Phoenix on July 19,
never could get completely comfortable as the Mercury battled like
it did here in the 1998 WNBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Still down by 16, 57-41, with 12:46 left and with Harrison in
the locker room trying to stop her nosebleed from a Thompson elbow,
Phoenix pieced together a 9-0 run to be back in contention at the
8:14 mark.
</P>
<P>
   It was even closer, 64-59, at 2:54, after which Comets center
Polina Tzekova threw up an ill-advised three-point try, returning
the ball to the Mercury. But the play called during a timeout at
2:27 never came off as the 5-foot-4 Harrower was charged with an
offensive foul against the 6-4 Tzekova.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to protect myself because she was running
straight through me,'' said Harrower, who put her arms up to fend
off Tzekova. ``She does it all game, but I don't know, what can you
do when you're so small? It's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston scored seven of the next eight points to clinch its
fifth straight. The Mercury failed in its try for a
franchise-record fifth in a row and dropped to 3-9 away from
America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not like the last road game, an uncompetitive 84-63
loss in Los Angeles on July 21. Phoenix held up its end of
entertaining a sellout of 16,285 with an effort that would have
beaten almost any other team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know they're going to come back. They're just too good a
basketball team,'' Chancellor said. ``You see what happens to the
Comets, the expectations are so high that when another team comes
back, there naturally has to be something wrong with the Comets. It
can't be that the other team has played extremely well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury shot better than Houston (48.3-44.8 percent) and led
in rebounding (29-27). Center Marlies Askamp had her fourth
double-double (14 points, 11 boards), but it couldn't overcome 19
turnovers and the Comets' 14 steals and 17 points on fast breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd have had the second half like the first half, then we
would have been really disappointed,'' Michele Timms said. ``We're
upset about losing, but we know you can't give a great team like
Houston such a great head start and expect to win. But we can use
this as momentum.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
