r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-FREE-AGENCY-     08-01 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-FREE-AGENCY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS MEET WITH HARDAWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There's a Penny in the Suns' thoughts, but not
necessarily in their future.
</P>
<P>
   The pursuit of the free agent guard kicks off today as the NBA
lifts its monthlong moratorium on trades and free agent signings.
The Suns are one of several teams that 6-foot-7 Penny Hardaway is
interested in joining, but working out an acceptable sign-and-trade
deal with Orlando is no easy task.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Colangelo, the team's general manager, confirmed that the
team met Friday with Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a meeting,'' he said. ``We exchanged a lot of
information and had a chance to sit down with Penny and his
representatives face to face. We'll know soon enough what Penny
decides to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no timetable on that decision. There are a lot of
details involved in what is a very complicated transaction in a
sign-and-trade. Not only does Penny have to decide where he wants
to play, but then there is the matter of making a deal with Orlando
to accomplish that. There is leverage in different corners.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said ``several people from our staff'' met with
Hardaway and his agents, but he indicated that a deal is not
imminent. Expect Clifford Robinson to return. He appears close to
signing a four-year deal with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a few things we can get done (today),'' he said.
``It's possible we'll be able to get something done with Cliff.
That would be a significant step if we can get that taken care
of.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the Hardaway sweepstakes are the Toronto Raptors, who
are rumored to be offering Charles Oakley and Tracy McGrady. It may
be the best offer the Magic receives, but it may not be the one
most attractive to Hardaway, who has said he would like to play in
a warm weather city.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway met with Suns Coach Danny Ainge.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando, which would rather receive something than nothing, will
have to listen if it opts not to agree to Hardaway's seven-year,
$85 million demand.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hardaway is one of 140 free agents, don't expect an
abundance of player movement. Other than Toronto, Chicago and the
Los Angeles Clippers, few teams have salary cap room and most are
restricted by the terms of the NBA's labor agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Others free agents include forward/center Vin Baker, shooting
guard Mitch Richmond and big men Lorenzen Wright and Jermaine
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   The best bets for the Suns are a trade and to make good use of
their $2 million and $1 million salary cap exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``How we utilize those exceptions will be determined largely by
the progress of negotiations and what happens throughout the
league,'' Colangelo said. ``Everybody is waiting. We're looking for
the best basketball players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns took care of one piece of the puzzle Friday when
first-round draft pick Shawn Marion signed a four-year deal worth
just less than $5 million. But the team hopes to address other
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   After being swept by Portland in the first round of the
playoffs, Ainge said, ``We need to be tougher, that's the No. 1
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need some interior defense and some interior offense. If
you watch the teams that are successful in the playoffs, they have
at least one guy they can go to who is going to make the defense
double team.''
</P>
<P>
   Marion helped address the team's need for athleticism, but the
Suns still hope to upgrade a group that never quite seemed to mesh
last season and struggled in games that went down to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the team's wish list is a backup center.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns got an up-close look at several available players at
their recent free agent/rookie camp. &QL; 
Staff writer Bob Young contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
