<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-PANAM-PHOENIX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAN AM GAMES IN PHOENIX AREA? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINNIPEG, Manitoba _ They are the Games without the names.
Neither Maurice Greene nor Michael Johnson was on the track last
week. Neither Gary Hall Jr. nor Misty Hyman will be in the pool
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the No-Name Games continue. There are more than 5,000
athletes from 42 nations at the Pan American Games, an
Olympic-style event that is nearly 50 years old.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some drama, provided mostly by the U.S. and
Canadian baseball teams. And there has been some clock-and-dagger
controversy, thanks to the Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   But other than an angry Fidel Castro in Havana, and the
community in Winnipeg, itself, these Pan Ams have not been detected
on the continental radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   South of Grand Forks, N.D., they might as well not be happening
at all. In an era when television is reality and vice-versa, the
13th Pan Ams are not being carried by any U.S. network. Headline
writers are beginning to call them the Panned Ams. As an
advertising vehicle, the spin is not exactly positive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are three U.S. bids for the 2007 Pan Ams. A group
from North Carolina wants them in the tri-city area of Raleigh,
Durham and Chapel Hill. A South Florida committee is bidding to
host them along the Atlantic seaboard strip between Fort Lauderdale
and Miami. San Antonio says it will stage them within the Alamo
City, itself.
</P>
<P>
   Question:
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   The cost to the host city has been estimated at $100 million by
David Perez, an aide to Miami Mayor Alex Penelas. Winnipeg
newspapers say the city will wind up with a $38 million debt. A
contract with Canadian television and surprisingly brisk ticket
sales within Manitoba are offsetting much of the cost. But Winnipeg
had hoped for a U.S. television deal, perhaps with ESPN or ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of television coverage, and the absence of the biggest
stars are raising doubts about whether the Pan Ams are worth the
investment, both in money and time.
</P>
<P>
   The Pan Ams have been mentioned in passing as a possibility for
the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have discussed it informally,'' said Mike Sculley,
executive director of the Maricopa County Sports Commission. ``We
think of it as possibly part of 10-, or 15-year plan. Is it
realistic? At this point, who know?''
</P>
<P>
   First, Sculley said, the commission will pursue the Goodwill
Games, a scaled down Olympic-style event that already comes with
television. The Goodwill Games are a made-for-TV event by Ted
Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Sculley said he met with Turner official in Atlanta about eight
months ago. The costs of bidding are minimal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I think Turner places it it in region where he
wants for the best of his medium,'' Sculley said. ``It's not a
money-maker for him. There's some tax write-off, and it's a great
vehicle for his medium''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the gigantic Pan Ams, the Goodwill Games involve only 12
Olympic-core sports. In other words, leave the roller skates at
home. It also is not limited by geography. If the Goodwill
organizers wanted to ensure a swimming rematch between Hall and his
Russian rival, Alexander Popov, they could do so.
</P>
<P>
   The Pan Ams are further hamstrung by key events that have been
scheduled by some of the various sports. The best in track will run
next month at the World Championships in Spain. The best swimmers
are going to the Pan-Pacific Games in Sydney. The boxers are
preparing for the World Championships in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Goodwill Games are flexible. Organizers can simply schedule
them at a time when the best athletes are available and the
audience will watch.
</P>
<P>
   Still, nobody in the Valley has ruled out the Pan Ams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think of them as potentially part of a logical
procession,'' Sculley said.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley, as well as the state, already has several Olympic
links that potentially could lead to the Pan Ams.
</P>
<P>
   The United States Olympic Committee held its Congress in
downtown Phoenix last October. The 1996 Olympic swim team competed
in a final tuneup at a Phoenix Swim Club before the Atlanta Games.
USA Baseball is headquartered in Tucson. The 1992 Olympic boxing
trials were in Tempe. Herman Frazier and Sandra Baldwin of the
Valley are USOC vice-presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the facilities and the ability to host the Pan Ams,
right now,'' said Frazier, Arizona State University's associate
athletic director, who is the mission chief for the U.S. delegation
in Winnipeg and also a member of the committee that will review the
2007 bids.
</P>
<P>
   The dorms at ASU could serve as a Village. There's a first-class
track at the Tempe school, as well as a world-class pool, diving
well and arena for basketball, wrestling, boxing and volleyball. In
addition, there are Sun Devil Stadium, America West Arena, Veterans
Memorial Coliseum, Bank One Ballpark, Cactus League parks and the
Phoenix Swim Club.
</P>
<P>
   All were a key to a bid for an Olympic Sports Festival after the
1996 Atlanta Games. But the Festival encountered some of the same
problems currently facing the Pan Ams. It was a big event at a big
expense with young, mostly-unknown athletes. That's a tough sell.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC pulled the plug in 1995 and returned a $25,000 bid fee
to the commission, which was then known as the Maricopa County
Sports Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought we had the Festival,'' said George Weisz,
then the Authority's chairman and now an executive assistant to
Gov. Jane Hull. ``We learned a lot from that process. In addition
to the facilities, this community has the spirit to pull something
like that off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always exceeded what people coming into town for an
event expect.'
</P>
<P>
   Weisz argues that the community benefits in ways that aren't
reflected on a balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   ``A young girl who wants to be gymnast might work as a volunteer
and see what it really takes,'' Weisz said. ``That's the sort of
thing I'm talking about. The Pan Ams have a real record of
excellence. I think it's viable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, there are questions. Can you market it?''
</P>
<P>
   For the current Pan Ams, that's a tough question. For now, the
No-Name Games are also without an easy answer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 0125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
