<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-CARBAJAL-ARCE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARBAJAL COMES BACK FOR TKO IN 11TH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIJUANA, Mexico _ It was a war, a bloody war. A war in which
Michael Carbajal was getting pummeled.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the time it takes to throw and land a devastating punch
on the jaw of an unsuspecting opponent, Carbajal emerged from the
depths of boxing hell Saturday with a stunning 11th-round technical
knockout over World Boxing Organization junior flyweight champion
Jorge Arce.
</P>
<P>
   Carbajal's surprising victory was manifested in El Torreo de
Tijuana, a downtown bullring.
</P>
<P>
   Well, no wonder.
</P>
<P>
   These were two bulls, two raging bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Except, for the longest time, it was Carbajal playing the role
of a defeated bull, his blood-soaked trunks looking like something
out of one of those ``Nightmare on Elm'' ``Street'' diatribes.
</P>
<P>
   Yuck.
</P>
<P>
   Carbajal (49-4, 33 KOs), now 4-0 in his comeback from temporary
retirement, was trailing badly, 98-91, on all three judges' cards
entering the 11th of a scheduled 12-round fight.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of cautiously tip-toeing his way through the final
two rounds, which likely would have assured victory, the
inexperienced, 19-year-old Arce couldn't resist trading more
punches.
</P>
<P>
   And Arce paid dearly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was behind,'' said an exasperated Carbajal, who was
subjected to one more shot to the head in an impromptu post-fight
interview when an upset fan splashed him with a cup of beer. ``I
knew I couldn't win a decision. I figured I had to knock him out in
one of the last two rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbajal nearly knocked Arce senseless.
</P>
<P>
   The telltale blow, a piston-like lead right hand at 1:53, caught
Arce flush on the chin. Arce's knees buckled, but Carbajal didn't
budge.
</P>
<P>
   Carbajal continued to land left and right combinations, and the
two warriors eventually wrestled each other to the canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Carbajal got up.
</P>
<P>
   Arce didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not right away.
</P>
<P>
   When Arce did reach his feet, referee Raul Caiz, a Douglas
native now living in West Convina, Calif., saw a look in the
fighter's eyes that he hadn't seen in the first 10 rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Caiz saw stars.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of about 12,000 booed Caiz's decision and began to pelt
the ring and anyone in its path with everything from beer to limes
the size of softballs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a jubilant Carbajal danced in the center of the ring
and began hugging his cornermen as if he hadn't seen them in 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   What a reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Arce didn't much feel like spilling his guts
afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   But a spent Carbajal, despite slicing cuts over both eyes, one
of which was badly swollen, didn't mind a chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Arce) is a strong fighter, really quick,'' Carbajal said.
``He was quicker than I thought he'd be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to land that right hand all night. But he was so young
and quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbajal did land it once, in the sixth round, that momentarily
floored Arce.
</P>
<P>
   But at age 31, Carbajal, a world champion for the fifth time,
admitted he isn't nearly as quick as before.
</P>
<P>
   But, boy, can ``Manitas de Piedra'' (Little Hands of Stone)
deliver a punch to the nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lost a little bit of speed,'' said Carbajal, who, with
the win, signed a two-fight option with Top Rank. ``But I was still
strong enough to catch (Arce).''
</P>
<P>
   Good enough to send Arce (20-3-1, 15 KOs) home a loser when it
seemed to almost everyone he would be going home a winner.
</P>
<P>
   In the main event, Erik Morales (34-0, 28 KOs) knocked out
Reynante Jamili in the sixth round to retain his World Boxing
Council super bantamweight crown.
</P>
<P>
   Brother Diego Morales also successfully defended his WBO junior
bantamweight title with a win over Ysiais Zamudio. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 0126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
