<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTBREAK OF INJURIES NECESSITATES SEARCH FOR TIGHT END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. - Cardinals officials are spending many of
their waking hours looking for an available tight end.
</P>
<P>
   With a hamstring injury suffered by second-year pro  &UR; Terry Hardy
on Friday, the team is down to two healthy tight ends _  &UR; Derek
Brown and
 &UR; Jarius Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   Starter  &UR; Johnny McWilliams already was out because of an ankle
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're way down in numbers there,'' Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin said.
``Having only two guys causes a strain at that position and other
spots. We are trying to sign another tight end, but there are not a
lot out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy was running with the first team before his injury. He is
listed as day to day but likely won't return for several days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just tightened up on me,'' Hardy said. ``I just need to
stay off of it. I was counting on being out there. This (camp) is
my big chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said he didn't know when McWilliams will be available. He
was placed Thursday on the physically unable to perform list after
failing his physical.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can run all right, but he can't push off (the ankle) and
cut,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a former first-round draft pick of the New York Giants,
has been impressive the first two days of training camp. ``He looks
better in pads than without pads, which is a good attribute,''
Tobin said. ``A lot of guys look better without the pads. He has
caught the ball pretty well.'' &QL; 
Position switches
</P>
<P>
   An injury to starting right tackle  &UR; James Dexter (ankle) and the
absence of first-round pick  &UR; L.J. Shelton forced the Cardinals to
make two position switches on their offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jon Clark, who had been working strictly at right tackle, also
was used some at left tackle Saturday. Shelton was expected to
battle with veteran  &UR; Matt Joyce and second-year pro  &UR; Anthony
Clement at left tackle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ernest Dye, who had been playing guard, was moved to right
tackle to offset the loss of Dexter.
</P>
<P>
   Also hurting on the offensive line is backup center  &UR; Allen
 &UR; DeGraffenreid (neck).
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't run (the team) at the end of practice because I don't
like to condition the squad piecemeal,'' Tobin said. ``We have a
few positions that are so thin, we couldn't run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing this year that all of the injuries are on the
offensive side of the ball.'' &QL; 
Good news &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive day,  &UR; Eric Swann participated in
several drills, his most extensive work since having knee surgery
in December.
</P>
<P>
   He seems to be moving fine north and south, but his movement is
restricted laterally.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's moving a lot better than in minicamp,'' defensive line
coach
 &UR; Joe Greene said. ``He moved well (Friday). He moved even better
(Saturday).'' &QL; 
Close race &QL; 
Don't expect the place-kicking competition between  &UR; Joe Nedney
and &UR; Chris Jacke to be decided soon. Both are listed on the first
team, and Tobin expects it to remain that way for much of camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a hard call,'' Tobin said. ``We'll see how
well they kick in the preseason. Sometimes it boils down to a gut
decision by the head coach, and that could be the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jacke's career was on hold a year ago. What he did for us
coming in and winning those games down the stretch increased his
value around the league. Nedney also made a lot of clutch kicks for
us and has a tremendously strong leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacke, out of football for nearly two years, had three
game-winning kicks after replacing Nedney, who suffered a knee
injury on his kicking (left) leg while making a tackle in Kansas
City on Nov. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Nedney also had three game-winning field goals before being
injured. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
