<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANDERS BEST, MANY CARDS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cardinals players held an informal survey Friday to pick the
best running back of all time.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive players, including history buff  &UR; Corey Chavous,
picked career rushing leader  &UR; Walter Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the offensive players, including starting running back
 &UR; Adrian Murrell, voted for  &UR; Barry Sanders, the league's
second-leading rusher of all-time, who informed the Lions last week
that he was retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I'm a modern day player, I look at what Barry is doing
against guys bigger, faster and stronger,'' Murrell said. ``What he
has accomplished in 10 years is incredible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing against him in '97 when he got 2,000 yards and
got it against (the Jets) in the last game. In the first half, he
had about 20 yards. In the second half, he broke a run about 30
yards. From that point on was an amazing run. It looked as if he
was going to break a big one every time he touched the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals cornerback  &UR; Aeneas Williams has played against Sanders
for nine seasons and been a teammate on the NFC's Pro Bowl team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's symbolic to trying to hit a fly,'' Williams said of
trying to tackle Sanders. ``That's what I'll remember, his change
of direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a doctor on ESPN said in order for someone else to
do this (run a similar style to Sanders), he literally would have
to have a broken ankle. The ankles would have to dislodge.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders has caught a lot of criticism for informing the Lions
right before training camp started that he had retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a coward,'' said  &UR; Kirk Gibson, the former major league
outfielder who was a two-sport star at Michigan State. ``Barry
Sanders should have announced his retirement before a packed house
at the Silverdome. He hung 'em out to dry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he's not a phony, but it sure looks like it.`
</P>
<P>
   Williams can't believe anyone would call Sanders a coward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he could have let the team know a little earlier, but I
don't know when it finally hit him that he didn't want to play,''
Williams said. ``Coward is not even in the picture. I don't
understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he understands how Sanders could leave the game,
about 1,400 yards away from breaking Payton's record because
``Barry never allowed this to determine who he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as one individual in the Lions organization put it: ``What
does it tell you when a man is willing to give up $7 million just
to get away from your organization?''
</P>
<P>
   That is the amount Sanders will be asked to return from the $11
million signing bonus he received two years ago as part of a
six-year, $34.56 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions say they won't trade him, but don't be surprised if
several teams, particularly the 49ers and the Dolphins, where his
college coach at Oklahoma State,  &UR; Pat Jones, is an assistant, try
to acquire him in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Lions players know how much Sanders will be missed. They were a
5-11 team last year with him. They could do much worse this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You almost took it for granted that eight guys would be in the
box waiting to tackle Barry, and there'd be less traffic
downfield,'' wide receiver  &UR; Johnnie Morton said. &QL; 
Smashing debut &QL; 
It's easily forgotten that Sanders played his first pro game
against the Cardinals in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   He signed two days before the season opener, practiced for the
first time the next day and then entered the game in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On his first run, he gained 18 yards. He finished with 71 yards
and a touchdown on nine carries. &QL; 
Reluctant participant &QL; 
All-Pro guard  &UR; Randall McDaniel, the Arizona State and Agua Fria
High School graduate, was scheduled to report to Vikings camp
today, ending any threat of a holdout or possible retirement.
</P>
<P>
   He won't show up a happy camper. He still is furious that the
team reneged on its promise to renegotiate his four-year, $12.5
million contract, a deal that has two years remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy with what happened,'' McDaniel said last week.
``I feel a promise was broken . . . I wish they would step up and
honor what they said to me. I would hope they would.''
</P>
<P>
   Vikings Coach  &UR; Dennis Green, who blots all negative thoughts out
of his mind, including his 2-6 playoff record, was asked about
McDaniel's unhappiness and how it might affect his team's
chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any player's not happy, he'll probably be by himself
because we come to camp with a happy team,'' Green said. ``That's
our style. The leaders on this football team, whether it be  &UR; Cris
Carter or  &UR; Robert
 &UR; Smith or  &UR; Johnny Randle or  &UR; Robert Griffith, come to camp on a high
road. Anybody not on a high road is going to be out of place. I
don't care who it is.'' &QL; 
Presumed innocent &QL; 
Jets offensive tackle  &UR; Jumbo Elliott doesn't seem concerned that he
is facing a lot of legal trouble.
</P>
<P>
   He is charged with misdemeanor assault, harassment, disorderly
conduct and public lewdness after allegedly urinating in the sink
in the women's bathroom at a bar and then punching a woman in the
chest, causing nerve damage to her chest and back. Elliott then
allegedly punched the woman's friend, breaking the friend's jaw.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott and former teammate  &UR; Matt O'Dwyer, now of the Cincinnati
Bengals, have been sued for $6.3 million by three police officers
and two bar patrons.
</P>
<P>
   The July 10 incident doesn't have Elliott worried. In fact, he
thinks he has done little wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, basically, from Day 1 _ and I've been playing in New
York for 12 years and regardless of that _ it has been total
character assassination,'' Elliott said. ``You flip on
``SportsCenter'' and you hear you're the next  &UR; O.J. Simpson. I
mean, what the hell is that crap?
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd wish the thing could go to trial and let the system do
what it has to do instead of listening to a couple of people, and
everybody rushing to judgment and just looking for headlines and
flashy stories. I'm not worried about any of this stuff because I
think in court, it'll come out.`
</P>
<P>
   Short shots &QL; 
Sometime this week, the Cardinals will back off their 1940s
negotiating stance and sign their two first-round draft picks _
 &UR; David &UR; Boston and  &UR; L.J. Shelton. If the rest of the league is
giving rookies ``bells and whistles,'' the Cardinals will have to
do it, too. They can't be on an island.
</P>
<P>
   There is a reason the 49ers are playing in next year's Hall of
Fame game. Quarterback  &UR; Joe Montana is a lock to enter the Hall and
safety  &UR; Ronnie Lott likely will join him.
</P>
<P>
   The newest member of the Cowboys, defensive end
 &UR; Alonzo Spellman, says ``Big D'' is the perfect place for him. He's
right because if he has another meltdown and takes on a SWAT team,
the Cowboys probably will forgive and forget and let him back. Look
how many chances they've given  &UR; Michael Irvin. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at 602-444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
