<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU_FACILITIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU OVER HAULING SPORTS FACILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - When Jon Clanton, a former Peoria Centennial High
football standout, walked into Nebraska's weight room for the first
time, his jaw dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the biggest place I've ever seen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clanton soon committed and is now a nose tackle with the
Cornhuskers. His reaction is the type Arizona State hopes to spark
with numerous capital improvements that will upgrade _ and in some
cases replace _ nearly every campus sports facility.
</P>
<P>
   Several projects have been completed, others are under
construction and a few won't get under way for several years. ASU's
recent successful fund-raising efforts provided the impetus for the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an ambitious undertaking,'' Athletic Director Kevin White
said. ``But we feel when all is said and done, we'll have some of
the finest facilities in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   White is pleased with the results of one of ASU's earliest
completed projects: a new batting cage and weight room for Packard
Stadium. The Sun Devils led the nation in batting average and runs
per game at the end of last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something's working,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   Other completed projects include a new track surface at Sun
Angel Stadium and a 65-yard artificial turf practice field for the
football team.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the improvements is an addition to the
Intercollegiate Athletics Complex, which sits on the south end of
Sun Devil Stadium and houses coaches and administrators, as well as
the ticket office, sports medicine, academic services and the
football locker room and weight room.
</P>
<P>
   The new addition will extend farther south, almost to Stadium
Drive, and add approximately 40,000 square feet. The building will
be renamed the Student-Athlete Center.
</P>
<P>
   Key components in the facility include a 15,000-square-foot
weight room that is more than three times the size of the current
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Nebraska weight room, when you walk in there, you get the
impression they will make you the best athlete they can possibly
make you,'' said Vic Cegles, ASU's lead associate athletic director
for external affairs. ``You walk into their student services center
and you get the feeling that you're going to graduate, and that's
what they tell you. That's what we want.''
</P>
<P>
   A hall of fame room near the entrance of the facility will be
added, as well as a repositioned ticket office. A 150-seat theater
room will be built on the second floor in addition to breakout
rooms for football position coaches and their players.
</P>
<P>
   The entire third floor will feature an academic service area
that White believes ``will be as good as anybody's in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the ground-level football locker room will be
expanded, and a stadium club will be added on the fifth floor for
pre-game, post-game and halftime use by select groups. It will turn
into a training table for athletes during the week and a study area
in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building is going to be state of the art, first class,''
White said. ``We believe it will rival anybody's.''
</P>
<P>
   Construction is scheduled to begin in August 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Another key project is the addition of an Olympic Training
Center off Wells Fargo Arena. The 25,000-square-foot building will
house practice facilities for wrestling, gymnastics and volleyball.
It is a sorely needed building. Gymnastics and volleyball currently
practice away from Wells Fargo, and although wrestling is within
the building, its practice room is small and features a pole in the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to make a tremendous impact,'' ASU wrestling Coach
Lee Roy Smith said. ``It's an opportunity for us to impress our
recruits with more than just the campus, academics and tradition.
First and foremost, when you recruit blue-chippers who hope to
excel in their sport, they want to feel good about where they'll
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cegles: ``I think recruiting is a major part of this
project. When you're recruiting, say against Pac-10 schools,
everybody, for the most part, has full scholarship allocations.
What makes the difference is what your facilities are like, and
your coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``You now have the chance to recruit the most outstanding
athletes, I don't think there's any question.''
</P>
<P>
   One project near completion is the $700,000 Robson Player
Facility at the Whiteman Tennis Center. It adds 4,500 square feet
of locker room, office space and an observation deck.
</P>
<P>
   Construction has begun on softball and soccer stadiums that come
with a $5.2 million price tag.
</P>
<P>
   Other additions to look for include new Sun Devil Stadium video
boards that will be 50 percent larger than the current ones and
$700,000 worth of stadium suite enhancement. Both are expected to
be completed by football season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
