<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIFT REQUIREMENT PROVES BOOST, NOT BUST, RAISING $6 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Two years after the uproar that accompanied
sweeping changes in athletic fund-raising, only one sound can be
heard around Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ka-ching.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletic Director Kevin White's decision to overhaul the way the
Sun Devils raise money and sell tickets has proven fruitful for the
university and did not result in a mass exodus of supporters, as
some predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Major gift and corporate support has increased from $2 million
to $6 million in three years. Football season ticket sales,
although down from last year, still likely will be the
second-highest total of the decade, White said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still educating people,'' said Vic Cegles, ASU's lead
associate athletic director for external affairs. ``It will still
be a few years before everyone understands, but we're a lot
closer.''
</P>
<P>
   After no ticket price increases in a decade, White announced in
1997 that about half the seats in Sun Devil Stadium would require a
gift, ranging from $50 to $2,500, from new season ticket
purchasers. Some current ticket holders saw modest increases up to
$50. The approximately 34,000 seats that do not require gifts
belong to students or are in and around the end zones.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, gift donations as low as $100 and as high as
$25,000 would qualify the donor for perks such as newsletters,
apparel and access to bowl tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're paying a little more, but not much,'' said season ticket
holder Kristen White, 44, of Mesa. ``After the initial grumbling of
having to throw in another $50, it really doesn't seem like that
big of a deal. We kind of had the feeling that's what other
(universities) are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   White initiated the move so that ASU's fund-raising
infrastructure would resemble that used by most major universities.
By separating the gift requirement from the ticket price and
sending them in separate mailings, the department gives fans a
clearer sense of their benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thought was we needed to better acknowledge donors by
providing benefits commensurate with giving level,'' White said.
``This is what a lot of other institutions have been doing for
years.''
</P>
<P>
   And many have been quite successful at it. Last year, Tennessee
made $10.7 million from contributions tied to ticket priorities.
</P>
<P>
   It was still a risky venture on ASU's part. Unlike the schools
it is trying to emulate, ASU does not sell out its stadium on a
regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   But on the heels of a 5-6 football season, 84 percent of fans
have renewed, and the Sun Devils expect to sell 7,000 to 8,000 more
tickets once students return to school. Currently at 34,678 season
tickets, ASU will not reach last season's 47,371, in part because
of the loss of a home game against Notre Dame. Last year, many fans
purchased season tickets to have access to tickets for the Notre
Dame game.
</P>
<P>
   Another decision by White was to bring ASU's booster groups,
which had control of season ticket sales, under one athletic
department umbrella. Previously, the Sun Angel Foundation
controlled distribution of prime seats at Sun Devil Stadium, but it
has since merged with Intercollegiate Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very dependent upon the activity of the Sun Angel
Foundation,'' White said. ``They're a very important part of
enhancing all of our resources. The merger was our attempt to build
centrality.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, White would like to see the number of donors increase
from 9,000 to 20,000. Tennessee has nearly 11,000 donors and
Florida even more.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Angel Foundation President Don Bocchi said the Sun Devils
plan to pursue out-of-state donors more aggressively than in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to talk to alumni groups in northern California,
Southern California, Chicago,'' he said. ``Now that it's easier to
communicate and stay in touch, we feel it's an area to tap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing, to stay competitive in this market, is that
we have to establish loyalty. And that's what we're working on
doing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
