<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME AROUND, ROCKET WAS A DUD 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As triumphant returns go, this one fell shy of Tuna
Bowl II, when Bill Parcells's Jets KO'd the Patriots on ``Monday
Night Football.'' This wasn't President-elect JFK coming home to
address the Massachusetts Legislature. It wasn't even Larry Bird
bringing his Indiana Pacers to Boston to show Rick Pitino who's
boss.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his life, Roger Clemens took the Fenway
mound Saturday wearing a Yankee uniform. It was weird. It was a
little like watching Natalie Jacobson on MSNBC or reading Mike
Barnicle in the New York Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox won the game in dramatic fashion when Clemens's
longtime teammate, John Valentin, dumped a ninth-inning,
still-unseen single into the hidden holy ground of the left-field
corner.
</P>
<P>
   But when the important win is long forgotten, the memory of this
sweltering Saturday in July of '99 will be the cascade of boos that
rained down on the big head of the man who won a franchise-record
(tied with Cy Young) 192 games for the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   From the time he was introduced until he was mercifully yanked
in the sixth, Clemens was hooted by Red Sox Nation. They also
insulted him with a mock cheer of ``Rog-er.''
</P>
<P>
   In a hideous postgame interview, Clemens gave new meaning to the
word obtuse. He claimed he was happy with his performance and that
he did not hear the hazing. It was amazing. Evaluating a
performance (5 innings, 4 runs, 3 walks, 2 strikeouts, unable to
make a 5-2 lead stand up) that was miles shy of true Rocketry,
Clemens sounded like my dear old mom evaluating one of my
not-so-great report cards. He could only see the positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' he said. ``I was real strong and I tried to
harness that. Sometimes being a little wild is good. It was pretty
much the same as usual . . . I felt great out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Huh? Why do we even bother to write this stuff down? Better to
leave the man alone than to repeat these preposterous remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter: Were you disappointed?
</P>
<P>
   Roger: Not at all. It was a hard-fought game. We had our
chances. We'll get 'em tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter: Did you hear the boos?
</P>
<P>
   Roger: No. You hear cheers and you hear boos. There were a lot
of Yankee fans and it was great to hear them cheering.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter: But this was harsh today. There were a lot of boos.
</P>
<P>
   Roger: I didn't notice it.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens can claim he didn't notice that the left-field wall is
still green, but his shaky start provided much titillation for the
angry masses. This was the day when the Rocket discovered what
happens when a former New England sports hero is found sleeping
with the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a big deal, guys,'' he said. ``I've been gone from
here a long time. I've been a Yankee for a while now and it's
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. Coming to Fenway with the Blue Jays was one thing, but
there's simply too much hard feeling for Boston fans to be rational
about Clemens-as-a-Yankee. He may yet wear a Red Sox cap when he
enters Cooperstown in the next century but right now he cannot be
loved here because he is a member of the hated Pinstripe posse.
</P>
<P>
   The Gotham Rocket struggled mightily. His control was awful (54
strikes, 40 balls) and hardly anybody swung and missed. There was
none of the mastery we saw here for a dozen seasons, and none of
the perfect rage that made him so dominant when he was here with
the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're surprised when he pitches the way he did today,''
admitted New York manager Joe Torre. Leaking a little more truth,
the skipper said, ``He seemed pretty relaxed. I didn't notice
anything other than his disappointment with the way he pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been one wacky weekend for Red Sox fans. Friday night
they suffered the indignity of a 13-3 beating and saw the Sox fall
behind the Jays in the wild-card fight. There were several fights
in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the New York cops and firemen up here for a holiday
weekend,'' said a Boston cop. ``They're the ones starting all the
fights.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything flipped Saturday. The crowd was peaceful (save for
the verbal abuse heaped on Clemens), the Sox roughed up the Rocket,
and Boston won in the ninth in front of George Steinbrenner and a
national television (Fox TV, and we're still waiting for a shot of
the winning hit) audience. There were more boos than booze.
</P>
<P>
   The series concludes Sunday night with another made-for-TV
special. Bret Saberhagen never walks anyone, but it might be a good
idea to pitch around Chuck Knoblauch (two leadoff homers so far) at
the start of the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
