<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL FIRED UP AS MILLOY MELLOWS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Perhaps five or 10 minutes before the end of
the Patriots' first practice, Lawyer Milloy wandered over to an
area not often visited by defensive players _ far behind the
offensive huddle. Milloy knelt next to wide receiver Terry Glenn
and began talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to let Terry know that we need him,'' Milloy
said Saturday in what may turn out to be the most important
half-hour of this New England camp. ``I told Terry, `I have all the
respect in the world for you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn listened. Milloy kept talking.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours earlier, Milloy had exploded, upset that his
friend Willie Clay had been cut loose from the Patriots secondary.
``I don't care about one spectacular season somebody had,'' Milloy
said Friday, adding the team ``couldn't depend on someone who is
coming back from injury all the time every year.'' Milloy didn't
name names, but Glenn fit the profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Terry that he's a great player but he can't help us
from the sidelines,'' Milloy said as the two, each on one knee,
watched a play Saturday morning. ``I told Terry, `Out of everybody
on the field, you're the one who makes everybody's job easier,
including myself.' I told him that I respect him and that I want
him to be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The fissures that divided the team late in the 1997 season, when
the offense fell apart and the defense felt it had shouldered too
much of the load, seemed back. An angry Milloy said Friday the New
England players most known to the fans were not the ones to count
on, similar to words said by other defensive players after the 7-6
playoff loss in Pittsburgh. That problem was not evident last year;
now it was creeping back.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pete Carroll heard of Milloy's tirade and talked to his
safety Friday night and again Saturday morning. Milloy said he had
a long night and decided to rectify what he called ``a mistake in
judgement'' in publicly questioning some teammates. Milloy decided
to apologize to teammates; Glenn was the first.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn took Milloy's words as a ``kind of'' apology. The receiver
said Milloy ``is a grown man and he's going to say what he's going
to say and I'm one of those guys who comes down here to do my job
and all that other stuff I leave outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy got up to leave, heading back to the defensive side.
Glenn mingled with Troy Brown, Vincent Brisby, Shawn Jefferson, and
the other receivers. A few more plays were run. Practice ended.
</P>
<P>
   And then Carroll called his players together, stood in the
middle of a large circle and spoke, and pointed his finger, and
shouted, and waved his arms, and pointed his finger some more, and
shouted again, and waved his arms again. The coach stood in that
circle for more than 10 minutes; virtually every player listened
raptly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to be done before anybody could talk to these
guys,'' said Carroll of his heated, emotional speech to the
players. ``And that's why I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   All the questions about the 1999 Patriots were erupting, not
bubbling, from the surface only moments into camp. To some, it
seemed Carroll had taken a callous approach to releasing a player
so close to the start of camp, because if Clay had been released
earlier, he might have had a jump on finding another job.
</P>
<P>
   To others, it seemed Carroll was repeating a move from last
offseason when cornerback Jimmy Hitchcock was traded to Minnesota,
a move that had a domino effect on the New England secondary. As
with Hitchcock, this move was made without clearly having a player
to step in and fill Clay's position.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Carroll's status as a coach ``on the hot seat,'' as
Milloy insinuated Friday, was brought into the open almost
simultaneously with the opening of camp. Carroll had to react.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the situation called for,'' Carroll said. ``It's
an emotional time for (Milloy) and our club and we had to deal with
it. And we hit it right between the eyes. And I think we'll become
better because of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a big mistake,'' Carroll said of Milloy. ``He stepped
out of line and said some things we don't want our players to
represent.'' Carroll told the team that individuals can speak their
mind in this country ``but when you represent a club, a team, a
business, or a group or whatever, you have to be conscious of the
impact of your statement.''
</P>
<P>
   In Milloy's case, Carroll went on, ``our guy got emotional,
spoke from his heart, and was hurt by what happened and what came
out of him was all kinds of things. He feels bad about it.''
</P>
<P>
   After speaking to the team, Carroll walked over to the edge of
the circle where Milloy was seated and motioned to his player to
step into the circle. ``Lawyer did it voluntarily,'' said team
owner Bob Kraft. Added Carroll, ``Lawyer volunteered and that was
exactly the way he wanted it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next two minutes, as Carroll retreated to the
background, Milloy spoke to teammates and apologized for his
comments Friday. ``I was upset and it was my fault,'' Milloy told
teammates. ``I know you injured guys are trying your hardest to get
back on the field. I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy added, ``They know I'm an outspoken person and they still
respect me. I didn't throw out any names (Friday) and I didn't
implicate guys. My teammates know that I'd die for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, in explaining his heated speech, said he had met with
Milloy Friday night after the positional meetings and also Saturday
morning and that his strong feelings carried beyond what harm
Milloy's words might cause the team. It's too common in American
society, let alone sports, for people to be too individualistic
when they are part of a group, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not OK, when you represent a lot of people, to speak on
your behalf only,'' Carroll said. ``I think you have to learn how
to speak while being conscious of the group you represent.''
</P>
<P>
   Tackle Bruce Armstrong, one of the team's leaders, said he was
glad Carroll and Milloy stepped before the team ``and nipped this
in the bud. (Carroll) seemed to take this heartfelt and maybe it
had hurt him a little bit and he really got his point across. And
Lawyer? We all know how emotional Lawyer can be but there is no
more of a team guy on this team than Lawyer. We don't hold it
against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy tried to leave Friday without speaking to the media only
to circle back and speak his mind about Clay's dismissal. ``You
guys know I tried to leave but there was a lot going on in my head
and I came back, which I probably shouldn't have. As far as what I
said, there was some truth to it. You guys know I speak from the
heart. But you live and die with whatever you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy and Carroll said there were no fines levied. ``The way
I'm going to get through this is to lead by example,'' said Milloy,
``and get everybody ready against the Jets (in the opening game).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 0231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
