<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA PRESSURE, CONCERN FOR KIDS DROVE HASEK OUT 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Dominik Hasek was asked during a conference call on
Thursday whether he would change his mind about retiring if someone
offered him outrageous money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone would offer me $25 million to play, I would say,
`No, thank you,' '' Hasek replied.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the Buffalo Sabres goalie, the best in the world at
what he does, is leaving a boatload of money on the table for
reasons he says have more to do with sanity and quality of life
than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, who said he will quit the NHL after this season to return
to his native Czech Republic, is walking away from $16.5 million
that he would've been paid over the 2000-01 season and the option
year after that.
</P>
<P>
   It's not $25 million, but it's close enough.
</P>
<P>
   He said he still has the competitive fire in his belly to play
in the league, but he has enough money and the harsh media
spotlight and the American influence on his children are more than
he can bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will speculate (about his reasons), like they did when
I was injured,'' Hasek said. ``But I'm doing this for two reasons:
my kids and too much pressure from the media.''
</P>
<P>
   The 34-year-old father of two _ Michael, 9, and 4-year-old
daughter Dominika _ said he and his wife, Alena, were very
concerned about his children losing touch with their culture. Hasek
said every offseason, when they return to the Czech Republic, he
sees his children struggle more to adapt to their surroundings and
keep fluent in their native language.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the media pressure, Sabres owner John Rigas said Hasek
nearly retired this spring after contemplating it last November,
but he was talked out of it. From the way Hasek talked Thursday, he
doesn't sound like he will be talked out of it this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attention I receive is overwhelming,'' he said. ``I don't
enjoy it. It's time to take a step back to a different life. I
don't want to live behind a wall. I hope once I retire, it will be
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Czech Republic native Jaromir Jagr, the league's MVP this
season after Hasek was awarded the honor the previous two, said he
can relate to Hasek's frustration. ``I'm sure he's done the best
thing for him and for his family, although he's in such great shape
that he could play for another 10 years,'' said Jagr.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it will be only one more year. Then the league, which
has already lost Wayne Gretzky, will be short another superstar as
it prepares to welcome two more teams into the fold in a league
already short on talent.
</P>
<P>
   More's the pity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I have a confession. I'm going to miss Dale Hunter. Hunter
announced his retirement after 19 seasons and will take a
front-office job with the Washington Capitals. He finished the
season with the Colorado Avalanche because the Caps' classy GM,
George McPhee, wanted to give Hunter a chance to win a Stanley Cup.
He didn't, therefore completing his career without one, much as we
fear will be the case for Ray Bourque in Boston. Who can forget
Hunter grinding Craig Janney's face into the Boston Garden ice
during the 1990 Conference championships? Of course, Hunter went
way too far in jumping Pierre Turgeon when it became clear the
Islanders were going to eliminate Washington in the '93 playoffs.
He served his unprecedented 21-game suspension at the beginning of
the 1993-94 season for injuring Turgeon and went on to terrorize
opponents right up until he said goodbye. Hunter's distinction is
that he had 300 goals and 3,000 penalty minutes, but I'm still
struck by something I saw at the '97 All-Star Game, Hunter's first.
He looked uncomfortable, and friend Dino Ciccarelli said it was
because he was sitting with all the stars that he was being paid to
harass throughout the season. Hunter, who turned 39 Saturday, is as
humble and nice off the ice as he was a menace on it. When asked
about him a few years back, one of his former teammates in
Washington said, ``Why would anyone be afraid of him? He's just a
farmer.'' He was referring to Hunter's offseason occupation on the
family farm in Ontario. Yes, he was a farmer, making him an expert
at pitchforks in and out of the rink. And he was fun to watch. He
always looked for every edge he could find. He was a competitor and
went about his business quietly . . . The Sedin twins are all
signed up in Vancouver, but that's still no assurance they will
play for the Canucks this season. It's possible they could be in
attendance at training camp, but word out of that city is that the
youngsters _ Henrik and Daniel _ will remain in their native Sweden
for one more season, playing for MoDo of the Swedish Elite League.
If they do decide to stay home, Canucks GM Brian Burke said the
club won't do any lobbying to change their minds. ``That's not all
bad from our perspective,'' said Burke. ``If they elect to go back,
there won't be any hard sell from our standpoint.'' Henrik, a
center who was taken with the third pick in the June draft after
his brother (a left wing) was taken with the No. 2 selection, said
the twins would love to be in training camp, at least for the
experience, but since Sweden's season begins very early, it's
likely they won't be able to attend. Burke said even if the Sedins
committed to playing in the NHL for this year, it would take time
for them to adapt, as we all saw here with Joe Thornton. ``They
would be like most 18-year-olds,'' said Burke. ``Minimal impact
until Christmas time, until they learn the league and their way
around the smaller ice surface.'' What's funny is that the kids
look so much alike, the team color-coded them so reporters could
tell the difference at their news conference . . . This has nothing
to do with hockey (it is summer, after all), but I have to say the
Cummaquid Golf Club is home to some of the funniest people I've
ever met. Thanks for my one-day honorary membership despite my not
knowing the difference between a driver and a 9-iron.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ottawa Senators have told star Alexei Yashin, who was a
finalist for the Hart Trophy as the NHL's most valuable player this
past season, that they will not renegotiate his contract or trade
him. Yashin, who is due to make $3.6 million in the final year of
his pact, reportedly wants between $8 million and $10 million. ``We
will not discuss changes in this contract,'' wrote Senators GM
Marshall Johnston in a letter to Yashin's agent, Mark Gandler.
Gandler relayed the information by telephone to Yashin, who is in
Paris on vacation. ``I spoke with him briefly,'' said Gandler. ``He
didn't appear overly concerned about the situation.'' It's widely
expected that Yashin will threaten to sit out the year with the
expectations that he'll make up what he loses this season in his
next contract. All of you sympathetic to Yashin's bratty plight,
raise your hands. Not a one? I didn't think so. These strong-arm
tactics designed to elicit more money on an existing contract are
nothing short of extortion. If you don't plan to honor it, then
don't sign it. If you sign it, live up to it. Simple. It won't ever
happen, but that's why one-year contracts across the board make the
most sense . . . The Canadiens are hoping, as well as expecting,
that forward Saku Koivu will be ready at the start of training
camp. Koivu has had a couple of ailments. He suffered a broken hand
at the world championships, but more bothersome was a left knee
problem that required surgery. He suffered the original injury Dec.
7, 1996, at which time he was leading the league in scoring. He
missed 32 games that season. It has been speculated he hasn't been
the same since. Playing on a team in a downward spiral probably
didn't help either . . . Much like the estimable Bourque, veteran
Guy Carbonneau keeps on ticking. The forward, who turned 39 in
March, has re-upped with the Stanley Cup-champion Dallas Stars for
two more years. Carbonneau will enter this year 31st on the
all-time games played list (1,249). He has won three Cups, with the
other two earned in Montreal in 1986 and '93. Carbonneau and Stars
GM Bob Gainey are the only two players to win the Selke Trophy as
the league's top defensive forward on three or more occasions.
Gainey won it four consecutive years _ 1978-81 _ as a member of the
Canadiens . . . Speaking of Jagr, he went back to his native land
this summer for two reasons besides taking a vacation. He opened a
bar and enrolled in college. ``Now that I'm 10 years older, I have
realized that after proving myself as a hockey player, I should try
something different,'' said Jagr of his reasons for his new
business venture. ``Then, I think, it wouldn't hurt to finish my
studies. I have to complete six college tests this summer in
Kladno, and four more tests are awaiting me in the winter. I would
return home for a few days to master it.'' . . . Only 34 days to
training camp, and the first regular-season game is Oct. 2. Tell
the truth: Are you painting those ``Sign Dafoe'' banners for
opening night yet? Better get busy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
