<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS TAKES BLAME, PROMISES CHANGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Angels manager Terry Collins couldn't take it.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had just lost to the Minnesota Twins 8-0 on Saturday
night. They were shut out by Eric Milton, who went into the game
3-8 with a 5.30 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   So Collins let off some steam to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stink!'' he said. ``It's my fault. Nobody else's. The
responsibility comes to me. (Today) you'll see changes. There will
be no more finger pointing. The finger pointing should go right
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no pressure on us. We need to relax and we need to
play the game the right way. I'm sickened by it. But it's my fault.
Some things happened and we couldn't stop the snowball.''
</P>
<P>
   No deal: The Angels didn't make any deadline deals, but general
manager Bill Bavasi said the team came close to trading pitcher
Jack McDowell to a National League team.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our opinion, Jack should be pitching for a contender if
he's healthy,'' Bavasi said. ``We tried to accommodate that.
Pitching here is almost a waste.''
</P>
<P>
   No worries: The possibility of being traded might affect some
players, but not pitcher Ken Hill. At least that's what he claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't control that, I can't worry about that,'' he said.
``I'm not worrying about it. I've already been traded five times.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility that Hill will be traded still exists because
trades can take place after the deadline, but players must clear
waivers. And it is doubtful any team would claim Hill off waivers
considering his history of elbow problems and his salary ($5.6
million next season).
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead: Now that the trading deadline has come and gone,
what next for the Angels?
</P>
<P>
   There are two months left in the season and nothing to play for
but pride. And of course, a nice paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I play because I enjoy it, plain and simple,''
shortstop Gary DiSarcina said. ``If you don't enjoy it, you won't
stay in the game very long. I missed 2{ months this year and it
reminded me how much I just want to be out there on the field every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Mo Vaughn said he believes the last two months
will show who belongs and who doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to show a lot about you as a player,'' Vaughn said.
``As players, we put ourselves in this situation. We've got to live
with it. I played in situations like this in Boston, and it's very,
very tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Replacing Omar: Omar Olivares was scheduled to start tonight's
game against the Twins until he was traded Thursday to the Oakland
A's. Saturday, he gave up one run and four hits in seven innings to
get the victory in a 5-1 win over Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels will start Steve Sparks tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher almost back: Pitcher Tim Belcher threw 80 pitches in a
simulated game Saturday and could be activated this week. He's been
out since June 26 with a broken right pinky finger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
