</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GLENN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY GLENN PREPARED TO SILENCE CRITICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By NICK CAFARDO 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ It's all in the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   That's all you need to know about Terry Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   When he plays, the Patriots have a .676 winning percentage _
23-11. When he doesn't, the Patriots are 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a great number,'' said Glenn after a vigorous first day
of practice in which he got a lot of reps and looked in midseason
form catching balls from Drew Bledsoe against Ty Law, Steve Israel,
Kato Serwanga, and company. ``I don't know if that's all true, and
when they say that it makes me feel good because I've been hurt.
Even when I came back on the field, I felt the wrath of what it
means to have all your good players there to win.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Terry Glenn gets it.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pete Carroll said at his daily press conference he's never
seen Glenn as physically and mentally prepared to start a season as
he is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in great shape right now,'' said Glenn. ``I really didn't
do things on my own (at the strength and conditioning program). It
was structured, and I had guidelines. Me and Coach Carroll talked
back and forth, and we went back and forth on what we need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll tried to get into Glenn's head this offseason, talking
to him constantly about his ``awareness on the field.'' Glenn was
talked to about being able to see what was going on around him
better and reacting to situations with more awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn harkens back to his rookie year, as most Patriots fans do.
He said it wasn't so much conditioning that made him play well, but
a better mental approach. He said that had nothing to do with the
coach at the time, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first year, I was more in tune and more apt to do what I
had to do,'' said Glenn. ``It's become more like in your second
year and your third year, you forget about what got you there. You
come in and it looks like you're in great shape, but then a guy
turned over my ankle. I'm not sure that had anything to do with
conditioning.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of holding back, Glenn went full steam Saturday.
Cornerbacks are playing him tough and getting physical with him
when need be. The word is out that Glenn needs to be in playing
shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going all out,'' said Glenn. ``I got a lot of reps. I
don't want to overdo it, but I want my to get my reps in. Last year
Lawyer (Milloy) hit me and it was a hit I'd take in a game so that
was fine. You want to make sure you're ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn said he is sick of always being talked about and whether
or not he ``gets it.'' But he understands only he can silence his
critics. He says he's greatly motivated by negative articles about
him in the newspaper but realizes he needs to stay healthy and be a
player of great impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm coming here and I'm trying to stay healthy for the team
and for myself. It's frustrating. I can pull my hair out all day
long, but I have to come here and go at it. I guess I do (get a bum
rap), but there's nothing I can do about it. When you get paid to
play 16 games and you don't play, then that's what happens,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn is not getting down on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought I was a good receiver, not one of the best in
the league, but I do what I need to do to get the job done. I can
do what needs to be done,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 0243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990801.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1572 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      08-01 2815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW IS TIME TO DEBATE FEATS OF CLAY 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Eventually, the anger will subside in Lawyer
Milloy and Ty Law and others who disagreed with the Patriots'
cutting of Willie Clay.
</P>
<P>
   Milloy and Law will go on to be All-Pro defensive backs with or
without Clay, but the question is how the Patriots will be affected
by the loss of another veteran.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe published reports last week, Clay was a
malcontent, a cancer who'd whisper bad thoughts in the media's ear.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, no player wanted things done right more than Clay.
The truth is that Clay was a winner, not a whiner, who played 48
games in three years. Missed tackles? Apparently he made some. He
had 103 tackles, 66 solo, which was third-best on the team, and he
averaged more than 95 tackles and four interceptions a year.
</P>
<P>
   One would have to say he was a good investment for a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Clay was the leader on defense. When players didn't understand
things, which player did they go to? Clay. When things were falling
apart in the locker room, to whom did the players turn? Clay. This
was a bad guy? When the team went through its roughest road a year
ago, why did someone in the organization tell Clay to ``bring this
team together and win in spite of the coach''?
</P>
<P>
   He was verbal, perhaps too much so for the current regime. He
was also someone who was brought in by Bill Parcells. In fact, the
only player now remaining from the group of free agents Parcells
signed in 1996, which included Clay, Mark Wheeler, Monty Brown,
Michael McGruder, Pio Sagapolutele, Larry Tharpe, and Tom Tupa is
Shawn Jefferson, and his days may be numbered.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of that, Clay never was perceived as a ``Parcells
guy,'' nor was he a ``Pete Carroll guy.'' He merely wanted things
done right, and when they weren't, he spoke up. Whispering things
to the media doesn't make you a bad player.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it wasn't a surprise that one NFC Central executive was
shocked when he saw Clay's name on the waiver list.
</P>
<P>
   ``For that team, Willie Clay was a perfect player,'' he said.
``Willie is a guy who can really help a team on the verge of
winning something because he understands the game. He's one of the
smartest players in the league. He can read defenses. He can tell
people where they're supposed to be on the field. Every team has to
make tough cuts, but this was a strange one, especially this late
in the game. They must feel they have someone who can play in his
spot, or they wouldn't have made the move.''
</P>
<P>
   Corwin Brown, the former Patriot now with the Jets, told a group
of New York writers Saturday, ``I know Willie's not happy about
being cut, but I'm sure he's glad it happened. A lot of guys want
out of there. Willie is being painted as a whiner, but he never
whined when Bill was there. Lawyer doesn't want to be there either.
I don't know why they do any of the things they do up there.
Everybody is saying bad things about Willie, but you look around
the league at some of the bums playing his position, and he's
better than all those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not proper for anyone not in the football business to
criticize Carroll and Bobby Grier's judgment on players. They have
spent their lives playing, coaching, and evaluating talent on all
levels. That is what they do for a living.
</P>
<P>
   But the feelings and words of Milloy and Law should not be
discounted either. Despite Milloy's outburst on Friday and his
subsequent apology to teammates he might have offended, he would
also not take back his thoughts, and they are the views shared by
many. Some chose not to make a big deal of it for the sake of team
chemistry and respect for the people making those decisions. And
those who chose the silent route did so admirably.
</P>
<P>
   But for the players who are on the field, when an offensive
formation looked funny and there was confusion, the person they
looked to for order is Clay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't possibly expect the new guy to be able to come in and
make the same reads and recognize the things that Willie did,''
said Law. ``That's years of studying the game. He had that ability
that you have to have on the football field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't the fastest or the quickest, but he was so smart,''
said wide receiver Terry Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Third-round pick Tony George may become a great player. His
agent (as if he isn't biased) believes George will be an All-Pro.
That's terrific. If he's the next Milloy, then the move would be
worth it. But he won't be the next Milloy right off the bat. For a
team that tried to get a more veteran presence, the Patriots have
just gotten younger at a crucial position. They've had to make that
same sacrifice at center (Damien Woody for Dave Wohlabaugh), at
outside linebacker (Andy Katzenmoyer for Todd Collins), and now at
free safety (George or Chris Carter for Clay).
</P>
<P>
   These sacrifices aren't unique to the Patriots. Every team has
to make them in the new era of big-money deals that have strapped
teams to the limit. Andy Wasynczuk is forced to work miracles on a
daily basis so the Patriots won't be in tough situations in the
years to come and find themselves, like the Jets, already $13
million over the cap for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots obviously have a game plan in restructuring their
contracts, though two things stood out this offseason: The team
didn't do a major renegotiation of Drew Bledsoe's deal, which would
have freed up major money, but opted for a smaller maneuver
guaranteeing part of Bledsoe's enormous salary. Under the cap
rules, the team can't renegotiate a new deal for the quarterback
until next winter.
</P>
<P>
   The other question is why the Patriots didn't restructure Ben
Coates's deal. If anyone deserves to have more money thrown his
way, it's Coates, a future Hall of Famer who, even more than Glenn,
is essential to the success of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Coates is in the second year of a three-year deal and is being
paid $2.1 million this year. That cap number could have been
reduced significantly, but the Patriots never spoke to his agent.
Why? There's a method to what they're doing. But Coates not making
as much money as Mark Chmura or Frank Wychek?
</P>
<P>
   Those renegotiations probably could have led to keeping Clay and
possibly keeping Collins and Wohlabaugh.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, management and the coaching staff didn't want to
keep those people for whatever reason. Like Milloy said earlier
last week, it's not the popular players whose jerseys kids wear
most often who make a difference to a team; it's the less popular
players _ the middle-of-the-road salaried players _ who seem to
make the biggest difference in whether teams win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   Clay alone may not make a huge difference, but when you add his
loss to those of Wohlabaugh, Collins, Ferric Collons, Wheeler, and
others who added depth and veteran leadership to a team, it hurts.
</P>
<P>
   Now a younger player is going to have to make important reads.
Now Milloy is being forced to come out of his element a bit and
take over some of Clay's duties. Milloy became an All-Pro because
he didn't have to worry about those little things. He could just
play and hit people and be intimidating. Now he has to think more.
Will that affect him? Only time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   What's unfortunate is all of the mudslinging that goes on when a
player gets cut. Clay was a good player. Period. Everything else
said about him is nonsense. Certain players were told this week
that if Clay hadn't opened his mouth to the Globe and criticized
the decision to release him, the team might have reworked his
contract and re-signed him. Unfortunately, that sentiment never was
expressed to Clay.
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising that the first person to call Clay when he
was released was Bill Belichick, the former Patriots' secondary
coach whose input brought Clay to New England. Belichick told Clay
to be wise about the next team he plays for and to make sure it's a
team that can take advantage of his style. He told him that Clay
has the power to make a great impact on any defense because of his
smarts, his hands, and his ability to make the big play.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are a team that has field-savvy players and usually
keeps them around. Some of the Jets may be a little older, and
maybe they don't have the physical tools of a Tebucky Jones, but
they have the knowledge to make up for it. That's what Clay brought
to the table.
</P>
<P>
   But Carroll and Grier felt it was an area they could afford to
downsize and give a younger player a chance. We will watch the
outcome with great interest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every year it comes straight from the de facto captain's mouth.
This is the Patriots' world according to Bruce Armstrong:
</P>
<P>
   --On his new workout philosophy that has created a newly
proportioned body:
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of just lifting weights, I had a program. I did the
work. If I wanted to work out four days, I worked out five or six.
Instead of wrapping my workouts around my daily schedule, I wrapped
my daily schedule around my workouts. In the past, if I wanted to
play golf in the day, I used to work out at night. I didn't do that
this year. I was pretty much focused on getting the results I was
looking for. As you get older it gets harder. You have to work
harder. I didn't want to disappoint my teammates or the coaches. I
had to find a way to get something more out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   --On the importance of training camps:
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the fact that I detest training camp, hate it with a
passion, it's a necessary evil. You can't get this kind of
preparation anywhere else. I used to joke with my neighbors in the
offseason about how hard training camp was. In other sports, as a
basketball player you can find five friends for a pickup game. As a
baseball player you can go hit balls and throw. As a football
player, you can't go get 10 of your buddies and go out and beat the
(expletive) out of each other. There's nothing you can do to make
up for it. Training camp has to be hard.''
</P>
<P>
   --On whether Carroll's camps have been hard enough:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been different. The hardest training camp I'd ever been
under was Rod Rust and we went 1-15. We hit both practices with
full pads because Rod thought the team had gotten a little soft
under Raymond Berry. What he wanted was a battle-hardened team. You
have to find the right gauge. There are teams who don't practice in
pads at all. The 49ers never use pads. The Broncos the past couple
of years don't wear pads and they won two Super Bowls.''
</P>
<P>
   --Are the Patriots playing to save the coach's job?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm talking to the players, I'd say, this is a great team
sport. It's full of individual performances. What are you playing
for? For prestige, money to make the team, for a championship? If
you get the most out of each guy no matter what his motivation is,
that's good for the team. I hope everyone's motivation is to win a
championship because then everything takes care of itself. Are you
playing so that your head coach doesn't lose his job? I can't
answer for anyone else, but for me that's not a consideration. I'm
better off if he stays because that means we're winning, and that's
what I want.''
</P>
<P>
   --On the negativity surrounding the team:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's a problem. It's shocking to say we'd be
fifth or fourth at best. Nationally, we're not thought of well. But
the year we went to Super Bowl, I said no matter what the
predictions are, you have a chance to disprove them.''
</P>
<P>
   --On the fractured leg that hindered his play last year:
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt for a long time. Hopefully last year was an aberration
and that I can play the way I'm capable of playing. Sometimes it
was fine, and sometimes the pain was shooting. When it hurts, there
was nothing there; I couldn't push off from it. Luckily, it healed.
It shouldn't be a factor. I know what kind of player I am. If I
don't play to the level I think I'm capable of, there's no bigger
critic than me. You have to ask, `Is the guy not playing at the
high level he's accustomed to, or does the guy just suck?' I don't
think I suck. I think I was still contributing to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   --How good the Patriots can be:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's realistic to win at least one game. That's if Drew gets
picked off by a sniper and Ben gets captured by one of those
aliens, and if we had no players. If the people on this team who
have Pro Bowl ability play like Pro Bowlers, then this team can win
it all. This team had some great moments. As long I've played, we
never could beat Pittsburgh at Pittsburgh, we beat San Franciso in
a big game, and the Buffalo and Miami games we won gave me the best
feelings I've ever had after a football game. We didn't quit, and
something good came out of it. We also had some times when guys
were hurt and had some problems. The bottom line is I want to win.
All you can do is get that across to other people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A call was placed to Ray Anderson's Atlanta office Thursday
afternoon, but the agent who represents Milloy didn't return it. It
wasn't until Friday morning when Anderson called this reporter.
``Sorry I couldn't get back to you,'' said Anderson. ``There were
some real-life things going on that I couldn't avoid.'' Anderson's
office is located in the building in Atlanta where a gunman opened
fire on workers. Anderson and his staff, advised that the gunman
was in the building, ran for their lives into the street. We were
glad to hear from Anderson Friday morning . . . Anderson was the
man who filed the complaint against Tank Black that got Black
de-certified by the players union Wednesday. Black has 20 days to
appeal, and it's almost certain Anderson will have to testify
against Black for alleged recruiting violations. Anderson was
especially peeved about Black's recent comments that he was being
targeted because he was black. Anderson, who is also black, said,
``The people he's screwed the most over the years are
African-Americans. How can he say that?'' . . . Despite problems
between management and 10-time All-Pro Vikings left guard Randall
McDaniel, he has committed to the team for the next two years amid
rumors he was retiring. McDaniel had been promised by former vice
president Jeff Diamond, now with the Tennessee Titans, that he
would have his deal redone after last season because he was the
third-highest paid offensive lineman on the team. A future Hall of
Famer shouldn't be third. But McDaniel decided to honor the final
two years, though he's not doing it without a bitter tone in his
voice that may be disruptive to Dennis Green in the future . . .
The Jamal Anderson contract situation gets nuttier by the day. It's
one thing to nickel and dime the best running back in the NFC (with
Barry Sanders gone), but it's another to insult him. Anderson is
asking to be in the same echelon with Terrell Davis, and on higher
one than Marshall Faulk. Seems sensible. Then what's the holdup? If
he's available a second time and the Patriots don't bite, even if
it means releasing another veteran or two, shame on them . . . The
Bengals are demanding a first- and a third-round pick from
Baltimore for the services of disgruntled wide receiver Carl
Pickens. Right now the Ravens are offering only a two and a five,
which is the deal the Colts made with the Rams for Faulk. Right
now, it doesn't appear there will be a trade, and it looks more and
more as if Pickens will stage a holdout, perhaps for the entire
season . . . Mike Ditka may be using his own plane on road trips.
He recently purchased a plane and flew to the team's training
center in LaCrosse, Wisc. Wonder if anyone will ask, ``Why doesn't
he fly with the team?'' . . . It sure looks like former Denver
backup Jeff Lewis is being groomed to be the starter in Carolina.
While George Seifert insists it's Steve Beuerlein's job to lose, he
may lose it quicker than anticipated. The Panthers reworked Lewis's
deal, giving him a $1.2 million signing bonus and salaries of $1.5
million in 2000, $3 million in 2001, and 3.75 million in 2002.
Seifert said, ``Steve Beuerlein is still our starting quarterback,
and it's still a competitive situation.'' You can see now where
Carroll gets his coachspeak . . . Can you imagine with all that's
going on in the world, agent Fletcher Smith actually tried to use
the race card against the Eagles in negotiations with Donovan
McNabb? If Black gets decertified for giving out money and gifts to
college recruits, then what should happen to a guy who brings up
something so ridiculous in negotiations for a rookie football
player? He claimed that white quarterbacks like Peyton Manning,
Ryan Leaf, and Tim Couch all received the popular voidable years in
their contracts, but the Eagles wouldn't give him any because
McNabb is a black quarterback. The Eagles should have been a lot
more insulted than to have worked out a deal so quickly after those
comments.
</P>
</TEXT>
