<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEONARD FOCUSING ON RYDER CUP SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. _ Just two weeks ago at Carnoustie in Scotland,
Justin Leonard suddenly found himself being handed an opportunity
to win his second British Open when Jean Van de Velde, the leader
by three shots, blew up with a triple bogey on the 72d hole.
</P>
<P>
   It was not to be for Leonard, however, as Scotland's own Paul
Lawrie ran away from both him and Van de Velde in the four-hole
playoff with birdies on the third and final playoff holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still pretty tough,'' said Leonard as he recalled the
events at Carnoustie while he paused between rounds at this
weekend's Greater Hartford Open. ``I feel good about the things I
did, the decisions that I made. You know, hindsight is 20/20. If
I'd have known, I would have done things differently. At the time,
I think I made all the right decisions, and that feels good. It
certainly makes it easier. But it's tough to go through that for
four days and to get so close and just have four holes between
three guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two birdies on the last two holes would have been very hard to
beat. But if you go through all that and be so close to winning, it
really would have been something special.''
</P>
<P>
   There were various reactions in Dallas, his home town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through the story quite a few times,'' said Leonard.
``People have asked me, `When did you know? Where were you? What
was going on?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny to hear the stories about where my friends were and
what they were doing and how they had all turned their TVs off and
started doing something else. All of a sudden somebody called and
said, `You've got to flip it back on.' That happened to just about
everybody. My friends and family were great. Nothing but positives.
Those kind of things certainly help you get over something. I think
any golf fan was pretty surprised in watching what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ryder Cup has been high on Leonard's list of priorities.
``It's a great event,'' he said. ``It's unique. Playing with the
best 12 players from the US and to be a part of that group and be
together in some social occasions is great. I had as much fun in
the practice rounds and going to dinner two years ago at Valderrama
as you could want to have. It's a different kind of fun from the
actual competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed that . . . to be able to get in a situation where
you're pulling together and you just have one goal in mind. Right
now, I'm not thinking about Ryder Cup. I'm working harder to
impress my caddie. I figure if I play well these next three weeks,
that's all I can do, and hopefully everything will take care of
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The LPGA returns to Pleasant Valley CC in Sutton, Mass., this
week for the first time since Pat Bradley was a rookie in 1974 and
the LPGA Championship was there. This fills a void on the New
England calendar, since the Friendly's tournament left Crestview CC
in Agawam and Welch's event left Blue Hills CC after last year.
</P>
<P>
   The LPGA sold the rights to the event to Entertainment Sports
Equities of Brighton, and after a lengthy search for a title
sponsor, the event will be known as the areaWeb.com Challenge.
``Everything's in full gear,'' says ESE's Frank Neer. ``The tents
are up. The sky boxes are up.'' There has been talk the sponsorship
money isn't there. Neer said it is.
</P>
<P>
   There has been talk that other big sports events in Greater
Boston this year has strapped the corporate coffers, which has hurt
the LPGA event. ``What should be talked about,'' said Neer, ``is
that Boston has been blessed to have these events. The All-Star
Game, the Davis Cup, and the Ryder Cup won't be in the area next
year. The LPGA will.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament falls between the LPGA's fourth and final major
championship _ the du Maurier _ and the Weetabix British Women's
Open. The field seemed to be outstanding, but late defections by
SeRi Pak, who won the LPGA Championship and the US Women's Open
last year, Karrie Webb, and Kelly Robbins leave just five of the
top 11 money winners in the field: No. 3 Lori Kane, No. 7 Dottie
Pepper, No. 8 Sherri Steinhauer, No. 9 Kelli Kuehne, and No. 11
Rachel Hetherington.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, who stirred up the embers over a potential boycott
of the Ryder Cup in years to come, leaves the GHO Sunday night for
a flight to southern California and Monday's played-for-TV match
with Tiger Woods. The winner of the 18-hole match will collect $1.2
million. ``The way I look at it,'' said Duval, ``is it may bring a
few more people into the game. Because of the time it's going to be
on television, it'll hopefully be exposed to people who
traditionally don't tune in on Sunday afternoon. It's a showcase.
In the end, is it important who wins, and is it important to our
careers? Probably not.'' Duval was somewhat apprehensive when the
proposal was initially advanced. ``I didn't want it to be perceived
as an elitist competition,'' he said. ``It seems to me it has
become something that's an exposure of golf. It just happens
Tiger's 1 and I'm 2. I think it's pretty fair to say the most
important player of the match is Tiger, because of his popularity,
and the brightness of his star is certainly a lot greater than
mine. Once I realized we had to separate ourselves, I felt good
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Golfers are taking to the vineyards. David Frost seized the
opportunity to have a little wine-tasting gathering in the press
building on Wednesday night, and Greg Norman has a gala planned for
Monday and Tuesday ending on his yacht. ``I grew the grapes,'' said
Frost. ``He's just putting his name on the label.'' Frost, who grew
up in Cape Town, has a limited reserve of Cabernet Sauvignon
available this month, and he placed order forms in player's
lockers. Norman will preside over the opening of Mildara Blass/Greg
Norman Estates, with guests mustering at a press reception at The
Reef Bar and The Breakers in West Palm Beach, Fla. There is a golf
club outing on Tuesday, and upon return guests can choose from a
list of custom treatments ranging from a 45-minute Kur Exfoliating
Mineral Scrub to a 50-minute Warm Seafoam Body Wrap. Guests
eventually end up on Norman's yacht, Aussie Rules. It seems there
are enough receptions to enable everyone to sip wine without relief
. . . Brad Faxon, who withdrew from the GHO because he felt pain in
the left wrist he broke in a fall at his home in Barrington, R.I.,
on May 23, was on hand Friday recruiting players for the $1 million
CVS two-day tournament at Rhode Island CC Monday and Tuesday. He
and Billy Andrade are cohosts. Faxon played his first full 18
Thursday at Newport CC and hopes to play in the PGA Championship at
Medinah next week. ``I was pretty close,'' he said about entering
the GHO. ``I'll test it out at the CVS. The two-day format will be
a good test. I'll skip the Buick. I want to play the PGA and the
International. I'm not going to play unless I'm certain it's all
right. I don't have any problems hitting into the ground or in the
rough, just in the transition of my swing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara, who won the Masters and the British Open a year
ago, said he may back off after another year of intense competition
on the PGA Tour. ``I don't feel I'm out to prove anything when I go
out and play now,'' he said. ``I feel what happened last year was a
dream year. But I feel throughout my career I've been a very
consistent uplayer. I've had a little bit of ups and downs, but
when you look at the PGA Tour media guide and see how many times
I've finished in the top 30, how many times I've traveled around
the world and played here, it's a lot. This is my 14th event in the
US, but I've traveled around the globe quite a bit already.
Needless to say, I'm trying to capitalize on what happened last
year. Let's face it. I don't draw galleries like Tiger Woods and
Greg Norman, but I sat down last year and put a game plan together
with my manager. I said, `This is what I want to do. Now is my time
to shine a little bit.' I'm not 27. I'm not 32. I don't need to
worry about burning myself out. I need to think about trying to
capitalize on what happened last year, and I'm trying to do that.
If somebody sits me down in the media room and says, `You should
not have done that,' my banker says I should and my wife says I
should. I'm 42; I'm not a kid. I'm going to play this year and next
year, and then I'm going to back off and do more things with my
family. I may not play that much after next year. I might back down
really a lot.'' . . . There are no Ryder Cup tickets available at
this address.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
