<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 02:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1577 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-KEYPLAY-BO     08-01 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTIN FLY BALL BROUGHT FAIR RESULT 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-KEY PLAY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When John Valentin hit a fly ball into the left-field
corner Saturday, the universal sign for victory changed. The
split-fingered salute favored by war heroes returning home and
former president Richard Nixon became a two-handed gesture. After
the Red Sox' 6-5 victory over the Yankees, members of both teams
could be seen holding their hands 1 foot apart.
</P>
<P>
   For the Yankees, the gesture illustrated the narrow margin of
the Boston triumph. Manager Joe Torre, third baseman Scott Brosius,
and left fielder Shane Spencer held up their hands and looked down
at a distance so small they could only smile and shake their heads.
For the home team, the gesture was thanks for the peculiarities of
Fenway Park. Those steeped in Red Sox lore know the difference a
foot and a favorable breeze can make in matters foul or fair. Both
sides used the two-handed signal as an explanation of the Red Sox'
winning play.
</P>
<P>
   With the stage set for a come-from-behind victory in the ninth,
Boston fans held their breath as Valentin's shot to left traveled
along the foul line. The Yankee infielders and outfielders were
playing shallow with Jose Offerman representing the winning run on
third. The ball traveled past Spencer on a trajectory that deviated
little from the line.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee left fielder could only hope for interference by a
fan or for it to go foul. The angle of the ball and its distance
precluded any chance for Spencer to throw out Offerman at the plate
if he caught it. The ball dropped behind the left-field stands and
beyond the view of the anxious crowd. It fell just a foot inside
the line, ending the game as Offerman scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I hit it, I thought it was foul,'' said Valentin.
``But as I looked at it, it started to just stay there. It didn't
hook at all. When it didn't hook, I kind of knew it was going to
come back fair from just the experience of playing here. I've seen
so many balls come back to the left fielder. I was just hoping it
did so he could catch and, basically, (I'd have) a sacrifice fly to
win the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer was left with a Catch-22. In the visiting clubhouse, no
one wanted to talk about the outfielder's RBI or his fifth multihit
game this season. Yet, there really was no play. Whether he caught
the ball or let it drop, as he did, home plate was out of reach.
The second-year player denied that left field at Fenway was the
most difficult corner he has patrolled, ranking Yankee Stadium
tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It carried,'' he said of Valentin's drive, which fell
approximately 5 feet short of the wall. ``It got up there and was
foul and kept carrying. It was foul for a while and then it just
came back. Anything toward the (warning) track, you pretty much
know you're not going to be able to make a play anyways. That's why
we were playing real shallow. That's all you can do right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius, who had a good view of the play from third base,
thought the ball would stay foul. He agreed that Spencer made the
right decision and complimented Valentin for sending the ball to
the right spot.
</P>
<P>
   Added Torre as he opened his hands a foot wide, ``We can't see,
but we could guess what happened. That if he does catch the ball,
(Offerman's) going to score anyway. The ball was foul and it blew
back and it was fair, I guess, by yea much at the end. It's a
decision that you make there and I can't fault that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Red Sox dugout faces left field and has
unobstructed sight lines to the foul pole, Torre's counterpart
didn't have a much better sense of the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even see third base from where I am,'' Jimy Williams
said.
</P>
<P>
   But his third base coach saw all that he needed. Wendell Kim
watched the wind blow the ball back. He also saw the ball blow far
enough away from the fans that they had no chance to interfere. The
coach told Offerman to stay at third until the outfielder caught
the ball or let it drop. Kim said making a play facing the wall was
difficult, because the outfielder must stop and turn around to have
any chance of reaching his target.
</P>
<P>
   A 305-foot throw looks very long when a 1-foot difference can
decide a one-run ballgame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
