A1578 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANALYSIS-B     08-01 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON VICTORY WAS MANUFACTURED 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Sometimes we forget this is a different Red Sox team.
They know they can't win games by trading cannon shots with a club
like the New York Yankees. But on any given day they can bump and
grind and beat anybody. That's especially true at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody understands this more than veteran third baseman John
Valentin, one of the heroes of Saturday's 6-5 victory over New
York. Twice he drove in the tying run to overcome deficits of 2-0
and 5-4. In the ninth inning, he won it with a moon shot to left
field that fell for a single, scoring Jose Offerman, who had
tripled.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin accomplished all this, mind you, while facing Roger
Clemens and two excellent relievers in Jason Grimsley and Ramiro
Mendoza. Later, after the sellout crowd of 33,179 had departed,
Valentin summed it all up logically.
</P>
<P>
   ``We approach all the games the same way, every day,'' he said.
``Sure, it's a little more exciting when the Yankees come in. But
that's because the fans make it so. Basically, we pitched well
today and that gave us an opportunity to score runs. Our style is
almost like a National League style, unlike Red Sox teams of the
past. We're a team that puts the ball in play. When you do that
you're going to get contributions from all sorts of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody gave Valentin and his teammates much of a chance against
Clemens, who came in with a 3-0 record in five career starts
against Boston, two of the victories coming with Toronto. The other
was a 4-1 decision May 19 at Yankee Stadium, and twice he had
no-decisions. Saturday, Clemens was given a 2-0 lead in the first
inning, but it vanished in the third as quickly as you could say
Trot Nixon. The rookie's home run was followed by a walk to
Offerman, a stolen base, a wild pitch, and a sacrifice fly. They
score like that all the time in the senior circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who had taken the opener of this weekend series,
13-3, Friday night, took a 5-2 lead but single runs by Boston in
the fifth and sixth ended Clemens's day. In the seventh, Offerman
walked and again scored, this time on a wall double by Valentin.
Then came the kind of ninth inning that can only happen at Fenway.
A shot to the triangle that Offerman turned into a triple followed
by a fly ball that gave Boston the win. ``I knew it was going to
come back,'' said Valentin. ``The left fielder let it drop because
if he'd caught the ball, it would have been a sacrifice, game over.
Anything that is hit into the air on the line usually comes back
into fair play. I was hoping it would do that, and that's exactly
what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin has 10 home runs this season but is happy to settle for
the kind of hits he got Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my job,'' he said. ``I try to play hard and do the best
I can when I'm out there. Offerman got on base a bunch of times and
did a good job. The bullpen did a great job against a good hitting
team. All around, we did a good job.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you face a Roger Clemens, you come out prepared for his
best game. He had some control problems and he got in trouble. He's
still Roger Clemens. He still pitched very good. We were just able
to tie the game and win it.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Valentin also worked his magic on defense,
robbing Scott Brosius of a sure double with a leaping catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to time my leap just right so I could catch the
ball,'' Valentin said. ``But it wasn't hit that hard and if it had
gotten by, it would have caused some trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   What Valentin did Saturday was something his teammates have been
doing a good portion of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have confidence in everybody who comes to the plate, be it
veteran or a first-year player,'' Valentin said. ``We stick
together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
