<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION QUELLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA _ Ariel Graziani displayed some inspiring touches and
excellent offensive instincts in his Revolution debut
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. But Graziani could not be expected to solve the
team's defensive problems and lack of midfield spark during a 4-1
loss to the Tampa Bay Mutiny.
</P>
<P>
   This was a demoralizing defeat, the Revolution's third in
succession, as once again they did not appear competitive, falling
behind early and displaying few resourceful qualities.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the team could change with the return of John
Harkes and Joe-Max Moore from US national team duty, possibly in
time for Friday's visit to Colorado. But, like Graziani, neither
can be expected to solve the Revolution's defensive
vulnerabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution will have to regroup quickly to avoid a prolonged
slump such as the nine-game losing streaks they endured the last
two seasons. They are in fourth place in the Eastern Conference
with 18 points in 19 games, but have earned points in only one game
since June 19, a win over the Mutiny. And they have been outscored,
11-3, in the last three matches.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they surrendered a sixth-minute goal to Raul Diaz
Arce, then seemed to be fighting an uphill battle, bogged down by
lack of possession and straining against the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Carlos Valderrama directed the Mutiny offense. Or,
more accurately, he wandered around the Raymond James Stadium field
and dissected the Revolution with slick touches and sharp passes.
The Revolution had few responses, and Valderrama and Mauricio Ramos
were virtually untouched as they applied pressure in the offensive
zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave Valderrama too much room,'' said Revolution defender
Dan Calichman, who departed at halftime after reinjuring his hip.
``He was on the ball too much and he hurt us pretty badly. We were
late to balls all night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running fine in the first half. The injury is not an
excuse for letting in two goals.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution had avoided early deficits and appeared to have a
more organized defense under player-coach Walter Zenga this season.
But the team's weaknesses have become apparent in recent games.
</P>
<P>
   The first goal set the tone for the game. Diaz Arce, who scored
18 goals for the Revolution last year, outmanuevered Ted
Chronopoulos near the penalty spot as Valderrama curled a pass over
the defense in the sixth minute. Diaz Arce trapped the ball and had
time to slot the shot low to Zenga's left.
</P>
<P>
   Chronopoulos had actually played Diaz Arce offside, but teammate
Mario Gori kept him onside. Gori, though, should not be blamed,
since this was not a situation for an offside trap, especially
against a goal-poacher such as Diaz Arce.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani provided a threat almost immediately. But the
Revolution struggled to link between midfield and attack, so he was
seldom in a scoring position in the first half. His first shot, in
the second minute, was a leftfooted laser just wide from 30 yards.
Midway through the half, Graziani simply touched on a through ball
to send Jamar Beasley into the penalty area, but Beasley squandered
the chance.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution nearly tied the score when Jair sent Graziani in
alone on goalkeeper Scott Garlick, but Graziani chipped the shot
onto the top of the net in the 43d minute. Seconds later,
Valderrama sent Diaz Arce in on Zenga, and Diaz Arce found Musa
Shannon in front of an open goal for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mutiny clinched the win as Valderrama set up Steve Ralston
for a give-and-go, with Ralston converting in the 55th minute.
Substitute Carlos Parra drilled a 30-yard blast for the Revolution
in the 76th minute, and Diaz Arce scored again in the 88th minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
