<SLUG> BC-CYCLING-ARMSTRONG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG PROVING INSPIRATIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Karl Haussmann has a message for the thousands of people who
have been calling, writing, and e-mailing the Lance Armstrong
Foundation: ``Please be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Armstrong won the Tour de France last Sunday, the
foundation that he helped create in his hometown of Austin, Texas,
in December 1997 has been deluged _ not just by cycling fans
responding to his feat of becoming only the second American to win
the race, but by people awed by his comeback from life-threatening
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Haussmann, executive director of the foundation, said he first
caught wind of the magnitude of interest soon after Armstrong had
crossed the finish line in Paris. More than 500 e-mails were dashed
off even as TV viewers watched the American raise his hands in
victory on the Champs Elysees.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came in the next day, there were too many, and we had
some trouble with the system,'' he said. ``But it's a great
problem. We're loving it.''
</P>
<P>
   The correspondence ranges from congratulations for Armstrong, to
questions about how one can help his foundation, to personal
stories from others who have battled cancer and found the cyclist
an inspiration. ``Those are the most heart-wrenching,'' Haussmann
said.
</P>
<P>
   All this electronic response has convinced Haussmann that it's a
good thing the US Postal Service team didn't let Armstrong, a
computerphile, take his laptop on the road. In an interview during
the Tour, Armstrong said he was answering as many e-mails as he
could, although he answered only ones about testicular or
urological cancer, his initial diagnosis. ``I can't respond to
every one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong discovered that often it's not the patient who writes
the e-mails. ``Mostly they come from a family member or a friend,
so when I contact them, they have no idea how I got their
address,'' he said, smiling at the Secret Santa-like role he was
playing.
</P>
<P>
   Nike, which has an endorsement deal with Armstrong, donated
$25,000 to the foundation, which according to Haussmann has raised
more than $1 million for research, education, and awareness of
testicular cancer _ most from much smaller donations.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation holds a fund-raising ``Race for the Roses'' over
Memorial Day weekend, which includes a road race and criterium
(both of which Armstrong rides in) as well as a family and kids
race. Those who raise $3,000 in pledges are flown to Austin to
participate in the race and parties. Last year 150 reached that
level of pledges.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong flew to the United States last week for a whirlwind
tour of talk shows and other appearances, including a press
conference in New York at which Mayor Rudolph Giuliani proclaimed
last Thursday Lance Armstrong Day. Now Armstrong is back in Europe,
wearing the yellow jersey in criteriums in different cities, a
tradition for the Tour de France winner.
</P>
<P>
   Next week he and his wife, Kristin, will fly back to Austin,
where he'll likely be welcomed with a parade. And he'll get to see
Haussmann, who has been busy with all the correspondence pouring
into the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a nice kind of busy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lance Armstrong Foundation can be reached at www.laf.org or
800-496-4402.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
