<HEADLINE>
SANTERRE'S RIDING HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
 RACING NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Andy Santerre's long, uphill climb began in
February when he suffered multiple fractures of his right leg in a
crash at the Busch Series opener at Daytona International Speedway.
Against all odds, Santerre fought to get back on his feet and back
behind the wheel of his Busch Series car _ with some sense of
trepidation, of course _ only to face even more adversity when he
failed to qualify in his first two races back at Dover, Del., and
South Boston, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Filled with self-doubt, Santerre wondered if he was capable of
driving the No. 47 Monro/Muffler Brake Chevrolet for car owner
George deBidart. After receiving a vote of confidence in a June 13
closed-door meeting with his owner and Innovative Motorsports
teammates, Santerre emerged with a sense of restored confidence.
</P>
<P>
   It showed last month when the 30-year-old native of Cherryfield,
Maine, returned to his New England roots and won a Busch North
Series event at New Hampshire International Speedway, where he had
never won before. Last Saturday, that victory helped catapult him
to another, his first Busch Series triumph of his career at Pikes
Peak, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going up to New Hampshire and winning there was special to
me,'' said Santerre. ``I got the chance to go back home and to be
with family and friends. It gave me a big boost of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly enough, Santerre's ascent to the heights of euphoria
came in the rarefied air of Pikes Peak International Raceway, where
he started 20th, ran door-to-door with Dale Earnhardt Jr. before
taking the lead from him with 16 laps to go, and, finally, fought
off runner-up Tim Fedewa to win the NAPA AutoCare 250.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotionally, it's been a tough year for us,'' said Santerre,
who carried so many expectations into his sophomore campaign in the
Busch Series after winning Rookie of the Year honors last season.
``We had a lot of lows, with the first one being Daytona. We went
into that one with our heads high, thinking we were coming off a
pretty good freshman year. We had a lot of expectations here at
Innovative Motorsports.''
</P>
<P>
   But his crash at Daytona, which resulted in a four-month layoff,
proved the first and foremost of the obstacles Santerre faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty tough to deal with that, so we put Elliott
Sadler in our car and he had some pretty good runs, but he also had
some problems with engines and whatnot,'' Santerre said. ``It was a
tough start, but I came back and thought I was in A-1 shape and
thought I was ready to get back in, but we missed the first two
races and couldn't qualify. At that point, I was pretty down on
myself, and I'd been through a lot, and I didn't really know if I
was doing the right thing by coming back. . . . I sat down with my
team and my car owner and said, `Hey guys, you know you're better
than this, and you've run decent with Elliott, and you deserve
better. If I'm the weak link here, I'm going to do something about
it and step aside and let someone else drive the car.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But my car owner would have no part of that,'' Santerre added.
``He said, `If you want to drive, you're our guy, you're our
driver.' He said, `If there's anybody here that doesn't want to
stick behind you, they can leave now.' But the whole team said,
`No, no. We want Andy to drive.' So this first win was for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't for them, I probably wouldn't be here because I
was going to step aside and let somebody else take over. But they
wanted to stick with me and encouraged me to stay. It worked out
pretty well, and I'm glad I stayed now,'' said Santerre heading
into Saturday night's Gateway 200 at Gateway International Speedway
in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jack Birmingham, a 57-year-old businessman from Boston, threw
his hat into the ring as a NASCAR Winston Cup owner this week by
purchasing Bahari Racing from Chuck Rider. Birmingham, who has
homes in Osterville and Vero Beach, Fla., indicated that Derrike
Cope will remain as driver of the No. 30 Pontiac through the end of
the 1999 season, but he did not make any commitments to Cope or the
rest of the team beyond that. ``I've been looking to retain a
business interest in the sport for some time,'' Birmingham told the
Associated Press. ``This seemed like it would be a challenge but a
lot of fun, too.'' There will be plenty of challenges as Birmingham
assumes control of a team _ which he plans to rename Bahari-Eel
River Racing _ that has won five poles and no races in 13 seasons
on the Winston Cup circuit. ``I think purchasing Bahari Racing
gives us an opportunity to turn the fortunes of the team around and
eventually go on to be a winning Winston Cup team,'' said
Birmingham . . . After he was knocked out of third place by a Turn
3 crash in the July 11 Jiffy Lube 300 at NHIS, Bobby Labonte
rebounded last weekend by winning the Pennsylvania 500 NASCAR
Winston Cup race at Pocono, Pa., marking a clean sweep of both
events at the track. ``It wasn't a pretty picture,'' Labonte said
of his NHIS wreck, which totaled the car he had driven to victory
at Pocono in June. ``I know when I got out of the car, I was trying
to tell them what was wrong with it. I told (crew chief) Jimmy
(Makar), `You think you can get it back by Pocono?' He said, `I
don't think so.' '' Labonte's victory, his third of the season,
enabled him to climb to third in the standings with 2,731 points,
almost 300 behind leader Dale Jarrett (3,014) . . . Next stop for
the NASCAR Winston Cup Series: Indianapolis Motor Speedway. Jeff
Gordon, a homegrown Hoosier from Pittsboro, Ind., will make a
triumphant homecoming Saturday for the Brickyard 400. Gordon won
the inaugural race in 1994, a momentous victory he credited for
launching his career. ``When you grow up racing in and around
Indianapolis,'' said Gordon, who also won the 1996 Brickyard 400,
``you can't help but dream of one day racing at one of the greatest
speedways in the world. Once I decided my future was in stock car
racing, I figured I might never have the chance to race at Indy.
But when NASCAR made the announcement that the Winston Cup Series
was going to race at Indy, I couldn't believe it. To be able to go
out and win that first race was a very emotional experience.'' . .
. The Indy Racing League resumes action Sunday in the MBNA
Mid-Atlantic 200 at Dover, Del. Eddie Cheever Jr. is one driver who
hopes not to reprise his performance of a year ago when he and
former teammate Robby Unser tore up a lot of expensive equipment at
Dover's Monster Mile. ``I had just come from the big prize money
win at Indy and proceeded to leave Dover with $800,000 less on my
balance sheet,'' Cheever recalled. ``It was the fastest dissipation
of assets in my life . . . with the exception of my divorce.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 0258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
