<HEADER>
A1582 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-     08-01 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY STAYS AND LOSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Chuck Finley did not clean out his locker Saturday. He
did not say his goodbyes or make travel arrangements to Cleveland
or New York.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Finley pitched.
</P>
<P>
   The trading deadline passed at 9 p.m. Saturday and Finley was
still an Angel. In fact, Finley was the losing pitcher in the
Angels' 8-0 loss to the Minnesota Twins before 37,011 at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Finley (5-10) gave up five runs and eight hits in six-plus
innings. The Angels have now lost 14 of their past 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who said he would waive his trade veto rights if it
meant going to Cleveland or New York, never got the opportunity to
say yes or no to a trade.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Angels general manager Bill Bavasi couldn't come
to an agreement with Indians general manager John Hart. The
Yankees, Bavasi said, were never serious contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really put myself anywhere else but here,'' Finley
said. ``I'm not disappointed I'm here. . . . Any player would be
crazy not to want to be in a situation like Cleveland or New York.
But I'm deeply rooted in this team. Nobody in this clubhouse has
experienced the highs and lows except the two trainers, (vice
president) Tim Mead and Billy Bavasi. The high point came in '86
and the low point is right now. It's no fun, but I know there are
good times ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   But that won't be until next year at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi and Hart agreed that speedy Indians second baseman
Enrique Wilson would be part of a package for Finley. But that was
all they could agree on. Bavasi wanted three minor-league pitchers
included in the deal, but Hart would only give up two. The Angels
had interest in Willie Martinez, David Riske and Jared Camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a main player (Wilson) and we felt pretty good about
him,'' Bavasi said. ``We wanted to make sure there was enough
behind him to make the deal worthwhile. So probably from their
point of view we were looking for too much behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi said Hart called him at 1:15 p.m. Saturday and said he
wouldn't meet the Angels' demands. And that was that.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the morning we gave them a group of players, what it would
take, and left it there,'' Bavasi said. ``There were further
discussions throughout the day, but we didn't feel we should lower
the bar and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last season, when Bavasi felt bad about not making a deal
at the deadline, Bavasi said he felt fine about not trading Finley.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one of the very, very few times, and it'll probably
never happen again, when we were in a win-win situation,'' he said.
``We were doing this in part for us and in part for (Finley). If a
deal went though or if it didn't go through, we felt we couldn't
lose. In talking to Chuck, he felt the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   After 14 years with the Angels, Finley said he doesn't know how
he would have responded to a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to say goodbye to my teammates,'' he said. ``I
don't know what would have happened if it had gotten to that
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bavasi said he was a little surprised a deal wasn't done.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Finley) was a special commodity in the market because of his
status as a Yankee killer,'' Bavasi said. ``So I thought yeah, (the
Indians) would do this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees apparently made plenty of noise but never were
serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one serious team and the other team was a mirage,''
Bavasi said. ``The second team, it took us a day or two to flush
them out and get them to admit they were a mirage and quit calling
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi said it was a relief to have the process over,
considering it was Finley who was being discussed. After all, it
was Bavasi's father Buzzie who let Nolan Ryan get away 20 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Finley is in his 14th season with the team, the longest tenure
of any player in franchise history. (Brian Downing played 13
seasons, 1978-90). Finley holds club records in games pitched
(425), victories (158), starts (358) and innings pitched (2,590).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
