<HEADER>
A1583 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAILING-AMERICA'SCUP-     08-01 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAILING-AMERICA'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWPORT HAS CHANCE TO RENEW GLORY 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In 11 weeks the gun will sound in Auckland, New
Zealand, to begin an America's Cup competition that could return
the oldest trophy in sports to Newport, R.I., its home for 132
years.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time since 1987 that the New York Yacht Club
has had the chance to compete for the Cup. Because in the Cup's
most recent US residency it was held by another club, the San Diego
Yacht Club, the New Yorkers who had lost it in 1983 were not able
to mount a challenge to get it back.
</P>
<P>
   But since New Zealand won the Cup from San Diego in 1995, New
York now has a clear shot at reclaiming it through a series of
challenger round-robins _ the Louis Vuitton Cup _ capped in
February by a best-of-seven series between New Zealand and the
surviving challenger.
</P>
<P>
   While it is far too early to ante up the bets, the early
handicapping has Young America, John Marshall's second attempt with
the 1995 PACT syndicate, in the top three.
</P>
<P>
   The other choices to win the 31st America's Cup are the single
defender, New Zealand, and Italy's Prada syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, 12 years ago, the betting also would have gone to the
New York Yacht Club to win the Cup back in Fremantle, Australia. It
had plenty of money, a reason to be inspired, and what seemed a
strong young team with John Kolius at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   But in any sport, expert guesses are still just guesses, and the
1987 New York entry in Fremantle came apart like a blown spinnaker.
Dennis Conner (the Cup's loser three years before) went on to beat
the Aussies and take the Cup to San Diego, where it resided until
New Zealand won it eight years later.
</P>
<P>
   So take all early bets with about as much salt as they deserve
here, three months before we see anything like relative team
strength. That will be apparant only when boats sail in anger in
Auckland on Oct. 18.
</P>
<P>
   But should New York prevail in February and bring the Cup back
to Harbour Court, New York City's Newport outpost, or to its empty
pedastal in Manhattan, it will have a broad representation of
sailors and boatbuilders from New England.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Young America is based in South Portland, Maine,
home state of CEO John Marshall. The waterfront training facility
is in Quonsett, R.I., the state in which both New York racing boats
are being built, at Goetz Boat Builders in Bristol. The spars are
coming from Hall Spars in Rhode Island, and North Sails in
Connecticut is building most of the challengers' sails.
</P>
<P>
   The newest member of the Young America team is JB Braun, vice
president of Doyle Sailmakers in Marblehead, who will be manager of
the sail program for the New Yorkers. Aside from his many national
titles in a variety of boats _ Mumm 30, Melges 30, Flying Dutchman,
and 505s _ Braun's most noteworthy achievement was taking the helm
of the 80-foot Nicorette for a world record-setting Atlantic
crossing in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Young America will have two boats in New Zealand, one to be
launched in early August and the second coming in the fall.
According to Bob Campbell, vice president of operations for Young
America, the boats are similar enough so they can leapfrog in their
progress through the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making them radically different is too big a chance,'' says
Campbell, a veteran of both Bill Koch's Cup winner and the Conner
campaigns. ``There are slight variations, but we still believe that
we always have to know where we are and work to get better. When
one boat is radically different, you can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Young America will not be the first US challenger in the water
this Cup season. On May 26, Dawn Riley's America True campaign,
based in San Francisco, launched the first US boat, after Italy's
Team Prada became the first challenger in the water.
</P>
<P>
   Some other developments on the America's Cup scene:
</P>
<P>
   --Also based in San Francisco is Paul Cayard's America One
Challenge. Fresh from his Whitbread round-the-world victory last
year, Cayard will helm the new boat, launched this month.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Cayard helmed Italy's Il Moro team to a semifinal
victory in San Diego, beating the favored New Zealand team for the
honor of losing to Bill Koch's America/3 in The Match. In 1995,
Conner chose Cayard as his co-helmsman on Stars &AMP; Stripes.
</P>
<P>
   --Though Conner's winning 1987 Stars &AMP; Stripes team trained in
Hawaii, the first America's Cup Class yacht ever built in that
state, Abracadabra 2000, was launched and christened on June 12.
This Waikiki Yacht Club challenge, Aloha Racing, is skippered by
Kolius, whose Cup background stems from 1983, when he helmed
Courageous, the trial horse for Tom Blackaller and Gary Jobson's
Defender. Some believe that Kolius and the Courageous team could
have given Conner's Liberty campaign a better fight for the
defender's role in '83, the year Conner lost the Cup to the
Australians.
</P>
<P>
   --Still at it after 25 years, Conner will be the last American
to launch his boat; it will happen this week. Though based in San
Diego, Stars &AMP; Stripes 2000 built its single boat at New England
Boatworks in Portsmouth, R.I. From there it will be shipped
straight to Auckland to begin trials.
</P>
<P>
   --Don't expect to see the Fremantle Doctor _ the big onshore
wind that came up almost daily in Australia's Cup season, creating
a condition known as ``full-blown survival'' sailing. New Zealand
has a strong wind, but often it blows offshore, so the seas stay
flat. When it comes out of the Northeast, wind and sea are so heavy
that they are well out of range of IACC yachts, at least in the
trials. Sustained wind above 23 knots will allow for an abandoned
race in the trials. There have been no wind limits set yet for The
Match in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
