<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Monday, Aug. 2, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WEEKEND DUTY EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   IN ATLANTA: Fauve Yandel, 404-526-5456 (office),
</P>
<P>
   IN WASHINGTON: Elliot Jaspen, 703-551-1033; 703-725-7031 (cell
phone)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TOAD _ BASTROP, Texas _ The endangered Houston Toads' mating
chorus _ an unmistakable high-pitched trill that cuts through the
warm, humid air of late winter evenings in the Lost Pines of
Bastrop County _ has lost some of its resonance in recent years.
Biologists have taken stock of the muzzled mating calls and
concluded recently that the fragile toads are disappearing at a
dangerous rate that throws their survival in the balance. U.S. Fish
and Wildlife Service officials met in April with Bastrop County
leaders to share their findings _ that the toad, first listed as
endangered in 1970, is hurtling toward extinction due in part to
haphazard development within the loblolly pine forests the toads
call home. (Gee, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ On the morning of Jan. 28, 1986, I
was in the newsroom when a pressman brought the unbelievable: ``The
space shuttle blew up.'' For all these years the fatal plume of
that obliterated space ship has been bookmarked in our minds. Now I
have another image that won't be dislodged. Last Tuesday night,
gawking Central Texans got a most spectacular scene _ shuttle
Columbia speeding through Earth's atmosphere on its way to a Cape
Canaveral landing. (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald.) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   LEGGETT-COLUMN _ DENALI NATIONAL PARK, Alaska _ Alaska is a
state where people don't have to leave home to touch the
wilderness. It comes to you. Literally. (Leggett, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HALIBUT _ HOMER, Alaska _ Fish heads and Spider Wire _ one a
body part used for bait, the other a brand of braided line _ may be
the oddest compoments of halibut fishing, but the main attraction
is still the flatfish himself. Alaskan halibut have a little bit of
sea monster lure about them. They live in water colder than 40
degrees, at depths exceeding 400 feet, and in places where being
seasick is about as common as being at sea. (Leggett, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
