<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perez makes no apology for retaliating
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Braves catcher Eddie Perez didn't make any apologies
for starting the Friday night fight against the Phillies,
retaliating an inning after he was hit by a Paul Byrd pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if he's trying to hit me or not, I've got to do
something,'' said Perez, who was good friends with Byrd when they
were teammates for parts of the past two seasons. ``I've been
getting hit too many times. I can't take it anymore.... I did what
I'm supposed to do. That's part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Since replacing the injured Javy Lopez, Perez has taken a
beating from foul tips and now pitches. Saturday, he wore a bandage
just above his left elbow, where Byrd's pitch hit him.
</P>
<P>
   Perez said he got more frustrated as the game continued. After
getting hit by the pitch, he was called out for interference on a
baserunning play. In the top of the fourth, John Smoltz got ejected
for hitting Alex Arias with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd maintained that he didn't hit Perez on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``God blessed me with a short right arm that only throws 85
miles an hour,'' said Byrd, who leads the majors with 13 hit
batsmen. ``I have to throw inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, a devout Christian who has considered entering the
ministry after his baseball career, made it a more civilized and
surely a shorter brawl when he began praying aloud at the bottom of
the pile, which stunned Perez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just stopped doing what I was doing,'' Perez said. ``I said,
`Stay with me Byrdie.'... We used to be best buddies. I think he
knows what happened last night was part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez hasn't heard yet from the National League office about a
possible suspension, but he probably will. Manager Bobby Cox may be
suspended too because he went out on the field during the brawl
after he'd been ejected while arguing the interference call against
Perez.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just sit down here,'' Cox said. ``When your team is
out there on the field, you've got to make sure nobody gets hurt,
and that's what I did...
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unfortunate,'' Cox said of the fight. ``Eddie probably
went a little too far there. Quite honestly, I don't know if Paul
was trying to hit him or not. We're not a head-hunting team, and
neither are they.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan to be tested Monday
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan will have an MRI and a bone scan on his sore right
hand Monday. He was out of the lineup for almost a week to rest the
hand, which was hit by a Mike Thurman pitch on June 22, before
returning on Friday night. He was 3-for-5 with four RBIs Saturday
night, but wants to have his hand examined further because he's
felt no improvement despite two cortisone shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way I'll know if I'm hurting it or it's something I can
play through,'' Jordan said. ``I'm kind of nervous about it because
after a couple cortisone shots I thought the pain would lessen.
That leads me to believe something may have to be taken care of,
now or later on. Hopefully later on.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said batting was painful on Friday night, especially on a
checked swing during his third at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz update
</P>
<P>
   Overshadowed by the brawl and the loss on Friday night was the
condition of Smoltz's right elbow. Smoltz has gone almost
exclusively to throwing fastballs and change-ups with only an
occasional breaking ball.
</P>
<P>
   His slider may be his best pitch, but it's the one that causes
him the most pain. The Phillies took advantage by scoring four runs
in 3 2/3 innings, but it's how Smoltz is going to have to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say rest until the playoffs,'' he said. ``I could be
resting for a long time. It's not a given thing. The simple fact of
the matter is we have to do the little things better. I'm just
trying to contribute any way I possibly can.'' Smoltz said the next
several weeks would be critical in determining whether he can
continue pitching in his current condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't do me any good to speculate,'' Smoltz said. ``That's
not to say I can't pitch like this and be better.... Mentally I've
got to be tougher, stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading north
</P>
<P>
   Recently released reliever John Hudek was signed to a
minor-league contract by the Toronto Blue Jays on Saturday and sent
to their Class AAA team in Syracuse. The right-handed Hudek, 32,
was 0-2 with a 7.64 ERA in 17 games for the Braves and the
Cincinnati Reds.... Wednesday's Braves-Pirates game in Pittsburgh
has been changed to a 7:35 start and will be shown on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
