u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS02-COX     08-01 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Creaking Cowboys will stretch age limits
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The early exit from the NFL playoffs last
season exposed a glaring weakness in the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   They have old legs.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, which defeated the Cowboys 20-7 in a surprisingly easy
game, looked younger, quicker, sharper. Cardinals quarterback Jake
Plummer spun like a swizzle stick while dodging would-be tacklers.
Were the Cowboys really as tired as they looked that January
afternoon?
</P>
<P>
   Nate Newton, his untucked jersey covering his massive belly,
could have used a cane to walk away. Other Cowboys left Texas
Stadium with their heads down, wondering how a team with three
Super Bowl titles in the decade could lose to the Cardinals. Maybe
the team of the '90s has evolved into the team of the 30s. The
Cowboys' combined three-year record after winning Super Bowl XXX is
27-24. Most of their best players are at least 30 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Jerry Jones has heard critics contend his once-proud
team is too old to make another serious challenge for the Super
Bowl. When pressed on the subject during a recent chat, Jones
paused several seconds before responding.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have great players _ and we have a base of great
players _ it warrants erring on the side of hanging on too long as
opposed to being too quick to make a change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Which begs this question: Did the Cowboys wait too long for a
transfusion of new blood?
</P>
<P>
   Jones steadfastly believes Super Bowl contenders are built with
veteran players, no matter how many years of NFL service they have.
NFL champion Denver, for example, was the oldest team in the league
last year. Jones has invested heavily in players who were stars in
the Super Bowl years.
</P>
<P>
   As the Cowboys prepare for the 1999 season, the majority of
contributors already reached the pinnacle of their careers long
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith and Michael Irvin have each lost a step. Erik
Williams and Daryl Johnston have had career-threatening injuries.
Kevin Smith and Chad Hennings might not be starters much longer.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are training without their best defensive players,
Leon Lett and Deion Sanders. Lett is serving another drug
suspension and Sanders has nursed a bad toe for eight months.
</P>
<P>
   And these are some of the team leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an older group,'' 32-year-old quarterback Troy Aikman
said. ``There is no question about that. I still think we have some
good years left. We can still be a productive team. I think we have
a nice mix (of veterans and young players).''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but the majority of Cowboys prospects are unproven.
Defensive linemen such as Kavika Pittman (25), Greg Ellis (23),
Ebenezer Ekuban (23), Darren Benson (24) and Michael Myers (23)
have not made an impact so far. The Sporting News ranks the Cowboys
defensive line 30th in the 31-team league.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the youth movement Jones was referring to?
</P>
<P>
   There is very little youth on the offense. The only starters who
are younger than 30 are guard Everett McIver (28), wide receiver
Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail (29), tight end David LaFleur (25) and
tackle Flozell Adams (24).
</P>
<P>
   If one player symbolizes the plight of the aging offense, it's
the 33-year-old Irvin. In the last year of his contract, Irvin must
recapture the game-breaking ability he displayed in the early part
of his career.
</P>
<P>
   All of the veterans need to improve on what they did last year,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to prove that we're a better football team than we
were last year,'' Irvin said. ``More importantly, we have to show
we're a better football team than 10-6. For a lot of teams, that
would be a great accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were10-6 and swept the division. A lot of teams would sit
back and rest and say we've accomplished something. But this
football team, with the nucleus it's had for the last few years,
that's not acceptable to us. You want to come out, you want to work
hard, you want to try to accomplish more. You think you deserve
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has injected some youth into the system. Ismail and
newcomer James McKnight (27) bring speed to the passing game.
Although Aikman and Irvin have been a terrific combination on
intermediate passes, the Cowboys have not had a consistent deep
threat since former teammate Alvin Harper left the club after the
1994 season.
</P>
<P>
   Smith will continue to get the majority of carries, but the
Cowboys hope they can rest him occasionally. That was the plan last
year, too, but backup running back Chris Warren, who boasts four
1,000-yard seasons in his NFL career, was sidelined for much of
last season with a groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   Smith responded well, finishing with his eighth straight
1,000-yard season. But he rushed for 100 yards only once in the
last seven games.
</P>
<P>
   To add punch to the lineup, Smith and Warren will be in the
backfield at the same time at various stages of games. The Cowboys
hope to prolong Smith's career by taking some of the focus off him
in running situations.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, the new additions _ namely Ismail, McKnight
and center Mark Stepnoski _ will jump-start the offense. If
anything, the Cowboys should be faster than they showed in their
playoff loss to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed poses a threat to defenses,'' Irvin said. ``As long as
they know you can do it, they have to account for it. If we can get
defenses to account, maybe with the safety staying back in the
middle of the field that may give us the opportunity to get some
things open on the other side one-on-one.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Cantu writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-31-99 2129E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
