<SLUG> BC-HALIBUT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Going deep for halibut
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOMER, Alaska _ Fish heads and Spider Wire _ one a body part
used for bait, the other a brand of braided line _ may be the
oddest compoments of halibut fishing, but the main attraction is
still the flatfish himself.
</P>
<P>
   With weights exceeding 300 pounds, two eyes on the same side of
their head and a huge, toothy mouth only a mother could love,
Alaskan halibut have a little bit of sea monster lure about them.
They live in water colder than 40 degrees, at depths exceeding 400
feet, and in places where being seasick is about as common as being
at sea.
</P>
<P>
   When halibut surface on the end of a heavy rod, it's with an
aura of the unknown ocean depths. Smart captains dispatch them with
a .410 round before brining them on board, lest the thrashing
behemoth play havoc with rods, cameras and other equipment.
</P>
<P>
   But, let's face it, halibut are really not much more than
flounder on steroids with an affinity for one of nature's least
hospitable, yet most scenic and alluring pieces of oceanfront
property.
</P>
<P>
   Who could resist? Certainly not my wife and I when our friends
Jan and Jerry Wilt, of Anchorage, invited us to join them on the
charter boat they own with businessman Mike Alred. The prospect of
big fish, flaky, white fillets and the wilds of Alaska's Barren
Islands was too much to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   Thus we found ourselves banging around the Hit-A-Homer two hours
out of Homer, listening to other captains talk about calm seas and
fishing any place they wanted. Though we were dry and warm inside
the sturdy steel boat's cabin, things didn't look all that calm
from where we sat.
</P>
<P>
   Just as we cleared Port Graham, though, where a left turn would
have taken us toward Prince William Sound and the famous ''inside
passage'' route to British Columbia, the seas flattened out and the
sun broke through. It was a great day to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   Whales (humpbacks, minkes and orcas) spouted in the distance.
Loons and puffins and marbled murrelets bobbed on the water near
the boat. Alred and Wilt rigged rods with hooks and weights, then
tipped them with salmon heads. ''Reds,'' Wilt said. ''Halibut love
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Alred explained the long ride and our current location, half a
mile from one of the uninhabited islands that make up the small
group, about 40 miles south-southwest from Homer. ''That's Kodiak
Island there in the distance,'' he said. ''There's a shelf here
where the water is only about 120 feet deep and the halibut really
like it. We usually can't come this far because the water is too
rough.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with a 3-pound weight as a sinker, bait takes a little time
to reach bottom in 120 feet of water. ''Some of the boats are
fishing in 400 to 500 feet,'' Alred said, ''but there's nothing fun
about reeling a big halibut up from that far down.''
</P>
<P>
   Once on the bottom, with four or five baits out for maximum
coverage, we waited for the beginning of the tidal movement. When
the water moves, salmon and other fish move with it. Halibut line
up along the bottom to vacuum up whatever swims by. If it fits in
that mouth, they'll eat it.
</P>
<P>
   Alred scored first, using a big white jig bounced wildly off the
bottom. He boated a large ling cod, a prehistoric looking, very
aggressive and highly prized food fish. Two more lings followed,
one of them a 49-inch monster that Jan Wilt caught.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the ling frenzy, lines suddenly moved toward the
back of the anchored boat. The tide had begun to move and all the
halibut veterans on the boat got ready for action.
</P>
<P>
   My wife Rana got the first halibut bite, a 40-pound class fish
that bit a salmon carcass and stripped line quickly before she got
him stopped. Jan Wilt caught one, Jerry caught a pair and I caught
another. Three of the fish were in excess of 50 pounds. Then we
quit. The limit is two fish per person per day, but there was no
need to kill any other fish.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's just about as big as you want to keep to eat,'' Wilt
had explained earlier. ''Much bigger than that, they get mushy and
they just aren't that good.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There are some really big halibut in this area,'' Wilt said.
''In the past, we didn't have to come this far, but there's more
competition and pressure on them than ever before. We don't like to
see people keep the giants, 150 and 200 pounds, or the small ones.
We call those chickens.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There are still lots of halibut in Alaska, but there are more
people than ever fishing for them,'' Wilt said. ''We have to take
care of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Leggett writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
