<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGGETT-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Making a grizzly discovery
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENALI NATIONAL PARK, Alaska _ Alaska is a state where people
don't have to leave home to touch the wilderness. It comes to you.
Literally.
</P>
<P>
   Snow-covered mountains loom above every town on the map. Black
bears chase little kids in their yards. Salmon, pursued by beluga
whales from Cook Inlet, swim upstream through downtown Anchorage,
the state's largest city.
</P>
<P>
   Whales may circle your fishing boat today and seals might steal
your salmon. Bald and golden eagles perch along the highway, and
moose fight off the summer heat by soaking in kiddie wading pools.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the 240-mile drive up Alaska Highway 1, from Anchorage
to Denali National Park, is one long, stomach-churning adventure in
search of the signature Alaskan wildlife: the grizzly bear.
</P>
<P>
   The grizzlies of Denali are not the monstrous brown bears of
coastal Alaska or the1,000-pound heart-stoppers of Kodiak Island,
though they are plenty big.
</P>
<P>
   Denali bears _ the main reason we made the long drive and got up
at four in the morning to claim our seat on the bus _ are of the
famed blond variety, the Toklat grizzly of early Alaskan history
fame, that live and thrive in this virtually untouched wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment our driver and guide, Frank, pulled away from
the visitors center, to the time two hours into the trip that we
saw our first grizzly, 50 sets of eyes were glued to the slopes and
canyons of the park's back country.
</P>
<P>
   Park administrators do a remarkable job of handling the massive
numbers of international tourists who travel to Alaska and then to
the park. Personal vehicle traffic is limited, but buses run often
enough and far enough to allow everyone a chance to see a part of
America that can't be found anyplace else.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere past the Savage River parking area, past the lone
Arctic wolf, a couple of golden eagles and a few caribou, a large,
extremely blond young male was spotted feeding on berries and sedge
near the bottom of a small hill.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, who said he'd been driving the route for five years, had
given us the requisite warning about talking too loud and treating
the animals as if they were living in a zoo. That didn't stop the
''oohs and aahs'' or the comparisons with people or even the
occasional ignorant outburst about how clumsy he looked.
</P>
<P>
   I could have pointed out that the bear, if he wished, could have
covered the 100 yards from his feeding spot to the bus, UPHILL, in
three or four seconds. When he got there, he could have opened up
the vehicle like a sardine tin and fished out a tourist or two for
brunch. All without breaking a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   But it was enough to know we'd seen the first grizzly of our
trip, the first that my wife had ever seen. The next would be even
more memorable, a sow and cub on a feeding jaunt that brought them
to within 25 yards of the astounded crew on the shuttle bus.
</P>
<P>
   I've been close to bears on rivers as they fished for salmon and
inland as they laid claim to a moose I'd just killed. But this big
female and her youngster were special. The bond that keeps a young
grizzly alive his first few years was apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Baby bears face lots of obstacles to adulthood, the most
dangerous one being other bears. At the very top of the food chain,
bears fear little else in the wild. Males often kill young bears
and even other adults. While we were in Alaska, one male known as
BB killed a bear cub in full view of the stunned human visitors to
salmon fishing grounds on the Brooks River.
</P>
<P>
   But this female kept a close watch on her young one, even while
allowing him to roam and play while she dug for ground squirrels
next to the road. The smaller bear eventually lay down and went to
sleep while she dug.
</P>
<P>
   After his mother gave up and began to wander off, the cub
climbed over into the 3-foot deep hole for a quick lesson in
digging before loping off to join her.
</P>
<P>
   Those sightings alone would have been enough to make our trip to
Denali, but we saw another eight or nine bears on the way in and
out to Eielson Visitor Center, 67 miles into the sprawling park. It
was a splendid trip, rivaled by no other in the country for
wildnerness or wildness.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Leggett writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
