u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOAD02-COX     08-01 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOAD02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toad specie disappearing at alarming rate from Texas home
 &HT;    By Robert W. Gee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BASTROP, Texas _ The endangered Houston Toads' mating chorus _
an unmistakable high-pitched trill that cuts through the warm,
humid air of late winter evenings in the Lost Pines of Bastrop
County _ has lost some of its resonance in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists have taken stock of the muzzled mating calls and
concluded recently that the fragile toads are disappearing at a
dangerous rate that throws their survival in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service officials met in April with
Bastrop County leaders to share their findings _ that the toad,
first listed as endangered in 1970, is hurtling toward extinction
due in part to haphazard development within the loblolly pine
forests the toads call home.
</P>
<P>
   That set the stage for a struggle that is only beginning for the
cash-poor Bastrop County government, which finds itself caught
between the federal endangered species act and a seemingly
contradictory new state law that does not allow counties to
``discriminate'' against home builders for land that lies within
the habitat of an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone of us wants to save the pine trees,'' says Bastrop
County Judge Ronnie McDonald. ``We need authority. Right now, we
can't dictate whether a person can cut down a pine tree or not.''
</P>
<P>
   And property owners, developers and real estate agents worry
about the future of several thousand acres of county-approved but
undeveloped subdivisions within the Lost Pines, the habitat of a
toad that few residents have ever seen but also prime land for
development in the fast-growing county. About one-third of all new
homes in Bastrop County are built north of the Colorado River, many
within the toads' domain, according to the county's health and
sanitation department, which issues permits for new homes.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists say that if nothing is done to protect the toads'
habitat, it may soon be too late to save them. Officials estimate
their numbers in Bastrop County to be about 5,000. In a
representative sample within Bastrop State Park studied by the
Texas Parks and Wildlife Department over the past 10 years, the
toad's numbers have dwindled by half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reaching a crisis point with this species,'' said Lisa
O'Donnell, biologist with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, the
agency charged with enforcing the endangered species act. ``My
concern is if development continues at this rate _ random, all over
the place _ you're going to preclude your options forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Toad does exist in smaller numbers in eight other
Texas counties _ and no where else in the world _ according to a
1990 survey, but the largest and historically most robust
population is in Bastrop County.
</P>
<P>
   In the April meeting, O'Donnell suggested that the county start
work on a habitat conservation plan that would include 15,000 acres
of undeveloped prime habitat for the small, secretive toads, who
spend much of the year burrowed under the soft, sandy soil. County
officials say they don't know the first thing about establishing a
habitat conservation plan and, furthermore, couldn't possibly
afford the estimated $20 million cost of the land needed for a
permanent toad habitat. The county's annual budget is $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   In late June, Fish and Wildlife officials, concerned about the
county's inaction, ordered their legal staff to determine whether
or not the county could be found culpable in facilitating the
destruction of endangered species by continuing to issue sanitation
and development permits within the roughly 50,000-acre toad habitat
area of Bastrop County. Federal wildlife officials met with county
leaders again on July 9 to inform them that they may be breaking
the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some verbal (legal) opinions that there is some
liability involved in issuing a permit that would allow the 'take'
of an endangered species,'' said Bill Seawell, assistant field
supervisor of the Austin office of the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service.
</P>
<P>
   The county immediately stopped issuing sanitation and
development permits _ the necessary steps to start building a home
_ for lots within the loosely defined toad habitat area, a broad
swath running east and north of Bastrop to the Lee County line. But
county officials worried that that move could run counter to the
Texas Legislature's Senate Bill 1272, signed into law in June and
effective in September, which does not allow a county to deny
building permits solely because the platted land falls within the
habitat of an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, on July 19, the county decided to resume issuing
permits, but included a disclaimer that informed property owners
that they may also need to apply for an additional permit with the
U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   The new state law ``kind of makes (county officials) choose as
to which law they wish to obey,'' Seawell said. ``And I think
they've taken the middle road.''
</P>
<P>
   But the state law, which was designed to ensure private
landowners aren't coerced into contributing land to a regional
habitat conservation plan, doesn't preclude a county from
establishing a conservation plan, which is a solution touted for
Bastrop County since April by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a voluntary effort to pull something together on a
regional basis,'' O'Donnell said. ``The flip side of that is to
make every single person in the area get in line and wait for a
permit.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a regional habitat conservation plan, the county would
apply for an umbrella permit for ``incidental taking'' of the
endangered species, which would allow new development to harm or
kill the toads as long as it doesn't put the species' survival in
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   The linchpin to such a plan would be the preservation of a
minimum of 15,000 acres of contiguous property to ensure the toad's
survival. The 3,700-acre Bastrop State Park would probably be a
part of that. One thousand acres will come from the Texas Parks and
Wildlife Department. The remaining 10,000 or so acres would be
private land that the county, or someone, would have to preserve
from development.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service will provide a consultant to
help the county find funding, which could include matching grants
from foundations or corporations or a bond issue from taxpayers.
Then the county would need to determine how to preserve the land,
either through the outright purchase of land, or through the
purchase of the development rights through conservation easements,
which would keep the land in property owners' hands and on the tax
rolls.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald, the county judge, appealed for help in paying for the
land. ``It would be a tremendous strain for the people of Bastrop
County to fund a project of this magnitude without the help of
outside sources,'' he said. ``If we're going to be the torch-bearer
for the Houston Toad . . . this is something that goes beyond
Bastrop County, beyond Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   One source of funding for the conservation area will likely be a
mitigation fee charged to new home builders in the toads' habitat
area. That fee would be similar to the $1,500 charged to most new
home builders within the habitat area of the endangered golden
cheek warbler in western Travis County, under the Balcones
Canyonlands Preserve plan.
</P>
<P>
   In several interviews last week, some real estate agents,
subdivision managers and property owners in Bastrop County said
they think a mitigation fee and a three- or four-month wait time
for the permit would hurt new home builders, and that the fee could
steer development away from the Lost Pines region.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service officials said their Austin
office was receiving about 20 calls a day last week from concerned
property owners in Bastrop County.
</P>
<P>
   Paying to protect the toad first became an issue in 1990, when
the Texas Department of Transportation touted a $628,000 project
that would build toad crossings underneath a portion of Texas 21
northeast of Bastrop. The agency ended up spending only $100,000 to
build special fences to herd the toads into existing culverts.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Trull, 58, who lives in a rental home with his wife and
children in Cedar Creek, hopes to break ground soon on a
1,850-square-foot home in a subdivision located within the toad's
habitat. He said a $1,500 mitigation fee wouldn't deter his plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty good chunk for us,'' Trull said. ``(But) I
definitely don't want to upset any ecological balance. I'd be very
concerned if in the long run we helped to hurt the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Trull, like many property owners, said he wasn't sure how
to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, (the situation) is leaving the citizens
panic-stricken in some cases,'' said David Coombs, director of the
county's health and sanitation department. ``They don't know what's
expected of them and we don't sometimes have the answers to give
them.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Fish and Wildlife officials hope to provide those answers
at a public hearing Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Gee writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
