   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, August
2:
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE (Moving in ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK-SEXISM (Undated) _ Woodstock '99 underlined the return
of an ugly brand of sexism in pop music. By Ann Powers.
</P>
<P>
   PEW-CULTURE-POLICY (Undated) _ The Pew Charitable Trusts, the
$4.7-billion foundation that put its weight behind causes like
global warming, civic journalism and campaign finance reform when
they were first emerging, has a new crusade: shaping a national
cultural policy. Over the next five years, the Pew plans to devote
about 40 percent of its culture budget, some $50 million, to an
attempt to get policymakers to focus on issues like arts financing,
intellectual property rights, zoning in historic areas and an arts
curriculum for public schools. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY-NOTEBOOK (Undated) _ A Critic's Notebook on the joys and
confusions of reading three mysteries at one time while sick in bed
and on medication. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   MOSTLY-MOZART-REVIEW (New York) _ Anthony Tommasini reviews the
Mostly Mozart Festival Orchestra, with Pinchas Zukerman conducting,
at Avery Fisher Hall.
</P>
<P>
   CITY-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt reviews
``City of Light,'' by Lauren Belfer. (A `time-and-place' novel with
turn-of-the-century Buffalo, N.Y., as background.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-THANKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Anita Gates reviews ``Thanks''. A
limited run sitcom about the Pilgrims, it is making its premiere on
CBS stations on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL (Moving in ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-IMAGE (Undated) _ The public's impression of Microsoft
is less favorable than it was just a few years ago, according to a
New York Times-CBS New poll. We analyze that finding, as well as
research by a Harvard marketing professor which indicates that
people tend to see Microsoft in terms of a master-slave
relationship (compared with Apple Computer as a workmate, say, or
Harley Davidson as a buddy). By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   HEWLETTPACKARD-SOFTWARE (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ Rajiv Gupta, who
was chief architect of Hewlett-Packard's IA64 project with
Microsoft, is an inveterate hardware designer. Now, though, he has
a big software task: leading Hewlett's effort to steal mind share
and market share from Sun Microsystems in the Internet software
business services arena. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-ACCESS-ASSESS (Undated) _ News Analysis: analysing the
apparent contradictions in America Online's insistence that it
receive open access to cable television systems at the same time it
resists efforts by Microsoft and Yahoo to link their
instant-messaging systems to AOL's. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   NOSMOKING-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Tobacco ads have long been a
mainstay of the tobacco industry. But lately, stop-smoking ads are
becoming a dominant force _ whether as pro bono or nonprofit work,
or as ads paid for by companies pitching stop-smoking products. By
Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Digital Commerce column; details
TK. By Denise Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   DANKA-TURNAROUND (Undated) _ Danka Business Systems plans to
report financial results this week for the first quarter of its new
fiscal year, and revenue will probably be way down, debt high and
profit minimal, at best. But for several weeks now, Danka's top
brass have beamed as they anticipated showing those numbers to the
world. Who can blame them? Scarcely six months ago, no one was
certain that Danka, which is incorporated in Britain but run out of
St. Petersburg, Fla., would survive at all. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Brief news items about computer
technology.
</P>
<P>
   SUN-MICROCHIP (San Franciso) _ Sun Microsystems plans to
announce a new chip on Monday. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-BUYING-DECLINE (Undated) _ The percentage of people
with Internet access who are making purchases from Web sites
declined slightly last quarter after four sequential quarters of
spectacular growth, according to Greenfield Online Inc., the
Internet marketing research firm based in Westport, Conn. By Leslie
Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-NEWSCLIPPERS (Undated) _ A look at the
do-it-yourselfers who assemble news-clipping services like
MediaGossip.com and other Internet outlets that act as filters for
online news and commentary _ whether through collections of links
that are posted on a Web site or distributed by e-mail to a list of
subscribers. By Andy Wang.
</P>
