<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, Aug. 2:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SUSPECT-TALKS (Washington) _ Wen Ho Lee, the man suspected
of helping the Chinese gain access to U.S. nuclear weapons secrets,
is speaking on 60 Minutes. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VIOLENCE (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ More violence and
tensions in Kosovo. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-POLITICS (Berlin) _ A look at conflicts within the
governing Social Democratic Party in Germany. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Beijing) _ Chinese authorities seized a Taiwanese
freighter over the weekend near a front-line Taiwanese military
post on Matsu, a heavily-fortified island under Taiwanese control.
By Seth Faison. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-POLITICAL-SATIRE (Caracas, Venezuela) _ To open a
newspaper or turn on a newscast here these days is to be subjected
to an avalanche of insults and aspersions. When President Hugo
Chavez is not branding his opponents a corrupt ``nest of vipers,''
they are proclaiming him ``a demagogue endowed with an ability to
arouse hatred and violence.'' Fortunately, however, Venezuelans
have found a place they can go to defuse the political tensions _ a
satirical political revue. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   The following five foreign stories are tentative and may be
held:
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ZEDILLO (Mexico City) _ Mexico's President Ernesto
Zedillo promised not to meddle in the first primary the ruling
party has ever run to choose his successor. Problem is, the man he
does not favor is the party favorite. Will Zedillo intervene? By
Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-AIDS-CONFLICT (Washington) _ Developing nations and AIDS
activists say the Clinton administration is putting the interests
of American pharmaceutical companies ahead of concern over the
worldwide AIDS epidemic by demanding tight patent enforcement
overseas for AIDS drugs. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-SHORTAGES (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ A look at life and
people in Belgrade: enjoying the summer as if normal, but nervous
about a winter of no electricity and little joy. By Steven
Erlanger. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   PEACEKEEPER-TRAINING (Fort Bragg, N.C.) _ A look at how the U.S.
army trains peacekeepers. Since the Balkan wars, other militaries
are enrolling in these courses that are the direct descendant of
the institution that taught U.S. soldiers how to occupy Germany
after WWII. The biggest issue isn't how to transform lethal
fighters into flower-power peacemakers but into practical
small-town mayors. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-U.N.-RELATIONS (United Nations) _ Relations between the
United States and the United Nations are at an all-time low. U.N.
officials blame not only Congress, but also the Clinton
administration. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-COALITION _ The Christian Coalition, which for 10
years has led the charge of the religious right in national and
local politics, is now weathering serious financial and leadership
turmoil that could affect its ability to exert widespread influence
in the 2000 election, current and former staff members say. By
Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   ARK-STARR-RELIEF (Little Rock, Ark.) _ For many in this state,
the mood these days is like the familiar exhale of relief that
follows the destructive storms of summer. Kenneth Starr, the
Whitewater independent prosecutor, has said the Arkansas phase of
his investigation is over. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CHESAPEAKE-BAY (Portsmouth, Va.) _ A new report by Chesapeake
Bay scientists, after years of life-support experimentation on the
oyster, recommends an all-out commitment to three-dimensional reef
construction _ not mere flat-bottom beds _ as the key to restoring
the oyster to its central place in the life of the bay. (With
photo, map.)
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY _ The new leaders of the Reform Party began
retooling the organization last week in an effort to recruit a
presidential candidate who would appeal to a broader spectrum of
voters than the base of support established by Ross Perot. By Mike
Allen.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIVER-SURGERY _ An experimental surgery that requires
tremendous self-sacrifice as well as surgical virtuosity is gaining
currency: the partial liver transplant for adults. By Denise Grady.
(With photo, graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   COBURN-PROFILE _ Rep. (and Dr.) Tom Coburn, a leader in the
fight over HMOs in Congress. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   AMTRAK-FAST-TRAIN (Pueblo, Colo.) _ Amtrak is testing a new
high-speed train, due to enter service in the eastern corridor
soon. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BEHAVIOR (Washington) _ Hillary Rodham Clinton talks
about her husband's efforts to overcome his womanizing. By
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ Details to come. By Bob Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: William Safire is on vacation.
</P>
