<HEADER>
A1756 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOSMOKING-AD-COLUMN-A     08-01 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOSMOKING-AD-COLUMN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNSELLING THE CIGARETTE: REVERSING THE OLD MESSAGE, AD SELLERS
SWITCH SIDES
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Fla., Ariz., Calif., Mass., Wash., Minn., N.J., Va., Hawaii,
Texas)  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, Madison Avenue was as hooked on cigarettes as any
two-pack-a-day smoker. Agencies vied for the big accounts of the
big tobacco companies as avidly as they did for the accounts of
automakers, brewers, soft-drink bottlers and other free-spending
marketers of mass consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   The pages of trade publications like Advertising Age were once
filled with the comings and goings of cigarette brand assignments.
Which agency was going to get the Camel account? Was Lucky Strike
on the loose? Would Winston advertise good like a cigarette should?
</P>
<P>
   But now, to paraphrase the old slogan of another smoke,
Tareyton, many shops have determined they would rather switch than
fight for cigarette accounts. While tobacco marketing is still a
huge source of revenue for agencies, a significant countertrend is
building as increasing sums of money are devoted to what could be
called the unselling of smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertising has really been the No. 1 accomplice in selling
smoking,'' said Alex Bogusky, partner and creative director at
Crispin Porter &AMP; Bogusky in Coral Gables, Fla. ``The reason for
cigarettes being among the most powerful brands in America is us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a shameful role in this for a long time,'' he
added, ``so I'm excited about us as an industry trying to fix what
we did wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The unselling efforts are being fueled by a turnabout in
societal attitudes about smoking, coupled with the intensification
of so-called social marketing campaigns, aimed at changing
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, people accepted smoking,'' said Stephen Badenhop,
president at Jordan McGrath Case &AMP; Partners/Euro RSCG in New York,
part of the Euro RSCG Worldwide unit of Havas Advertising, whose
agency produces campaigns for anti-smoking drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the last five to 10 years, it has become acceptable for
people not to smoke,'' he added, ``and agencies like to get
involved with trends that are topical and important to vast numbers
of consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The stepped-up efforts to fight smoking include spending by
states like Arizona, California, Florida and Massachusetts on
campaigns intended to dissuade youngsters from taking up the habit;
a coming national anti-smoking initiative, also aimed primarily at
young people, to be funded by the recent $206 billion settlement
between 46 state attorneys general and the tobacco industry; ads
for a panoply of prescription and over-the-counter drugs like
Nicorette and Nicotrol meant to help smokers stop, and even a
handful of anti-smoking campaigns aimed at young people by tobacco
marketers like the Philip Morris Cos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's suddenly changing dramatically,'' said William D.
Novelli, president of the National Center for Tobacco-Free Kids, an
advocacy organization in Washington. ``It's a totally new day, and
I'm very thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, the money is there for some major
countermarketing against tobacco,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   By one rough estimate, the amount of money spent in 1998 to
unsell tobacco totaled $200 million. That compares with the $575.7
million spent to advertise tobacco products in print, through
outdoor advertising and over the Internet in 1997, the most recent
year for which figures were available. (The total tobacco marketing
budget that year was $5.66 billion, which includes promotional
spending like display allowances for retailers and signs in
stores.)
</P>
<P>
   The sums on the unselling side of the equation will increase
substantially with the planned national anti-smoking campaign, to
be overseen by an organization known as the American Legacy
Foundation, based in Washington. Its initial annual budget for
advertising, marketing and public relations will be $150 million to
$225 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The classic reaction is to go where the money is,'' Novelli
said. And indeed, some of the best-known, most creative agencies in
advertising, joined by several leading public relations shops, are
vying for the foundation's account.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome the sea change'' in Madison Avenue's attitudes about
smoking, said Chuck Wolfe, the foundation's executive vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some amount of, shall we say, realization among
agencies that maybe they've been part of the problem,'' said Wolfe,
who earlier directed a pioneering anti-smoking advertising effort
sponsored by Florida. ``They see the handwriting on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``And some are more calculating,'' he added, ``interested
because there's money on the street: `If we can't get tobacco
business, maybe we should get the anti-tobacco business.'''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the motivations, the agencies that have been in the
hunt for the foundation's account work on familiar, blue-chip
brands like Foot Locker, Intel, Kellogg, MCI Worldcom, Mitsubishi,
1-800-FLOWERS, Snapple, Southwest Airlines, Target, Volkswagen,
Volvo and Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many opportunities are there to do the right thing?''
asked Lisa Unsworth, executive vice president and group director at
Arnold Communications in Boston, the unit of Snyder Communications
that is among the agencies competing to create the foundation's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``A campaign like this should redefine the way society as a
whole thinks about tobacco,'' said Ms. Unsworth, who oversee
Arnold's work on anti-smoking ads for the Massachusetts Department
of Public Health, ``whether smokers, kids or advertising
agencies.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Late last week, the foundation narrowed the competition for its
account to four groups from nine. The finalists are: Arnold, teamed
up with Crispin Porter, the agency for the Florida anti-tobacco
campaign, and the Porter Novelli unit of Omnicom Group; Kirshenbaum
Bond &AMP; Partners in New York, teamed up with Asher &AMP; Partners in Los
Angeles and Rogers &AMP; Associates in Los Angeles; Messner Vetere
Berger McNamee Schmetterer/Euro RSCG in New York, also part of the
Euro RSCG Worldwide unit of Havas, teamed up with Dan Klores
Associates in New York; and Richards Group in Dallas, teamed up
with the Golin/Harris International unit of the Interpublic Group
of Companies. A decision is expected in September.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be everywhere the tobacco industry is and put up
roadblocks,'' said Bruce Dundore, a partner and the creative
director at Asher, which is the agency for the anti-tobacco
campaign sponsored by the California Department of Health Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never completely stop the tobacco charge,'' he added,
``but we can consistently thwart them.
</P>
<P>
   ``An educated public, a more knowledgeable public, tends to
change its behavior,'' Dundore said. ``And we'll keep educating
people until they feel that putting a cigarette in your mouth is
the same as putting a lit torch in your mouth _ and few people do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Many smokers have started to use gums, inhalers or patches to
help them stop smoking. Spending on ads for anti-smoking products
totaled $121.5 million in 1997 and $106.2 million in 1998,
according to Competitive Media Reporting, a unit of VNU N.V. that
tracks ad spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 40 million or more smokers out there,'' said
Badenhop at Jordan McGrath, whose agency creates ads for the
Nicoderm and Nicorette anti-smoking brands sold by SmithKline
Beecham. ``And smokers all know they shouldn't be smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   The money spent to unsell smoking ``is nowhere near what the
tobacco companies spend in a couple months,'' he added, ``but it's
a good, competitive amount of money.''
</P>
<P>
   And that amount will grow further because of the foundation's
national anti-smoking campaign, scheduled to begin before the new
year, as well as additional states joining the anti-smoking
crusade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have six states now with meaningful campaigns,'' said
Novelli of the National Center for Tobacco-Free Kids, ``and about
10 new ones coming on board, including Washington, Hawaii, New
Jersey, Minnesota and even Virginia, believe it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   When the prototypical tobacco-growing state begins to spend
money on ads against smoking, Madison Avenue takes notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got into the business, one of the keystone accounts you
needed as an agency was a cigarette,'' said Jonathan Bond,
co-chairman at Kirshenbaum Bond. ``They were the most visible
products with the most money behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, not smoking is the better image,'' he added. ``I wish
every category had an `anti'; the whole ad business would double.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
