<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1763 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-IMAGE-ART-2     08-01 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-IMAGE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEWER COMPUTER USERS GIVE MICROSOFT A POSITIVE RATING
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Calif., Wash.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The company is thriving, the shareholders are rich and its name
is synonymous with high technology and success. But is the
Microsoft Corp.'s sterling image losing some of its luster?
</P>
<P>
   That is the question posed, at least, by the latest New York
Times/CBS News poll.
</P>
<P>
   In a nationwide telephone survey two weeks ago, 60 percent of
the people who use a computer at work or at home said that they had
a favorable opinion of Microsoft. Most companies would envy such an
approval rating. But Microsoft is no ordinary company.
</P>
<P>
   Just a year ago, 67 percent of computer users had a favorable
opinion of the company in a Times/CBS poll. And when the same
question, word for word, was asked in a Gallup poll in October
1997, 73 percent of computer users held a favorable view of
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend is troubling, even though Microsoft's
favorable-rating level remains very high,'' said Nicholas
Donatiello, president of Odyssey, a market research firm in San
Francisco that studies consumers' views on technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says that its own market research _ using a somewhat
different methodology than the Times/CBS and Gallup polls _ finds
no erosion in its public image. The big software maker says its
favorable ratings have long held steady at 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Times/CBS poll did find some good news for Microsoft on
other fronts. People, according to the survey, are less convinced
than a year ago that the government is doing the right thing with
its major antitrust suit against the company. And the Times/CBS
survey found that people, especially computer users, are far more
likely to agree with Microsoft that its practices are good for
consumers instead of harmful to them, as the government contends.
</P>
<P>
   Yet marketing experts say Microsoft should be watchful for any
hint of declining support for the company in general, as suggested
by the recent Times/CBS poll. Susan Fournier, an associate
professor at the Harvard Business School, says Microsoft could be
particularly vulnerable because of the relationship that consumers
tend to have with the software maker.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fournier applies ``relationship theory'' to consumer-brand
research. Based on surveys of adults, she has characterized the
primary relationship consumers have with products they are familiar
with. For example, Harley-Davidson, the motorcycle brand with a
fanatic following, is ``best friend.'' The ``mother-child''
relationship tends to be how consumers regard Johnson &AMP; Johnson and
AT&AMP;T, while McDonald's and Kraft Foods' Jello dessert brand fall
into the category of ``childhood buddy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft relationship, according to Ms. Fournier, is
``master-slave.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other kinds of brands, she says, fit into the master-slave
grouping: monopolies like the local cable television supplier or
the local telephone company, and products that are addictive like
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, Ms. Fournier points out, have double-edged feelings
about technology in general _ that it both frees and enslaves,
saves time and consumes time, assimilates and isolates. Still, she
notes that some Microsoft rivals like Apple Computer Inc. evoke
more ``positive socio-emotional responses'' from consumers. Apple,
her research suggests, is seen as a ``close friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fournier warns that if genuine alternatives to Microsoft
products develop _ say, the Linux operating system for Internet
server computers or a newly resurgent Apple in the consumer market
_ the slaves may quickly side with the competition. ``Microsoft
should see this as a huge red flag,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft should be particularly concerned about its image among
information technology professionals, according to Techtel Inc. The
market research firm, based in Emeryville, Calif., conducts
quarterly opinion surveys of about 900 information technology
professionals, who work with and buy business computer products.
</P>
<P>
   Techtel found that Microsoft's ``net positive rating'' _ the
percentage of those with a positive opinion of the company minus
the percentage with a negative opinion of it _ peaked in the second
quarter of 1997 at 60 percent and has since declined to 44 percent
in the second quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's net positive rating within the nontechnical business
community and among households _ two other groups that Techtel
surveys quarterly _ has also declined, but not as much as among
information technology experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are the most forgiving, but the most knowledgeable
people have come down the most in their opinion of Microsoft,''
said Michael F. Kelly, president of Techtel. ``This is a building
and significant problem for Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Times/CBS poll shows that opinions about Microsoft _
as a corporate symbol of wealth and technology _ can be complex and
ambivalent, and still generally positive. The Times/CBS poll,
conducted July 17-19, surveyed 1,178 adults. Seventy-three percent
of them said they used a computer at home or at work.
</P>
<P>
   One finding that intrigues polling experts is that while
Microsoft's favorable ratings fell, so did the percentage of people
who have an unfavorable opinion of the company _ to 11 percent
among computer users last month, down from 17 percent in the fall
of 1997. With both the favorable and unfavorable percentages
dropping over time, the various categories of uncertainty _
including ``neutral/neither,'' ``mixed'' and ``don't know'' _ have
increased.
</P>
<P>
   To Frank Newport, editor in chief of the Gallup poll, the
growing pool of undecided respondents suggests an increasing public
ambivalence about Microsoft. He compares it to the phenomenon that
in political polling is termed ``hiding out,'' as people become
less enamored with an incumbent or front-runner but have not yet
decided to side with anyone else.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The Times/CBS poll also has comforting news for Microsoft about
public opinion concerning its long-running antitrust battle with
the Justice Department and 19 states. The government's suit and its
courtroom attacks on Microsoft may have tarnished the company's
reputation. Still, there is less support for the government's
position than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   People in the Times/CBS poll were less likely than a year ago to
agree that the government did the right thing by suing Microsoft.
And people were more inclined than a year ago to agree with
Microsoft that its practices are good for consumers _ 52 percent of
computer users agreed with Microsoft versus the 25 percent who
agreed with the Justice Department that the company's practices
harm consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Herbold, the chief operating officer at Microsoft,
said two weeks ago that the company's own polls found that most
people viewed the antitrust case as consumers. ``The American
public looks at this from the standpoint of what's in it relative
to the capabilities of the personal consumer and what they can do
for us, and are we being harmed,'' Herbold told a gathering of
securities analysts in Seattle. ``The general answer, as you can
see, obviously is no.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as obviously, though, the outcome of the Microsoft
antitrust case will be determined in the federal courts _ not in
the court of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, when the polling data and market research on Microsoft
are combined, people still have an overwhelmingly favorable opinion
of the company, even if they describe their relationship with
Windows or Microsoft Office as master-slave. What does that make
Microsoft? A benevolent dictator, perhaps?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 1650EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
