<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Aug. 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Cooler, drier Canadian air will filter to the south across much
of the Northeast and the Middle Atlantic states Monday as a
refreshing area of high pressure moves into the region. The cool
front that is the leading edge of this air will move into the
Southeast, sparking showers and thunderstorms over the Carolinas.
Behind the front, several locations in the Northeast will have
below normal temperatures for the first time in over a week.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms are also likely across the central
Plains as a weak area of low pressure becomes nearly stationary
over the region. Winds blowing up the gently sloping terrain
towards the Rockies on the north side of this low will lead to
showers, along with a nearly solid deck of low stratus clouds. To
the southwest, the monsoon will remain active in New Mexico with
showers and thunderstorms likely.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Great Lakes will remain dry as high pressure slides
to the south. A jet stream disturbance at 18,000 feet will clip the
northern Lakes, however, bringing cloudy skies and some isolated
showers to the region. Meanwhile, farther south, there will likely
be a few showers along the coast of Florida and along the Gulf
Coast as sea breezes undercut and lift very warm and humid air.
</P>
<P>
   The interior West will be sunny and turning hotter under
abundant amounts of sunshine. Along the coast in Washington and
Oregon, low clouds and fog are likely as ocean air gets pushed
inland. A weak disturbance aloft will promote isolated showers in
interior portions of Washington and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: TWO-FACED RALEIGH
</P>
<P>
   Raleigh, North Carolina sweltered under 104 degree heat on
Saturday, its second highest reading on record. This also marked
the seventh time in July and eighth time this season that the
mercury eclipsed 100 degrees, a feat that has never been matched
before in the capital. However, Raleigh residents need only recall
the second week of July when on four consecutive days the afternoon
high temperatures were the lowest on record. During the midsummer
cool spell, clouds, showers and a brisk wind from the ocean brought
the respite from the hot weather. This week should be cooler.
</P>
</TEXT>
