<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1776 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGICOM-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-01 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGICOM-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL COMMERCE: INSTANT MESSAGING AND OTHER `STICKY' ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DENISE CARUSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The keening outrage in the national news media last week over
America Online's proprietary behavior toward its Instant Messaging
customers strikes many veterans of the computer industry as just
plain goofy.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate question is whether America Online has the right
to enforce _ and by what means _ the network barriers that separate
its 80 million Instant Messaging customers from (a) the clutches of
its grasping competitors and (b) the rest of the instant-messaging
world.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, this is just business as usual. Examine the
practices of any market leader and its products in the last 20 or
30 years _ IBM, Digital Equipment, Lotus Development, Microsoft _
and it is clear that America Online is simply acting out one of the
most enduring concepts in the technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   Today's buzzword for the concept is ``stickiness,'' a rather
glib term for how a company gets and keeps customers in the
notoriously slippery world of the Internet, where a Web site can be
come-and-gone at the click of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sticky'' has also long been the goal of vendors and service
providers. Many have built their biggest successes upon enticing
customers with sweet-smelling technical solutions that, once
installed, make it extremely painful to switch to a competitor's
product.
</P>
<P>
   This has been the dominant, albeit unheralded, business model of
the computer and software industry since its inception.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the days of ``big iron'' mainframe computers and
workstations, companies like IBM Corp. and Digital Equipment Corp.
were the biggest flypaper vendors in town, selling the computers,
the operating systems and often the software, too.
</P>
<P>
   Their hegemony was broken by the personal computer _ and then
stickiness between Windows and its applications catapulted
Microsoft to its monopoly in the PC industry.
</P>
<P>
   That's because once buyers commit their customer databases,
corporate documents and financial data to an operating system and
brand of application software, they are basically stuck. Anyone who
has tried even to switch from one company's word processor to
another's can imagine the exponential agony of trying to move an
entire corporation from, say, Unix to Windows.
</P>
<P>
   But that is a classic sticky application, one that effectively
``persuades'' customers to stick around. First they are enticed by
how convenient it is to use the product. Then they stay because it
becomes so terribly inconvenient to leave.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, stickiness has more to do with collecting
valuable personal information about consumers and holding their
attention than with storing their data bits. Finding a way to
create consumer stickiness is a high priority most particularly for
portal sites _ Yahoo, At Home's Excite, Lycos, America Online,
Microsoft's MSN _ and retailers like Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, it seems, these vendors hang a few more strips of
flypaper: free e-mail, custom news services, address books and
directories, calendars and event planners, gift services, personal
Web sites. Customers sign up and stick around, plugging in more and
more personal and family and financial information as they return
again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like America Online and Microsoft are planning
``digital wallet'' services that will enable users to consolidate
all their sign-in names and passwords. The sales pitch is
convenience _ ostensibly consumers would not need to keep
re-entering the same personal information over and over as they
travel and shop the Web.
</P>
<P>
   But obviously such wallets are also powerful flypaper
applications that, if successful, will tie up consumers' data with
a single vendor who will process all their Internet purchases and
activities.
</P>
<P>
   This type of ``service'' raises the collective eyebrow of those
who remember the enormous power shift in the technology industry
when the Internet's open protocols and the Web's freely available
programming language, HTML, first loosened the hold that the
flypaper vendors had on their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the goal of the free market economy is to whup all
your competitors and become the de facto flypaper standard.
</P>
<P>
   And that is fine as far as it goes.
</P>
<P>
   But as the technology food chain has lengthened to include
hundreds of millions of consumers, the concept of ``sticky'' versus
``stuck'' has taken on new cultural and economic portent.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, America Online's competitors _ particularly
Microsoft _ are acting purely in their own commercial interests.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, the great imposer of unilateral standards, provided
the industry with a Fellini-esque moment last week when an
executive was quoted as saying, ``We should all just speak the same
language,'' adding, ``It shouldn't matter what software or phone
you are using.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaining access to America Online's Instant Message system, thus
its customer database, puts a crimp in the online giant's growing
domination of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   But you can bet that if America Online's competitors succeed,
they will scramble for a way to alter any new standard to their own
ends, just as Microsoft unilaterally rewrote two key open Internet
languages, Sun Microsystems' Java and Netscape's Javascript.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, an open standard for instant-message
applications has the potential to unstick consumers and reconnect
them to the rest of the Internet. Which is why today, battles for
dominance of the Internet are of great public interest. Everyone is
watching, and millions more people have a stake in the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   As one entrepreneur said last week, ``It's the users who are
going to decide if they prefer to stay in a segregated community or
talk to other communities.'' And that is the kind of sticky
situation the industry may not have a strategy for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
