<DOCNO> NYT19990801.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1777 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-DANKA-TURNAROUND-AR     08-01 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-DANKA-TURNAROUND-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANKA, COPIER-WAR CASUALTY, IS BACK ON ITS FEET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add graphics note)  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Danka Business Systems plans to report financial results this
week for the first quarter of its new fiscal year, and revenue will
probably be way down, debt high and profit minimal, at best.
</P>
<P>
   But for several weeks now, Danka's top brass have beamed as they
anticipated showing those numbers to the world. Who can blame them?
Scarcely six months ago, no one was certain that Danka, which is
incorporated in Britain but run out of St. Petersburg, Fla., would
survive at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not declaring premature victory,'' said Larry Switzer,
Danka's chief executive. ``But we got our hands around the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Any immersion in black ink is a triumph for Danka, the
second-largest distributor of copiers, which posted sales of $3.35
billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since last fall, when Danka's board changed the company's
management, plucking Switzer from Fruit of the Loom and selecting
Brian Merriman, from Toshiba, as president, the two men have been
cutting, chopping, negotiating and otherwise wrenching Danka back
from the brink of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   They talked the company's banks, which were poised to call in
loans, into extending more credit. They persuaded Eastman Kodak Co.
to let them wriggle out of a contract that forced Danka to buy
copiers it could not sell. They got Xerox Corp. to buy back a
lackluster business for servicing older, scattered Xerox machines.
</P>
<P>
   And they squeezed $108 million out of yearly costs. Danka used
to have 48 warehouses; it now has three. It had 45 billing centers;
five now suffice. The new team sharply cut prices to move older
inventory. It eliminated 1,400 jobs, reducing the work force to
17,000, and integrated data systems. It sold Danka's facsimile
business, closed its wholesale business and cut out ``a ton of
superfluous marketing programs,'' Merriman said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they are phasing out products from all but three vendors:
Canon, Toshiba and Heidelberger Druckmaschinen AG. The German
company bought Kodak's copier business in March, giving it
ownership of the Digisource 9110, the only copier fast enough to
rival Xerox's Docutech line.
</P>
<P>
   Danka's operating expenses are still high, as are the
double-digit interest rates it is paying on its $1.1 billion debt.
A deal to sell its international operations to Schroder Ventures, a
British holding company, fell through in June, depriving Danka of
cash it needs to service debt. Its sales remain sluggish. And
competition keeps getting fiercer as more companies introduce
digital copiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may see more pricing pressures on everyone in the next 12
to 18 months,'' warned Jack Kelly, an analyst with Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Danka no longer seems headed for extinction. ``We've seen
the last really horrendous quarter,'' said B. Alexander Henderson,
an analyst with Prudential Securities Research.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are coming around. Danka's stock closed Friday at
$11.21875, nowhere near the $51 it traded at two years ago, but
well above the $1.75 it had sunk to in October. ``I bought this
stock at $4, and I expect to make a lot of money on it,'' said
Frank Cannata, who edits a copier-industry newsletter and who said
he expects Danka share price to top $15 in a year. ``They've made
progress in every critical area.''
</P>
<P>
   To fully understand the magnitude of Danka's turnaround, one has
to first understand the depths to which the company had sunk.
</P>
<P>
   Danka, which was formed in 1977, immediately began gobbling up
other dealers. It, in turn, was purchased by a British holding
company in 1986, and Danka's shares began trading in London that
year. Its American depository receipts began trading on Nasdaq in
1992. By last year Danka was an international giant, handling more
than 40 copiers from six manufacturers, each with hefty costs for
training and spare-parts inventories.
</P>
<P>
   But few Danka dealers carried the entire product line. If a
large customer wanted to install one type of equipment in all its
branches, Danka could not guarantee service at every location. That
problem became critical as more companies moved to digital copiers
that could link throughout their networks.
</P>
<P>
   Woes intensified in 1996, when Danka bought Kodak's copier sales
operation for $558 million. Danka never consolidated facilities or
data systems and was left with huge overhead costs and slow data
flows. Culture clashes caused many of the best sales
representatives to jump ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danka's sales force was a street-fighting machine, while
Kodak's people were genteel, slow-moving, paternal,'' said
Henderson of Prudential. ``Frustrations were surfacing even as
Xerox was introducing its first digital products in 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   Merriman ruefully agreed. ``The difference in sense of urgency
was night and day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, sales plummeted. That was no problem for Kodak,
since Danka had agreed to buy products whether they sold or not.
But the growing gap between what it bought and what it sold pushed
Danka to the point of insolvency.
</P>
<P>
   In desperation, Switzer and Merriman reported to the Securities
and Exchange Commission that Danka might file for bankruptcy. ``We
had to shock Kodak and the banks into realizing how serious our
situation was,'' Switzer said. The move worked: In December, Kodak
let Danka out of its contract.
</P>
<P>
   Danka has since been helped by fortuitous timing. Both Canon and
Toshiba came out with full lines of digital copiers, helping Danka
flesh out its scrawny digital product line.
</P>
<P>
   And Danka negotiated a deal with Heidelberger for distributing
the Digisource that does not involve high fixed prices or promises
to take Heidelberger's entire output. While the distribution
contract is not exclusive, Danka's participation in Digisource's
development _ and its relationships with Kodak's customers _ gives
it a head start in selling and servicing the machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've even had other potential distributors of the device ask
us if we would service the machines for their accounts,'' Merriman
said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Still, Danka's path to growth remains obstacle-strewn. Since it
has stopped servicing Xerox's older machines, it has lost an
invaluable foot in the door to some clients of Xerox, which uses
neither Danka nor the country's largest distributor, Ikon Office
Solutions. Meanwhile, IBM has announced its own high-speed copier.
And many of the Kodak salespeople who left Danka have customer
relationships they can build on for rival distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Merriman has been reorganizing Danka's sales force, putting
former Kodak people in charge of many major accounts and leaving
most of the aggressive selling to the Danka sales force. Still,
several analysts say that sales is Danka's weak link.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that Danka has the experienced personnel to sell
high-speed digital devices,'' said Edward Lee, a senior analyst at
Lyra Research.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Danka's revival has not prompted its competitors or
suppliers to shift strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're targeting more than 200 resellers for our products, and
no change in Danka's prospects will have an impact on our marketing
plans,'' said a spokesman for Hewlett-Packard Co., which is pushing
a line of hybrid printer-copiers called mopiers, that it had once
planned to distribute through Danka.
</P>
<P>
   And Canon is trying to bring its direct sales up to 45 percent
of total revenue from 35 percent now. The company also stopped
granting any independent distributors exclusive territories. That
can help Danka sell equipment and service packages to large
customers _ but, it can help Ikon do so as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danka has a lot of potential to grow with us, but Ikon is
still a bigger channel for us,'' said Tod Pike, senior vice
president for Canon USA's imaging systems group.
</P>
<P>
   Ikon also spent much of this year paring vendors and shoring up
a sagging bottom line, and it has said that it will concentrate on
pumping up sales of a few big vendors _ including Canon _ when its
2000 fiscal year starts in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Narrowing down vendors is a smart move for anyone,'' said
Dennis Le Strange, senior vice president for Ikon North America,
``but we remain focused on our own plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of Danka's competitors hope the company makes it.
They see a revived Danka as an ally in the battle to prevent Xerox,
which declined to comment for this article, from getting the same
hammerlock on the digital copier market that it has enjoyed in
analog copiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll root for any company that can persuade customers to buy
from someone other than the big X,'' said Jim Ivy, chief executive
of Savin Corp., a copier manufacturer owned by Ricoh. ``If Danka
grows, it'll be more effective in competing with Xerox, and anyone
who hurts Xerox is good in my books.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
