<SLUG> BC-MYSTERY-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: ILLNESS AND 3 RENDELL MYSTERIES, ALL AT ONCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   By a happy conjunction, or so it seemed at the time, just as I
was felled by a bout of illness, three new paperback reprints from
the extensive works of Ruth Rendell arrived to keep me company.
Between spurts of pain and the cushion of painkillers, I was in no
shape for heavy reading and mysteries seemed just undemanding
enough yet sufficiently diverting to occupy my weakened
constitution.
</P>
<P>
   I was not unaware of Ms. Rendell's lustrous reputation as a
practitioner of what are known as classic British mysteries. She
has earned three Edgars, four Gold Daggers and something called the
Grand Master award, although some of these may rightly belong to
Barbara Vine, her occasional pseudonym. But I had never read one of
her books. So here was my chance, and I went at it with gratitude
and anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   The well-designed reprints, from Vintage Crime/Black Lizard,
made a tidy package, and it felt disrespectful to separate them. I
kept the neat pile at bedside, where I found myself switching, as
is my custom with weightier books, from one volume to another.
Impatient with the mystery apparatus, my technique was to pick up
whichever volume lay close at hand and test myself on fragments of
plot to see whether I could keep track from one work to another. I
had read enough of other mysteries to recognize the formulas on
which many are constructed, and I felt up to the challenge between
author and reader.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rendell's language did not prove much of a guide. It turns
out that she has a literary bent (``So shalt thou feed on death
that feeds on men, and death, once dead, no more dying then.''),
and I found myself confronted by chapter headings from Sir Thomas
More's ``Utopia'' along with such unhelpful sound-alike titles as
``Murder Once Being Done'' and ``Some Lie and Some Die'' as well as
``No More Dying Then.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, all the books feature Inspector Wexford, a country
chief inspector of shrewd insights, high standards and testy
disposition who has served the author at least 17 times. So overlap
was invited. As the denouements approached, specifics of the
particular felony to which the inspector was applying himself
tended to merge in my misty pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Was that gent who liked children a threat or was he a figure of
sympathy or was he just there to start a scene or two? Was the
unlikable character who allowed a child to drown on his watch just
forgetful or was it something more menacing? What was I to make of
that curious figure who is so fond of fur coats? What about those
mothers who seem to be a trifle careless with their children, and
how is one supposed to distinguish between adopted babies and
others and what difference does it make many years later?
</P>
<P>
   Such perplexities were of my own doing, of course. I was asking
for them. Yet trying to handle three books at once did illuminate
the elements that have served Ms. Rendell so well. She is attentive
not only to the character of Wexford but also to his subordinates,
like Detective Inspector Michael Burden, who have their own
troubles. The family lives of detectives, which can be slightly
dreary and keep getting in the way of their professional endeavors,
is a specialty.
</P>
<P>
   As for Wexford, that good man can be pretty pretentious in his
reach for high values, deep reflections and a touch of the poet.
Here, for example, are his reflections on the nature of criminal
responsibility: ``Who kills, Tate, the one who holds the knife, the
one who says `Stab!' or the one who sends the victim to the
appointed place? Which of the three Fates is responsible for our
destinies, she who spins the thread, she who cuts it or she who
merely holds the scissors?'' It can be a relief when he forgets
domestic arts and gets back to manly police work.
</P>
<P>
   The Rendell plots are filled with vanishing children and
psychologically disadvantaged adults. The conscientious reader may
resort to devising charts of significant relationships across the
years to abet memory. I wouldn't be surprised if Ms. Rendell made
use of such schematics in her plotting.
</P>
<P>
   There are intimations of violence, usually off the page, but
nothing gross. Ms. Rendell keeps her distance from the bloody
encounters with which much of the crime genre is obsessed. The play
between detective and perpetrator is mostly psychological. Her
subject, as reviewers have noted appreciatively down the decades,
is the human mind or heart, not the vulgar organs.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some of her colleagues who have illusions of being
humorists, she shuns jokiness. She is earnest about her work and
concerned for those dedicated and fallible creations, her sleuths.
And she gives good value, with plenty of plot tangles, even if you
read her books one at a time. With three at once, the herrings of
diverse shades kept straining my weakened comprehension.
</P>
<P>
   In the crowd of suspects and the required complexities, I often
lost track of things. Was I following Ms. Rendell's plot or my own
dreamy variations? On one medicine-influenced afternoon I found
myself reaching the climax of a mystery, as Inspector Wexford
carefully wrapped matters up, only to realize that I couldn't
remember where I had been introduced to the murderer, if indeed I
had met him at all.
</P>
<P>
   I was hurting, and kept hurting for a week. My resort to ever
more powerful sedatives added a new, ferocious figure to Ms.
Rendell's already large cast. Drifting between fiction and reality
I found my prime suspect in my doctor, who was causing me such
misery.
</P>
<P>
   So there in my shadowy discernment and residual ache was that
good old mystery mastermind, the evil doctor. A culprit worthy of a
nightmare. Arrest her, Inspector Wexford! Get her off the streets
before she does even more damage!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
