<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSTLY-MOZART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSTLY MOZART FESTIVAL: A SMALL AND EMINENT PACKAGE OF MOZARTEAN
EXPERTISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alicia de Larrocha has long been called the ``first
lady of the Mostly Mozart Festival.'' Of course it is mostly the
public relations branch of the festival that keeps attaching this
title to the renowned Spanish pianist, and what was once, arguably,
an affectionate promotional gesture has become patronizing.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Ms. de Larrocha remains deeply popular with Mostly
Mozart audiences. Her appearance on Saturday night in Mozart's
Concerto No. 19 in F Major, with Pinchas Zukerman conducting, was
joyously received. She is a pianist of unquestionable integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Her fingerwork was limpid and supple, though an occasional
awkward passage indicated that at 76 she may be losing technical
resiliency. Her trademark pearly bright and singing tone was as
always a pleasure. And this diminutive woman (standing up she was
barely taller than the seated first violinist) offers a lesson in
how to produce full-bodied tone without force. Her playing was
consistently lyrical and tasteful.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all its fine qualities, Ms. de Larrocha's Mozart has
never been everyone's ideal. I prefer Mozart pianists who surprise
me more.
</P>
<P>
   This concerto is filled with impish humor, unexpected turns of
phrase and rhythmic gymnastics that other pianists capture more
vividly. The marchlike first movement was here taken at a rather
leisurely tempo. Perhaps Ms. de Larrocha was trying to uncover
deeper eloquence in the music. But it lacked buoyancy. The final
Rondo was quite satisfying, played with fleetness and greater
fancy. Zukerman and his players provided sympathetic and informed
support.
</P>
<P>
   In Mozart's Sinfonia Concertante for Violin and Viola, a de
facto double concerto, Zukerman, playing viola and also conducting,
was joined by Viviane Hagner, a 22-year-old German violinist making
her New York debut. In January the Munich-born artist performed
Prokofiev's Concerto No. 1 with the Berlin Philharmonic under
Claudio Abbado, a performance reportedly so successful that the
conductor invited her to repeat it at the prestigious Easter
Festival in Salzburg.
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of this first hearing Ms. Hagner seems an
accomplished and already mature musician. She has a resourceful
technique, and her tone is special: vibrant but slightly dark in
color, almost plaintive. The color of her sound lends a poignancy
to her playing, even in passages where the music is cheerful. And
in the work's lamenting slow movement the effect was deeply
affecting.
</P>
<P>
   Zukerman's dramatic, burly musical temperament is quite
different. He seemed to be admirably trying to match Ms. Hagner's
approach, especially in the slow movement, where he played with
beautifully subdued lyricism. Here and there in the work, however,
he could not control his penchant for layering lines with schmoozy
vibrato and dispatching passagework with bursts of
attention-grabbing energy.
</P>
<P>
   The personnel of the Mostly Mozart Festival Orchestra is
contracted each year; this summer's ensemble is strong. The program
began with Schubert's Third Symphony and at first the performance
was off-putting: Zukerman's conducting of the slow introduction to
the first movement was terribly ponderous. But in the allegro
section, and for the rest of the work, the performance had
confidence and brio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
