<HEADER>
A1786 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-01 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CITY OF LIGHT': ILLUMINATING DARK SECRETS IN VICTORIAN BUFFALO 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(js) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one of its dimensions, Lauren Belfer's impressive debut,
``City of Light,'' is a stereopticon of a novel, sepia-tinged at
the edges yet bursting with color at its center. Its title refers
to Buffalo at the turn of the 20th century, when that city by Lake
Erie and Niagara Falls was a leading commercial center, a vital
maritime and railway hub, the most important inland port in
America, a gateway between East and West and, in the words of
Louisa Barrett, the novel's narrator, ``flush in an era of
extraordinary economic prosperity and civic optimism.''
</P>
<P>
   The city was proud to have sent two presidents to the White
House, Millard Fillmore and Grover Cleveland, and of being chosen
as the site of a world's fair to be called the Pan-American
Exposition, which, as Louisa relates, ``would celebrate the
commercial links between North and South America as well as
America's technological breakthroughs, particularly in the area of
electricity, which was being developed at nearby Niagara Falls.''
</P>
<P>
   About the promise of that electricity, Louisa's friend, Thomas
Sinclair, the director of the power station at Niagara, tells her:
``I have found light. Literally. It's become a kind of religion to
me, as sacrilegious as that may sound: creating electricity from
water, using alternating current to send the electricity wherever
it's needed.'' Tom concludes: ``Electrification is a fundamental
change in the nature of life itself. I know that sounds ridiculous,
but it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course there are also those who are less optimistic about the
city's prospects. The workers who must inhabit industrial
shantytowns, the women whose roles are constricted by Buffalo
society, the black people who feel misrepresented by the
Pan-American Exposition, the so-called Preservationists, who worry
that the production of electricity may divert all the water from
glorious Niagara Falls: these people see Buffalo as a city of
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   In the crosscurrents of these powerful forces, Louisa shares the
intimacies of her life with us. To all appearances a spinster and
bluestocking whose position as headmistress of the elite Macaulay
School has earned her the confidence of the city's leaders, Louisa
harbors a secret concerning Tom's young daughter, Grace. As Louisa
explains, 10 years earlier her best friend, Margaret Sinclair,
after years of childless marriage to Tom, ``had feigned pregnancy
when she learned that a child from a good family might be available
for adoption.''
</P>
<P>
   Louisa had been the intermediary in that arrangement, under
circumstances threatening to respectability, of whose details she
believes she alone is aware. In gratitude the Sinclairs had made
her Grace's godmother. In the meantime Margaret had finally become
pregnant but had died in childbirth, and Louisa has grown ever
closer to Grace and Tom. Now, at the novel's opening, the murder of
one of the power plant's engineers not only serves to concentrate
the city's contending social forces, it also threatens Louisa's
relationship with her beloved goddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   This somewhat fustily Victorian plot is not the novel's
strength. The evidence of who committed the murder points so
strongly to Tom that the reader knows he cannot possibly have been
responsible. And for anyone even dimly aware of American history,
the knowledge that eventually President McKinley will show up at
the Pan-American Exposition and be assassinated hangs somewhat
heavily over the story's development.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the plot, which is serviceable enough, is not really what
counts in ``City of Light.'' What matters more is the vivid sense
of the time and place that Ms. Belfer has created: the heaviness of
the architecture with its classical pillars and coffered ceilings
and mahogany wainscoting; the layout of the city with its system of
parks designed by Frederick Law Olmsted, and the weight of a social
order in which commerce alone conferred power.
</P>
<P>
   Louisa glimpses the light, both literally and figuratively. Here
she is, entering Tom's newly electrified house. ``I stopped,
leaning against the banister to look. To gawk. I had never been in
a house lit by electricity. The change was _ miraculous. I'd heard
that in cities like New York and Chicago, the rich had been showing
off their wealth by installing steam generators and electrifying
their homes for the sake of novelty. But here in Buffalo, the old
families had no need for novelty, and the nouveaux riches emulated
the old. Compared to this, the other homes I visited were shadowy
and claustrophobic. Here the air itself seemed clear, vibrant and
somehow invigorating. All at once I knew why: Gaslight consumed the
oxygen in a room; electricity did not.''
</P>
<P>
   But the hypocrisy of a society where wealth matters more than
justice threatens to darken Louisa's life. Symbolic is the conduct
of Grover Cleveland, who, when he was a rising politician in the
city, Louisa reminds us, carried on an affair with a widowed shop
girl, Maria Halpin. As Louisa relates it, Cleveland acknowledged
the resulting illegitimate son, but ``refused to consider marriage
to Mrs. Halpin, who was known to have bestowed her favors on other
well-to-do men of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Louisa continues: ``To console herself, she'd begun drinking,
and Cleveland arranged to have his son taken from her by force and
adopted by an established local family. When Mrs. Halpin refused to
accept this separation, Cleveland had her committed to an insane
asylum, where she remained until she saw `reason.' '' The story
caused a ``national trauma'' when it came out during Cleveland's
1884 presidential campaign, Louisa concludes. But Cleveland was
elected for two terms nonetheless, and Buffalo society eventually
forgave him and welcomed his return.
</P>
<P>
   Whether we've progressed from those times remains highly
debatable. But in her powerfully atmospheric book Ms. Belfer makes
them seem real and very far away, and at the same time eerily
familiar and relevant to the present.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `CITY OF LIGHT'
</P>
<P>
   By Lauren Belfer
</P>
<P>
   518 pages. The Dial Press. $24.95.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
