<HEADLINE>
HISTORICAL CAROUSEL; O'NEILL PLAYS; NEW AT LONDON'S GLOBE; FREE
PERFORMANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the turn of the 20th century, some of its
historical figures _ from Albert Einstein and Neil Armstrong to
Lucille Ball and Mohandas K. Gandhi _ will be taking a spin through
Grand Central Terminal beginning on Friday aboard a grand carousel
created by the School of Visual Arts. Redesigning and restoring a
neglected 1909 Victorian-style carousel, 36 feet in height and 42
feet in diameter, students and faculty replaced the horses with 29
moving three-dimensional images and objects like a Swanson's TV
dinner and an Andy Warhol Campbell's soup can. Accompanied by music
and cinematic time lines furnishing background on people and
events, ``The Turn of a Century: A Carousel Celebrating 100 Years
of Ups and Downs'' will revolve most of each day for about 5
minutes at 20-minute intervals until Sept. 9 in the terminal's
Vanderbilt Hall. Information: (212) 592-2010.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing Anchor
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the opening Tuesday of a program of three short
plays, including ``Bound East for Cardiff,'' ``Abortion'' and ``The
Movie Man,'' the Playwrights Theater of New York starts the second
year of its Festival of Eugene O'Neill at the Provincetown
Playhouse in Greenwich Village where, in 1916, ``Cardiff'' became
the first O'Neill play to be produced. Traversing chronologically
the 8th through the 13th of O'Neill's 49 plays, this year's
segment, ``Birth of an Artist,'' offers three more productions
after the short plays close on Sunday. ``Servitude'' is to be
staged for the first time beginning on Aug. 10, ``Sniper'' will
open on Aug. 24, and the first staging of ``The Personal Equation''
starts on Aug. 28. Information: (212) 998-5801.
</P>
<P>
   Saint and Sinners
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time the works of an up-and-coming playwright named
William Shakespeare were presented at the Globe Theater in London.
Little wonder, then, that its reincarnation there, Shakespeare's
Globe, is home not only to Shakespeare's works but to new dramas as
well. Beginning on Friday, Shakespeare's Globe will present its
first commission, ``Augustine's Oak.'' Written in verse by Peter
Oswald and based on Bede's ``Ecclesiastical History of the English
Nation,'' it tells of a mission to the pagan English by St.
Augustine in the year 597 A.D. ``Augustine's Oak'' is to run in
repertory through Sept. 24. Information: 011-44-171-902-1406.
</P>
<P>
   Plaza Sweets
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dave Brubeck and Randy Weston offering classic jazz
in the Damrosch Park Band Shell. The Ballets Trockadero de Monte
Carlo dancing the New York premiere of Merce Cunningham's ``Cross
Currents.'' A weekendlong Carnival of the Americas, with music of
Haiti, Cuba, Tobago, among other places. All these attractions are
elements of ``Carnival of the Century,'' the 29th season of free
music, dance, special events and family entertainment that is
Lincoln Center Out of Doors. The 116 performances on the plazas of
Lincoln Center begin on Friday and end on Aug. 29. Information:
(212) 875-5108.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
