<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BEHAVIOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON SAYS ABUSE LED TO PRESIDENT'S INFIDELITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hillary Rodham Clinton says in a new magazine
interview that she thought her husband had overcome his womanizing
10 years ago, but that deep scars from an abused childhood had led
to his infidelity and that he had not sufficiently examined those
problems to conquer them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was resolved 10 years ago,'' Mrs. Clinton is
quoted as saying in an article titled ``The Intimate Hillary,'' to
be published this week in the premiere issue of Talk magazine. ``I
thought he had conquered it; I thought he understood it, but he
didn't go deep enough or work hard enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said that President Clinton ``has been working on
himself very hard in the last year,'' adding, ``He has become more
aware of his past and what was causing this behavior.'' She
attributed his infidelity to ``abuse'' caused by conflict between
his mother and grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said she had to remain ``vigilant'' about her
husband's behavior but that his infidelity did not negate the rest
of his life and she would not abandon him. Asked what would happen
to their marriage when she is off campaigning for the Senate in New
York, Mrs. Clinton said, ``He's responsible for his own behavior
whether I'm there or 100 miles away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
