<SLUG> BC-HEWLETTPACKARD-AGILENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HP'S EQUIPMENT SPINOFF RESTARTING LIFE AS AGILENT
</HEADLINE>
  (With HEWLETTPACKARD-SOFTWARE) 
(nk) 
 By LAURIE J. FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Edward W. Barnholt, Nov. 1 will be a day of reckoning. That
is when the test and measurement equipment business of
Hewlett-Packard is to begin operating as Agilent Technologies Inc.
with Barnholt at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett announced in March that it would spin off the
test-equipment business to shore up the company's core computer and
printer business. Since then, Barnholt, a former engineer with more
than three decades of experience at Hewlett, has had the delicate
task of carving a new company out of one that is nearly 60 years
old and is among Silicon Valley's most revered institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Hewlett announced the name and specific plans for
Agilent, which will have annual sales of about $8 billion and plans
a public stock offering next year. Agilent will also take 43,000
employees, many of whom, like Barnholt, have been been with Hewlett
for most of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Barnholt, 56, who is known as Ned, said last week he felt sad
leaving Hewlett-Packard. ``There was a sense of loss, of sadness to
no longer be with the company where I'd spent 32 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever initial disappointment they may have felt,
employees seem to be getting on with the business of making the new
arrangement work, and the company has not seen any rise in
departures.
</P>
<P>
   Agilent plans to make its headquarters on the same Palo Alto,
Calif., site where the original Hewlett-Packard building stood in
the 1940s. It builds test equipment for the electronics industry,
including the testing of semiconductors and wireless networks.
Agilent's other products include medical diagnostic devices like
ultrasound machines. There is also a semiconductor products group
that supplies chip sets for hand-held devices and communications
systems, as well as a chemical analysis group that builds systems
for analyzing biological substances.
</P>
<P>
   The spinoff will be made easier by the fact that the computer
company and the Agilent businesses have long behaved as two
distinct operations, said Tim Bajarin, an analyst with Creative
Strategies International, a Santa Clara, Calif., market research
company.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett executives decided to leave the Hewlett-Packard name
with the computer and printer operation because that business sells
to both corporate and consumer customers. The test and measurement
operation, on the other hand, sells strictly to a business and
professional clientele, through a direct sales force. ``Our
customers know us well,'' Barnholt said of the test and measurement
group. ``So we made a business decision, not a sentimental one.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnholt, who has managed the test and measurement operations
since 1990 and will be its chief executive, said the advantages of
the spinoff were already readily apparent. Within Hewlett, the test
and measurement group accounted for only 16 percent of overall
revenues of $47.1 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what we did, we hardly made the needle wiggle,''
Barnholt said. As an independent company, he said, ``we're coming
out from the shadows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
