<SLUG> BC-COBURN-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COBURN IS A PHYSICIAN WHO CAN FIND REMEDIES IN CONGRESS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ About once a week, Dr. Tom Coburn, a family
practitioner in Muskogee, Okla., gets into a fight with an
insurance company over some service he wants to provide to a
patient. Nothing unusual there; a study released last week showed
the vast majority of doctors struggling with managed-care companies
over what they would cover and what they would deny.
</P>
<P>
   But Coburn gets to engage in what may be every doctor's fantasy.
``When they deny me, I call 'em up and say, `Do you know who you
just denied? We're going to fix this for this patient. And you're
exactly the reason you're going to get a law.''' Very quickly, he
said, the hapless bureaucrat realizes that Dr. Tom Coburn is also
Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., a leader in the fight for new patient
protection in the era of managed care.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn, who still practices medicine on weekends, is one of a
handful of Republican doctors in the House who are bucking their
leadership and much of their party to pursue a broader, tougher
patients' rights bill than the one recently passed by the Senate.
It is a stand that has rattled their leaders, but one very much in
keeping with Coburn's political career path of scorched-earth
independence.
</P>
<P>
   This is, after all, a man who cheerfully describes himself as
``a pain in the butt'' in this year's appropriations process, who
proudly declares that he is ``a purist to a fault,'' who readily
admits he has become so annoying to some colleagues that his
amendments are sometimes doomed from the start. He could be exhibit
A on the liberating effect of term limits; he does not have to
worry about the long-term effects of breaking ranks and irritating
committee chairmen because he will not be here over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   A staunch conservative and an emblematic member of the
Republican class of 1994, he vowed to serve no more than six years
and will retire next year, a citizen legislator to the end. ``I'm
one of those who really believe in term limits,'' he said late last
week, happily energized by all his fights. ``I don't know that six
years is the right number; I don't know the exact number. I just
know that there comes a time when Washington influence displaces
home influence up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Coburn has, indeed, kept Washington at arm's length. He said he
has spent only two weekends here in the last five years, both of
them because votes were scheduled. Carolyn Coburn, his wife of 31
years, ``brings me back to earth every Friday night when I get
home,'' he said, ``makes me realize `you're a husband and a father
and a grandfather first, and you're a congressman three days a week
when you're not here.''' He also stays grounded in medicine,
delivering 97 babies last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it makes me a much better congressman,'' he said,
scoffing at legislators with little experience outside politics. In
fact, he said, he has advised some young Republicans thinking about
running for Congress: ``You need to get more life.''
</P>
<P>
   Coburn's life was pretty full by the time he decided to run for
Congress in July 1994, at 46, because he was ``disgusted with
Congress.'' He became a doctor at 35, after working in his family's
large optical business, and winning a serious bout with cancer in
his 20s. He has three grown daughters and two grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   With an array of anecdotes at his command, Coburn makes the case
for a variety of procedural safeguards in managed care, like an
external appeal process ``with some teeth in it'' for cases where
coverage is denied. He is scathing about the managed care and
insurance industry's argument that more regulation will
automatically mean higher premiums and ultimately fewer people
covered. ``They've just been atrocious in their claims that if we
do anything we're going to hurt people,'' he said. ``That's like
saying child labor laws hurt employment in this country. There is a
bigger good.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignagni, president of the American Association of Health
Plans, said it was not clear whether the Republican doctors in the
House were representing the interests of the patients or the
practicioners. ``The practitioners have a very strong self-interest
in this legislation, as do the health plans and others,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn's other great crusade this year has been the
appropriations process, challenging one spending bill after another
as excessive and outside the party's budget goals. ``We know what
we want to do, what we stand for, but the candy jar in front of us
is just so tempting,'' he said. ``What happens is you get addicted.
It's easy to say, `Oh, I can do it for my district because it's
just a little amount.'''
</P>
<P>
   His stance has, at times, infuriated Democrats and Republicans
alike, and he acknowledges he has ``taken a lot of abuse.'' But
Coburn finds solace in the to-the-barricades fiscal conservatism
that fired the class of 1994. ``I'm doing it for the next
generation, for our kids,'' he said. ``What we're doing right now
is sacrificing their standard of living because we don't have the
courage to make the tough decisions that we were sent up here to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Coburn is flummoxed when a reporter asks what he would like his
legacy to be when he leaves the House. ``I don't really desire a
legacy here,'' he said. ``That's the genius of this place _ when
you come and you leave, nobody remembers you were here.'' Maybe, he
said, he would like his legacy to be a little restoration of public
trust.
</P>
<P>
   He won't miss campaigning, he said. ``The thing I hated most
about this job was campaigning and raising money,'' Coburn said.
</P>
<P>
   A politician who hates campaigning?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I don't like it,'' he said. ``You know? I'm walking down
a parade saying, `Hey, I'm Tom Coburn.' It's counterintuitive. What
you need to be doing is saying, `Here's what I believe. If you
agree with that, come vote with me. If you don't, don't.''' He was
laughing halfway through his explanation, as if recognizing his own
orneriness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
