<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISER-SUBSIDIZED SNAIL MAIL  
 HONK LOUD FOR MOTORING SAFETY  
 PATENT TALK ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 &HT;    
 &HT;    E-mail has become an indispensable mode of communication for
many people these days. Not only is it speedy, but it is free for
frugal souls in exchange for putting up with advertising taglines
at the bottom of their e-mails.
 &HT;    But what if someone were to take the same concept _
advertiser-subsidized correspondence _ and instead apply it to
snail mail?
 &HT;    That is what Joshua Reiter, a management consultant in
Baltimore, has done. He recently patented a way to reduce the costs
of mailing an old-fashioned stamp-and-envelope letter _ by printing
advertisements directly aimed at a specific household on the
outside of mail delivered to that household.
 &HT;    ``Originally, I thought about doing this on the Internet,''
Reiter said, ``but too many people were doing something similar and
so I thought there was no way I would get a patent on it.''
 &HT;    ``Then I thought, well, regular mail is still going to be viable
for many years,'' he said. ``People are still going to be sending
regular letters. The U.S. Postal Services handles 190 billion
packages and letters a year, and that number seems to still be
going up. I couldn't believe no one had thought of putting
advertising on the outside of envelopes before.''
 &HT;    Reiter's patent covers a computer system that tracks the
individual tastes and interests of vast numbers of households and
then prints advertisements tailored to specific households for
mailers who want to save on postage.
 &HT;    So, for example, a credit card company wanting to shave off a
few cents for each monthly statement it sends out would allow
advertising for other companies to be printed on its envelopes.
 &HT;    A family with small children might see an ad for a toy company
on the outside of their monthly bill. Meanwhile, a globe-trotting
elderly couple might receive an offer for a discounted cruise-ship
excursion. And an athletic middle-aged bachelor might be exhorted
to buy a new pair of running shoes.
 &HT;    ``Since the message is on the outside of the letter or parcel,
it must be seen by the recipients,'' Reiter said. ``They can't
discard it, as they might with an advertisement inside an
envelope.''
 &HT;    Reiter is quick to downplay any Big Brother overtones to his
invention. ``Advertisers have all this information already,'' he
said. ``We know a lot about who lives in a particular household.
Today with bar-coding information, you can identify who the
household is.''
 &HT;    He likened his system to groceries where cashiers print coupons
based on what a shopper has just bought. ``If you buy peanut
butter, they give you a coupon for jelly,'' he said.
 &HT;    The patent also covers the printing of coupons on
advertising-subsidized mail and even musical advertising that
recipients hear when they open an envelope.
 &HT;    Reiter acknowledges that his system is more likely to benefit
mass mailers rather than an individual mailing a birthday card to a
cousin.
 &HT;    ``If you only send out one letter you're probably not interested
in saving a nickel,'' he said.
 &HT;    Reiter, who received patent 5,819,241, said he is attempting to
license his invention. ``This would work for the Postal Service or
Federal Express or Airborne Express,'' he said, noting that he
thought his concept would also work well with new types of
electronic postage.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Car Horn Linked to the Gas Pedal
</P>
<P>
   Chester Cotter says the inspiration for a new car horn came to
him sometime after a harrowing drive on the interstate. ``I nearly
got smacked by an 18-wheeler who was trying to move into my lane,''
he said. ``The driver had earphones on and was too busy boogeying
to hear me.''
</P>
<P>
   Cotter and his friend, Henry Darlington, have recently patented
a car horn whose volume increases proportionally to the speed of
the car. Their electronic relay system fits into a two-inch cube
that is attached to the speedometer. ``Ideally it would be factory
installed,'' Cotter said. The device has three settings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very polite horn when you're driving downtown,'' he
said. ``When you're driving from 30 to 50 miles an hour it sounds
like a normal horn. But when you really get going on the highway it
sounds like the Queen Mary pulling out of port.''
</P>
<P>
   The physics of horn projection necessitate the different
volumes, according to Cotter. ``If you're out on the highway, the
wind just blows the sound away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cotter and Darlington hope to license patent 5,883,571.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service &QC;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   New Commissioner Plans Online Chat
</P>
<P>
   Q. Todd Dickinson, who was officially nominated last month by
the Clinton administration to take over the top spot at the Patent
and Trademark Office, will field online questions from inventors
and patent lawyers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The online conversation with Dickinson, the acting commissioner,
will take place from noon to 1 p.m. ET. Anyone wishing to
participate or observe should log onto the agency's Web site during
that time at www.uspto.gov and click on the home-page link marked
``Online Conversation with the Commissioner.''
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
