<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990801.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1804 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     08-01 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRONICLE </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ACK UP YOUR TROUBLES IN YOUR OLD KIT BAG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Worried about the effects of Y2K on computer-driven banking, air
traffic control, heart pace-makers? Relax.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post quotes Senate Banking Committee Chairman
 &UR; Phil Gramm &LR; , R-Texas, at a hearing last week: ``Well, it seems to
me we ought to be encouraged that in the year 1000, they had to add
a new digit, and yet no evidence of economic disruption. And then a
millennium before, we had dates going down, and then they started
going up, and yet no evidence of disruption of chaos in the
economy. So if they could do it then, surely we can deal with it
now, it seems to me.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Nikki Lastreto &LR;  read the bold print on her Burning Man
ticket, ``You voluntarily assume the risk of serious injury or
death by attending,'' but she says she's going anyway. ``What fun
would it be if it were safe?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REAL DOCTOR HAS EYES WIDE OPEN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stanley Kubrick &LR; 's ``Eyes Wide Shut'' tells the story of a
young doctor, William Harford, and his wife, their marital
troubles, sexual fantasies and escapades. In his online journal
 &LR; healthcentral.com &LR; , East Bay physician  &UR; Oscar London  &LR; compares the
capers of the fictional doc, as played by  &UR; Tom Cruise &LR; , with the
capers of a real-life doctor:
</P>
<P>
   Harford's practice ``consists of seeing four patients a day in a
spacious office with eight assistants, knee-deep rugs and black
marble counter tops. ... By subtle contrast, I'm a Berkeley
internist with a practice that requires me to see 25 HMO patients a
day in a small, 50-year-old office that was recently given six
months to live by a specialist in dry rot.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the movie Harford makes a house call. After he
finds the patient dead, the patient's daughter ``throws herself at
him, kisses him with maximum passion and professes her love for
him. ... Many years ago, I made a house call. I don't remember
exactly when or precisely why. But I do recall that the elderly
patient's son, a haggard, unshaven man in his 50s, threw a copy of
the Columbia Desk Encyclopedia at me. ...''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. In other news of doctors, German radio reported late last
week that the ``Portrait of Dr. Gachet,'' feared destroyed by a
Japanese businessman who didn't want his heirs to pay inheritance
taxes on it, was sold early this year to an anonymous buyer in the
United States.  &UR; Kiyonori Yamamoto &LR; , president of the International
Auction Organization in Tokyo, said the work had been sold for
between $87 million and $130 million, which is a big between.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Austin Powers rules:  &UR; John Sloan &LR;  notes that a story in
Thursday's Examiner about the arrest of the leader of the Falun
Gong meditation group was datelined ``Shaghai.''
</P>
<P>
   - The  &UR; Queen Mother &LR; , who will be 99 years old this week, is
getting ready to invite  &UR; Camilla Parker Bowles &LR;  to stay with her at
Balmoral, reports the Mirror of London. This might smooth the way
for an eventual meeting between  &UR; Queen Elizabeth  &LR; and Parker
Bowles, her son's best pal.
</P>
<P>
   - Who or what do you love? Bazaar magazine asked a list of
celebrities. ``The DKNY store opening on Madison Avenue and 60th
Street,'' answered shopkeeper  &UR; Donna Karan &LR; . ``It's a dream come
true. My blanket skirt; and all of the C words: century,
celebration, cotton, cashmere, comfort, candles, crystals, caring,
children, charity, cold, Caribbean and change.''
</P>
<P>
   - Several readers have sent word that  &UR; Del Close &LR; , who willed
his skull to his Chicago theater troupe, was a founder of The
Committee in San Francisco. Also a hearty band of readers,
including the still-hearty  &UR; Bruce Mackey &LR; , have sent word that it
was Close who died (as the item said), not Mackey (as the item also
said).
</P>
<P>
   - Consuming interests:  &UR; Saul Feldman &LR; , a connoisseur of all
things spudly, was captivated by last week's Safeway ad for potato
salad ``Made with real chunks of potatoes.'' And when she was stuck
in traffic on 880 the other day,  &UR; Laurie Roberts &LR;  noticed a woman
in a Volvo eating corn on the cob as she drove.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the 1990s, simple design was reserved for those with
enough old-money insouciance or cultivated modesty to downplay the
appearance of success. ... In this era, of democratized and
virtually institutionalized good taste, where a Camry looks an
awful loot like a BMW, and J. Crew's pleated gray wool skirt might
be mistaken for Marc Jacobs' less itchy version, personal flair is
harder and harder to achieve. The bag, worn as a complement to the
monochromatic urban uniform, has become one of our few means of
individual fashion expression.''
</P>
<P>
   - From a Metropolis magazine essay on the handbag, one of the
few remaining ways to tell the haves from the have-nots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 1829EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990801.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1805 &Cx1f; tth-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      08-01 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS TEPID HOT DOGS HAVE LED TO A HOWLING FOOD BUSINESS SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I first met Rich Komen over a hot dog.
</P>
<P>
   Make that a few thousand dogs.
</P>
<P>
   With mustard.
</P>
<P>
   That's what he was serving as the concessionaire in the
University of Washington's Husky Stadium when I wrote a newspaper
column complaining that fans were being served lukewarm ``red
hots.'' A tepid hot dog is the culinary equivalent of a blocked
punt, as Komen admitted during our conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Komen was new to the business. On Friday nights before home
games he would buy a case of beer and invite neighbors over to help
bag peanuts. Hot dogs were another problem, due to the antiquated
facilities and restrictions then in place at Husky Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But he was a quick learner. Komen solved the problems at the UW
and within a few years controlled virtually all the sports
concessions in Seattle. In a few more years he was running food
services at the Kansas City and Oakland sports complexes.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he sold out to a conglomerate and entered the
restaurant business, establishing the highly successful
Clinkerdaggers chain of public houses in the Northwest. Komen
studied and introduced new concepts, then established his own
Restaurants Unlimited company.
</P>
<P>
   And it all started with a lukewarm ``red hot.''
</P>
<P>
   So there is hope for the pup pushers at Safeco Field. First time
around they became the butt of a good news-bad news joke.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that people were walking away hungry from the
long concession lines.
</P>
<P>
   That was also the good news, in the view of food safety
inspectors, who credited Volume Services and their vendors with
more errors than the 1962 New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   If Safeco's lines are still too long during and you find
yourself shut out at the hot links concession, wait until you get
home and pig out on some:
</P>
<P>
   Hoke's Pokes
</P>
<P>
   One-half pound hot Italian sausages, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced green pepper
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup diced celery
</P>
<P>
   Black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Pita bread rounds
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded Swiss or Jack cheese
</P>
<P>
   Fry the sausages slices in a skillet until browned. Add the
onion, garlic, mushrooms, green pepper and celery. Keep cooking
until the veggies are softer than the sweet spot in Alex
Rodriguez's mitt. Season with pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the pitas in half, open up the pockets and stuff with the
sausage filling. Sprinkle with cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Place sandwiches upright in baking pan and shove into a
400-degree oven for 10 minutes, or until the cheese melts.
</P>
<P>
   The kielbasa dogs got a good rating from those Seattle Mariner
fans who could score a few. The others can feast later on:
</P>
<P>
   A 14th Inning Feast
</P>
<P>
   1 pound kielbasa sausage
</P>
<P>
   4 medium new potatoes, quartered
</P>
<P>
   4 large carrots, cut in 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 small head cabbage, quartered
</P>
<P>
   2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brown sugar, packed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   Chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Dump the sausages into a large saucepan. Add the potatoes,
carrots, cabbage and water. Cook, covered, 30 minutes, or until
veggies are fork tender.
</P>
<P>
   Drain, reserving the liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Dump the sausage and veggies on a platter and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Combine in a saucepan three-fourths cup of the pot liquid with
the flour, brown sugar, vinegar, dry mustard, salt and pepper.
Stir-cook until thickened.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the sauce over the kielbasa and veggies and serve in bowls
to four sports fans.
</P>
<P>
   As for sports concessions, just look up the word in your
dictionary:
</P>
<P>
   Concession. 3. A privilege granted by a government, company etc.
</P>
<P>
   See, it's not a right, it's a privilege. Shut up and eat your
hot dog ... if you can find one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 1829EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
