A1812 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMIT     08-01 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKPLACE STARS AREN'T BORN _ THEY'RE MADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not hard to spot the stars at work.
</P>
<P>
   They're the people who get the coveted assignments, the biggest
bonuses, the fastest promotions. They're the 10 percent to 15
percent of workers known as the ``10-for-oners'' _ people who
outshine and outproduce their peers by a factor of 10 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying what makes those people star performers, however, is
trickier, and it turns out it's not what most people think.
</P>
<P>
   Stars are not generally smarter than average performers. They
don't necessarily work harder, and they're not better at
schmoozing. They aren't more creative, bigger risk-takers or born
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   People tend to believe that star performers are somehow better
in some fundamental sense than average performers, said Robert
Kelley, author of ``How to be a Star at Work'' (Times Business,
1999, $12). And by extension, they believe that average workers
lack the necessary qualities to turn themselves into exceptional
producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But stars are made, not born,'' Kelley said. The difference
between an average performer and an exceptional one doesn't boil
down to talent as much as how people use their talents.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley, a professor in the graduate school of Industrial
Administration at Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh, first
got interested in what makes some people shine at work when Bell
Labs asked him for help improving the productivity of its workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had all these really smart, really talented people,''
Kelley said. And they were facing deregulation of their industry.
They knew they were going to have to get exceptional work out of
their workers to compete, but they didn't know how.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley started by gathering data about what people believed made
a star performer. He came up with 45 qualities believed to be
associated with stars, including higher IQs, improved logic and
reasoning skills, high self-confidence, ambition and enhanced
interpersonal skills. Then he subjected 200 star and average
performers to a two-day battery of tests to figure out how they
rated in the 45 traits. He eagerly analyzed the data, expecting a
profile of star qualities to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he got nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Zippo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found none of those things separated the stars from average
performers,'' he said. ``In terms of unlocking productivity
secrets, our data showed no appreciable cognitive,
personal-psychological, social or environmental differences between
stars and average performers.''
</P>
<P>
   So what makes the difference?
</P>
<P>
   ``Average performers are not lacking in talent, motivation,
effort,'' he said. But they tend to use trial-and-error to try to
get ahead, and they often apply their talents in self-limiting
ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star performers do their work very differently than the solid,
average-performing pack,'' he said. They apply a different set of
strategies to their work.
</P>
<P>
   Star-making strategies include taking initiative, networking,
gaining multiple perspectives on problems, being both good
followers and good leaders, knowing how to work on teams and being
savvy about organizational politics.
</P>
<P>
   Star-building initiative, for example, means taking charge of
tasks that fall in the ``white space'' between people's
responsibilities _ those opportunities that are critical to the
organization but aren't any one person's responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Average performers take initiative, too, but they tend to
volunteer for non-critical extras, such as planning corporate
events or recruiting for the company blood drive.
</P>
<P>
   Star performers approach networking differently as well.
</P>
<P>
   An average performer thinks of networking as building a
communications grapevine to keep abreast of office gossip. Star
producers develop a network of ``knowledge experts'' who can help
them troubleshoot problems or do their jobs better.
</P>
<P>
   Another star strategy involves building multiple viewpoints.
Average performers tend to have tunnel vision, concentrating on
developing their own points of view and trying to get them across
to others in the organization. Star producers see projects or
problems through the eyes of others, including customers,
competitors, co-workers and bosses. That depth of perspective leads
to better solutions to problems.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, stars take charge of their own work life, what
Kelley refers to as ``self-management.''
</P>
<P>
   Average performers think of self-management as techniques to
help them better manage their time and projects. But star producers
view self-management as creating new opportunities for themselves.
They're constantly asking how to make themselves more valuable and
looking for ways to get the experiences and skills they need to get
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   By applying these strategies, Kelley said, workers can double
their productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can be a star.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
