<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BLUEJAYS-GREEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE JAYS' GREEN BEING COMPARED TO WALKER, PARKER AND CLEMENTE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Jim Fregosi, longtime baseball man and current manager of
the Toronto Blue Jays, was asked to compare his 26-year-old right
fielder, Shawn Green, to players of the past or present, he started
with an All-Star and ended with a legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about Larry Walker at Colorado and Dave Parker, who
used to play right field for Pittsburgh,'' said Fregosi, who has
been a player, manager or executive in the major leagues since
1961. ``Those guys were complete players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can even go back to Roberto Clemente, a guy that could run
and throw, hit for average, hit for power and drive in runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Fregosi did not hesitate when mentioning the great Clemente. The
name of the Hall of Fame right fielder flew from his lips as easily
as a fastball from a pitching machine, perhaps because Fregosi
knows that Green has been compared to even better. In 1991, when
Green was a gangly star at Tustin High School in California, the
Blue Jays scout Moose Johnson was so impressed that he likened the
youngster's swing to that of Ted Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying at this time that Shawn's going to be a Hall of
Famer,'' Fregosi said. ``But he has the ability, if he can do it
over a long period of time, to put up the numbers that would make
him that kind of player.''
</P>
<P>
   No one watching Green this season would argue with Fregosi's
assessment. When Green leads the Blue Jays into Yankee Stadium for
a three-game series that begins Monday night, he will do so on the
heels of a franchise-record 28-game hitting streak, the longest in
the American League this season, which ended Sunday against
Detroit. He ranks among the American League leaders in seven
offensive categories, and is the league leader in fielding
percentage (.995) at his position. After becoming the first Blue
Jays player and only the ninth American Leaguer to record at least
30 home runs (35) and 30 stolen bases (35) in the same season in
1998, he has a chance to do it again, with 31 homers and 18 steals
in 24 attempts so far this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I always thought the home runs were harder, but now
I think it's the stolen bases that are tougher,'' Green said. ``You
get some sore legs here and there and get in situations where you
can't run as much, depending on the game. So it's a lot harder to
get those 30 to 40 stolen bases. I'd like to try and steal some
more this year, but it's been a little bit of a grind.''
</P>
<P>
   So was Green's major league career, at first. After Johnson's
glowing evaluation led the Blue Jays to select Green with the 16th
pick of the 1991 draft and pay him a $700,000 signing bonus _ the
second-largest in baseball history at the time _ Green spent four
seasons in the minors and the past four full seasons in Toronto.
The thinking throughout the organization was that Green, who bats
left-handed, could not hit left-handed pitchers, and some of the
club's officials even thought it might be best to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   But Green was not moved, and last season Tim Johnson, the Blue
Jays' manager at the time, decided to make him an everyday player.
Green went on to post career highs in nearly every statistical
category and hit .287 against both left- and right-handed pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   While that has been a pleasant, if shocking, development for the
Blue Jays, Green's power was just as unexpected. Carrying only 200
pounds on his slender 6-foot-4-inch frame, Green looks like
anything but a slugger. And before last season, his career best was
16 home runs in 429 at-bats in 1997. He did not even show power in
the minors, where he hit only 13 homers in 433 times at bat at
Syracuse in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was anything that he ever really accented,''
the Blue Jays' General Manager Gord Ash said. ``He was a gap-type
hitter who really was going to hit for a high average and who was
going to be strong enough to hit 15 to 20 home runs. But he's
proven to be a unique combination of power and speed. To look at
him, you don't see that power build of a Mark McGwire or a Canseco.
But he has very, very strong arms and very quick wrists and that
allows him to hit with power.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite missing 11 starts with a broken left wrist after being
hit by the Yankees' Andy Pettitte on May 28, Green is on course to
hit at least 40 homers this season. The Blue Jays' other power
hitter, Carlos Delgado, who at a burly 6-3 and 225 pounds looks the
part, has been amazed by the strength of Green's stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came back this year with unbelievable power,'' said
Delgado, who has played with Green since 1992. ``I mean, last year,
he hit some balls good. But now, it seems like everything that he
hits is just like, `boom.' It just takes off. Sometimes, you go:
`Did you hit that ball that good? It went 450 feet!'''
</P>
<P>
   Green made his first All-Star appearance this season, the talk
show host Larry King has referred to him as ``the game's next great
superstar'' and reporters and fans everywhere are beginning to
descend on him. While Green appreciates the attention, his quiet,
unassuming personality leads him to treat it more as a chore than
as a pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really had to deal with much of this stuff,'' Green
said. ``I'm pretty much a private person. I'm pretty quiet, so I
guess it takes a little getting used to, dealing with all this
attention. But to get the attention, you have to perform well, and
obviously I want to perform well. So I'll just take whatever
consequences that come with that as part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Green has come to cherish one product of all the attention: an
increased awareness of his Jewish heritage. In a sport that
historically has boasted few Jewish stars _ Sandy Koufax and Hank
Greenberg are the only Jewish players in the Hall of Fame _ Green
has become a source of ethnic pride, drawing cheers from Jewish
fans in practically every ball park he enters and being featured in
numerous Jewish publications.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely get a lot of support from the Jewish community,''
Green said. ``I might not get booed as bad as somebody who isn't
Jewish in certain cities because there are always some Jewish fans
at the games that are cheering a little bit, and it feels good to
be welcomed like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, who said he was not reared in a religious household, has
even decided he wants a bar mitzvah. ``Since I've been in the big
leagues, I've learned a lot more about my religion, my heritage,''
he said. ``I would like to have a bar mitzvah. I've got a full
plate right now, but I'm going to see if I can somehow accomplish
that.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation that the Yankees would love to
acquire Green when he becomes a free agent after the 2000 season,
mainly because of his talent but also because his Jewish background
would be a draw. While Green says he is happy in Toronto, he
admitted to being a Yankee fan as a youngster in New Jersey and
California, one who dreamed of playing in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every kid has dreams of putting on those Yankee
pinstripes,'' Green said. ``I remember being a little kid, going to
a Yankees game, and it was like watching the Beatles or something.
That's the dream of a little kid, but at the same time, I've got to
do what's best for me when that time comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Blue Jays, not wanting to lose the next Roberto
Clemente, will do everything in their power to keep Green in
Toronto, even if he didn't grow up dreaming of playing in Sky Dome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
