<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASSEL SAYS BETTER PLAYERS WILL ALLOW GIANTS TO OPEN UP OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Giants had the worst offense in the National
Football League when Jim Fassel arrived as head coach in 1997. Two
seasons later, the Giants offense ranked 29th out of 30 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel acknowledges that this is mildly embarrassing, since his
forte is offensive artistry. It certainly troubles him, but he has
felt inhibited by the talent of the team he inherited.
Specifically, Fassel believes Dave Brown and Danny Kanell, his two
starting quarterbacks at the beginning of the last two seasons,
were unpolished and somewhat overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   To make it easier on them, Fassel sacrificed ingenuity for
simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   But at his third Giants training camp this summer, Fassel is
emphasizing something new about his offense. He says he is not
holding back any longer, promising to put in a host of new
wrinkles. He is assuring one and all that the Giants will attack.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel says the game plan will no longer be to play conservative
and hope the defense can win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting aggressive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NFL training camps are full of such tough talk. But since
aggressive offenses often make mistakes that lose games, Fassel
could well find himself pulling in the reins to survive the season.
It's what happened in each of the two previous seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Meticulous to a fault, Fassel has thought this out and he
believes that this time his offense does not have to be dull to be
dependable.
</P>
<P>
   Why? For the simplest reason of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have better players,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel is convinced his situation at quarterback is much
improved and that the quarterback, whether it is Kent Graham or
Kerry Collins, will have better players to aid the cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year, Dave Brown was struggling with a lot of
things,'' Fassel said. ``He hadn't played well and he was
struggling with his self-confidence. He had been sacked more than
any quarterback in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't ask him to do too much. The priority was boosting
his confidence and keeping enough blockers in to reduce the sacks.
That's not going to lead to an aerial circus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next season we had Danny, who was only in his second year
starting. He was a young guy still learning, and we couldn't put
too much on his plate or we might set him back.''
</P>
<P>
   So Fassel largely ignored the parts of his playbook that threw
the ball downfield, that aggressively split a tight end at the end
of the formation like a wide receiver. He didn't have a tight end
with those kind of pass-catching skills, and he didn't have a
quarterback who had ever demonstrated he could successfully throw
the deep pass.
</P>
<P>
   Graham may be 10-14 as a starter in the NFL and Collins may be
coming off a turnover-filled season, but Fassel sees the tandem as
experienced and poised.
</P>
<P>
   ``At quarterback, I'm not as worried about building confidence
as I was before,'' he said. ``I'm implementing more and more new
plays and a lot of new fronts. We have to display explosiveness. We
have to be more threatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've advanced to where we can handle more. Our offensive line
is more athletic. Pete Mitchell at tight end is very knowledgeable
about how to get open and catch passes at his position. The offense
has changed a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell will most likely step in as the new third-down
possession receiver, a role filled in the past few seasons by Chris
Calloway, whom the Giants released this winter. Amani Toomer, who
is 6 feet 3 inches, will give the Giants a big target downfield _
and he seems to be Graham's favorite receiver, whereas Calloway was
a favorite of both Brown and Kanell.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was quarterback of the Arizona Cardinals in 1996 when
Fassel was the team's offensive coordinator. To Graham, Fassel is
turning back the clock to that season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We attacked, tried a lot of things and the offense opened
up,'' Graham said. ``Everything is related. Your running game is
made better by a long pass attempt. Even if you don't complete that
pass, you make the defense nervous, and they back off the line of
scrimmage.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Fassel is convinced this Giants offense can handle a
more comprehensive system of plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any choice,'' he said. ``We have to get better.
To go to the next level in this league, you can't be ranked where
we are offensively.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
