<SLUG> BC-GLF-DUVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL SAYS A RESTED WOODS HAS NO ADVANTAGE IN PRIME-TIME MATCH
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. _ Having earned $57,500 for his four rounds of
work in the Canon Greater Hartford Open, David Duval left for
California and a head-to-head, made-for-television match Monday
night against Tiger Woods that will earn the winner $1.1 million
and the loser $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   After shooting a seven-under-par 63 Sunday, Duval said he was
not concerned about playing for such high stakes 3,000 miles and
three time zones away against an opponent who took the week off.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can't play golf five days in a row, maybe I should find
something else to do,'' the 27-year-old Duval said.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who boarded a private jet at Bradley International
Airport in Windsor Locks, Conn., about 30 miles from here, a few
hours after completing his round, was asked whether he thought
Woods might have an edge after not playing in a tournament this
weekend. Duval endured temperatures in the 90s for four days at the
Tournament Players Club at River Highlands, finishing at 11-under
269 and tying for 11th place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel fine, and I'm not worried about it,'' he replied.
``I'll get to California by 5 this afternoon and have plenty of
time to rest up. Also, I'll be able to sleep late, since we're not
teeing off until 5 o'clock in the afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Some golf purists have criticized the Duval-Woods match, which
will be broadcast by ABC, saying that it may lead to other
prime-time television matches involving the game's biggest stars
while diminishing some regular tour events. Duval disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good for golf,'' said Duval, who has won four
tournaments and more than $3 million this year. ``A lot of people
will be watching, and so it can't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   While Duval was competing in the Greater Hartford, Woods was
resting in California and getting in several practice rounds at the
site of Monday night's match, the Sherwood Country Club in Thousand
Oaks, Calif. Though the event is not sanctioned by the PGA Tour,
the PGA has reportedly agreed to accept $1 million from
International Management Group, the sponsor of the match, which
acts as the agent for both Duval and Woods.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-hole match will bring together, in a rare head-to-head
competition, the two players generally acknowledged as the best in
the world. On the strength of his record over the last two years,
Duval is widely considered No. 1. Through 16 tournaments this year
he has nine top-10 finishes, and with $3,076,500 in earnings he is
the leading money winner. The 23-year-old Woods, meanwhile, has
been in the top 10 in 11 of 15 events, while winning three titles
and collecting $2,624,105 for second place behind Duval.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the Greater Hartford Open, Woods was leading the tour
in scoring average (68.66), followed by Duval, and in all-around
ranking, where Duval was fourth. Duval, meanwhile, led in hitting
greens in regulation and in birdie average.
</P>
<P>
   Given his flair and his length off the tee, Woods has
overshadowed Duval. After his record-breaking Masters victory in
1997, Woods, then only 21, was being projected as the most dominant
player for years to come. But then Duval began his remarkable run,
which has included 11 tournament titles within the last 21 months.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Duval-Woods is hardly a rivalry comparable to, say,
Arnold Palmer and Jack Nicklaus. For one thing, Duval has yet to
win a Grand Slam tournament and Woods has won only one.
</P>
<P>
   So what will the match prove? Not much, probably, other than
that it will make both Duval and Woods much richer while scores of
professionals are trying to get through Monday qualifying and make
it into the main draw of the next tournament, with no guarantee of
making any money whatsoever. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
