<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-RISKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN CAN CONTROL SOME RISKS OF HEART DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BY SARAH SKIDMORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several factors increase the risk of heart disease for women.
</P>
<P>
   There are fixed risks, such as age, heredity, diabetes or
previous heart attack or stroke.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are some variable risks that can be controlled ,
such as weight, tobacco use, cholesterol level, blood pressure,
physical activity, weight, use of oral contraceptives, alcohol
intake and stress.
</P>
<P>
   _Age: As women grow older, the chance of developing heart
disease also increases. After menopause, the loss of natural
estrogen may increase a woman's susceptibility. Hormone replacement
therapy _ the replacement of estrogen and progesterone _ has been
used in some cases to help reduce risk. A recent study suggests
that the hormone prostaglandin, secreted by the uterus, may also
have protective value. The effects of taking hormones vary
according to the individual and should be discussed with a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   _Heredity: A history of heart disease or stroke in close
relatives increases risks.
</P>
<P>
   _Diabetes: Diabetic women have double the risk of having a heart
attack. Additionally, diabetes doubles the risk of a second heart
attack in women, but not in men.
</P>
<P>
   _Race: Black and Asian American women are in a higher risk pool
than their Caucasian counterparts because of traditionally
higher-than-average blood pressure levels. For ages 35-74, the
death rate from coronary heart disease for black women is almost 72
percent higher than white women. Native Americans and Hispanics are
more likely to develop diabetes, which can in turn increase
cardiovascular risk.
</P>
<P>
   _Previous disease: A previous heart attack or stroke increases
risk of a second attack. In 1999 an estimated 1.1 million Americans
will have a coronary attack. Of these, about 650,000 will be first
attacks and 450,000 will be recurrent attacks.
</P>
<P>
   _Weight: Being overweight by more than 30 pounds is itself a
risk factor for heart disease and stroke. However, excess weight
can contribute to high blood pressure, high cholesterol and
diabetes _ all of which, in turn, put you at higher risk.
</P>
<P>
   _Tobacco: A smoker's risk of heart attack is more than twice
that of non-smokers. Secondhand smoke also raises the risk of heart
disease. Smoking is also the greatest risk factor for peripheral
vascular disease, which causes the blood vessels to the legs and
arms to narrow.
</P>
<P>
   _Cholesterol: The odds of a heart attack are doubled with
cholesterol at high levels. Blood cholesterol is considered at a
high level when it rises above 240 mg/dL (milligrams per deciliter
of blood). However, blood cholesterol levels between 200 and 239
are at an intermediate level. Approximately 52 percent of the
American population has blood cholesterol in the intermediate risk
category; 21 percent are in the high level.
</P>
<P>
   _Blood pressure: Almost half the women 55 years and older have
high blood pressure. High blood pressure increases the heart's
workload. This forces the heart to enlarge and eventually weaken.
It increases risk of stroke, heart attacks and congestive heart
failure. When it is paired with obesity, smoking, high cholesterol
or diabetes, the risk of heart attack is greatly increased.
</P>
<P>
   _Birth control: Some forms of oral contraceptives can increase a
woman's risk of heart disease. Pills with high levels of estrogen
and progestin afford the highest risk. However, high levels of
hormones are traditionally found in older pills; newer forms are
lower risk. Women who smoke or have high blood pressure increase
their risk with the use of any contraceptive pill.
</P>
<P>
   _Alcohol: Moderate drinkers, women who average one drink per
day, are at lower risk than non-drinkers. However, more frequent or
greater intake of alcohol can contribute to weight gain and high
blood-pressure, which leads to heart attacks and stroke.
</P>
<P>
   _Stress: An individual's reaction to stress could lead to heart
disease or failure. Common responses such as smoking, overeating or
drinking place people in higher risk categories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
