<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-OPPOSITION     08-01 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-OPPOSITION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARGE RALLY PLANNED TO PRESSURE MILOSEVIC TO RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Yugoslavia's opposition plans to hold a
large rally in Belgrade on Aug. 19 to press President Slobodan
Milosevic to accept a transitional government and resign,
opposition officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The rally, which will be announced on Monday, will be the first
called for the capital since a rather haphazard series of rallies
by competing opposition factions after the Kosovo war ended in
June.
</P>
<P>
   The rally will have the support of Patriarch Pavle, the head of
the Serbian Orthodox Church, who will attend, and it will take
place on the religious holiday of Preobrazenje, or the
Transfiguration.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition figures had been saying there would be no rally here
until at least September, when students return and it is easier to
turn out big numbers. But Washington has been pressing the
fractious opposition to unite and not to lose momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the rally, which may be accompanied by a warning strike by workers,
will be sponsored by the church and the organizers of a ``pact of
stability for Serbia.'' General support is expected from the
Serbian Renewal Movement of Vuk Draskovic and the Alliance for
Change, a grouping of opposition parties dominated by Zoran
Djindjic of the Democracy Party. The rally is also supported by
Momcilo Perisic, the former army chief-of-staff, who was fired by
Milosevic in November and who has come out in favor of the
president's resignation and is contemplating the formation of his
own party.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to name a transitional Yugoslav and Serbian
government of experts to serve a year, in which they would renovate
ties with the West, liberalize the economy and prepare free and
fair elections with outside monitors. Milosevic would be asked or
pressed to resign, though Draskovic believes that he might be able
to remain as a figurehead until calling new elections.
</P>
<P>
   The prime mover of the stability pact is Mladjan Dinkic, a young
professor and economist. Dinkic is considered a leading candidate
for the post of Serbian prime minister in any transitional
government along with Dragoslav Avramovic, 79, the former central
banker who ended Yugoslavia's hyperinflation in January 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The post of Yugoslav prime minister is reserved under the
constitution for a Montenegrin, to be chosen by that sister
republic's president, Milo Djukanovic.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the transitional government, should it come to
pass, are supposed to promise not to run in the elections in a
year's time.
</P>
<P>
   Other key figures behind Dinkic and the Stability Pact are
Slobodan Vucetic, a member of the Serbian Constitutional Court;
Ljubodrag Simovic of the Serbian Academy of Sciences; Dusan
Kovacevic a writer and playwright; and Predrag Markovic, a
publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Important differences remain among the opposition, and Vladan
Batic, the coordinator of the Alliance for Change, has said
Dinkic's project does not have the full backing of his members and
that ``it's too early to talk about a firm deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Djindjic is said to think that a transitional government need
not have cabinet ministers, and the Alliance generally backs
Avramovic, who is old enough not to want to hang on to power even
if he agrees to take it.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, in a news conference, Avramovic said he would consider
taking the transitional post of Serbian prime minister if and when
Milosevic resigns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
