<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-AIDS-CONFLICT-720(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG MAKERS BLOCK DEVELOPING COUNTRIES' ACCESS TO GENERIC AIDS
DRUGS  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.Africa)  (js) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. pharmaceutical industry, with help from
the Clinton administration, is trying to protect its patents by
blocking developing countries ravaged by the AIDS epidemic from
producing generic versions of life-saving medicines that are now
too expensive for most AIDS victims outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical companies are especially alarmed at efforts
by South Africa to allow local companies to make generic versions
of patented AIDS drugs or to import the drugs from countries where
they are sold more cheaply. Each day an estimated 1,500 people in
South Africa are infected by HIV, the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Through court battles in South Africa, the U.S. companies have
so far managed to block a two-year-old law that would reduce the
price of AIDS-fighting drugs by allowing them to be manufactured
locally or imported without the permission of patent holders.
</P>
<P>
   But if a court injunction blocking the law is lifted, South
African companies are reported to be ready to begin producing or
importing the generic drugs within months.
</P>
<P>
   In a nation where the per capita income is only $500 a month,
many South African AIDS sufferers cannot afford even basic medical
care, let alone the new patented chemical cocktails known as
protease inhibitors that are prolonging the lives of many American
victims of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, those drugs can cost a single patient more
than $10,000 a year. The drugs are sold in South Africa at a
similar price.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. drug company executives regard the South African law as
patent infringement that undermines their industry's
multibillion-dollar research efforts and could hinder the
development of new AIDS-fighting medicines.
</P>
<P>
   While the administration has not endorsed the industry's call
for a ban on the manufacture of generic versions of AIDS drugs that
are otherwise protected by patents, it has asked that South Africa
clarify exactly how it will protect the rights of patent-holders.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. trade representative, citing the 1997 law among other
factors, has placed South Africa on a ``watch list'' of countries
that can face sanctions if they do not revise their trade policies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the tussle between the companies' patent rights and
the need for developing countries to try to control an epidemic
that is killing millions of people has political implications for
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Within the Clinton administration, Gore has long been seen as a
champion in the fight against AIDS. But he has been heckled at
recent political appearances by activists who charge that he has
put the concerns of the pharmaceutical companies above those of
AIDS victims.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, who has also been the administration's point
man on relations with South Africa, has intervened to try to work
out a compromise between the South African government and
pharmaceutical companies that would allow more of the drugs to
reach AIDS victims there while protecting patent rights.
</P>
<P>
   Many AIDS activists say it is wrong to criticize Gore for
seeking a solution that would satisfy both sides.
</P>
<P>
   But others question why the United States would want to expend
any energy intervening in South Africa _ or other largely
impoverished, AIDS-ravaged countries _ on behalf of the powerful
and highly profitable pharmaceutical industry.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa, like many of its neighbors on the continent, is
being devastated by AIDS. Nearly a quarter of all pregnant women
test positive for the HIV virus, which causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what the Clinton administration is doing is immoral,''
said Mark J. Heywood, director of the AIDS Law Project of South
Africa, which is based in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember the context in which the United States is
acting,'' he said in a telephone interview from South Africa.
``This is a nation of almost 4 million people with HIV, and most
people are dying without any access to even the most rudimentary
medical treatments.''
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical industry insists that it is sensitive to the
health emergency in South Africa but that it must protect the
rights of its companies to profit from their research.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an excuse to attack the intellectual property rights
of the pharmaceutical industry,'' said Thomas Bombelles of the
Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers Association in
Washington.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bombelles questioned whether the South African government would
be capable of properly dispensing sophisticated AIDS drugs _ which
can do more harm than good when prescribed incorrectly _ if they
did become more widely available. ``The real problem in South
Africa is a health-care system that doesn't deliver health care to
a majority of the population,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In what may be a response to pressure from AIDS activists, some
drug companies have announced plans to discount their prices for
AIDS drugs in poor countries or, in some cases, to give them away.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In May, Bristol-Myers Squibb, which makes drugs that prevent the
HIV virus from replicating, announced that it would spend $100
million over the next five years in South Africa and four other
African countries on the development of community AIDS-control
projects and on AIDS research.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, Glaxo-Wellcome, manufacturer of the anti-HIV drug
AZT, announced that it would cut the drug's price in the developing
world by as much as 75 percent _ down to about $100 for a course of
treatments of the drug _ to prevent mother-to-child transmission of
HIV.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rosshirt, a spokesman for the vice president, said Gore
``never put pressure on South Africa and never threatened trade
sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's goal, he said, has been to resolve a
dispute between pharmaceutical companies and the South African
government that, because of the court action, was blocking the
distribution of more medicine to AIDS sufferers.
</P>
<P>
   He said the vice president expressly opposed a request by
drug-industry lobbyists to step up the pressure on South Africa by
imposing trade sanctions if they did not revoke or revise portions
of the 1997 law.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said in a letter in June to the Congressional Black Caucus,
``I support South Africa's effort to provide AIDS drugs at reduced
prices through compulsory licensing and parallel importing, so long
as they are carried out in a way that is consistent with
international agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   Compulsory licensing is a legal term that refers to the right of
countries to allow the local manufacture of a patented product _ in
this case, drugs _without the permission of the patent holder.
Parallel importing refers to importing a patented product from
another part of the world where it is sold more cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   Under international trade agreements overseen by the World Trade
Organization, all countries can engage in ``compulsory licensing''
and ``parallel importing'' so long as certain conditions are met.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions are looser in situations in which there is a
``national emergency,'' a description that might apply to South
Africa as it attempts to grapple with the AIDS crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The South African government has not joined in the criticism of
Gore, who has close ties to the new president, Thabo Mbeki. A
spokesman for the South African Embassy in Washington, Vicky
Maharaj, said that Gore appeared eager ``to work constructively to
resolve this issue _ we're not aware of any pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical industry fears that if South African courts
ever lift the injunction that has so far blocked implementation of
the 1997 law, small South African drug companies will begin to
manufacture low-cost, generic versions of a range of patented drugs
useful against HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Other local companies are likely to begin importing the same
drugs from India and other nations where patent rights are not
enforced and where AIDS drugs made in India and other countries can
be bought for a fraction of the price they command in pharmacies in
the United States or South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Love, director of the Consumer Project on Technology, a
Washington-based research group that is harshly critical of the
pharmaceutical industry, said the law should allow many AIDS
sufferers in South Africa to have access to a range of more basic
drugs that would otherwise be too expensive for them to buy,
including antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed that despite the pharmaceutical industry's
position, generic drugs produced or imported under the 1997 law
would be prescribed and used properly in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   While poor by Western standards, he said, ``South Africa
probably has the best infrastructure in Africa to deliver medical
care to its residents, but their ability to deliver that care is
dependent on the price they pay for drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 law was designed to revamp the pharmaceutical industry
in South Africa, where there is little competition among drug
companies and drug prices are notoriously high. AIDS sufferers
without health insurance are generally left to seek help at
overcrowded public hospitals, where many AIDS drugs are unavailable
because of their price or because of theft. Alternatively, they
seek aid from traditional healers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
