<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PHILLIES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves show big bats
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Braves general manager John Schuerholz had that giddy,
post-trade look about him on Sunday morning, like he was overjoyed
to finally hang up the phone, catch up on his rest and watch his
team go to work for the last two months of the season.
</P>
<P>
   His day only got better.
</P>
<P>
   If there was disappointment that Schuerholz hadn't addressed the
Braves' proverbial ``big bat'' void on Saturday night, the Braves
didn't show it Sunday. They played like they had plenty of good
wood in their lineup already, making the trade for pitcher Terry
Mulholland and utility infielder Jose Hernandez look just fine for
now, with a 12-4 victory against the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Vying for the big-bat title on Sunday afternoon were Chipper
Jones, with two home runs to increase his season total to 27,
Gerald Williams, who had his third career grand slam to give the
Braves their first lead at 8-4 in the fourth inning, and Andruw
Jones, who chipped in with his 22nd homer.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have not lost a series to the Phillies in Atlanta
since 1995 and under the hottest of circumstances _ on the field
and in the standings _ they sent the Phillies packing with a 2-1
loss in this series. Combined with the Mets' 5-4 victory against
the Cubs, the Braves kept their NL East lead of a half-game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the people to go out and score five, six runs a
game,'' Chipper Jones said. ``We can't rely on the front office to
give us help. If we hadn't traded anyone, this team would still
have been prepared to do whatever we had to to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves rose from the depths of an inauspicious start by Greg
Maddux, who allowed three hits and two runs before recording an
out. He spent the first inning frustrated with Larry Poncino`s
interpretation of the strike zone and his 4-0 deficit. But he
snapped back into form, retiring 20 of the last 23 batters he faced
to collect his 12th win.
</P>
<P>
   ``After he got mad, he started pitching better,'' catcher Eddie
Perez said.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux allowed four hits in the first but gave up just two hits
in his final six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to stay positive and realize it's a tough day to pitch
and you try to hang in there,'' Maddux said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillies rookie Randy Wolf has some first-inning troubles of his
own, giving up two runs. It got worse in the fourth when he yielded
consecutive singles and then fielded a Maddux sacrifice bunt,
thought about throwing to third and bobbled the ball to load the
bases for Williams. A changeup to Williams later, his outing was
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't beat the Braves,'' a frustrated Scott Rolen said.
``We're not going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
