<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA WILL BE ON PAC-10 THRONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN BEENE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are you ready for some COLLEGE football?
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, one month before UCLA and USC open their seasons,
the Pac-10 football media day is held here at the Sheraton Gateway.
</P>
<P>
   If you are just dying to know who will emerge as the No. 1
choice in the media and coaches polls, I'll save you the suspense.
It will be Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry Trojans and Bruins fans, but all signs point to this being
the year of the Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   They have both of their quarterbacks (Newbury Park's own Keith
Smith and Ortege Jenkins) back, plus their top running back (Trung
Canidate) and their top receiver (Dennis Northcutt). On defense,
their top six tacklers return.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Arizona returns 16 starters from last year's team that
went 12-1 and missed its first Rose Bowl when UCLA got blown away
in the Massacre at Miami. So the Wildcats settled for the Holiday
Bowl, where they beat Nebraska 23-20.
</P>
<P>
   __ For the curious, USC returns 15 starters, UCLA 14. The
Bruins, however, will be . . . handicapped . . . because of their
lack of an experienced quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   __ The weekend of Aug. 28-29 is shaping up to be a sofa spud's
dream.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, you've got the Pigskin Classic, featuring Arizona
against Penn State. On Sunday, it's Miami vs. Ohio State in the
Kickoff Classic.
</P>
<P>
   __ New L.A. definition for the NFL: No Financial Leverage.
</P>
<P>
   __ If you haven't seen ESPN magazine's cover, let me just say
this, as a bride, Ricky Williams makes an awfully good-looking
running back.
</P>
<P>
   __ Looking ahead, way ahead, to 2004, if Barry Sanders stays
retired, Canton is scheduled for one of the best Hall of Fame
classes ever. The class will include John Elway, Reggie White and
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   __ Look-alikes: Richie Phillips, head of the major- league
umpires union, and the Michelin man.
</P>
<P>
   __ If you are keeping score at home, the New York Mets, who are
threatening to end the Atlanta Braves' reign in the NL East, are
being led by: a hot-hitting catcher who's a former Dodger (Mike
Piazza); a speedy center fielder who's a former Dodger (Roger
Cedeno), and a wily old pitcher, who just happens to be a former
Dodger (Orel Hershiser).
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but aren't those three of the Dodgers' most glaring
weaknesses this year?
</P>
<P>
   __ Coincidence or not? Friday's Philadelphia Phillies at Atlanta
Braves game was delayed by a power outage. That phrase _ power
outage _ has been used a lot lately around Turner Field after
catcher Javy Lopez joined first baseman Andres Galarraga on the
sidelines for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   __ We've seen the future of baseball jerseys and the future
looks tacky.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, for some reason, thought ``Turn Ahead the Clock'' _
what uniforms would look like in 2021 _ would be a great promotion.
Unexplained black stripes, vertical lettering, oversized logos. Who
designed these things, Cyndi Lauper?
</P>
<P>
   The reason throwback promos work _ and this one doesn't _ is the
old jerseys are classically cool, much like a '67 Mustang or a '57
T-bird are cool. Turn ahead the clock, jerseys are as cool as a
Chrysler K car.
</P>
<P>
   They were so bad, it made the old Chicago White Sox unis from
the '70s _ remember the big collars, V-necks and shorts? _ seem
darn-right fashionable. Here's hoping this novelty doesn't catch
on.
</P>
<P>
   __ It should be noted eight teams _ the Yankees, Cubs, Toronto,
Texas, Montreal, Houston, Cincinnati and, thankfully, the Dodgers _
refused to participate in the Turn Ahead the Clock promotion.
</P>
<P>
   __ While we're talking fashion, what's up with all those Dodgers
caps in funky colors? I've seen UCLA-blue hats and black hats and
old Tampa Bay Buccaneers orange hats all emblazoned with LA on
them. THESE ARE NOT THE DODGERS COLORS. DODGERS HATS ARE BLUE.
</P>
<P>
   Got it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
