<SLUG> BC-GEN-YESTER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YESTERDAY IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the year 2000 approaches, here's a look at some
of the interesting anniversaries that will occur this week in Los
Angeles sports history (followed by the ranking of the event from
the book ``Unforgettable: The 100 Greatest Moments in Los Angeles
Sports History'' in parenthesis, where applicable):
</P>
<P>
   __ Aug. 3, 1959: For the first time, a second major-league
All-Star Game is held in the same season. At the Coliseum, the AL
wins 5-3 on a single by the Chicago White Sox's Nellie Fox.
</P>
<P>
   __ Aug. 3, 1984: At UCLA's Pauley Pavilion, 16-year-old Mary Lou
Retton scores a perfect 10 on the vault to win the all-around gold
medal in women's gymnastics at the Olympics. (58).
</P>
<P>
   __ Aug. 3, 1997: Former Dodgers manager Tommy Lasorda is
inducted into baseball's Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   __ Aug. 4, 1932: After winning the gold medal in the javelin on
the first day of competition, 21-year-old Babe Didrikson breaks the
world record in the 80-meter hurdles (11.7 seconds). Three days
later, she wins the silver in the high jump to finish off an
achievement that might never be duplicated _ winning Olympic medals
in the same games in running, jumping and throwing events. Women
were at that time only allowed to compete in three events. (60).
</P>
<P>
   __ Aug. 4, 1985: Angels future Hall of Famer Rod Carew becomes
the 16th player to collect his 3,000th career hit. It's an
opposite-field single off his old team, Minnesota, and pitcher
Frank Viola in the third inning. (99)
</P>
<P>
   __ Aug. 5, 1992: Taft High grad Quincy Watts establishes an
Olympic record in the 400 meters with a 43.50 clocking in
Barcelona, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   __ Aug. 5, 1984: In the first women's marathon in Olympic
history, American Joan Benoit crosses the finish line alone at the
Coliseum, outlasting favorites Grete Waitz and Ingrid Kristiansen
of Norway. Benoit records the third-fastest women's time in history
in 2:24.52. (89).
</P>
<P>
   __ Aug 5. 1979: In an 8-1 win over San Francisco, Dodgers
starter Don Sutton becomes the team's all-time strikeout leader
with 2,487.
</P>
<P>
   __ Aug. 5, 1969: Pittsburgh's Willie Stargell hits a ball
completely out of Dodger Stadium _ an estimated 506 feet over the
right-field pavilion off the Dodgers' Alan Foster. Stargell will do
it again four years later.
</P>
<P>
   __ Aug. 7, 1972: The Dodgers' Sandy Koufax is inducted into the
Hall of Fame at age 32, the youngest ever.
</P>
<P>
   __ Birthdays: Tuesday: Former Kings great Marcel Dionne (48) and
Chicago Cubs reliever (and Burbank product) Rod Beck (31).
Thursday: Former UCLA Heisman Trophy-winning quarterback Gary Beban
(53) and former Rams quarterback Roman Gabriel (59). Friday: Former
Dodgers and Angels pitcher Andy Messersmith (54). Sunday: Former
Dodgers slugger Frank Howard (63) and former star swimmer, actress
(``Take Me Out To The Ballgame'') and L.A. native Esther Williams
(76). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
