</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BURNS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEN BURNS TURNS HIS DOCUMENTARY SKILLS TO TWO NOTABLE WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eat your veggies! That was the unmistakable tone of a PBS
luncheon featuring turnips, squash, beets and Ken Burns' latest
historical documentary, ``Not for Ourselves Alone: The Story of
Elizabeth Cady Stanton &AMP; Susan B. Anthony.''
</P>
<P>
   With the finger-wagging zeal of a televangelist, Burns told TV
critics Saturday that Stanton and Anthony, pioneers of the women's
movement, are the two most important females in the American
experience, but most Americans know nothing about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are responsible for the largest social transformation in
American history,'' Burns said. ``I am outraged that this history
has been hidden from us, has been so long neglected. Not just on
our television screens, but in our history books.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns and co-producer Paul Barnes hope to rectify that Nov. 7
and 8 with their two-part documentary, the fourth in a five-part
series that has already profiled Thomas Jefferson, Lewis and Clark
and Frank Lloyd Wright. The fifth will be about Mark Twain.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said the Stanton/Anthony saga, rife with drama and
inspirational commitment to a cause, should be one of ``the
hallelujah stories'' taught in classrooms around the country.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't, Burns said, simply because ``men have written the
histories.''
</P>
<P>
   _Burns' brother Ric, probably best known for his 1992
documentary, ``The Donner Party,'' is on PBS' fall schedule with
``New York: A Documentary Film.'' Ten hours of the 12-hour project
will air Nov. 14-18, ending with the construction of the Empire
State Building. The final installment, to air sometime next spring,
will look at New York in the first year of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York's been kind of inventing the future for itself and
America for about 200 years now,'' Ric Burns said, ``and the space
that we've created for ourselves next year is to finish the story,
bring it down to the present and begin to look, at least
symbolically, at what the future is.''
</P>
<P>
   _Dick Wolf, producer of ``Law &AMP; Order'' and its new spinoff
series, ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit,'' is upset. He says
the new series, a police drama focusing on the aftermath of
particularly heinous sex crimes, is a 10 o'clock show, but NBC has
it penciled in on Mondays at 9, which is 8 p.m. for folks in the
Central time zone.
</P>
<P>
   Like its sire, ``Special Victims Unit'' is not violent. The
crime has already been committed when the show begins. Wolf said it
deals with the effect of violence on the victims, the families and
the investigators. Still, he says it's ``a mature show with mature
stories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The network knows how I feel about this'' said Wolf, who is
annoyed that the Monday edition of ``Dateline NBC'' has the 10 p.m.
slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have used every argument at my disposal ... and I'm very
surprised that the show has not been moved. I don't think it makes
a damn bit of difference where `Dateline' is. It's on five times a
week.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Ally McBeal'' has spawned much imitation in the
dramatic-comedy genre. One new entry is NBC's ``Cold Feet,'' about
three couples at different stages of the commitment tango. Based on
a British comedy, it has had a rocky development. Last year, the
plan was to give it a more serious tone, with characters living in
New York. This year's recast pilot episode was more upbeat and set
in Portland. After one more cast change, the producers say it will
now be set in Seattle (and shot in Vancouver, B.C.).
</P>
<P>
   No surprise, really. One of the producers is John J. Sakmar, who
had a hand in the short-lived ``Medicine Ball'' and ``Mr. &AMP; Mrs.
Smith,'' both of which had Seattle settings. Sakmar hopes to do
some shooting in Seattle, and he'd like nothing better than to have
a couple's relationship take a turn for the worse as the Kingdome
implodes in the background.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
