<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1870 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-CHILD-CUSTODY     08-01 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-CHILD-CUSTODY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN COURTS FAVOR GERMAN PARENTS IN CROSS-BORDER CUSTODY CASES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Great Britain)  (mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Didier Supersac and his German wife separated in 1993,
with an agreement that left the children in Supersac's custody in
France. With its legal protection, he thought, he sent their
4-year-old son, Maxime, and their 7-year-old daughter, Jeannette,
off to Augsburg to visit their mother in Germany that summer, and
then went off himself on a short vacation trip to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   When Supersac got back home, near Nantes, he found a letter in
the mailbox from a German court, curtly informing him that his wife
had charged him with mistreatment of the children and decided to
keep them with her.
</P>
<P>
   What followed, he says, has been a nightmare, with courts in
both Germany and France squabbling over jurisdiction and making
decisions that, in effect, allowed his former wife to kidnap their
daughter, now 13 1/2 years old, permanently to Germany after the
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk _ especially in Germany, Europe's biggest power
_ of a new Europe in which borders and even cultural divisions are
increasingly irrelevant, German courts often seem to side with the
German parent in contested cases of child custody, says Supersac
and others in situations like his.
</P>
<P>
   Even protests from President Jacques Chirac to the Germans, and
the considerable publicity generated by a Frenchwoman who is now
the wife of Britain's ambassador to Washington and has been unable
to see her half-German sons for five years, have failed to sway
German judges unwilling to order actions they considered to be not
in the children's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   Supersac eventually took his son home to France, in 1994, after
a German judge interviewed him and awarded him custody of both of
his children, he said. The court gave him permission to take his
daughter then, too. ``But when we went to school to pick her up,
she wasn't there,'' he said. ``For three years, every attempt I
made to find her ended in failure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The German court didn't even have the ability to enforce its
own decision,'' Supersac added. Other people in situations like his
say that German courts seem afraid of traumatizing children by
enforcing rulings.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he got a decision by the highest court in France
confirming the children's right to spend time with both their
parents. But Jeannette's mother did not send the girl to visit
Supersac last summer, so he did not send Maxime to visit his mother
in Augsburg, either. ``I can't take the risk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   French-German reconciliation over the past half century has
brought many benefits to the 138 million people of the two closest
countries in Europe, including the right to enter into
transnational French-German marriages that were all but unthinkable
until half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   But international law has loopholes big enough to lose a child
in if the courts in one country insist that only that country's
legal standards and procedures can apply in child custody disputes
where one parent resorts to abduction.
</P>
<P>
   And Germany's reputation for siding with the German parent in
cases like this was so bad in France until recently that, of about
100 child-abduction cases involving Germany and known to legal and
French government authorities, not a single one had ended in the
return of the kidnapped child.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Chirac raised the issue with the German
chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, angrily refusing to accept ``the law
of the jungle'' after Germany's highest court stayed a lower court
ruling ordering the return of a 3-year-old girl and her 7-year-old
brother to Cosette Lancelin, their mother in France.
</P>
<P>
   Their German father, Armin Tiemann, had hired five baby
snatchers, who used three cars to force Mrs. Lancelin off a French
back-country road on March 28, 1998, not far from the town where
Marshal Petain met Hitler in 1940 and was forced to pledge
collaboration. The Germans plucked the children out of Mrs.
Lancelin's car and whisked them off to the small north German town
of Kirchdorf where Tiemann is mayor.
</P>
<P>
   But things changed for Mrs. Lancelin this spring when the German
Constitutional Court in Karlsruhe rejected Tiemann's appeal of the
lower court ruling, which had awarded Mrs. Lancelin custody of the
children because she was 20 years younger than her husband and had
been at home with the children full time. They have been with her
in France since April.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have the impression that Tiemann accepts their being in
France,'' Mrs. Lancelin's lawyer, Michel Gendre, said in an
interview. ``But he is supposed to have the children visit him
again for three weeks this summer. We can only hope he will bring
them back.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the German court ruling in the Lancelin case has not
helped another prominent plaintiff in a painful child custody
battle in Germany, Catherine Meyer. Lady Catherine, a French
citizen who is now married to the British ambassador to the United
States, Sir Christopher Meyer, last saw her two sons, Alexander and
Constantin, in 1994 when she sent them off for a summer visit in
Verden, in northern Germany, with their father, Hans-Peter
Volkmann. He is now a doctor there; at the time, their mother was
working and living with the boys in London.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of returning the boys to London at the end of the
summer, as called for in the separation agreement, their father
kept them in Germany and applied to take custody away from their
mother. His action came as a complete surprise to his former wife,
who flew to Germany, fought to keep custody, and at first thought
she had won.
</P>
<P>
   The court in Volkmann's hometown in Verden turned him down, and,
with their mother in the courtroom, ordered him to turn the boys
over to her on the spot. Instead, he disappeared with them and
applied to a higher court, in Celle, for a stay in execution of the
order.
</P>
<P>
   As Lady Catherine recounts her story in her book ``They Are My
Children, Too,'' published this year by Public Affairs in New York,
the Celle court later awarded custody of the children to Volkmann.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Germany, like France, the United States and 52 other countries,
is party to an international agreement against international
parental child abduction called the Hague Convention, which
requires custody disputes to be settled in the country where the
children habitually live, and in this case that was Britain.
</P>
<P>
   But the Celle court ruled that they should stay in Germany with
Volkmann, partly because the boys themselves, then 9 and 7 years
old, had said that was what they wanted and that, as a German
child, Alexander had felt that Britain was ``an alien
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Although my sons were trinational and trilingual, to the Celle
judges they were not French, not English, not European; they were
solely German _ and this overrode everything else,'' Lady Catherine
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   She has not even been able to get visiting rights to see her
children since. ``The only thing I'm asking now is the right to
have my children visit on holidays,'' she said in a telephone
interview from Washington. Alexander is now 14 and Constantin is
12.
</P>
<P>
   Lady Catherine's book has not been published in Germany, where
Volkmann's lawyers have taken German newspapers that have written
about the case to court and made at least one television program,
the ZDF network's women's journal ``Mona Lisa,'' decide not to
pursue it.
</P>
<P>
   Volkmann could not be reached, but one of his lawyers, Manfred
Engelschall, said in a telephone interview from Hamburg, ``It's not
a sensational case. It's a perfectly normal one that Lady Catherine
happened to lose, that's all, and Volkmann will have nothing to say
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   James Rinaman, an American lawyer who said his 4-year-old
daughter was abducted by his wife to Germany before she got a
divorce there, said that he had concluded that German courts
considered Teutonic blood thicker than international law. ``I have
a visitation order but the courts won't enforce it,'' he said.
``They say they won't do it for the good of the child.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Setright, a British lawyer with wide experience in
international parental child-abduction cases, said the underlying
problem was German judges' inexperience with the Hague Convention.
``There's undoubtedly a lack of consistency worldwide in enforcing
the Hague Convention,'' he said in an interview in his chambers in
Lincoln's Inn law courts recently. In Germany, he said, there are
hundreds of judges ``who have no special Hague Convention
experience at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany, where courts and legal systems are split up into 15
separate state jurisdictions, is now changing its family court
decision-making on Hague Convention cases. Soon only 52 superior
courts, instead of 252 family courts, will be empowered to hear
them, German officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Setright and other lawyers say that fewer German judges with
greater familiarity with the accord might be less likely to turn
parental abduction cases into child welfare cases, because of the
Hague Convention's loophole for cases where returning a kidnapped
child to the previous home might carry a ``grave risk'' of
``physical or psychological harm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
