<DOCNO> NYT19990801.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1872 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATLANTA-FUNERALS-COX     08-01 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-FUNERALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Funerals for last week's shooting victims continue
 &HT;    By Jennifer Brett and Anne Cowles
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A mother of two. A father of three.
</P>
<P>
   A devout Hindu. A leader in the Jewish community.
</P>
<P>
   A housewife looking for extra income while her kids were in
college. A grocery store owner whose employees thought of him as
family.
</P>
<P>
   They may never have even met, but Vadewattee Muralidhara and
Allen Tenenbaum met the same terrible fate Thursday in a gunman's
frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   For the loved ones of Muralidhara and Tenenbaum, Sunday was a
day for saying goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 mourners attended a service for Muralidhara at the
Carmichael-Hemperley Funeral Home in Peachtree City, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Her body will be taken to Trinidad Wednesday, with cremation on
Thursday, said Dolford Payne, a friend. According to the Hindu
religion, her soul will be released from her body and remain with
the family for 12 days of mourning. On the 13th day, the soul goes
to its place in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony of this whole thing is that one of the reasons they
left Trinidad is the crime and the violence,'' Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   Muralidhara, 44, had recently returned from a pilgrimage to
India. The devout Hindu had returned with an inner peace, Payne
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gave of herself without expecting anything in return,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At Congregation Or VeShalom in Atlanta, light streamed through
the stained glass windows and onto the sweet, sad faces of
Tenenbaum's daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Megan, 11, and Brittany, 13, stood at the pulpit, just in front
of the chair their father sat in during services, and together read
Psalm 30 before the crowd of 600 who gathered for Tenenbaum's
memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Then Megan read a poem.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad is my shield, my protector and my knight in shining
armor,'' she said. ``When in doubt, ask Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Tenenbaum's widow, Debra, sat in the front row surrounded by
family. She gave each of her girls a kiss on the cheek after their
reading, and the three sat close throughout the service, comforting
one another.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral for Tenenbaum, 48, was Friday. He had served as
president of the synagogue, and several of his friends and
relatives shared their memories during the Sunday service. Some
were lighthearted, like the time he stayed to the end of an Atlanta
Braves game even when the team was down by a very wide margin. Many
more were bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved him as a son,'' said Stan Fox, Tenenbaum's
father-in-law. ``We all have broken hearts. But with faith in God
and inspiration from Allen, we will mend those hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Handmacher Chanin saw Debra Tenenbaum Thursday morning, and
Chanin extended her sympathy for the recent death of Frances
Gaynes, who was Debra Tenenbaum's sister-in-law. Debra Tenenbaum
told Chanin it was the first close relative the children had lost.
</P>
<P>
   At 11 p.m. that night, as Chanin, her husband and children were
watching the movie ``Pleasantville,'' the phone rang. The bearer of
the bad news, she said, was Scott Galanti, whose family is related
by marriage to the Tenenbaums, and has endured similar loss.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, cousins Morris Galanti and Isaac Galanti were shot to
death in separate crimes. Morris Galanti was killed during a
robbery at his grocery store. Isaac Galanti was killed during an
ambush while looking at some real estate. He also owned a grocery
store.
</P>
<P>
   Chanin said Allen Tenenbaum's uncle was married to the sister of
Isaac Galanti. Allen Tenenbaum looked up to Isaac Galanti, learning
from him both the grocery business and sensitivity, friends said.
</P>
<P>
   Marlene Capouya, president of the Or VeShalom Sisterhood, spoke
during Allen Tenenbaum's memorial. Sunday morning, while she was
gathering roses from her garden, she was still contemplating why
God would take a man in the prime of his life. Then, looking at the
bouquet she had arranged, she realized she had left the rose buds
that were not yet opened. She had also left the roses that had
begun to wilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that God must be a gardener too, for he will always
have Allen in full bloom,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Brett and Anne Cowles write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
