<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1873 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-COMMUNITY-CO     08-01 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-COMMUNITY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Henry county residents mourn two children
 &HT;    By Ralph Ellis
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jerry Martin, director of Scouting for The Rock
Baptist Church in Rex, Ga.,
</P>
<P>
   wept at the pulpit Sunday as he remembered Matthew Barton, 11, a
tenderfoot in the church-sponsored Troop 297.
</P>
<P>
   ''Scouting is like a family,'' Martin said. ''When you lose one,
it's like losing one of your own children.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said some members of the troop will attend Matthew's
funeral in their Scout uniforms today and will perform a flag
ceremony. He said counselors will attend Tuesday night's regular
Scout meeting at the church.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll meet together, cry together, seek God's help in getting
through this,'' Martin said in an interview after the church
service. ''We'll try to explain that it's an isolated incident.
It's not something that should bring fear to the rest of their
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bartons were not members of the church, but Matthew joined
the Scout troop earlier this year after graduating from a Cub Scout
pack, Martin said. Matt quickly earned tenderfoot rank. He attended
camp with the troop and earned several merit badges, which were
presented at a recent ceremony, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Barton was a member of the troop committee, which was open to
all parents of Scouts, but he did not take a leadership role in the
troop, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was just a John Doe parent,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin spoke to the church congregation at the end of the Sunday
service. The minister, Ronny Spillers, touched on the killings
during his sermon. He said members of the congregation should start
reaching out and really communicate with other people, not just
wave and say hello.
</P>
<P>
   ''I pray something good and redemptive will happen because of
this tragedy,'' Spillers said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Bristol Green apartments on Rock Quarry Road in
Stockbridge, where Mark Barton's wife, son and daughter were found
dead Thursday, things seemed to be getting back to normal. Gone
were the television trucks and swarms of reporters and
investigators. One Henry County police car was parked outside the
apartment complex office early in the afternoon. The yellow crime
scene tape was removed from the entrance to the Bartons'
second-floor apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Piled in front of the apartment door were half a dozen flowers,
mostly single roses wrapped in plastic. One note said: ''May you
rest in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   One resident of a nearby building, Brian Guild, said the
killings had changed him, though he didn't know any of the Bartons
personally.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't trust anybody now,'' Guild said. ''You cannot trust
your neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   Leng Tep, part owner of a convenience store near the entrance to
the apartment complex, said his business slowed down on Sunday,
mainly because the reporters had gone home. Television crews from
as far away as Germany and Japan had shopped at his store in the
last few days. Some even parked their trucks in the lot and slept
there overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now it's more like before,'' Tep said.
</P>
<P>
   Down Rock Quarry Road, Manoj Pendit ran the cash register behind
the counter at the Texaco.
</P>
<P>
   He said a wave of fear swept over his customers on Thursday as
soon as they heard about the killings. Customers started getting
change to use the pay phones. They called home to check on their
children.
</P>
<P>
   But the most unsettling thing, Pendit said, was hearing children
in the convenience store talk to their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of he kids were asking, 'If something happens to Daddy,
will he do that to me?' '' Pendit said, shaking his head. ''My own
daughter asked me the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pendit said he told his 9-year-old daughter that she was safe.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Ellis writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
