<SLUG> BC-GLF-HARTFORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER'S ADVICE HELPS GEIBERGER WIN HARTFORD OPEN BY 3 SHOTS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROMWELL, Conn. _ Brent Geiberger's claim to fame has always
been his father, Al, the first player to break 60 in a PGA
tournament when he shot 59 at the Danny Thomas Memphis Classic in
1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shoot 59 every time I go out and play,'' said the
31-year-old Brent, whose best finishes in three years on the PGA
Tour before this weekend were a pair of second places. ``But I
always have at least a couple of holes to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4-inch Geiberger, whose smooth swing and lean build
make him resemble his father, established a mark of his own Sunday
at the Canon Greater Hartford Open, shooting a three-under-par 67
at the TPC at River Highlands to finish at 262, for 18 under par
and a tournament record. He finished three strokes ahead of Skip
Kendall for his first victory as a professional and shattered the
previous low of 266 recorded last year by Olin Browne, Stewart Cink
and Larry Mize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to calling my father,'' said Geiberger,
who started to play golf at the age of 5. ``He gave me some good
advice on the phone yesterday when he told me to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Geiberger, who finished at five-under 211 Sunday in the
Senior Tour's Novell Utah Showdown, learned of Brent's victory as
he stood at the seventh tee. ``I went down the fairway feeling like
I had won the tournament,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Geiberger started the day with a three-stroke lead after
rounds of 66-63-66, and he increased the lead to as many as seven
strokes. But a double-bogey at the par-4 17th and a bogey at No. 18
reduced his margin of victory over Kendall, who shot a 66 Sunday.
Another stroke back were Mark Calcavecchia, Ted Tryba and Justin
Leonard. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
