<DOCNO> NYT19990801.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1875 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-TRADEFOLO-     08-01 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-TRADEFOLO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves welcome reinforcements
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It wasn't the blockbuster move some might have hoped
for, but acquiring pitcher Terry Mulholland and
infielder-outfielder Jose Hernandez from the Cubs appears to be
popular within the Braves organization.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, which gave up pitcher Micah Bowie, minor-league pitcher
Ruben Quevedo and a minor-league player to be named in a deal made
at the midnight Saturday deadline, had some offensive voids to fill
after the season-ending injury to Javy Lopez, plus the season-long
loss of Andres Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves say this move improves their depth with veteran
versatile players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a good trade,'' Chipper Jones said. ``Everybody
had heard Hernandez's name but nobody really thought about
Mulholland. Terry is going to give us a lot of flexibility. He can
be a starter, long reliever, a specialist, getting out a lefty.
Jose . . .plays every day. He's got speed. He's got power.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine said: ``It's easy to be disappointed because
everybody looks for a blockbuster deal around the deadline. To be
honest, I don't think many of us expected them to do anything. We
were able to add two quality guys who will help us win, which is
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuerholz had gone after some bigger bats _ Fred McGriff and
Will Clark _ but both would have come at too high a cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did all we could do,'' Schuerholz said. ``We helped to fill
the void back up some. We're a stronger team and a deeper team with
these two guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland, who was 6-6 with a 5.15 ERA for the Cubs, has made
16 starts and 10 relief appearances. The Braves can start him if
John Smoltz's elbow remains troublesome or if patience wears thin
with rookie Bruce Chen.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have some options with Hernandez on defense, but
priority No. 1 is getting him at the top of the order. Hernandez
hit .272 with 15 home runs and 43 RBI in 99 games for the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hernandez is a good player and Terry fits exactly what we were
looking for,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``If you ask people around
baseball who one of the best competitors is, his name is going to
pop up.''
</P>
<P>
   To make room for Hernandez on the roster, the Braves have an
interesting decision to make and it will likely come down to
releasing either Ozzie Guillen or Otis Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   In the simplest terms, the arrival of Hernandez means the Braves
have three shortstops along with Guillen and Walt Weiss. Guillen,
who's backed up Weiss, can play short, third or second, but so can
Hernandez. Guillen has outhit Nixon .234 to .188 and held his own
starting in place of the injured Weiss. But Schuerholz has stressed
how Hernandez could be the Braves everyday shortstop if Weiss'
quadriceps flares up again.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon hasn't been hitting this season and lost his attempt at
being an everyday left-fielder. But he is still a capable defensive
outfielder Cox can use late in games and he gives the Braves an
element Guillen doesn't, a consistent base-stealing threat.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon is still leading the Braves with 18 stolen bases and is
their best option as a pinch runner. Guillen's best chance at
sticking around appears to be if the Braves choose to use Hernandez
in left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby and I are still talking about it,'' Schuerholz said.
``We feel like Jose Hernandez is going to make us stronger than
whomever won't be on the roster.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez and Mulholland aren't joining the team until they
arrive in Pittsburgh on Tuesday. The Braves plan to take until then
to make the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland is in the first of a two-year, $5.9 million deal. He
is scheduled to make $2.6 million next season.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, 30, previously had stated a desire to become a free
agent after this season and the conclusion of a one-year, $2.4
million contract. The Cubs had made a ``significant'' offer
covering three years to keep him. Cubs general manager Ed Lynch
made a last-ditch offer after Saturday's game. He declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got into an argument with my wife when I got home after
yesterday's game,'' Hernandez told reporters in Chicago. ``I didn't
know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And now?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to move along,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland, 36, was none too happy to be moving along. He's
played for five teams in seven years, and bought moving boxes
earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it was a surprise,'' he said. ``I really believed
that after last year, we'd do bigger and better things. I still
believe these guys are capable of playing well. It kind of twists
in my gut that I'm not a part of it. On the plus side, I'll be with
Atlanta. It's a mixed emotion thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
