<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN HORN ULTIMATUM MET FOR 6-YEAR CONTRACT EXTENSION WORTH $73
MILLION
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In January, Keith Van Horn watched the Nets engage in posturing
in contract negotiations with Jayson Williams. In the regular
season, he saw his close friend Kerry Kittles struggle with the
pressure of playing in a contract year.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn vowed that he would not stand for such treatment when
it was his turn to get a new contract. So in June, Van Horn, the
Nets' leading scorer, issued an ultimatum: the Nets would have
seven days from Aug. 1, the first day teams were allowed to declare
player signings, to offer him the maximum amount of money possible.
</P>
<P>
   One day was enough. The Nets announced Sunday that they would
sign Van Horn to a six-year contract extension worth approximately
$73 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an automatic, frankly,'' said John Nash, the Nets'
general manager. ``We said it from the beginning. There was no
mystery about the fact that Keith is one of our more important
players, so from the first opportunity that we had to talk with him
and his representatives, it was made clear that we wanted to do
everything in our power to retain his services.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets also reached an agreement with Jamie Feick. The
free-agent forward, who averaged 10.3 rebounds in 28 games last
season, will receive a five-year deal believed to be worth $11
million. He turned down a similar offer from the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Feick and Van Horn, who is in Switzerland doing promotional work
for Nike, will sign later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get Keith signed was our No. 1 priority and to get Jamie
was No. 2,'' Nash said. ``Keith obviously is one of the league's
premier young players and Jamie is an emerging player.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn will be paid $3.4 million this season, with the
extension kicking in the next season. In Van Horn, Stephon Marbury,
Kittles and Williams, the Nets have a foursome that could make them
championship contenders. The group is under contract through at
least the 2004-2005 season.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old Van Horn, who averaged 21.8 points and 8.5
rebounds last season, and the 22-year-old Marbury, the dynamic
point guard from Brooklyn, are two of the most exciting performers
in the league and, in the eyes of many, have the ability to become
this generation's signature backcourt-frontcourt combination, its
John Stockton and Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're two of the up-and-coming players who will be
featured probably not only by the Nets in our marketing campaign
but also by the NBA,'' Nash said.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Feick, 25, gives the Nets 11 players under
contract and leaves them with only one available spot on the active
roster. They hope to fill it with Scott Burrell, the small forward
who played for them last season. The Nets have offered Burrell a
one-year deal worth $1 million, but he will probably wait to see
what he can command on the open market before making a decision.
San Antonio, Milwaukee and Cleveland have expressed interest in
him.
</P>
<P>
   If Burrell goes elsewhere, the Nets will try to sign an
experienced small forward who would contribute in the locker room
and on the floor. Among those available are Chucky Brown, Terry
Cummings and Chuck Person. Nash also mentioned the possibility of
trading for a small forward, and either of the team's backup point
guards, Eric Murdock or Elliot Perry, could be used in such a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Because the health of center Rony Seikaly remains a concern, the
Nets are interested in Gheorghe Muresan. The 7-foot-7-inch Romanian
has worked out at the Nets' Champion Center facility all summer and
played last Saturday at the Shaw Pro Summer League in Boston. In 16
minutes against the Knicks, Muresan had 9 points and 6 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really coming along quickly now,'' Nash said. ``We'll
monitor his progress over the month of August and determine whether
or not we want to extend a contract to him.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Nets sign Muresan, it will be for a one-year deal worth
$537,500.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
