<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS HAVE URGENT MISSION TO MOLD THEIR YOUNG GUARDS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Only minutes after the Jets' quintet of
untested guards heard their first encouraging words from Coach Bill
Parcells this training camp, they learned that he had gone out
Sunday and signed a veteran who has started at right guard since
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Beckles, a free agent who had been with the Philadelphia
Eagles the last two years after beginning his career with the Tampa
Bay Buccaneers, became the newest Jet and immediately said he
expected to start.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast. He worked out with the third unit Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll shape up the line,'' Parcells said. ``This is no cinch
deal here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Parcells does finally have a guard who has played the
position for pay. There had been five candidates for the two spots,
including three rookie draft choices.
</P>
<P>
   As problematic as that situation was, it became more serious on
Saturday when Erik Norgard, a veteran who had played guard but was
backing up at center, decided to quit. He had been Parcells' one
fallback on the team if none of the untested players could make it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Parcells was sounding upbeat about the guard position
after three days of training camp. He is impressed with the guards'
athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells reiterated Sunday that the club is deeper in some areas
than it was last season. But he understands his situation at guard
and asked rhetorically, ``What am I supposed to do, go out to the
guard tree and pull one down?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to force-feed some guys in,'' he said of the
urgency to get the guards in place. The first exhibition game is at
Green Bay in 13 days. Then again, he admitted: ``I don't have a
choice. Hey, we had to draft three guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Those rookies, Randy Thomas, David Loverne and J.P. Machado,
have demonstrated they can block for the run. So have the
carryovers (but inexperienced) Alex Bernstein and Doug Karczewski.
They have not yet demonstrated special abilities in pass
protection.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Muir, the offensive-line coach, as usual, has been
relentless in dogging the players as they struggle in the 90-degree
heat. To Loverne, there was this advice from Muir: ``I knew someone
would screw it up. What are you supposed to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells hounded Thomas by shouting: ``The coach told you
something four times. When are you going to get it?''
</P>
<P>
   Beckles escaped the coaches' wrath, who signed a one-year
$400,000 contract, at least for Sunday. He does have some
credentials, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Beckles is slated for right guard, where he has started 122
games. That creates a tense situation for Bernstein and Thomas, who
had alternated there with the first unit.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said of his chances to start, ``I've always been
confident.'' Thomas, a second-round pick from Mississippi State,
was the first player the Jets drafted in April and was considered
by their staff to be the top guard prospect in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference here is that everyone is quick on the line and
much smarter than college players,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Loverne, who played tackle at San Jose State but is being tried
at left guard, described his chance as ``the opportunity of a
lifetime; maybe one in a million rookies get this chance.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been able to focus on football recently after having
concerns about family in the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have uncles and aunts there,'' he said. ``Both my parents
are from Montenegro. But the family lives on farms and they've been
away from the bombing by NATO. They were able to feed themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   For Karczewski, the Jets' fifth-round draft pick in 1998, ``I'm
feeling a heck of a lot better than I did last year.'' Still, he
said: ``It's tough. No one is set anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Vinny Testaverde said it will be a long process. He
recalls that last season, which began with Glenn Foley as the new
starting quarterback: ``It was tough behind Todd Burger and Matt
O'Dwyer. It took time. Until this is over, it's hard to say how
this will work out.''
</P>
<P>
   There are so many potential offensive linemen in camp that
Parcells has brought in his favorite from his Giants and Patriots
days, William Roberts, to help with the coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I want to do this as a career,'' Roberts said.
``I'll have to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   But he brings a sense of humor to the fray, startling the
players at the beginning of practice, as well as the fans leaning
on the fences, by suddenly bellowing like a rooster.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, it sounds like a wake-up call to the guards.
</P>
</TEXT>
