<SLUG> BC-ARK-STARR-RELIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE ROCK WRESTLES WITH LEGACY OF CLINTON AS INVESTIGATION ENDS 
</HEADLINE>
 (rk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ For many in this state, the mood these days
is like the familiar exhale of relief that follows the destructive
storms of summer.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, has declared
the Arkansas phase of his investigation over. He has finished with
five years of intense scrutiny of hundreds of people, many of them
prominent citizens and associates of President Clinton and Hillary
Rodham Clinton, but also dozens of small merchants and peripheral
figures embittered by the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all weary like at the end of a war,'' said Max Brantley,
editor of The Arkansas Times, a weekly newspaper that followed the
Starr investigation with a distinctly local perspective of feeling
unfairly assailed and looked down upon by outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   While the after-effects of the investigation are still being
sorted out, it is clear that no one here could have predicted or
even imagined the raucous experience that was in store for the city
and state when Bill Clinton stood on a platform in front of the Old
State House in downtown Little Rock on election night 1992 to
celebrate his victory with thousands of local supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Many in Arkansas thought at the time that governor Clinton's
victory was the beginning of redemption for a small state striving
to better its reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I distinctly remember thinking that this was finally going to
wipe away the stain left by Faubus,'' said one of the state's most
distinguished citizens, a man who said he preferred to wear his
disappointment privately because he was still fond of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Orval E. Faubus tried in 1957 to prevent nine black
children from integrating Central High School, requiring President
Dwight Eisenhower to call out the National Guard. If the name
``Little Rock'' was no longer a symbol of that painful era, older
Arkansans felt their state had not yet overcome its backward image.
</P>
<P>
   Some saw Clinton's ascendancy as the chance for the state to
capture a new image; others saw it as a ticket for new
opportunities in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It has not quite worked out that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we in Arkansas came out of this just looking
foolish,'' said Lesa Baker, a housewife interviewed recently on
Main Street in Benton, the Saline County seat. Lots of people were
dragged into the investigation, she said, ``and I can't think of
much good that came along to balance it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people, including Ms. Baker, believe that Clinton must bear
some responsibility, while others say that the president has
largely been a victim of a vindictive prosecutor. But it seems that
no one, not even Clinton's detractors, has any kind words for
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Completely excessive,'' Ms. Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Two women getting their daily exercise by speed-walking through
the McCain shopping mall in North Little Rock agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Reed, a retired bookkeeper from nearby Sherwood, said that
Starr ``was on a witch hunt from the very beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna Williams of Little Rock, her exercise companion, said
Starr was ``on the edge of being evil. And he smiled the whole
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the July 25 issue of The Arkansas Times, an editorial
objected to a list of 10 ``very well-mannered'' public people,
including Starr, compiled by the National League of Junior
Cotillions. The Cotillion ladies got it wrong, the newspaper said.
The soft-spoken Starr was really like Heinrich Himmler, the Nazi
head of the Gestapo and the SS.
</P>
<P>
   The feelings about the Clintons may be less intense, but they
are more complex.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's run for the Senate from New York has caused
tender feelings in Arkansas, where people generally liked her even
as they suspected that she endured her time here more than she
enjoyed it. Many people said in interviews that they had never
expected her to run for office from Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure she ever really liked Arkansas,'' said Garrick
Feldman, a printing plant owner and the publisher of the Leader
newspapers in northern Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The ambivalence about Clinton was evident in the debate this
week in Little Rock over changing the name of a long stretch of
Markham Street to President Clinton Avenue. The city board of
directors voted for the change in 1997 _ before the Monica Lewinsky
scandal broke.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-block route passes several sites connected in the public
mind to Clinton, including the Old State House, the Greek revival
antebellum building that was the site of the 1992 election night
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Now a museum, the Old State House is flanked on one side by the
Excelsior Hotel. According to Paula Jones, that is where Clinton,
when he was governor, had her summoned to his room and made a crude
sexual proposition. Clinton settled Ms. Jones' lawsuit last year by
paying her $850,000 but did not admit doing anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the museum sits the Doubletree, another
hotel linked to an accusation against Clinton. According to Juanita
Broaddrick, that hotel, then the Camelot, is where Clinton forced
her to have sexual relations with him when he was state attorney
general, a charge he has denied.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in Little Rock refer to the hotels smirkingly as the
``Paula Jones Hotel'' and the ``Juanita Broaddrick Hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   Complaints about the plan to rename the street in honor of
Clinton resulted in a meeting of the city board on July 27 to
reconsider its decision.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the packed hearing room at City Hall, a woman forcefully
told the audience that the city should honor Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many people from Arkansas have been elected president?''
she asked. ``Just one!''
</P>
<P>
   Another woman in the crowd was escorted out by the police after
she shouted back: ``He's also the only one to have been
impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   A man held up a sign: ``Don't even name a toilet after him.''
</P>
<P>
   The board voted 8-4 to accept a compromise in which only about
six blocks at the east end of the street would be renamed President
Clinton Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That is where supporters of Clinton, who are trying to raise
more than $100 million from private donors, plan to construct the
President Clinton Library and Museum. The 27-acre site, alongside
the Arkansas River, will house the library, the repository of
Clinton's presidential papers, a museum about him and a Clinton
Center, which will probably be devoted to improving race relations,
said Skip Rutherford, a longtime supporter and friend of Clinton's
who is overseeing its development.
</P>
<P>
   It will also include a furnished apartment for the Clintons to
use when they are in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford said the Clinton project would complement a
neighborhood that was experiencing a commercial renaissance, with
new restaurants, an old-time market, a children's museum and a
planned office tower.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Valentine, a veteran American League baseball umpire who is
now the general manager of the Arkansas Travelers, a minor league
farm team of the St. Louis Cardinals based in west Little Rock,
said it was well to remember that the tribulations of the Clintons
and Starr concerned only a small segment of the state's population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regular folks, you know the down-the-road type of people,
never really paid much attention,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   But at a recent home game of the Travs, as they are called,
people lined up to get autographs from someone who owes her
celebrity to the Clinton presidency. Jones, who recently moved from
California back to Arkansas, to a small home in Cabot, 25 miles
northeast of Little Rock, happily signed score cards proffered by
children and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   And the Clintons' former business partner Susan McDougal has
also returned from California to live in Arkansas. Ms. McDougal
served 18 months in jail while refusing to testify before a grand
jury about the Clintons' real estate dealings. Last April, a Little
Rock jury cleared her of obstructing justice and deadlocked on two
counts of criminal contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDougal's trial illustrated as well as anything the
us-versus-them mind-set about Starr that prevailed in Arkansas.
Some of Little Rock's most elegant and stylish women, who
previously would have little to do with Ms. McDougal, made a point
of helping her buy clothes for the trial and seeing that her hair
was done properly.
</P>
<P>
   One remnant of the Starr investigation is the outpost of the
prosecutor's office on Center View Drive in west Little Rock. It is
still staffed by W. Hickman Ewing, the chief prosecutor for the
Arkansas phase of the investigation, and a handful of others who
are gradually winding down the office's operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
