</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAGUE ACCEPTS RESIGNATION OF UMPIRE WHO SAID HE NEVER RESIGNED
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drew Coble is one of nine umpires whose resignations Gene Budig,
the American League president, accepted last week. The only problem
is Coble said he never resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Budig also accepted Greg Kosc's resignation, but Kosc said he
had rescinded his resignation in the same period when other umpires
withdrew their resignations and saved their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Coble, a crew chief in his 18th year with the league, was
notified in a letter from Budig dated July 26 that he had received
on July 15 a letter of resignation from Coble dated July 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deeply regret,'' Budig wrote, ``that you decided to take
part in this concerted resignation plan instigated by the Major
League Umpires Association. However, you have left me with no
choice but to accept your resignation and to fill the vacancy that
your resignation has created along with the other vacancies that
were created by this mass resignation strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Coble said Sunday he did not sign a resignation letter dated
July 14 and did not attend the meeting in Philadelphia that day at
which more than 50 umpires did sign such letters. Coble said he was
at home in Graham, N.C., with his wife. ``Kim had chemotherapy that
day in the hospital,'' Coble said by telephone from his home.
</P>
<P>
   Coble said he was so involved with his wife's illness that he
was not even aware of the umpires' action until a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   He said he laughed when he received Budig's letter, but his
unemployment, scheduled to begin Sept. 2, the date of resignation
in the umpires' letters, is no laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough for them to accept a resignation they never
got,'' he said. ``The letter said my letter was dated July 14. I
didn't even know what went down until the 17th of July.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he did learn of the step his colleagues had taken to try to
induce baseball officials to begin negotiations for a new labor
agreement, Coble said, he decided to join them. ``I signed a letter
July 22 and sent it to Richie,'' he said, referring to Richie
Phillips, the umpires' lawyer and labor leader. ``To my knowledge
Richie never sent it to the league office.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips would not confirm that Coble had sent him a letter of
resignation, but whatever it was, Phillips added, ``I did not
forward to the league office.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, however, issued a news release July 22 saying that
Coble and Ted Hendry of the American League and Greg Bonin of the
National had advised the leagues that they were resigning. But both
Hendry and Bonin have retained their jobs, ostensibly because the
league offices never received their letters.
</P>
<P>
   Coble said he had heard from no one in the American League
office. ``They haven't even called to ask how my wife is,'' said
the 51-year-old umpire, who has not worked since July 3. Asked if
he has thought about calling the league, he said, ``I've been
tempted to call Budig, but I'm sure he doesn't have any answers for
me, so I've resisted the urge.''
</P>
<P>
   Budig was not at home Sunday. Phyllis Merhige, the league's
senior vice president, said the league would have no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Kosc's circumstance is a little different. He resigned,
rescinded his resignation and then rescinded his rescission. But
like Coble's letter, Phillips said, Kosc's letter reinstating his
resignation was never sent to the league office even though he,
too, was part of the union's July 22 news release.
</P>
<P>
   Kosc, in his 24th year with the league, was en route home after
umpiring a game in Cleveland Sunday and could not be reached. But
Phillips said Kosc revoked his resignation, just as eight other
umpires did, before the league hired 12 new umpires. Even if he did
change his mind, Phillips said: ``They don't have anything from
him. They went by newspaper accounts apparently.''
</P>
<P>
   When lawyers had conference calls last Tuesday about the federal
lawsuit the union filed against the leagues, Phillips said, he
raised the Coble-Kosc issue with Judge Edmund Ludwig of United
States District Court in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court made serious inquiry into the Coble and Kosc
situations,'' and the leagues had no response, Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Coble related one more element of his case. He said he had
received calls two days apart from two AL umpires who are
considered the leaders of the nonresigning faction.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Hirschbeck called and said his group was going with
baseball and if I went with them, I'd be `taken care of,''' Coble
said. ``Then Joe Brinkman called and said he talked to higher-ups
and explained what was going on.'' He meant with his wife's medical
condition. ``He said they agreed to make me an exception `if I
would go over to their side,''' Coble said. ``But he said I would
have to do it by that night.''
</P>
<P>
   But that same day the league sent notices to nine umpires
accepting their resignations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I received the letter the next day,'' Coble said. ``They
accepted a resignation that was never sent.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
