<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SUSPECT-TALKS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTIST ACCUSED OF LEAKING NUCLEAR SECRETS SAYS HE'S INNOCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaking publicly in his own defense for the first
time, Wen Ho Lee, the scientist dismissed from his job after
security breaches at Los Alamos National Laboratory, said on
television Sunday that he was innocent and that he had not divulged
nuclear secrets to China or to ``any unauthorized person.''
</P>
<P>
   On the CBS News program ``60 Minutes,'' Lee confirmed that he
had transferred data from classified to unclassified computer
systems at Los Alamos but said he had done so to protect the
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do that routinely,'' he said, and he asserted that ``it's a
very common practice.'' Legal papers for Lee say he wanted to
create a backup copy of the information, The Los Angeles Times
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said on the ``60 Minutes''
program that it was ``wrong and improper to download nuclear
weapons information'' from the classified system. ``This is
something that we are not going to tolerate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said Lee had ``massively violated our security
procedures'' by having ``improper contact with Chinese officials,''
by deceiving U.S. officials at Los Alamos and by transferring
nuclear weapons information to unclassified computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Department officials acknowledge that other employees
have sometimes violated computer security procedures, but say the
infractions were on a much smaller scale than Lee's.
</P>
<P>
   On CBS, Lee said: ``The truth is, I'm innocent. I have not done
anything wrong with _ what they try to accuse me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a naturalized citizen who was born in Taiwan, said he had
become a convenient scapegoat for U.S. investigators, in part
because he was the only Asian American working in the weapons
design group, known as the ``X division'' of the laboratory, in New
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why I was singled out for this particular
issue,'' Lee said. ``I still don't understand why. I know that many
people do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Richardson insisted: ``There was no effort to scapegoat this
man. We have tried to protect his legal status, his reputation, as
much as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is considering whether to prosecute Lee.
Federal authorities say it is unlikely that he will ever face
criminal charges of espionage, but officials say they are also
weighing other charges, related to the mishandling of classified
information.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lawyers for Lee have submitted legal briefs to the Justice
Department in a last-ditch effort to head off an indictment, The
Los Angeles Times reported. Arguments in those papers are similar
to the arguments Lee made on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The briefs contend that Lee transferred information from
classified to unclassified computers to protect it in the event of
a computer crash, the newspaper said. Even in his ``unclassified
machines,'' Lee said, the data were protected with three passwords.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three passwords,'' Lee said. ``It's almost impossible for
anybody to break in. You know, sometimes I even had a hard time to
break in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In summary, Lee said: ``The reason I downloaded the computer
code from a classified machine to an unclassified machine is part
of my job. To protect my code, to protect my file. I do that
routinely.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, after an extensive investigation, a congressional panel
said China had used nuclear secrets stolen from U.S. laboratories
to develop advanced miniature warheads and a mobile ballistic
missile. Counterintelligence officials have said they suspect that
China obtained the data in the mid-1980s, but U.S. authorities did
not realize that the information had been stolen until 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Asked on CBS if he had ever passed nuclear secrets to China,
Lee, a computer scientist, said, ``No, I never have done that, and
I have no intention of doing that at all.'' In addition, Lee said
he had never given secrets to ``any unauthorized person.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said he had been maligned. ``I devote the best time of my
life to this country, to make the country stronger, particularly in
the nuclear weapon area,'' Lee said. ``And I try to make the
country stronger, so we can protect the American people. But
suddenly, they told me I'm a traitor. And I'm just totally _ I
mean, I'm, I'm just _ don't understand this.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, investigators found that Lee had downloaded thousands
of secret codes used in the design of the most sophisticated U.S.
nuclear weapons, as well as the records of hundreds of weapons
tests.
</P>
<P>
   On CBS, Lee confirmed that he had had access to extremely
sensitive information. ``I know the top secret of nuclear weapon
very well, yes,'' he said. ``I'm one of the important people in our
division.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee's lawyer, Mark Holscher, could not immediately be reached
for comment and did not return messages left at his office. In May,
Holscher issued a statement denying that his client had spied for
China. In June, the lawyer said Lee had been ``unfairly injected
into a politically charged debate over America-China relations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
