<HEADLINE>
AMSTED AGREES TO BUY VARLEN, A SMALLER RIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After raising its unsolicited offer, Amsted Industries, which
makes products for the rail, truck and auto components industries,
said Sunday that it would acquire the Varlen Corp. for $740 million
in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Amsted, based in Chicago, will also assume $50 million of
Varlen's debt. Varlen, which is based in Naperville, Ill., makes
products and components for the transportation industries.
</P>
<P>
   Amsted said the boards of both companies had approved the
acquisition, which values Varlen at about $42 a share, or about 62
percent above the share price of Varlen on May 17, the day before
Amsted began its hostile takeover attempt.
</P>
<P>
   In trading on the Nasdaq market on Friday, shares of Varlen were
unchanged at $37.875 on light volume. Amsted is a privately held,
employee-owned company.
</P>
<P>
   Varlen was initially hesitant to reach a deal with Amsted but
was apparently swayed in recent weeks after Amsted raised its bid
from the $35 a share it originally offered.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have maneuvered warily around each other amid
reports that a competitor might emerge to counter Amsted's bid for
Varlen. But the companies decided to put aside their differences
and said in a statement Sunday that the merger would create a
``worldwide transportation equipment leader.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For our employees, this offers opportunities in an
organization which will have greater scale and resources,'' said
Raymond A. Jean, Varlen's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Amsted had revenue of about $1.3 billion last year, about twice
as much as Varlen, which reported sales of $647 million in 1998. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
