</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA SEIZES TAIWAN SHIP, ACCUSING CREW OF SMUGGLING
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Chinese authorities seized a Taiwan freighter over the
weekend near a Taiwan military post on Matsu, a heavily fortified
island under Taiwan control.
</P>
<P>
   During a tense diplomatic tussle between China and Taiwan, the
incident provoked concern in Taiwan that China might have acted
improperly, using the ship as a pretext to aggravate an already
strained situation.
</P>
<P>
   A Chinese coast guard vessel approached the ship on Saturday,
and four armed policemen boarded and forced it and its 10 Taiwan
crew members into a port on mainland China, accusing the crew of
trying to smuggle goods to China.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Taiwan officials countered by saying that the ship
had been conducting a normal operation of carrying provisions for
Taiwan soldiers posted on Matsu, a few miles from China's coast.
</P>
<P>
   Although only 6,000 civilians live on Matsu, with about an equal
number of soldiers, it remains a sensitive military post for
Taiwan, which military analysts say could be a strategic location
in any military conflict between China and Taiwan. Matsu was the
site of a military battle between Taiwan and China in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incidents like this will not benefit normal exchanges between
the two sides,'' Taiwan's justice minister, Yeh Chin-feng, said in
Taipei, and he urged China to return the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Yeh and other Taiwan officials, apparently careful not to
inflame a delicate situation, refrained from accusing China of
deliberately aggravating the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, according to information gathered by relevant
authorities, I haven't seen any linkage between the seizure and
political motivation,'' said Shi Hwei-yow, vice chairman of
Taiwan's semiofficial Straits Exchange Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's and China's military forces in the region have gone on
alert in recent weeks, after President Lee Teng-hui of Taiwan
asserted on July 9 that Taiwan would only talk with China on the
basis of ``special state-to-state relations,'' abandoning the
diplomatic framework that has kept peace between the two sides for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   China's leaders were outraged by Lee's new stance that China and
Taiwan are effectively separate countries, shedding the previous
framework of ``one China'' in which the two had recognized each
other as different political entities under a single Chinese
nation.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, Defense Minister Chi Haotian accused Lee of going
``further and further down the dangerous road of splitting the
motherland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We sternly warn Lee Teng-hui and the Taiwan authorities not to
underestimate our constancy of purpose,'' Chi said at a reception
to celebrate the Aug. 1 anniversary of the founding of the People's
Liberation Army. ``The Chinese People's Liberation Army is combat
ready, prepared at any moment to defend the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of the motherland and resolutely smash any
plot to split the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tough talk, China has so far shown little
willingness to take military action against Taiwan _ as it did in
1995 and 1996, when China fired several test missiles into the
ocean off the coast of Taiwan, causing alarm over the possibility
of military conflict that was quelled only when the United States
sent two aircraft carriers toward the region as a show of support
for Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   But China has pointedly reminded Taiwan that Beijing has never
renounced the possibility of using force against Taiwan if it
formally declares independence, even though the two have in
practice been separated and independent since China's civil war
ended 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, China's news media have covered several minor
military exercises in Fujian province, across the 100-mile-wide
Taiwan Straits from Taiwan. The relatively small size of the
exercises appeared to reflect an unwillingness to inflame the
situation, while subtly delivering a message that military action
is always possible sometime in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, seizing a Taiwan freighter and accusing it of
smuggling, a common form of trade in the area, may be a way to
tweak Taiwan's authorities without actually confronting them.
</P>
<P>
   Wen Nung-ti, owner of the freighter, told Reuters that the ship,
the Shin Hwa, was carrying provisions, including rice and canned
food, for the military servicemen in Matsu.
</P>
<P>
   Since Taiwan bans direct trade, transportation and communication
with China, smugglers willing to defy the ban ply the waters every
day, and China offers landing visas to Taiwan residents who make
the illicit passage.
</P>
<P>
   Chen Cheng-ching, a legislator from Matsu, was quoted in local
newspapers as saying that he believed the ship may simply have run
afoul of smugglers who pay the Chinese police to keep rivals out of
their areas of operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
