u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-TRADES-NYT     08-01 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TRADES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS AND ATHLETICS MAKE SIGNIFICANT CHANGES WITH TRADES
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine, the New York Mets' manager, never did like
Jason Isringhausen. He was young and sometimes did youthfully
foolish things, like playing softball when he was recovering from a
broken wrist. But the Oakland Athletics like Isringhausen; all they
do is look at his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a great arm for the future in Isringhausen,'' Billy
Beane, the Oakland general manager, said Sunday. It was the day
after the non-waiver trading deadline, and general managers _ those
who made trades in the hours before the deadline, those who tried
but could not complete them and those who sat out the dance _ were
studying the fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen teams were involved in trades on Saturday, some more
than once, making nine deals involving 28 players. It was not a
particularly awesome day for trades, but some teams made
significant changes.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, for example, including the Kenny Rogers deal made a
week earlier, have turned over 20 percent of their roster. The
Athletics have done the same. But Oakland made a most curious
combination of moves. Believing it is a wild-card contender, it
bolstered its starting rotation by adding Kevin Appier and Omar
Olivares after trading Rogers at his request. But the Athletics
traded their closer, Billy Taylor, for Isringhausen and Greg
McMichael.
</P>
<P>
   Beane explained the first part first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bullpen was very good in the first half but has struggled
in the second half,'' he said by telephone from Oakland. ``We
adopted the theory that you use when you strengthen the muscles
around an injured knee to support the knee. We improved our
starting pitching to help the bullpen. If the bullpen needs to get
only six outs instead of 12 or 15, we will improve our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bullpen still needs a closer, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy's done a great job here,'' Beane said of the 37-year-old
Taylor, who spent 14 years in the minor leagues and was a major
league rookie at age 32. ``But at some point, in the very near
future, we were going to have to address the fact that we don't
have a closer for the coming years. Everything we've done we've
tried to address the present and the future.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Beane said, 42-year-old Doug Jones will handle most of
the closing chores. He has been a closer for five other teams, has
had as many as 43 saves in a season and has a career total of 295
saves. He at least knows the territory, even if his ability won't
allow him to cover it well all the time.
</P>
<P>
   But this is where Isringhausen comes in. Beane doesn't want to
say it too loudly, but Isringhausen is the team's instant No. 1
candidate for closer of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he has the ability, but we have to be careful,''
Beane said. ``If you look at the history of closers, those who are
anointed closers before they do it usually fail. Good closers often
just develop into being closers. We're careful not to stamp him as
our closer. But he's got a great arm.''
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 26, Isringhausen, an injury-plagued right-hander,
has time to grow into the role (another general manager said
Oakland very likely will ``sneak'' him into save situations now and
then). Beane acknowledged that trading Taylor, who had 26 saves,
fourth most in the American League, was a risk, but with a $22
million payroll, he said, ``You have to roll the dice.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Mets bolstered their bullpen, which has
been overworked this season, by adding Taylor and Chuck McElroy,
who were quickly put into action Sunday in Chicago and combined for
two shutout innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets also got a new center fielder, Darryl Hamilton, who is
a better, more consistent hitter than the old one, Brian McRae, and
who once played an entire season (1996) without making an error.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves, actually struggling for the first time in
years and working hard to stave off the Mets, acquired a starting
pitcher, Terry Mulholland, and a shortstop, Jose Hernandez, because
they can't be certain about the health of John Smoltz and Walt
Weiss. But they were unable to address the hitting shortage they
have developed with the loss of Javier Lopez, their good-hitting
catcher, for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has an adage that the best trades are sometimes the
ones you do not make, but Sunday there were questions why some
teams didn't make seemingly obvious moves with certain players.
Why, for example, didn't Tampa Bay trade Fred McGriff, or even
Roberto Hernandez, their expensive, sought-after closer? Why did
Baltimore demand so much for Arthur Rhodes, a reliever-in-demand
who will be a free agent in two months? Why didn't Anaheim trade
Chuck Finley to Cleveland or the Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the second part of the last question is that the
Yankees didn't really want Finley; they were more interested in
making it difficult for the Indians to get him, dragging out talks
with the Angels until it was too late for Cleveland to strike.
``The Yankees were a mirage,'' Bill Bavasi, the Angels' general
manager, said from Anaheim. ``We flushed them out Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi provided the answer to the first part of the question,
too. ``We set the bar at a certain level,'' he said, and the
Indians refused to jump that high.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi declined to provide details, but the Angels wanted
Enrique Wilson, the attractive young second baseman, and three
minor league prospects, not necessarily all top-flight ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very realistic, in our opinion, in expecting what to
get back,'' Bavasi said. ``We don't feel we overcharged.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians did, especially with Finley's poor record this
season, and chose not to play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
