<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUN MICROSYSTEMS DESIGNS CHIP FOR THE POST-PC ERA
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems has disclosed the first details of a new
microprocessor design the company hopes could become a standard for
computing in the post-PC era. The new chip design, which is
scheduled to be formally introduced at an industry technical
conference later this month, is intended to be used in computing
applications beyond the standard desktop personal computer market
that is dominated by Intel.
</P>
<P>
   PAYMENT DELAYED FOR RUSSIAN DEBT
</P>
<P>
   Russia and 18 governments agreed to delay payment for 15 to 20
years on $8.1 billion of Soviet-era debt due this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   DANKA ON THE ROAD TO RECOVERY
</P>
<P>
   Danka Business Systems plans to report first-quarter results
this week, and revenue will probably be way down, debt high and
profits minimal. So why are the top executives beaming? Scarcely
six months ago, no one was certain that Danka would make it at all.
But ever since last fall, when Danka's board plucked Larry Switzer
from Fruit of the Loom to be chief executive and selected Brian
Merriman from Toshiba as president, the two men have been cutting,
chopping, negotiating and otherwise wrenching Danka back from the
brink of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   STUDY HINTS AT LIMIT OF WEB SHOPPING
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of people with Internet access who are making
purchases from Web sites declined slightly in the second quarter of
1999 after four sequential quarters of growth, according to
Greenfield Online, an Internet market research firm. The study
hints at the limits of market penetration of the medium as a
shopping platform _ suggesting a ceiling that has been unknown
until now.
</P>
<P>
   SIFTING THROUGH NEWS ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   The ability for virtually anyone with Internet access to operate
an electronic clipping service has spawned thousands of
do-it-yourself news summaries in addition to news links on big
portal sites. Some of the digest sites are catching on with a
discerning crowd _ including reporters and editors, who rely on the
sites to help filter information on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICA ONLINE FENDS OFF MICROSOFT
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between America Online and Microsoft over access to
America Online's instant-message system is an example of one of the
most enduring concepts in the technology industry: Entice customers
with products or services and then make it difficult to defect to a
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNALISTS PRAISE ATLANTA MAYOR
</P>
<P>
   As the news coverage of the shooting rampage in Atlanta unfolded
last week, journalists in the city were surprised by how quickly
Mayor Bill Campbell appeared on the scene and how regularly he
briefed reporters. Most gave him high marks for preventing rumors
from overtaking the coverage.
</P>
</TEXT>
