<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VIOLENCE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB DAMAGES INTERIOR OF A HALF-BUILT SERBIAN ORTHODOX CATHEDRAL
</HEADLINE>
 R- 
(Repeating to add photo note)  (ART ADV: Photo of Cathedral of Holy Salvation after the bombing
has been sent to NYT photo clients.dA map is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ NATO troops were guarding the half-built
Serbian Orthodox cathedral here after a thunderous explosion
damaged the interior and woke the city early Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The blast, at 1:20 a.m., did little structural damage to the
Cathedral of Holy Salvation, but it roused condemnation from church
leaders and United Nations and NATO representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Sava Janjic, known as Father Sava, spokesman for Bishop
Artemije, the leader of the Serbian Orthodox Church in Kosovo,
denounced the bombing as part of a campaign by Kosovo Albanians to
remove all traces of the church in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The attack follows several others on churches in Kosovo, mostly
on those built since 1981, when communist restrictions were lifted
and Serbian religious nationalism revived.
</P>
<P>
   The main church in the western town of Djakovica has been
demolished, and two others have been seriously damaged. Several
other churches have been desecrated in the six weeks since Serbian
forces left the province and Kosovo's Albanian refugees returned.
The real gems of architecture, including 12th-century monasteries
and churches, are under NATO protection and have survived
unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the NATO peacekeeping force in Kosovo condemned
the bombing, calling it a ``cowardly attack against a place of
worship.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernard Kouchner, the United Nations chief administrator for
Kosovo, visited the site Sunday and said he would not accept such
acts of revenge regardless of what the Albanians had suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the brick-and-cement shell of the cathedral, two small
holes and scorch marks indicated where the charges had exploded,
shattering bricks and twisting an iron girder. The interior
scaffolding was barely disturbed. Outside, the cathedral, with its
aluminium-covered domes and golden cross, looked serene amid a
wasteland of weeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not someone who knew what he was doing,'' said a
security expert working with one of the international relief
organizations. ``Or he was just making a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   However ineffective the blast, the message will not be lost on
the small number of Serbs remaining in Pristina. Sunday, the entire
Serbian population of the southeastern town of Zitinje packed what
belongings they could and fled Kosovo after weeks of intimidation
and violence, the American peacekeepers told Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
   With an American military escort, a convoy of 60 cars, tractors
and trailers moved toward the border of Serbia proper. All of
Zitinje's 450 Serbs were in the convoy, said a soldier observing
the exodus. The town's Albanians number 650.
</P>
<P>
   In Pristina, which had reverberated with the sound of the church
bombing hours earlier, the Albanian residents seemed to give little
thought to the explosion. Music and loud applause rose from the
soccer stadium a few blocks away Sunday afternoon as Albanians
enjoyed the first live concert since the end of the war. Children
splashed in the fountain on the square, and youths climbed into the
ruins of the Serbian special police headquarters, bombed by NATO in
March.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Albanians' Kosovo Liberation Army, meanwhile,
showed more concern for Russian peacekeepers' treatment of the
chief of staff of the rebel force, Agim Ceku, who was stopped and
briefly detained on Saturday when he failed to produce identity
papers.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders angrily protested the action as proof of Russian
anti-Albanian bias, but a spokesman for the NATO-led peacekeepers
played down the incident, saying the Russians followed standard
procedure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
