<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARGAS MUST FORGET PAST FOR FUTURE'S SAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It might be that the only person who can bring down Fernando
Vargas is Fernando Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   And based on recent events, no one will be surprised if one of
boxing's brightest young stars flickers and then fades into
darkness as a result of his own self-destructive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   It might turn out that the 21-year-old IBF junior middleweight
champion is innocent of assault, for which he was arrested with
four companions July 25 outside Santa Barbara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the manner in which he placed himself in this position
and handled a difficult situation should be disturbing to anyone
who cares about this normally friendly young man who can't seem to
grow up.
</P>
<P>
   His key failure on the day of his arrest became evident after he
fought with the boyfriend of a woman he was with, or was beaten by
two men, depending on who tells the story.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the smart thing to do would have been to leave and
call the police, if in fact he was a victim. Instead, he apparently
called his buddies from Oxnard, Calif., and had them come to the
home, where they allegedly pummeled a second man and established
the grounds for their arrest.
</P>
<P>
   He chose revenge and its ramifications in spite of the risks.
</P>
<P>
   That decision is a symptom of his greatest weakness: He reverts
to the don't-you-dare-disrespect-me street kid of his childhood
when he's among his friends in Oxnard. And, as evidenced by the
beating incident, that equates to trouble.
</P>
<P>
   This is one reason his promotional firm, Main Events, has had
him live and train much of his career on the East Coast; he's
separated from the elements many fear will lead to his demise.
</P>
<P>
   However, there's a better solution. Vargas must let go of the
past, which, frankly, might take more strength and determination
than he has.
</P>
<P>
   He must stop and think about his promising future _ a lifetime
of financial security for his family, unlimited fame, a sense of
tremendous accomplishment, the ability to do some good with his
celebrity and wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Weigh that against momentary satisfaction that revenge or any
other base instinct might provide and it's no contest. Indeed, to
trade a dream life for a nightmare in prison or on the streets in
the name of some macho street code is unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas, who is bright despite evidence to the contrary, must see
that.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, his sense of loyalty _ an admirable quality _ is
part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   All those who comprise Team Vargas were there when he was an
amateur. That's how loyal he is. Obviously, that sense of
responsibility also extends to those who he fought with and for
since he was a child on the rough streets of Oxnard.
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable. It's also stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas has said repeatedly he cares deeply about his family,
particularly his beloved son, Fernando Jr. And he has a longtime
girlfriend, his son's mother, who must have been hurt tremendously
by the genesis of last week's incident _ his liaison with a
stripper.
</P>
<P>
   What about them? Don't his loyalties and responsibilities to
them supersede those to his friends? And isn't his family more
precious than his perilous pride?
</P>
<P>
   If the answer to each of these questions is yes _ and Fernando
would agree it is _ it's time to prove it. It's time to prove he
can be a mature, responsible adult who can establish priorities in
his life and abide by them, not a street thug who can't handle
success.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Another aspect of Vargas' problem is his disposition. The fact
his father abandoned his family when he was a child, at least in
part has left him with a chip on his shoulder. He's wound up so
tightly that he's ready to fight _ in or out of the ring _ at
almost any time. It's as if he's convinced the world is against
him.
</P>
<P>
   Well, guess what? The opposite is true. Much of the world sees
him as an exciting, charismatic, immensely talented athlete who has
a chance to do something special and is opening its loving arms to
him.
</P>
<P>
   It's up to him to accept the embrace. Vargas must look into the
mirror and ask himself this question, ``What do I want?''
</P>
<P>
   __ Reid ready? WBA junior middleweight champ David Reid doesn't
have to fight tough Keith Mullings on Aug. 28.
</P>
<P>
   He could face a string of nobodies and wait for a big-money shot
at Vargas or Oscar De La Hoya. That he's not is admirable and could
prove to be wise.
</P>
<P>
   Mullings (16-5-1, with 11 knockouts) lost his WBC super
welterweight title to Francisco Castillejo _ who could be De La
Hoya's opponent at the Staples Center in December _ but is a crafty
boxer capable of giving anyone a tough fight.
</P>
<P>
   Reid (13-0, seven KOs) _ coming off a marginal performance in a
decision over quick, awkward Kevin Kelly last month _ is willing to
learn his craft under fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only his 13th fight,'' said trainer Al Mitchell,
referring to the Kelly bout. ``He's still learning. I'm glad that
happened at the time it did. He'll learn from it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be easy to find a guy to stand in front of him and
get knocked out,'' Mitchell added. ``That's not what we want,
that's not what will be good for him in the long run. He's learning
on the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Reid of Mullings: ``I !ital!need these fights to get ready
for the Vargases and De La Hoyas. Yeah, it's risky, but I can
handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   He probably will. Prediction: Reid by unanimous decision, which
will repair some of the damage done to his image by Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   On the Reid-Mullings card, San Fernando Valley product Lance
Whitaker will face unbeaten Monte Barrett in a 10-round heavyweight
bout.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker (18-1, 16 KOs) is coming off a loss to Lou Savarese in
which he almost knocked out the winner. Like Reid, Whitaker didn't
look for an easy opponent to rebuild any lost confidence; Barrett
(20-0, 12 KOs) is one of the best young heavyweights out there.
</P>
<P>
   If Whitaker loses, it will set him back considerably; if he
wins, a title shot might be around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   The card will be televised on HBO's ``Boxing After Dark.''
</P>
<P>
   __ More Reid: Reid and Co. once again dismissed questions about
his droopy eye, even though it seemed he had difficulty seeing
rights landed by Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchel said his youth was at the root of the problem, not his
eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``His (left) hand was down. It's as simple as that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Ruelas watch: Gabriel and Rafael Ruelas are scheduled to
return to the ring Saturday and Sunday, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Ruelas will face Jose Rodriguez in Miami on Telemundo.
Rafael Ruelas will take on Hicklet Lau the following night in Las
Vegas on Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, trainer Joe Goossen will not be in their
corners as both are working with new people.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who have followed the Ruelases' careers wonder
whether they should come back. Goossen doesn't believe it's his
place to say such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't expect me to tell guys who have done this their
whole lives what to do with their lives _ even their boxing
lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If they win this weekend and move back into the championship
picture _ as is the plan _ Goossen won't bemoan the fact he won't
be around.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it turns out that they're successful, obviously someone is
doing the right thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ At the Pond: Guty Espadas will seek his 10th straight victory
when he faces Prangky Mamuaya in a 10-round junior featherweight
Aug. 9 in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   In the co-main event, Israel Vazquez faces Nelson Medina in a
junior featherweight bout. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
