<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LEGISLATION BY STEALTH  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.M., Wash., Idaho)  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, August 2:
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the Republicans swept to power on Capitol Hill in
1994, they adopted a strategy of attaching last-minute legislative
proposals, or riders, to essential appropriations bills. The point
is to insure passage of controversial changes in policy that might
not survive if subjected to full hearings and debate as
freestanding bills. The Democrats have used this profoundly
undemocratic device, but the Republicans have perfected it _
especially the Western Republicans, who once again have produced a
batch of anti-environmental riders aimed at helping their allies in
the oil, gas, timber, mining and ranching businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Their vehicle this year is the Interior Department spending
bill, debated briefly on the Senate floor last week and likely to
come up again this week. In the name of fiscal restraint, the
Republicans have already slashed President Clinton's requests for
several important land acquisition and conservation programs. But
that has not stopped them from rewarding their special friends.
</P>
<P>
   One rider has already been approved, and it may be the worst of
the lot. With various contributions from Slade Gorton of
Washington, Harry Reid of Nevada and Larry Craig of Idaho, the
rider would overturn the 1872 Mining Law and later rulings by the
Interior Department that limited companies mining on federal lands
to one five-acre site per mine to dump their mine wastes. The
amendment will allow the companies to use as much public land as
they need to store mountains of toxic wastes, threatening the
landscape and increasing the potential damage to streams, fish and
wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Two other riders deserve note. One would invite federal agencies
to ignore their duty under present law to conduct detailed wildlife
surveys before proceeding with timber sales and other activities
that could destroy habitat for fragile species. The other, devised
by Sen. Pete Domenici of New Mexico, would invite the Interior
Department to renew thousands of expiring grazing permits on
millions of acres of federal land without requiring ranchers to
adopt responsible grazing practices mandated by the secretary of
the interior to minimize damage to the land and streams.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the House has been largely unaffected by the rider
mania, with one big exception. Urged on by home builders,
Republicans added a rider to an energy and water appropriations
bill that, despite some last-minute softening, would unnecessarily
complicate the administration's efforts to prevent the rapid loss
of valuable wetlands to development and other commercial
activities. This provision could be harmful to New York City, which
needs to preserve its upstate wetlands in order to protect the
purity of its water supply.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has threatened to veto the energy and water
bill, as well as the Interior appropriations bill, if they arrive
on Clinton's desk in their present form. But responsible members of
Congress can avoid that fate if they will recognize these
amendments for what they are _ special favors for powerful interest
groups _ and eliminate them from the bills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
