<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA MAYOR ACTS QUICKLY TO FILL GAPS IN CRISIS COVERAGE  
 SQUABBLES PERSIST OVER KENNEDY REPORTING  
 A WELL-KNOWN FACE IS TAKING TO THE STREETS  
 FALLOWS JOINS THE GROWING STAFF OF AN INTERNET BUSINESS MAGAZINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., N.Y.)  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching the horrifying news about the rampage of a deranged
gunman in Atlanta last Thursday, some were struck by how quickly
the city's mayor appeared on the scene, and how regularly he
briefed reporters as the crisis unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Atlanta journalists were surprised, too. And even
though they have not always had the smoothest relationships with
Mayor Bill Campbell, most gave him high marks for preventing rumors
from overtaking the coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to commend him for being accessible and for being in
command of the situation,'' said David Roberts, the vice president
and news director of WXIA, the Atlanta NBC affiliate, whose
helicopter pictures were the first to be seen nationally, via the
MSNBC cable network. ``The leadership role he took in disseminating
information made it easier to prevent the reporting of speculation,
rumor and potential misinformation to viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Carter, news director of WSB, Atlanta's ABC affiliate,
agreed. ``There certainly was an ease of information, which we are
not accustomed to,'' said Carter, adding that he had worked at
stations in six other cities and had never seen such cooperation
from city officials. ``Not that it was fast and furious, but it was
forthright and full of detail.''
</P>
<P>
   Some journalists did point out that, in his zeal to keep them
updated, the mayor conveyed incorrect information at one point
(saying the police believed the shooter, Mark O. Barton, had killed
his wife and two children after, not before, killing nine people in
two brokerage offices).
</P>
<P>
   CNN, although based in Atlanta, relied at the outset on local
stations' news reports, as it does in times of crisis elsewhere
around the country. The stations affiliated with ABC, CBS, Fox and
NBC are all CNN affiliates; the Fox station, WAGA, also serves the
Fox News Channel, one of CNN's competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Station news directors attributed the smoothness to two things:
the scope of the tragedy and the fact that Atlanta's police chief,
Beverly Harvard, was out of town when the gunman struck,
eliminating the sort of jockeying that often occurs between a
mayor's staff and the police about the logistics of releasing
information to the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to disparage Chief Harvard at all,'' Carter said, ``but
there was a void there, so the mayor stepped in to help.''
Campbell, who was elected in November 1993, has been through other
such crises, most notably the Olympic Park bombing in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that it will come to be seen as a watershed
moment,'' Carter said. ``But it certainly was refreshing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lawrie Mifflin &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Squabbles Persist Over Kennedy Reporting
</P>
<P>
   By late last week, the death of John F. Kennedy Jr. had finally
begun to fade as a news story, but at least one issue lingered in
the world of network correspondents: who knew what, and when did
they know it?
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, Media Talk said that the CBS correspondent Bob Orr
was the first to reveal, a few days after Kennedy's plane was
reported missing, the details of the radar track that indicated
Kennedy had turned out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   But some at ABC News are angry at CBS News for stealing their
thunder. That is because Lisa Stark of ABC News was the first to
disclose _ on Saturday, July 17 _ the radar reports that showed the
plane beginning the precipitous nose dive that eventually resulted
in the deaths of Kennedy, his wife and her sister.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest relevant radar story was that the plane took a
sharp descent into the sea,'' said Eileen Murphy, a spokeswoman for
ABC News. ``And ABC News had it before CBS did.'' Ms. Stark, Ms.
Murphy said, was the first to report that news, and CBS Radio and
Orr of CBS News ran stories counter to Ms. Stark's through Monday.
</P>
<P>
   From July 17 to July 19, the National Transportation Safety
Board denied that radar indicated the plane had begun a nose dive.
On July 19, Orr again reported the NTSB denials. Later that day,
the safety board finally revealed that the radar did indicate a
nose dive.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stark said the Kennedy accident was ``one of those
skip-and-jump stories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone had the one thing they broke,'' she said. ``But we
broke that story.''
</P>
<P>
   Orr defended his reporting. ``This was such a highly competitive
atmosphere that I think everybody was out there trying to be first
and trying to get it right,'' he said. ``The only thing I would say
is that we were aggressive in what we knew and when we knew it. The
thing that made me most gratified was that in the high-pressured
environment we had over the course of several days, we didn't make
any major mistakes and that's as important as reporting those
smaller incremental developments.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Well-Known Face Is Taking to the Streets
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Who was that familiar-looking dark-maned man standing
on West 88th Street in Manhattan a few weeks ago, wielding a
microphone and smiling into the camera? It looked like George
Stephanopoulos, but when he does television, he does it in the
precisely lighted, air-conditioned safety of an ABC studio.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't he?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to do new things,'' Stephanopoulos said,
confirming that a few weeks ago he began going out with camera
crews, acquiring new skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a commentator in the studio; now I'm learning how to
put together reported pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Regular sidewalk-pounding ABC News correspondents need not worry
that he will be taking one of their jobs just yet. For the
foreseeable future, Stephanopoulos will report only on political
topics, given his background as a campaign organizer, White House
aide and commentator for ABC's political coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, he will still be a political analyst, but he will
not necessarily remain in the studio. (He occasionally fills in as
a substitute host on ``Good Morning America.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't be the first reporter to start out in another
profession,'' said David Westin, president of ABC News, citing
several network news correspondents who previously worked in other
professions, usually as lawyers. ``It makes sense to have him do
politics; that's his area of expertise. We wouldn't ask him to
cover legal issues or the medical beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Westin said the two men had discussed expanding Stephanopoulos'
reporting career, in general terms only. Stephanopoulos said, ``I
don't have any hard and fast goals, but if the opportunity came up,
I'd love to broaden out.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he has reported a piece about the use of the Internet
in campaigning, and another on how and why politicians use
late-night comedy shows. ``We came up with some great old footage
of Nixon on `Laugh-In,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That piece taught Stephanopoulos a standard Reporting 101
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was supposed to run today,'' he said Friday, ``but it got
pre-empted because of the shootings in Atlanta. I'm learning those
kinds of frustrations, too.''
</P>
<P>
   _Lawrie Mifflin
</P>
<P>
   Fallows Joins the Growing Staff of an Internet Business Magazine
</P>
<P>
   If anyone in journalism has nine lives, James Fallows does.
Fallows, a former editor of U.S. News and World Report, outspoken
press critic, author of ``Breaking the News: How the Media
Undermine American Democracy'' and _ most recently _ Microsoft
consultant, will join The Industry Standard magazine as a
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Weber, the editor in chief of the Standard, a weekly
Internet-business magazine published by International Data Group,
is expected to announce the appointment Tuesday. And Fallows will
have plenty of company: within the last month, Weber has lured
reporters and editors away from several news organizations,
including Thomas Goetz from The Wall Street Journal, Kenneth Li
from The New York Daily News, and staff members from Inc. magazine,
Wired and The San Jose Mercury News.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday, Weber hired Amy Bernstein, the editorial director
of Brill's Content magazine. He said the editorial staff, which
last month had 27 members, would grow to 45 by the end of
September.
</P>
<P>
   Weber said that he had begun to think of the San Francisco-based
Standard as the Rolling Stone of the Internet business economy, and
of Fallows as a columnist who will help attract a broader
readership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are focused on the phenomenon of Internet business,'' Weber
said. ``But it is such a big and influential phenomenon with so
many different dimensions that there's an enormous amount of
interest from people who are not in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Standard's unaudited circulation base is 115,000. (By
contrast, Wired's is 425,000.) It says its advertising pages grew
140 percent from June 1998 to June 1999, with gains averaging 30
percent every quarter since the magazine was founded in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Fallows said that in joining the staff, he was ``trying to
create some version of my pre-U.S. News life, which is writing
books, magazine articles and writing a frequent column.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``My plan is basically to write about the outside
world and the Internet. What should the outside world make of these
castles being made of sand or of steel girders every day? How
should people building these castles think of themselves
historically and in the eyes of their citizens? Think of me as an
interested amateur observer.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Alex Kuczynski
</P>
</TEXT>
