<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-FAST-TRAIN-ART-840(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMTRAK TESTS NEW HIGH-SPEED TRAIN AMID RATTLESNAKES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUEBLO, Colo. _ Amtrak's first new train in a generation, the
fastest on the continent, is scheduled to be zipping passengers
past crowded streets, highways and runways from Washington to
Boston by the end of the year. But its first trials are being held
here on a desert track that runs amid the cholla cactus and the
rattlesnakes.
</P>
<P>
   Tests are going well, engineers say, but there are still
technical questions to work out. Not to mention what happened to
the antelope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding enough for the barbecue tonight?'' joked Wayne
Stadler, a test controller, as he and Real Sylvain, an engineer,
peered at the undercarriage of the train in search of identifiable
remains of an antelope it hit on the most recent lap.
</P>
<P>
   Antelope are plentiful this year at the railroad industry's test
track, where the train, the Acela, has been running for up to 16
hours a day. It barely seems to strain in 6-minute laps around a
test track 13.5 miles long. Sometimes it reaches 160 mph, although
its top speed will be only 150 when it carries passengers in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its speed, the Acela (the name is meant to convey both
acceleration and excellence) is unlikely to encounter antelope when
it begins service in the urban corridors from New York to Boston
and Washington. It is supposed to shave nearly two hours from the
Boston-to-New York run and 15 minutes from Washington to New York,
where current track equipment prohibits faster travel.
</P>
<P>
   The big problem is how the train will handle curves.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers, Bombardier Inc. of Quebec and the
French-British venture GEC Alsthom, have designed the coaches to
tilt in as they go around corners, a little like a bicyclist
leaning into a turn.
</P>
<P>
   The tilt, which moves the upper portion of the passenger car
while the undercarriage hugs the rails, is controlled by one of 21
computers in the locomotive of the Acela.
</P>
<P>
   The computer decides how far to tilt the cars after reading the
train's speed, the angle at which the tracks are banked, the
sideways forces as the locomotive goes around a corner and the turn
angle of the trucks, the structures that hold the wheels, relative
to the body of the locomotive itself.
</P>
<P>
   The computer tells each of the eight passenger cars how far to
tilt _ up to 4.2 degrees in either direction, which translates to a
six-inch movement at the top of the car. The signals are sent in
sequence, so that each car tilts at a different moment as it passes
through the curve.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, we said, `Oh, that's just a detail,''' said Philippe
Moslener, a design engineer with Bombardier. But tests showed
passengers would be more comfortable if the cars tilted in
sequence, rather than in unison. ``It's not a detail at all,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The tilt partly compensates for the sideways forces in a turn.
If it compensates completely, Moslener said, it somehow induces
motion sickness in passengers; designers are now experimenting with
compensating for 60 to 70 percent of the sideways forces.
</P>
<P>
   When the system was run as a test when the train stood still,
the cars rocked like an ocean liner in a steady swell. But when the
train is moving, the tilt will reduce the sensation of going around
a curve, making for a more comfortable ride.
</P>
<P>
   Within sight of Pike's Peak, with signs in the parking lot
warning of rattlesnakes, engineers are testing the train's
acceleration (about a mile per hour each second, roughly 20 percent
better than the Metroliner), stopping distance and other
characteristics. At 140 mph, a new Acela engine pulling six
old-style cars to simulate the weight of the new ones ran smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   With no reference point but the occasional cactus, speed was
hard for a passenger to judge. But when the train slowed down to 60
mph, it seemed to be crawling.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a second Acela locomotive, outfitted with the new cars,
was undergoing tests while parked. The passenger cars were still
bare of seats. But for every row there was a surge-protected power
outlet for laptop computers. And overhead were airline-style
luggage bins that were twice the size of those on most passenger
jets, and positioned higher to make it easier for passengers to
stand.
</P>
<P>
   On the floor were coffinlike plywood boxes filled with lead
bars, to simulate the weight of seats and passengers. Technicians
prowled the cars with standard tools like wrenches and screwdrivers
as well as laptop computers that talked to computerized components
of the train.
</P>
<P>
   When the cars enter service, sharp-eyed passengers may notice
changes designed to make the train safer in a crash. For example,
at the end of each car, in the four corners, are four steel
structures, each the size of a large flowerpot. In a collision,
these would match up end to end, absorbing some of the impact. And
the vestibule area, around the doors, is designed as a crumple
zone, so the passenger seating area would stay intact.
</P>
<P>
   The main innovation, though, is the way the locomotives use
electronic tricks that were not practical 20 years ago to get more
horsepower at higher reliability than the older technology allowed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak's Metroliners take alternating current from the overhead
lines and convert it to direct current for the motors that drive
the train. But these DC motors produce less horsepower than AC
motors for each unit of electricity, and they wear out faster.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the single overhead wire supplies AC current
in which the electrons dance back and forth 60 times per second,
all to a single beat. Big motors that run on such single-phase AC
do not operate reliably.
</P>
<P>
   So the Acela converts the AC to DC and then back into three
different AC circuits, each on a different, linked beat, like a
chorus singing ``Row, row, row your boat'' as a round. That allows
Amtrak to use the kind of modern motors in wide use in other
industries.
</P>
<P>
   The innovations are worthwhile, railroad officials said, because
after years of work new overhead electric lines have been installed
from New Haven all the way to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is being tested, including the pantographs, the
armlike structures that rise from the top of the locomotives to
contact the overhead power lines. At more than 100 mph, they tend
to develop lift, like a hand extended from a moving car, and that
interferes with keeping a constant pressure of about 22.5 pounds on
the power line. So the Acela's pantographs carry little winglike
structures, which the railroad calls ailerons, that can be adjusted
to maintain the correct pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers have been sweating the details _ quite literally.
Temperatures here rose over 95 degrees one afternoon, forcing the
train to slow down to a mere 80 mph, as required by a national
regulation because welded steel rail begins to change shape at that
temperature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
