<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A TIME OF TRANSITION FOR ARABS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, Aug. 2:
</P>
<P>
   As Israel's new prime minister, Ehud Barak, moves toward
intensified negotiations with Syria, Lebanon and the Palestinians,
encouraging trends in the wider Arab world may be working in his
favor, helping to create a more conducive climate for regional
peace. These changes include generational passages of power in
several countries, a strengthening Egyptian economy and a reversal
of attitudes in Algeria, whose president met last week with Barak
and praised his peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   None of these supportive developments will conjure away tough
issues like the future of Jerusalem, Jewish settlements and the
Golan Heights. But the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, and
Syria's president, Hafez al-Assad, may find it easier to make their
share of compromises if they do not have to worry about accusations
of betrayal from other Arab leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In Egypt, President Hosni Mubarak is again acting as a crucial
intermediary with Arafat. At Barak's behest, he is now trying to
persuade the Palestinian leader to consider postponing some Israeli
withdrawals promised under the Wye River agreement and moving
straight to negotiations on major issues like Jerusalem. Mubarak's
position has been strengthened by four years of successful economic
reforms that have broadened his political support at home.
</P>
<P>
   In Jordan, King Abdullah took over earlier this year after the
death of his father, King Hussein, a committed peacemaker. Abdullah
is already trying to arrange a meeting between Barak and Assad,
suggesting that he means to be as active as his father.
</P>
<P>
   A new king has also taken the throne in Morocco, following the
death last month of King Hassan II. It is too early to judge King
Mohammed VI, the new monarch. But at his father's funeral last week
he impressed Israelis by welcoming Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The new generation of leaders who seized power in Qatar in 1995
moved quickly to take a more positive attitude toward Israel. That
opening did not lead very far. But the diplomatic courtship is now
likely to resume. It could encourage younger leaders in other gulf
emirates to play a more constructive role.
</P>
<P>
   Algeria also has a new leader, Abdelaziz Bouteflika. Although
his election earlier this year was stained by charges of fraud and
a withdrawal of opposition candidates, he has since taken tentative
steps toward ending a murderous civil war with Islamic
fundamentalists. Now, he appears to be trying out a more
conciliatory role internationally as well. Continued support for
peace negotiations by a country with Algeria's radical pedigree
could license others to speak out favorably as well.
</P>
<P>
   Other powers will help shape Middle East politics, especially
Saudi Arabia, which is now playing a cautious, aloof role as it
faces its own transition to a new leader. Iraq is likely to cause
trouble as long as Saddam Hussein remains in power. But with help
from Mubarak, Abdullah and others willing to speak out for peace,
Barak, Arafat and Assad may make some progress.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
