<HEADLINE>
IN A PHOTO FINISH, VICTORY GALLOP WINS WHITNEY 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ In the kind of finish that creates
legends at Saratoga, they roared down the homestretch stride for
stride Sunday, Victory Gallop and Behrens, the top candidates for
Horse of the Year, locked in a furious duel in the 72nd Whitney
Handicap. And by a bob of his head and the length of his nose,
Victory Gallop prevailed in a photo finish and staked his claim to
be recognized as the best race horse in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The two stars of racing's handicap division staged their battle
before a roaring crowd of 49,137 spectators on a torrid afternoon,
and neither the tumult of the crowd nor the burden of the heat kept
them from giving maximum efforts. They hooked up when Victory
Gallop flew from sixth place into contention in the stretch, and
then in the final eighth of a mile they left behind the six other
horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``My plan was to run right by Behrens, not creep up beside
him,'' said Jerry Bailey, who was riding Victory Gallop. ``Behrens
is a fighter, and I didn't want to give him the chance to see us.
When Behrens saw him, he dug in. Like I said, that horse is a
fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Chavez, the jockey aboard Behrens, who came into the Grade
I Whitney with a four-race winning streak in stakes races, put it
bluntly: ``These two horses are the best in the world. I can't say
who is better because both of them are tough. I asked Jerry if he
knew who won the race, and he said he didn't know, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said that when he reached the turn for home, horses were
``stopping'' in front of him, so he took Behrens five horses wide.
Then Victory Gallop came streaking up on the outside and went wide,
too. For a moment, it looked as though he would shoot right past
Behrens. But Behrens refused to yield, and they mounted their duel
to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott Walden, who trains Victory Gallop for Prestonwood Farm,
said it was ``a fantastic race'' that was decided when his horse
went from last place after the first half-mile and made the
bounding move that is his signature. He won the Stephen Foster at
Churchill Downs in June with a dramatic rally generated by a huge
move, too. But Walden wondered if Victory Gallop might have waited
too long in the Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he makes that run, it's really scintillating to watch,''
he said. ``It's an awesome move, and he showed it again today. But
when he gets that far back in a race, it makes me nervous. And
Behrens showed guts and class. I started getting a little shaky
three jumps before the wire. But they made a tremendous move.''
</P>
<P>
   James Bond, who trains Behrens for William Clifton and the
Rudlein Stable, called it ``racing at its best,'' and added:
``Behrens has won two Grade I races, two Grade II's and lost by a
nose here. It looks to me like Horse of the Year will be settled in
the Breeders' Cup Classic this November.''
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop ran the mile and an eighth in 1:48 3/5, paid
$3.80 for a $2 bet to win and went home with $360,000, bringing his
career earnings to $3.5 million. Catienus finished third, 12
lengths back, and Sir Bear ran three lengths farther back in
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop and Behrens have come a long way since each ran
the Travers at Saratoga and each lost by a nose. Two years ago,
Behrens, with Jerry Bailey riding, lost that classic for
3-year-olds to Deputy Commander. Last year, Victory Gallop lost the
Travers to Coronado's Quest. In the Whitney, their noses were the
only ones that counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two champions,'' Walden said, ``showed up today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
