<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TRADES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES ARE HAPPY TO ALLOW PETTITTE A TWO-MONTH REPRIEVE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ George Steinbrenner was in a good mood Sunday night,
which was notable in itself because the day after the July 31 trade
deadline there is reason to reconsider what your team and your
rivals did or did not do.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees did not do a lot. They did not trade the left-hander
Andy Pettitte, who was given at least a two-month respite to
reprove himself to the organization. They did not trade for a
relief pitcher; rather, the organization figures it has as much or
more pitching depth to plug holes and figures that Jeff Nelson and
Mike Stanton will pitch better in the post-season, as they have
always done.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees did add Jim Leyritz, the perpetually grinning
slugger who arrived here Sunday pining for another post-season
experience in pinstripes. Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, told
Steinbrenner in the hours leading to the trade deadline that he
believed this team is good enough to win. ``The manager is happy,''
said Steinbrenner, the principal owner. ``That's good by me.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be difficult for the Yankees to augment their roster
with players from outside the organization in the final two months
of the season. Before any team can trade a player, it must first
pass that player through waivers. For example: if the Yankees
decided to deal Pettitte, they would first have to expose him to
all teams through waivers. If any team claimed him _say the Anaheim
Angels placed a claim _ the Yankees then could only deal Pettitte
to the Angels or withdraw him, and then they would not be able to
trade him until after the season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees do have some options developing within their
organization. Nelson, recovering from elbow surgery, is scheduled
to begin a rehabilitation assignment in Tampa, Fla., on Monday. He
will make four appearances, and if he comes through those without a
setback, he most likely will join the club during its West Coast
trip that begins Thursday in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   And both Steinbrenner and Torre spoke hopefully about the
possible return of Darryl Strawberry, currently suspended from
baseball for violating his drug after-care program. Bud Selig, the
commissioner, will most likely speak to Strawberry soon and then
reinstate him; in any event, Strawberry's 120-day suspension is
scheduled to end Aug. 11. According to Torre and Steinbrenner,
Strawberry has looked good in his workouts at the club's minor
league facility in Tampa, and, the owner said, Strawberry is
attending Alcoholics Anonymous meetings every day with his wife,
Charisse. Strawberry is waiting anxiously for Selig to reinstate
him, Steinbrenner said. ``I told Darryl, `You have to wait,'''
Steinbrenner said. `` `Wait your turn, pal.'''
</P>
<P>
   Once he is reinstated, Strawberry will probably be assigned to a
minor league team, and he will attempt to prove he can play left
field on a part-time basis. ``It'll be my guess he can play some
left field,'' Steinbrenner said. ``Maybe not day-in, day-out, but
he'll play some.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz ducked into the clubhouse to grab a bat for batting
practice Sunday, without noticing Steinbrenner standing nearby. But
Steinbrenner yelled at Leyritz to catch his attention, and they
hugged. Leyritz is a big-game hitter, Steinbrenner said _ ``Look at
what he hit,'' he said, referring to Leyritz's game-tying home run
in the fourth game of the 1996 World Series, the pivotal moment in
that championship. ``Talk about a big pressure moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, acquired from San Diego for Geraldo Padua, a minor
league pitcher, was among the first players to arrive at the
clubhouse before Sunday night's game against the Red Sox, and Chili
Davis and David Cone were among the first players he saw _ a big
thrill, Leyritz said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his first stint with the Yankees _ playing for
Torre in 1996 _ the manager viewed Leyritz as a guy who was tough
to deal with. ``But that doesn't necessarily mean he was a pain,''
said Torre, smiling. Leyritz wanted to play more, while Torre used
him as a role player. After the '96 season, Leyritz was traded to
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   But in speaking with Torre after the trade, Leyritz told the
manager he has a greater understanding of why the Yankees are so
successful; everything is done to help the team, he said,
everything is done for the sake of winning ball games. Leyritz is
going to be a role player in the final two months and the
post-season, as an occasional designated hitter or first baseman or
pinch-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with him. ``Whatever they need,'' Leyritz said, ``if
it's first base, if it's third base, coming off the bench,
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz had once said he would return to the Yankees one day.
``I always wanted to retire here,'' said Leyritz, 35. ``Maybe in
the next year or two, I'll have a chance to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz's dreams for the future were the only mention of
anything beyond the 1999 post-season. Steinbrenner acknowledged
that in keeping Pettitte, the Yankees now have all but assured
themselves of a difficult off season of tough financial dealings.
</P>
<P>
   But they'll think about that later. With their roster mostly
intact, the Yankees have two months to prepare for the championship
chase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
