<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-DUMAURIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4 BIRDIES ON LAST 5 HOLES LIFT WEBB TO HER FIRST MAJOR TITLE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIDDIS, Canada _ It was a great finish by a great player, and
it ended any doubt about Karrie Webb's readiness to win a major
championship. Making four birdies on her final five holes, and
erasing a late three-stroke deficit in dramatic fashion, Webb won
the du Maurier Classic by two strokes over Laura Davies for the
first major title of her young but stellar career.
</P>
<P>
   Webb finished at 11 under par for the tournament
(73-72-66-66-277), two strokes ahead of Davies (279), who shot a 72
Sunday, and three strokes ahead of Juli Inkster (280), who shot a
final-round 69, but was denied her third major title this year.
</P>
<P>
   Webb's finish was so magical, even she had trouble believing it.
She reached the 14th tee trailing Davies by three strokes, knowing
that the window of opportunity was closing rapidly. It was a
now-or-never situation, and Webb seized the moment, hitting
brilliant approach shots and making pressure putts. She birdied No.
14 after hitting an 8-iron approach shot to seven feet. She birdied
No. 15, hitting another 8-iron to eight feet, then making the putt.
She birdied No. 16, hitting a sand wedge to within eight feet, then
making still another putt.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she reached No. 18, the enthusiastic gallery, the
worried Davies and the hard-charging Webb knew something special
was happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe I do those things,'' said Webb, a native of
Australia who, at the age of 24 has already won 15 LPGA
tournaments, including six this year. ``If I watched it on TV, I
would have been in awe of the person doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb finished her remarkable run with another birdie at the par
5, 473-yard No. 18, reaching the back fringe in two shots, chipping
to five feet, then making her birdie putt. That gave Webb a
one-stroke lead over Davies, who had yet to play the 18th hole. Now
Webb had to wait. If Davies eagled No. 18, she would still win. If
Davies birdied, there would be a playoff. But if Davies made par or
worse, Webb's improbable comeback would be complete.
</P>
<P>
   After a solid 3-iron drive into the fairway at No. 18, Davies
hit her 4-iron approach shot into the right rough near the green,
and the ball settled in a terrible lie, nearly 40 feet from the
hole. Davies did well to chip the ball 15 feet past the hole,
leaving her with a birdie putt that could force a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   When Davies' putt slid inches past the left edge of the hole,
the realization hit Webb that she had won. Standing by the 18th
green, Webb immediately burst into tears of joy. She was hugged by
her mother, Evelyn, who had traveled from Australia to witness the
highlight of her daughter's career, while several players and
caddies who had remained for the finish surrounded Webb to
congratulate her.
</P>
<P>
   It was a well-deserved moment for Webb, who has become a
dominant player at a young age, but who has been burdened with
heavy expectations. Until Sunday, no matter how often Webb won, she
was regularly asked when she would win a major.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a set of questions that I don't get asked anymore,''
said Webb, who won $180,000, and leads the LPGA money list with
$1.25 million, already the most ever won by an LPGA player in one
year. ``I have only been out here three and a half years. For
things to have happened so quickly, it's hard to set goals, but I
love playing golf, and I love having a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know exactly what was going through my mind out there.
I know that there was a lot of adrenaline. I was nervous. But I
have so much confidence in myself, I just step up and do it. The
last six holes, it was like someone else was playing for me, like I
was watching someone else do it.''
</P>
<P>
   For Davies, it was a disappointing defeat, as she suddenly lost
control of a tournament that had appeared to be hers. She had
started the day with a two-stroke lead over Dawn Coe-Jones, who
finished fourth (284), and four strokes ahead of Webb. Putting, a
chronic problem for Davies, kept her from winning the fifth major
of her career.
</P>
<P>
   Davies made a costly three-putt bogey from 30 feet at No. 17,
hitting her first putt five feet past the hole, then missing the
comeback. Davies also three-putted No. 18, but it was the crucial
miss, a downhill 15-footer that would have forced a playoff, that
she will remember the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I holed the putt,'' said Davies, who needed 34 putts
Sunday after needing only 30 during each of the first three rounds.
``If Webbie hadn't been so good, level par would have won.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best player on tour proved it again. I must admit, I was
watching the board for Webbie all day long. I got beat by a better
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb actually started her tournament-clinching run at No. 13,
when she made a 20-foot putt to save par, keeping her three strokes
behind Davies at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The putt I made on No. 13 probably won it for me,'' Webb said.
``If I had made bogey there, I really didn't have a chance to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Inkster never made a final-round charge, but having already won
the United States Women's Open and the LPGA McDonald's Championship
this year, Inkster refused to be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finished third, and I played pretty well today,'' said
Inkster, who remained just one victory shy of qualifying for the
LPGA Hall of Fame. ``The first two days, I hit it poorly and putted
well. The last two days, I hit it well and couldn't putt. Go
figure. That's golf.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday's back nine, Webb made playing golf look easy. The
future looks fabulous for Webb. But the present isn't too bad
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever try to think of myself as the best player in the
world,'' Webb said. ``But I played like I was.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
