<HEADLINE>
WITH BUDGET NEAR, NEW YORK LEGISLATURE IS TURNING TO OTHER ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
   (See also NY-LEGIS-BILLS) 
(rk) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With the new state budget nearly completed, Gov.
George Pataki and legislative leaders are turning their attention
to other issues, including an overhaul of special education and a
bailout for Nassau County, along with criminal justice proposals,
like expanding the state's DNA database for tracking criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The 211 members of the state Legislature are to return here this
week to pass a $73 billion budget that, if it is not in place by
Thursday, will set a record as the latest budget in state history.
The budget was due on April 1, but for the 15th year in a row,
lawmakers have failed to meet that deadline. The tardiest budget
was adopted in 1997, 125 days overdue.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the stalemate over the budget has made it almost
impossible for lawmakers to do any other work. To date, the two
houses of the Legislature have passed just 607 bills jointly,
putting them at a pace to pass fewer laws than at any time in this
century. The last time that a session was this unproductive was in
1998, when the Legislature passed 671 bills, compared with 900 to
1,000 in most years.
</P>
<P>
   The relative inaction means that lawmakers will have to return
in the next few months for a special session to deal with
unfinished business. Chief among the unfinished work is determining
the fate of a state law that adds $2.6 billion a year to hospital
bills, mostly to help hospitals train doctors and care for the
poor. The law expires at the end of the year and is the focus of
intense debate between business leaders, who want the assessments
scaled back, and hospital workers and executives who say the
charges are essential to their survival.
</P>
<P>
   But aides to Pataki and legislative leaders have said they plan
to address as many measures as they can over the next few days
before wrapping up the 1999 legislative session. Although many
proposals are being negotiated by Pataki, the Assembly speaker,
Sheldon Silver, and the state Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno,
the ones that are considered most likely to produce compromises
center on criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
   One of those measures would give law enforcement officials
greater authority to collect DNA samples from felons and to log
them into state computers, as is now done with fingerprints. The
state already collects such DNA information _ usually from a saliva
sample _ but only from people convicted of sex crimes and some
other violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican, has been pushing to have DNA samples
collected from all felons, saying it would allow law enforcement
officials to use evidence gathered at crime scenes, like a strand
of hair, to catch people whose DNA samples are in the database.
</P>
<P>
   But his proposal has been opposed by civil liberties groups that
have influence with the Democratic leaders of the Assembly. In the
end, though, Democrats have signaled that they are ready to accept
a compromise to make the collection of DNA samples mandatory for
some crimes that are not covered under the current law.
</P>
<P>
   Another area of possible agreement involves a proposal to make
it a state crime to block access to abortion clinics. Although it
is already a federal crime , federal law enforcement officials say
they do not have the manpower to enforce the law. As a result,
Democrats have repeatedly proposed a state law that could be
enforced by local authorities _ only to see their efforts blocked
by Republicans who control the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Republicans passed a clinic access bill, but only
after tying it to additional penalties that they have been seeking
for stalking. Initially, Democrats voiced grave concerns about the
stalking proposal, saying it was so broadly worded that it could
lead people to be prosecuted for loitering or for ordinary
disagreements. But Democrats now say they are open to adopting a
more precisely worded stalking law, in exchange for the Senate's
support for their clinic access legislation. The two sides are
negotiating the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and legislative leaders are also close to agreement
on a plan to give the courts new powers to force the mentally ill
into treatment against their will. The plan would allow judges to
hospitalize people temporarily if they had a history of violence or
had been hospitalized before for mental illness and refused to
follow their prescribed treatment, aides involved in the talks
said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal has come under intense attacks from some advocates
for the mentally ill, but Pataki and legislative leaders have
removed just about every major obstacle that had held up a final
agreement. The one hurdle left is the question of whether the state
would oversee and pay for court-ordered counseling and other
treatment. Democrats want the state to assume that responsibility,
but Pataki would pass it on to local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Another focus of intense negotiations is a proposal to revamp
the state's program for educating disabled students. Aides to
Pataki and legislative leaders said they were close to a deal that
would overhaul the special education program to remove the
financial incentive to place disabled students in classes limited
to special education students.
</P>
<P>
   The program has been criticized as being a dumping ground,
particularly for black and Hispanic boys in New York City.
Lawmakers have argued for years over proposals for changing the
program but are now facing a threat by federal officials to cut off
hundreds of millions of dollars in aid if they do not end what are
seen as discriminatory practices.
</P>
<P>
   All sides also say they expect a deal to reinstate a law that
protects about 10,000 loft residents, most of them living in lower
Manhattan. The law expired in June, leaving loft dwellers
vulnerable to eviction proceedings from landlords who have long
lobbied for a repeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
