<HEADLINE>
BILLS THE NEW YORK LEGISLATURE WILL BE CONSIDERING 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-LEGIS) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following are measures that Gov. George Pataki and the New
York Legislature are seeking to adopt before the 1999 legislative
session ends.
</P>
<P>
   TREATMENT LAW: Would let courts force mental patients to accept
treatment against their will.
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL EDUCATION: Would remove the fiscal incentive for schools
to place disabled students in separate classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   NASSAU BAILOUT: Would let the county adopt a new tax on real
estate sales to plug a hole in its budget.
</P>
<P>
   DNA FINGERPRINTING: Would give law enforcement officials greater
authority to collect DNA samples from felons and to log the samples
into a statewide computer system.
</P>
<P>
   CLINIC ACCESS: Would create new state penalties for blocking
access to abortion clinics.
</P>
<P>
   STALKING LAW: Would increase penalties for stalking.
</P>
<P>
   LOFT LAW: Would extend rent protections for loft dwellers, most
of whom live in Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
