<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALZBURG-OPERA-REVIEW-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CRONACA DEL LUOGO': PARADE OF IMAGES WITH A CHOICE OF MEANINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALZBURG, Austria _ Site-specific is a term more for architects
than musicians, but here at the Salzburg Festival, Luciano Berio
has carved an opera out of a particular space much as a Frank Lloyd
Wright might have shaped a house to the context of a hillside.
</P>
<P>
   Carved is also the word for the theater itself: the
Felsenreitschule, whose stage burrows into rock face and leaves us
something dark, cool, resonant and ordered with three tiers of
stone galleries. Berio's operas and especially his new one,
``Cronaca del Luogo,'' or ``Chronicle of the Place,'' have never
suffered from lack of ambition, and in this unusual place
cosmological topics are argued between a wall and a stage, or
plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Theatricality and melodrama, hallmarks of the Italian tradition,
are by no means dead, although here Berio has lifted the usual
historical struggle and domestic violence to the world of ideas.
His last opera, ``Outis,'' at La Scala in Milan three years ago,
pondered the mysteries of being a non-being with the story of
Ulysses as backdrop. In ``Cronaca,'' which played here on Sunday
night, the Old Testament becomes a receptacle for memory.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least that is what I think it does. Linear  &UR;  &LR; argument is
out; plot is out. If there is explication to be had, it is left to
the accompanying written commentaries. To the operagoer's customary
tools of eyes and ears add a pair of reading glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing the story line is a supermarket of metaphor. A general
discourses with an angel and takes off his shoes; a construction
foreman propounds in gibberish; a klezmer trio wanders &UR;  &LR; the stage;
a girl plays hopscotch; doctors measure huddled choristers with
Auschwitz-like menace.
</P>
<P>
   We the consumers are left to make our way along Berio's shelves
full of goods, read the labels and pick the meanings we want. We
read in our program books that the wall represents permanence and,
for better or worse, authority, and that the plaza in front of it
stands for flux and uncertainty. The wall tells us what was and
remains, the plaza what is and might be.
</P>
<P>
   The wall is also God, unknowable and unnameable as Jewish belief
dictates. Repeated is the old Aristotelian distinction between
being and becoming. It is a long way from Donizetti's boy meets
girl, but maybe the best procedure is to listen first, look second
and think if you must.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As we work to decipher the images of ``Cronaca del Luogo,'' we
gradually notice that extraordinary music is being played. A huge,
brass-heavy orchestra has been dispatched piecemeal throughout the
galleries, intermittently visible from behind dark scrims. Singers
were in the wall as well, and whistling electronic effects emanate
from it.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the music moves in long, unbroken breaths: drones and
sustained chords with busy  &UR;  &LR; decoration played around them. The
colors are alternately exquisite and shattering. Another set of
commentators might have sent us in search of wholly different
meanings, but the music is incontrovertible. Indeed, the strongest
argument for the wall as fixed and permanent is the immovable
beauty of the sounds coming from it. The symbols and images played
out in front of them seem ephemeral in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing we have to a narrative glue is Hildegard
Behrens as the character R. (Is she Rahab, biblical prostitute of
Jericho? Who knows?) R wanders through the five scenes, more
moderator and editorialist than narrator. Berio's opera is
people-specific too. He intended the role for Miss Behrens, and her
obsessive intensity and slightly wasted soprano give R a ravaged
and desperate air.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, the part of Nino seems fitted precisely to the
flamboyant vocalises of David Moss. Frode Olsen is the General and
Matthias Klink is Phanuel, but this is a piece more for ensembles
than individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Claus Guth's direction moves choristers across a wide stage with
ritual gravity and spastic gestures. Christian Schmidt's set is a
tree, a pile of rocks, many trap doors and not much else. His
costumes are casual street dress and only occasionally costumes at
all.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra, if scattered, is huge. Anchors here are
Klangforum Wien and the Arnold Schoenberg Choir. Organizing all
this multiplicity and space makes the conductor's podium a command
post, and Sylvain Cambreling, after more than 250 hours of
rehearsal going back to the spring, achieves feats of organization.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's performance may have been more representative
than the one a few days ago, when Berio, without informing
Cambreling and much to his dismay, entered the control room and did
some impromptu adjusting of electronic levels.
</P>
<P>
   After a reportedly stiff confrontation, composer apparently
conceded to conductor. Perhaps compositions, like children, are to
be raised, nurtured and then let go. Parents, on the other hand,
find that hard to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
