<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SHOOT-VICTIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUSTOMERS AND FRIENDS MOURN A VICTIM OF THE ATLANTA MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Inside the neighborhood grocery, one of those few
places left in the South where neck bones and collard greens are
not considered especially exotic, the air-conditioning created a
cool oasis Sunday on Ashby Street, in Atlanta's West End.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the heat radiating off the black tar of the
parking lot, people at Great Savings grocery chose to linger
outside, looking at a tribute to a dead man scrawled on white
butcher paper and taped to the storefront window.
</P>
<P>
   Every few minutes someone would walk up with a pen and add words
of praise to Allen Tenenbaum, a 48-year-old son of an old Atlanta
Jewish family who had owned this store in a black neighborhood and
made lifelong friends here.
</P>
<P>
   Tenenbaum, a day trader who was president of his synagogue, was
one of the nine people shot to death in Atlanta's Buckhead
neighborhood on Thursday by Mark Barton, who later took his own
life.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the West End, Tenenbaum won his employees' and his
customers' respect over the decades by treating them with kindness
and mopping up messes himself when someone would break a jelly jar
in the grocery aisles.
</P>
<P>
   Barton's rampage, which had begun earlier in the week with the
slayings of his wife and two children, robbed this neighborhood of
one of its oldest friends, and as the neighbors here lined up to
sign their names to the giant sympathy card, people shook and bowed
their heads, and wondered, like everyone else in Atlanta, why such
insanity had enveloped them.
</P>
<P>
   Fanny Lyons, 65, just signed ``Fanny.'' She thought about it for
a few moments and then added, ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew him since he was a little boy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some people just signed their name, as ``Slick'' did, and others
wrote long passages. Almost all of them mentioned God, and asked
God to look over him. It did not matter that Tenenbaum was Jewish.
In the West End, it was the African Methodist Episcopal God that
people begged to welcome him. The people who knew him the longest
here said he would not mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny,'' said John Norwood, 59, who used to be a boxer before
age took his right, and his left. ``You'd expect it here. It
happens here, in a poor neighborhood.'' But the man everyone in the
neighborhood just calls Allen had never been afraid here, even with
the crime and the poverty, even though his skin was not the same
color as the people who worked for him, as the people who shopped
in his store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to work here,'' wrote one mourner. ``He was a fair and
caring man.'' It was signed ``Dayna.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as mourners honored him in their own way at his small
grocery, Tenenbaum's Jewish friends prayed for him and remembered
him in their own way in a special memorial service; he had been
buried on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The killing brought soul-searching to churches across Georgia
Sunday, and at the Lizella Baptist Church, near Macon, there was a
special anguish. A funeral was held there Sunday for the first of
Barton's victims, his wife, Leigh Ann, who grew up in Macon and was
killed with a hammer last Tuesday in her home in Stockbridge, a
suburb south of Atlanta. The Associated Press quoted the Rev. Doug
Davis as telling about 400 mourners at Mrs. Barton's funeral that
they should not allow ``her murder to cloud our memory of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, in this Atlanta neighborhood where money is tight, the
memory of Allen Tenenbaum was not clouded at all Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The neighbors on Ashby Street here were angry that Tenenbaum,
who had given food away when people were without money, had been
taken by a man to whom money seemed so important. Police have
speculated that Barton's rampage may have been brought on by his
anger and despondency over losing money in the stock market. Barton
had lost roughly $105,000 in 15 days of securities day trading that
began on June 9, said James Lee, the president of Momentum
Securities Inc., where Barton killed four people, in a letter to
the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The people who worked for Tenenbaum, who lived in Atlanta's
Crestwood Point neighborhood, said they were always impressed that
even though he came from a well-off family, he worked in the
grocery that had been in his family for a generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stocked the shelves, he picked paper up off the floors,''
said Roy Lango, 32, the market manager. ``If the floor needed
mopping, he would get up and do it himself. Every morning when he
came in, he spoke to me by name and every evening before he went
home he spoke to me by name. It meant a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't nothing about race here. We don't do that here.
Now, we're just trying to grieve,'' Lango said.
</P>
<P>
   The grocery, a neighborhood gathering place, would not have been
unique 30 years ago. But now, as mom-and-pop stores have given way
to supermarkets, pushing the door open into its cool interior is
like opening a window in time.
</P>
<P>
   Men and women with shopping carts ask each other how they are,
not out of obligatory politeness, but because they seem to really
want to know. ``How you doin','' said one middle-age woman to a man
passing time with the store's manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm blessed,'' the man said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, you are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The meat counter is stocked with the staples for backyard
barbecues _ chicken wings, big pork spare ribs, not in little
one-pound packages, but enough for a serious barbecue, enough for a
family. Tenenbaum had been just as much a fixture as the staples in
the counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allen grew up here,'' said Joseph Sutton, 45, a retired police
officer. ``He was real. He was the face you expected to see when
you walked in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the words of tribute on the butcher paper taped to the
window kept growing. ``We love you always,'' wrote ``Sara &AMP; Rick.''
Under that, someone had just signed ``Joe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
