<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YANKEES PUT PETTITTE ON THE PLANK FOR MOTIVATION
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Can you imagine what the last month has been like for
Andy Pettitte? Three seasons ago he was a runner-up for a Cy Young
Award; 10 months ago he was helping to shut out the San Diego
Padres and complete a World Series sweep for the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Pettitte is a Yankee by the slender thread of Joe Torre's
faith that his 27-year-old pitcher will pull out of a deepening
funk.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with Andy Pettitte? That question has resonated for
weeks before Saturday night's trading deadline, and everyone has an
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   All Pettitte knows for sure is that he found himself walking the
Boss' plank, and it wasn't a great feeling. I happen to think the
Yankees sent him down the plank with no real intention of pushing
him over _ trading him _ but rather with the idea of giving
Pettitte something to think about. The Boss' idea of motivation.
</P>
<P>
   So the Yankees gave the serious, perfectionist left-hander the
opportunity to agonize, fret and beat himself up. He obliged.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte is making $5.95 million this season and could make more
next year when he is eligible for salary arbitration. When the
subject of money came up earlier this week, George Steinbrenner
scoffed and said, ``How can he look at that after the type of year
he's having now?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Boss has it all wrong; maybe Pettitte figured out
as much when he was out there on the plank. You can argue that the
Yankees are still paying Pettitte for what he did in 1996, when he
nearly won the Cy Young Award and won Game 5 of the World Series
with a shut out against Atlanta's John Smoltz. The Yankees are
still paying Pettitte for last October, when he outdueled Kevin
Brown in Game 4 to complete the World Series sweep. The Yankees
aren't really paying Pettitte for this season, which still has 60
games to go.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said as much when he came to Pettitte's defense. Torre
said he could not defend what Pettitte has done so far this season,
``I can only defend what he's done in the past, and what he can do
to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week in the heat of trade talk, Steinbrenner said that
Pettitte had had ``plenty of opportunities to show us he's getting
better'' and added, ``I've been saying all along they've got to get
him straightened out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the Boss said: ``He should be very relieved that certain
people have put faith in him. Our manager seems to think things are
all right. I have great confidence in my manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday afternoon, the Yankees' principal owner, asked again
about Pettitte said, ``He should be very relieved that certain
people have put faith in him.''
</P>
<P>
   The sensitive Pettitte was not encouraged by the Boss'
ambivalence. He lamented, ``You want your owner to want you
around.'' But if they didn't want him around, they would have
pushed him overboard.
</P>
<P>
   The Pettitte issue has caused an internal debate. Last week
against Chicago, he allowed eight hits and three runs in three and
a third innings against the Chicago White Sox. ``The other day I
wasn't pleased with what he did,'' Torre said, ``but it doesn't
mean I want to trade him.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the sudden infatuation with Hideki Irabu this season,
these are the facts: Pettitte is a powerful 27-year-old left-hander
with 75 victories in less than five full seasons with the Yankees.
He was a crucial piece of two Yankee championship teams. Right now
he's an emotional adjustment from getting back on track. Don't be
fooled: a lot of teams will be willing to take Pettitte off the
Yankees hands eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the carefree Jim Leyritz is back in town for his second
tour of duty, the Yankees hope that he can remind Pettitte of the
good times in 1996 when they were teammates and Leyritz was
Pettitte's personal catcher. Leyritz probably won't catch Pettitte
much this season, but his loose personality might help Pettitte
unwind, loosen up.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, in 1996 Leyritz tied Game 4 of the World Series with a
home run; the Yankees went on to win 8-6 in 10 innings and Leyritz
was hailed as the Yankee hero. Two months later he an Anaheim
Angel, having been traded.
</P>
<P>
   Before Leyritz back to New York he was in Boston for a brief
spell last year. The cumulative effects of the trades and movement
has made Leyritz become a lot looser about the business of baseball
than Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday Leyritz said he was happy to be a Yankee again. But
last year he was happy to be with San Diego, and three seasons ago
he was happy to be with Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte has to loosen up, stop banging his head against the
wall. ``He just has to get comfortable,'' catcher Jorge Posada
said. ``Don't try to strike out every hitter, when you're not a
strikeout pitcher. He's a perfectionist. He tries hard every time
out there. Sometimes you just have to lay back a little and
relax.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a difficult order when you're standing on the edge of the
plank and the sharks are waiting. But Andy Pettitte's not on the
plank anymore, and he won't be again. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
