</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH BAT AND ARM, METS' MAHOMES ENDS LONG WILD GAME WITH AUTHORITY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Pat Mahomes has resurrected his career with the New
York Mets this season as a long reliever, and he looked like an
improbable hero Sunday when his run-scoring single in the top of
the 13th inning gave the Mets their third lead of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But there would be one more twist in this 4-hour-25-minute
roller coaster of a game at Wrigley Field. In the bottom of the
inning, the Cubs reliever Scott Sanders, batting because his team
had run out of position players, lined a double off the wall in
left field with two outs. The Mets appealed, claiming Sanders had
missed first base _ it would have been an appropriate way for the
game to end _ but were overruled.
</P>
<P>
   So Mahomes, who turns 29 next week, struck out Jeff Reed on a
2-2 pitch. And then Mahomes, who spent last season exiled in Japan,
let out a loud whoop to let everyone know that his once-promising
career was back on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked so hard to get back and it seems like it's all paying
off,'' Mahomes said after the 5-4 victory. ``The 5-0 record and the
hitting, all that's a plus. I'm just trying to re-establish
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes, who pitched four and two-thirds innings on Friday to
earn a victory, is batting four for 10 with three runs batted in in
his first season in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Granted, I haven't hit in nine years, but I've always been
able to hit pretty well,'' he said. ``I knew I wasn't going to
strike out.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory kept the Mets a half-game behind the Atlanta Braves
in the National League East.
</P>
<P>
   The early candidate for Mets hero was Al Leiter, who had a
career-high 15 strikeouts and gave up just two hits in his seven
innings. He left with a 3-2 lead. But on Armando Benitez's first
pitch in the bottom of the ninth, Henry Rodriguez drilled a
game-tying home run into the wind blowing in from center field. It
was the struggling Benitez's fifth blown save of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets regained the lead in the top of the 10th on Edgardo
Alfonzo's sacrifice fly. But after Chicago loaded the bases in the
bottom of the inning _ with the help of two walks by Benitez _
first baseman John Olerud made a rare error that allowed another
tying run to score and made the afternoon even longer.
</P>
<P>
   For Benitez, who cost Leiter a victory for the second time this
month, it was a third consecutive perplexing performance. In those
three appearances he has allowed four runs, five hits and six walks
in two and two-thirds innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just has a little thing,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said of
Benitez. ``Hopefully, Armando will get it out of the way and regain
his dominating form of all season, except for these last three
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Leiter's dominance Sunday _ his 15 strikeouts were the
most by a Mets pitcher since David Cone struck out 19 at
Philadelphia on Oct. 6, 1991 _ he did not get the Mets' first
complete game of the season. He threw 135 pitches before being
removed, 31 pitches in the fifth inning when the Cubs pieced
together three consecutive two-out hits for two runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had a lot of strikeouts, so my pitch count would be
up,'' said Leiter, whose previous strikeout high was 11, which he
had accomplished five times. ``Fifteen strikeouts, a couple of
walks and a lot of 3-2 counts, it's kind of hard to pitch a
complete game.''
</P>
<P>
   The length of the game allowed three of the Mets' new players,
picked up in trading-deadline deals Saturday night, to contribute
right away. Darryl Hamilton, acquired in the trade that sent Brian
McRae to Colorado, started in center field, and his run-scoring
single in the sixth gave the Mets their 3-2 lead. Billy Taylor,
acquired from Oakland, retired Sammy Sosa on a meek grounder to
first with runners on first and second in the 10th. And reliever
Chuck McElroy, also newly arrived from Colorado, began the 11th and
retired all five batters he faced before Mahomes came on in the
12th.
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes gave up just Sanders's double in his one and a third
innings, and his own bloop hit off Sanders (4-5) just evaded a
diving Rodriguez's grasp in short left center. It drove in Roger
Cedeno, who had doubled into the left-field corner to lead off the
Mets' 13th, and made the Mets 57-1 this season when leading after
eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really tired,'' Valentine said after the Mets escaped
Wrigley Field with two victories in three games _ the shortest of
which was 3 hours 29 minutes. ``Two real hot days, and one real
long one.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
