<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CALLAWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMUEL RODGER CALLAWAY, 85, RETIRED BANKING EXECUTIVE
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Samuel Rodger Callaway, a retired executive vice
president and chief trust officer of the Morgan Guaranty Trust Co.
of New York, died July 24 at Danbury Hospital. A former resident of
Cold Spring Harbor, N.Y., he was 85 and lived in Southbury, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Callaway was in charge of the bank's Investment and Trust
Division from 1968 until he retired in 1976 after 40 years of
service. He oversaw the division's move in 1974 from Wall Street to
modern quarters at 9 West 57th St..
</P>
<P>
   A Manhattan native, he graduated from Harvard in 1936 and joined
JP Morgan &AMP; Co. that year. He moved to the investment branch in
1942, served in the Navy in World War II, and rose to assistant
vice president at the company.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected a senior vice president at Morgan Guaranty Trust
in 1967 and became an executive vice president the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Callaway is survived by his wife of 62 years, Dorothy Harding
Callaway; two daughters, Joan Pratt of Brentwood, N.H., and Dorothy
Munson of Richmond, Mass.; a son, Samuel R. Jr., of Redding, Conn.;
seven grandchildren, and three great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
