<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1997 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-WOMEN-SPI &LR;      08-01 1582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-WOMEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY WOMEN, AND DOCTORS, UNAWARE OF HEART DISEASE RISK IN WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SARAH SKIDMORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Carolyn Day thought she had a sinus infection. The
pressure around her eyes and ears throbbed all day. Close to
midnight, a sudden pressure in her chest grabbed her attention.
</P>
<P>
   Day had experienced only limited health problems during her 65
years. But she instinctively knew something was wrong, and told her
son to take her to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   At Overlake Hospital in Bellevue, Wash., a suburb of Seattle,
she found out the blood vessels that serve as pathways to and from
her heart were seriously blocked. The doctors performed a
triple-bypass surgery at 7:30 the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking it was heart problems because my symptoms
didn't seem right,'' Day said. ``I didn't have the pain going to
the shoulder and I didn't have the gripping chest pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Day is one of millions of women who suffer from problems with
heart disease in the United States. Like Day, many are unaware of
their risks, and unaware that their symptoms can vary from those of
men.
</P>
<P>
   The American Heart Association lists heart disease as the No. 1
cause of death for both men and women in America. Yet heart attack,
stroke and other cardiovascular diseases have killed more women
than men every year since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, however, heart disease was considered a male
problem. Even many medical professionals remained unaware of the
high risk for women.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Hammond of The Hope Heart Institute, a
cardiovascular disease research center in Seattle, attributes the
lack of awareness to training and research oversights.
</P>
<P>
   Reports such as the Framingham Study, a commonly cited report on
heart disease, focused primarily on early onset of heart attacks
and heart disease. That almost eliminates women, since the majority
of heart problems occur in women after menopause.
</P>
<P>
   In the 45-to-64 age range, 1 in 10 women has some form of heart
disease. These odds increase to 1 in 5 women 65 and older,
according to the national Heart, Lung and Blood Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Hammond said awareness of women's risks for heart disease is
increasing among medical professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the past five to eight years, doctors are becoming
drastically much more aware,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sarah Speck, chief of cardiology at Seattle's Swedish
Medical Center and director of the Dean Ornish Program for
Reversing Heart Disease, said one reason women's risks have been
overlooked is that their conditions may differ from men's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think physicians and providers now know that the risk
factors are equivalent in men and women,'' Speck said. ``However,
women's symptoms are different and that's where the level of
awareness needs to be raised in the public and the medical
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical signs of a heart attack include: repetitive pressure or
squeezing in the chest; shooting pain to shoulder, arms and neck;
sweating; shortness of breath.
</P>
<P>
   Women, however, may experience additional symptoms, including:
stomach pain or nausea, unexplained fatigue, racing heart rate and
jaw pain.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, most women do not seek help until two to six hours
after the first symptoms, according to Speck. This cuts into
valuable time when a patient could be saved or serious damage to
the heart prevented.
</P>
<P>
   Men seek help more quickly because they are more aware of
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think women don't complain about their health ailments often
and they don't seek medical attention as often as they need to,''
Speck said. ``If you have the risks ... you need to think of heart
disease first.''
</P>
<P>
   Those risks include a family history of heart disease, diabetes,
high blood pressure, high cholesterol levels, and use of oral
contraceptives, tobacco and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Women who do suffer from heart attacks are also more likely to
die than men. According to a recent study conducted by Yale
researchers, 17 percent of female heart attack victims die while
still in the hospital; only 12 percent of men do.
</P>
<P>
   For women younger than 50, the odds are even more skewed. Only 3
percent of men die and 6 percent of women do.
</P>
<P>
   Heart attacks among young women are especially rare _ one reason
they may be misdiagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   Corrine DeJong, 28, was watching a high-school basketball game
in 1988 at Ferndale High School in Ferndale, Wash., when chest
pains grabbed her attention.
</P>
<P>
   The pains grew sharper. She was having difficulty breathing. The
17-year-old DeJong ran outside. It was raining and cold, but she
felt fiery hot. Sweat poured from her skin. A friend saw DeJong
leave and followed her.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the gym, DeJong blacked out and fell to the ground, but
she could hear someone say she was going to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   At the hospital, the medical staff told her she was fine. DeJong
said one doctor told her she had heartburn and sent her home with
Maalox. He suggested the reason she passed out was because she was
flustered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was embarrassed because the doctor made me feel like I was
an idiot,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   DeJong's episodes continued with varying frequency and intensity
for two years. She went from being outgoing and athletic to
becoming a social recluse who couldn't jog to the mailbox without
her heart racing uncontrollably.
</P>
<P>
   At times she would experience chest pains or shortness of breath
several times a day.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of what she calls ``living hell,'' Dr. James
Brodie of Seattle's Providence Medical Center examined her and
correctly diagnosed her heart problem in just 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Several tests confirmed DeJong suffered from a heart murmur, an
arrhythmia and a condition called vasovagal syncope, which causes
veins to constrict and make her pass out.
</P>
<P>
   The problems are not immediately life-threatening, but life as a
``normal'' person will never be in DeJong's future. Her heart beats
faster than most and she cannot pursue many athletic hobbies she
used to enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   DeJong, is small-framed, 5-foot-7 and 125 pounds. Her curly
brown hair and bright hazel eyes complement a glowing complexion _
hardly the typical picture of someone with heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not your classic heart patient,'' said DeJong. ``I've
never smoked, I'm not male, I'm young, I'm not overweight, I look
fairly healthy, but I am not.''
</P>
<P>
   She attends massage school and volunteers for the American Heart
Association to help raise awareness of heart disease. She said her
experience can help others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what was going on inside me was not right and I want to
reach the women whose doctor or boyfriend or family, whoever, is
telling them they are all right when they know they are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the women that stop going to the doctor and those
are the women who end up dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Awareness is key to women at risk of heart disease. They can
reduce the chance of disease by analyzing personal risk factors,
avoiding high-risk behavior and being conscious of danger signs.
This can mean everything from eating a healthy diet to asking the
doctor the right questions.
</P>
<P>
   One person who wishes she had asked more questions is Carolyn
Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize now I should have been more aware,'' she said.`` I
was at risk and I didn't know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Day paid the price. For six weeks after her surgery, she could
sleep only on her back. Simple movements were difficult and
painful. Even sitting down or getting up from a chair was
excruciating. The pain in her chest from the massive surgery was
numbed by medication that left her in a daze much of the time.
However, by recognizing that something was wrong, she avoided what
could have been a serious heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the behaviors that lead to her problem, Day has set
out to regain control of her life. Since her surgery in April, she
has quit smoking and started exercising. As a patient of a cardiac
rehabilitation program at Evergreen Hospital Medical Center in
Kirkland, she walks on a treadmill and rides a bike machine.
</P>
<P>
   She is starting to forfeit some of the meats and cheeses she
loves and is eating more vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of lifestyle changes, Day said she is feeling better
than she did before the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Tips on lowering risk
</P>
<P>
   One in 5 women in the United States has some sort of heart
disease. Women can lower their risks by:
</P>
<P>
   _Exercising. Physical activity can strengthen the cardiovascular
system and help control weight, blood pressure, diabetes, and
cholesterol levels. While regular vigorous activity is encouraged,
even low levels can be beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   _Eating right. Eat a well-rounded, moderate, healthy diet. Find
information from heart-disease institutes, doctors or dietitians on
heart-healthy eating.
</P>
<P>
   _Stop smoking. Regardless of how long you have smoked, quitting
will still drastically reduce your risks.
</P>
<P>
   _Limit drinking. Limit alcohol intake to a moderate level.
</P>
<P>
   _Take hormones. Use hormone replacement therapy if your
physician finds it a suitable treatment.
</P>
<P>
   _Limit stress. Find healthy ways to cope with stress.
</P>
<P>
   Resources are available in print and online for more information
about heart disease and women.
</P>
<P>
   The American Heart Association:
http://www.women.americanheart.org or at 800-242-8721.
</P>
<P>
   The Heart, Blood and Lung Institute:
http://www.nhlbi.nih.gov/nhlbi/nhlbi.htm
</P>
<P>
   The National Health Information Center:
http://nhic-nt.health.org or 800-597-6300.
</P>
