<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1998 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELEVISION-FUTURE-HDT     08-01 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEVISION-FUTURE-HDTV </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO VALLEY BLOOMS IN THE GARDEN STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAN FOST  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
PRINCETON, N.J. _ The future of television technology is springing
from labs in New Jersey's Video Valley.
<P>
   In the Garden State, where television itself was born and then
given color, engineers are toiling to develop equipment for the
coming age of digital high-definition television.
</P>
<P>
   That's right: Don't think of New Jersey as a place 3,000 miles
from Silicon Valley innovation, the burial ground of mobsters and
industrial waste, the butt of bad jokes on ``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, think of it as the state where Edison and Einstein
promulgated their greatest achievements, where Bell Labs invented
the transistor, and where proximity to TV network headquarters in
Manhattan has drawn many of the leading TV hardware-makers to set
up elite research labs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge research-and-development and industrial
tradition in New Jersey,'' said Alex Magoun, curator at Sarnoff
Corp.'s museum. ``This is the birthplace of America's second
industrial revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Just outside of Princeton, Sarnoff Corp. occupies the same
sprawling headquarters it has had since 1942.
</P>
<P>
   It was there that Sarnoff, originally founded as RCA
Laboratories, invented the color television tube, the liquid
crystal display (or LCD) and technology that made video cameras
possible.
</P>
<P>
   And it's there that Sarnoff is now working on a host of new
technologies, including the HDTV sets that promise sharper, more
detailed images than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   HDTV will bring cinema-quality pictures to television, with
broadcasts twice the quality of conventional TV and CD-quality
sound. The federal government is requiring all broadcasts by 2006
to be in HDTV, and the phase-in has already begun in San Francisco
and other cities, albeit slowly.
</P>
<P>
   The people at Sarnoff who work on HDTV are drawing on a
tradition of 18-hour days, where the mandate was results and the
employees were driven to invent new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain cultures that permeate organizations, and
that's the special thing about Sarnoff as it exists today,'' said
Glenn Reitmeier, a Sarnoff vice president and one of the country's
leading advocates of HDTV. ``It still astounds me what the
inventors of (the original television standards) were able to do
with a handful of tubes.''
</P>
<P>
   Their innovation lasted 50 years, Reitmeier said, crossing from
vacuum tubes to transistors to integrated circuits. Now, Reitmeier
and others in the HDTV business have finally come up with a new
standard. ``I hope it lasts 50 years, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With such companies as Sarnoff in New Jersey, other firms _ most
notably Japanese consumer electronics conglomerates _ have
established similar laboratories devoted to the changing nature of
television.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp Electronics Corp. has its U.S. headquarters in Mahwah,
N.J. NEC, a $40 billion Japanese company, has a research lab near
Princeton. Panasonic, Sony, Siemens, Toshiba, Hitachi America,
Samsung Electronics _ all maintain a significant presence in New
Jersey's so-called ``Video Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Having so many big players in one region ``really helped speed
things in the early stages of this digital television era,'' said
Chris Pfaff, spokesperson for Lucent Digital Video, a division of
Lucent Technologies in Murray Hill, N.J. Lucent still maintains
Bell Labs, which conducts some video research, although it's mostly
focused on telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Panasonic, a division of the Japanese giant Matsushita Electric
Industrial Co., has its New Jersey headquarters in the oft-maligned
city of Secaucus, at the edge of the Meadowlands. But in Burlington
on the other side of the state, near where George Washington
crossed the Delaware River, Panasonic established a small lab for
advanced video research.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is exploding,'' said Jukka Hamalainen, president of
the lab. ``We are growing like crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   At the lab, Panasonic is working on plasma screens, sleek thin
televisions that now cost a small fortune but look great in a
living room. Other engineers are midwifing the convergence between
televisions and personal computers, trying to bring HDTV broadcasts
to the PC.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, HDTV will make the picture better, but some argue
that's not really what's wrong with television. Almost proving the
point, the Panasonic engineers work by day, testing TVs
broadcasting couples smooching on soap operas and a Jerry Springer
episode titled ``Guess What ... I'm Really a Woman!''
</P>
<P>
   But programming isn't Panasonic's forte. Instead, Hamalainen,
68, talks about his beginnings in television as a college student
in Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Hamalainen and his brother-in-law pioneered the first television
broadcasts in Finland in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia had started the first television transmissions in
Estonia,'' only 60 miles from Helsinki, Hamalainen said. ``We
wanted to be sure Russian-type televisions were not sold in
Finland. We felt part of the Western world. It was totally
political.''
</P>
<P>
   He ultimately went to work for RCA, first in Europe, and later
in New Jersey. But in 1985, with RCA's best days behind it,
Hamalainen retired _ and took over a Panasonic lab with a mere
three people in it.
</P>
<P>
   He saw the chance for innovation like in the early days.
``Everything I wanted to do was digital,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the U.S. Federal Communications Commission is mandating
the adoption of digital high-definition television, Hamalainen is
once again at the forefront.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a renaissance of sorts for Sarnoff Corp., which keeps
itself out of the limelight but has placed its technology in many
common appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Sarnoff bears the name of ``General'' David Sarnoff _ he earned
the honorific after helping the Army establish a communications
system in World War II, and forever after insisted on being called
``General.'' He was a Russian immigrant who clawed his way up
through the American Marconi Wireless Telegraph Co., largely by
pushing the idea of using the radio as a broadcast medium.
</P>
<P>
   Although the General died in 1971 and the labs foundered in the
years that followed, the emergence of HDTV has spurred a
renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   The company now has 630 people busily working in labs along the
corridors of its Princeton campus, with a range of video
innovations in the works: boxes to convert HDTV broadcasts for
existing analog television sets, videoscopes that analyze
mammograms and help in the treatment of breast cancer, controls of
movement in handheld video cameras that create dazzling freeze
frames and isolated video scenes, and technology that warplanes use
to monitor their targets, which was most recently on display in the
Predator plane used in the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But for Glenn Reitmeier and his team _ and for the millions of
television-watching Americans _ HDTV is the thing.
</P>
<P>
   And for those skeptics who doubt whether it will happen, noting
HDTV sets that now cost about $6,000 and an extreme shortage of
high-definition programming, Reitmeier is willing to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the industry is off to a pretty good start,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's already moving on to newer technologies: ``It's so
revolutionary, there are so many possibilities,'' he said. ``We now
have to figure out what's the best way to take advantage of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
