<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEVISION2-FUTURE-SIDEBAR </SLUG>
  
THE FATHER OF NEW JERSEY'S TV CONNECTION &HT;    By DAN FOST
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCETON, N.J. _ This state owes its standing as the
headquarters of the digital television revolution to a Russian
immigrant who died nearly 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Although he wasn't a technologist himself, David Sarnoff had the
vision and ambition to pull off some of technology's greatest
achievements of the 20th century: radio, television, color
television, fax machines. And along the way he spawned today's No.
1 television network, NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Sarnoff arrived in the United States at age 9, knowing no
English, and ``he didn't have a head for math,'' said Alex Magoun,
the curator of the museum at Sarnoff Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But he did talk his way into a job sweeping floors at the
American Marconi Wireless Telegraph Co., according to Joel Brinkley
in the book ``Defining Vision,'' and he never looked back. In 1912,
he received the first radio distress signals from the doomed ship
Titanic. By the time he was 24, Sarnoff persuaded Marconi that
radio could be more than just communication between two people _
that it could send music and information to hundreds of thousands
of people, thus sparking radio's golden age.
</P>
<P>
   Marconi Wireless eventually became RCA, which launched NBC as a
radio broadcasting network in 1926, Magoun said. By 1930, Sarnoff
was running the company.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, he built his crown jewel: the research labs outside
Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's greatest concentration of tech work is now done
along Route 1, a crowded highway that connects Rutgers and
Princeton universities.
</P>
<P>
   The RCA labs _ now known as Sarnoff Corp. _ occupy the same huge
building that went up in 1942, on a grassy 300-acre campus.
</P>
<P>
   From the inside, it resembles a high school: long corridors
lined with brown linoleum. But behind the orange doors are
whiteboards chock full of algorithms and flow charts, and labs full
of the latest technology equipment.
</P>
<P>
   In those labs, color television was developed, as well as
technology that allowed wire services to transmit photos to
newspapers _ the genesis of the modern fax machine.
</P>
<P>
   Sarnoff had already debuted television at the New York World's
Fair in 1939, and in the following years, he transformed his NBC
radio network into a TV network. ``He literally invented the
concept of network broadcasting,'' said Sarnoff spokesman Tom
Lento.
</P>
<P>
   The lab was Sarnoff's love, much to Wall Street's consternation.
``RCA never declared very big dividends,'' Magoun said. ``They
poured a lot of money into the labs. Sarnoff would say, `We have
sound, let's make it better. Let's add light to sound.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sarnoff had enough of an ego that he insisted people call him
``General,'' even though he earned the title more for technological
contributions than for moving up the ranks of the military.
</P>
<P>
   But his ego also meant that he never groomed a successor. Magoun
said that in 1971, when Sarnoff died and his son took over the
company, ``that's when people say RCA fell off the technology
map.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, General Electric acquired RCA, but split the company
up. It sold the consumer electronics business to Thomson, which
still makes products under the RCA brand. It kept the appliance
business and the NBC television network. And it donated the labs to
a Silicon Valley nonprofit: SRI of Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Sarnoff remains the for-profit division of SRI,
developing technology and licensing it to others without really
caring whether its brand reaches the public.
</P>
<P>
   And in the ground floor of its headquarters, Sarnoff's monument
survives, with old picture tubes, plaques and portraits, and a bust
of the man they called ``General.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
