religious right in national and local politics, is now weathering
serious financial and leadership turmoil that could affect its
ability to exert widespread influence in the 2000 election.
(Kirsten Elstner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PORTSMOUTH, Va. -- Aug. 1, 1999 -- CHESAPEAKE-BAY-2,
8-01 -- Marine scientists examine man-made reef along Chesapeake
Bay. Oysters filter impurities from the water, a process that
scientists say would help clean the bay. A new consensus report by
the bay's principal scientists, after years of life-support
experimentation on the once supreme Chesapeake Bay oyster, has
recommended an all-out commitment to three-dimensional reef
construction, as the key to restoring the oyster to its central
place in the life of the bay. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PORTSMOUTH, Va. -- Aug. 1, 1999 -- CHESAPEAKE-BAY-1,
8-01 -- Man-made reefs, like this one on a branch of the Elizabeth
River, are the foundation of a plan to restore the oyster
population of Chesapeake Bay. A new consensus report by the bay's
principal scientists, after years of life-support experimentation
on the once supreme Chesapeake Bay oyster, has recommended an
all-out commitment to three-dimensional reef construction, as the
key to restoring the oyster to its central place in the life of the
bay. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) PUEBLO, Colo. -- Aug. 1, 1999 -- AMTRAK-FAST-TRAIN, 8-01
-- Amtrak's new high-speed train, the Acela, being put through its
paces on a test track near Pueblo. Amtrak's first new train in a
generation, the fastest on the continent, is scheduled to be
zipping passengers past crowded streets, highways and runways from
Washington to Boston by the end of the year. (Kevin Moloney/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- Aug. 1, 1999 --
KOSOVO-VIOLENCE-2, 8-01 -- Ethnic Albanians walk past the Serbian
Orthodox Cathedral of Holy Salvation, after a thunderous explosion
damaged the interior of the cathedral and woke the city early
Sunday. The attack on the cathedral, which has been under
construction since 1981, follows several others on churches in
Kosovo, mostly on those built since 1981, when communist
restrictions were lifted and Serbian religious nationalism revived.
(Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- Aug. 1, 1999 --
KOSOVO-VIOLENCE-1, 8-01 -- A British soldier with NATO inspects the
half-built Serbian Orthodox Cathedral of Holy Salvation in
Pristina, after a thunderous explosion damaged the interior of the
cathedral and woke the city early Sunday. The attack follows
several others on churches in Kosovo, mostly on those built since
1981, when communist restrictions were lifted and Serbian religious
nationalism revived. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) MEXICO CITY -- Aug. 1, 1999 -- MEXICO-ZEDILLO-2, 8-01 --
Francisco Labastida Ochoa, the Interior Minister of Mexico, shown
in his campaign headquarters. President Ernesto Zedillo, who has
pledged to be the first incumbent not to choose a successor,
nonetheless favors Ochoa. (Wesley Bocxe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PUERTO DE MARQUEZ, Mexico -- Aug. 1, 1999 --
MEXICO-ZEDILLO-1, 8-01 -- Roberto Madrazo Pintado, 47, campaigning
in the tiny village of Puerto de Marquez for the presidential
nomination of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party in
Mexico. Madrazo leads in polls and is a rival of President Ernesto
Zedillo, who has pledged to be the first incumbent not to choose a
successor but favors the Interior Minister, Francisco Labastida
Ochoa. (Wesley Bocxe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 1, 1999 -- SCI-LIVER-SURGERY-2, 8-01 --
Members of the transplant team at Mount Sinai Hospital study liver
scans as they prepare for an operation involving the use of a
living donor to provide a liver transplant for an adult. The
operation involved Felicia LaBlanca, 50, a perfectly healthy woman,
and her older brother, John Vilardi, 54, whose cancerous liver was
to be removed and be replaced with 60 percent of her liver. (Angel
Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 1, 1999 -- SCI-LIVER-SURGERY-1, 8-01 --
John Vilardi, 54, and his sister, Felicia LaBanca, 50, before the
operation last Thursday at Mount Sinai Hospital, that gave part of
her liver to him. The daring procedure, the use of a living donor
to provide a liver transplant for an adult, has been performed
fewer than 100 times in the U.S. over the past year and a half, at
only a few medical centers. ``Take care of him,'' she told the
nurse who wheeled Vilardi away. ``Take care of her,'' he called to
the nurse attending to his sister. (Angel Franco/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 1, 1999 -- COBURN-PROFILE, 8-01 --
Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., has a reputation for independent
thinking. Rep. Coburn is also Dr. Coburn, a leader in the fight for
new patient protection in the era of managed care. Coburn, who
still practices medicine on weekends, is one of a handful of
Republican doctors in the House who are bucking their leadership
and much of their party to pursue a broader, tougher patients'
rights bill than the one recently passed by the Senate. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SAN FRANCISCO -- Aug. 1, 1999 -- HEWLETTPACKARD-AGILENT,
8-01 -- Edward W. Barnholt, 56, newly named head of Agilent
Technology, the Hewlett-Packard spinoff that will concentrate on
test equipment. Hewlett announced in March that it would spin off
the test-equipment business to shore up the company's core computer
and printer business. Since then, Barnholt, a former engineer with
decades of experience at Hewlett, has had the delicate task of
carving a new company out of one that is nearly 60 years old and is
among Silicon Valley's most revered institutions. (Peter Da
Silva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SAN FRANCISCO -- Aug. 1, 1999 -- INTERNET-NEWSCLIPERS,
8-01 -- Dave Pell, managing director of Arba Seed Investment Group
in San Francisco. Pell summarizes technology stories for more than
1,500 subscribers and publishes a free e-mail newsletter called
Davenetics. Pell started Davenetics in February with about 50
subscribers, after realizing that he often e-mailed his business
associates several times a day about news stories he had found.
Davenetics now has more than 1,500 subscribers. (Thor Swift/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
