<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2003 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     08-01 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY'S HOMER ELBOWS ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Todd Hundley knows the season is a long shot, but
for one at-bat Sunday he found the odds in his favor.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley had gone deep on Andy Benes before. A lot in fact. The
switch-hitting catcher saw left-hander Greg Swindell getting loose
in the Arizona bullpen with two on in the sixth inning but was
hoping to face Benes just one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Benes stayed in the game and Hundley won it with a three-run
homer that gave the Los Angeles Dodgers a 4-2 victory over the
first-place Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   It gave Hundley six homers in 48 career at-bats against Benes.
It also gave the last-place Dodgers a quick smile before leaving
town for 10 games, including the next seven against two of the
hottest teams in baseball, Houston and the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good to finally get one,'' Hundley said after the Dodgers had
dropped the first two games of the series. ``Especially heading out
on the road and with as good as the Diamondbacks are. It is good to
finally beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Why Hundley ever got the chance to bat in the sixth was curious.
Against left-handers, Hundley has just four hits in 33 at-bats.
When he faced Swindell the next inning, he struck out on three weak
swings.
</P>
<P>
   But Arizona manager Buck Showalter claims he was more concerned
with the Dodgers lifting Hundley for pinch-hitter Gary Sheffield, a
.309 hitter who did not start Sunday. Hundley was batting just .224
and seemed like a good bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had Sheffield, (Adrian) Beltre and (Angel) Pena on their
bench and I just as soon not put Sheffield in the game,'' Showalter
said.
</P>
<P>
   For a guy whose team came in with five consecutive victories and
10 in their last 12 games, it seemed like the kind of strategy that
works for winning teams. For the Dodgers, who had dropped 10 of 12,
it was a situation that has blown up all season.
</P>
<P>
   But after losing the first two games of the series, the Dodgers
showed surprising resiliency. Besides Hundley's homer, the play of
the day was a sliding catch by Dave Hansen near the Dodgers dugout.
Todd Hollandsworth also made a running catch at the railing in left
field.
</P>
<P>
   Devon White, who has raised his average 40 points since July 1,
had two more hits and glided to the center-field wall in the ninth
inning to take away extra bases from Matt Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Onan Masaoka (2-2) picked up for a struggling Chan
Ho Park in the sixth and pitched two scoreless innings. Jeff Shaw,
who had blown consecutive save opportunities, pitched a perfect
ninth for his 22nd save.
</P>
<P>
   And even Raul Mondesi, who has come under fire for two awful
months, returned after a day off to contribute two hits and a
stolen base.
</P>
<P>
   But for a team that has anxiously waited for Hundley to
contribute, this was his day.
</P>
<P>
   His 16th homer came on a 3-1 changeup by Benes (6-10) and
traveled 445 feet to dead center. To illustrate how desperately the
Dodgers need him, Hundley now has more home runs than any Dodgers
left-handed hitter since Darryl Strawberry hit 28 in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to see someone like Todd win a game like that,''
said Dave Hansen, who started for Beltre at third. ``He has worked
so hard to get back to where he is. This is good for him and the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's slow recovery from reconstructive elbow surgery has
been one of the factors in the Dodgers' miserable season. He
couldn't throw out baserunners, couldn't hit right-handed pitchers,
couldn't keep fans from wondering about last winter's three-way
trade with the Mets and Orioles that cost the Dodgers catcher
Charles Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Hundley lost his job to rookie Angel Pena and spent
nearly two weeks working solely with coach Rick Dempsey on his
throwing mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   His daily regimen still includes extensive weight training to
strengthen the elbow. Hundley did not emerge from the weight room
for nearly an hour after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knock on wood, my elbow has felt the best it has since I've
been 21 years old,'' Hundley said. ``We're over the hump and now
I've got to take care of it and protect it. I would like to wipe
out the first half of the season and mentally I have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
