<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2014 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLE-KAN &LR;      08-01 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDIT REPORTS GROWTH OF POLITICAL CONTRIBUTIONS BY GAMBLING
INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Contributions from the gambling industry to federal
election campaigns grew by 400 percent from 1992 to 1998, a rate 10
times that of political contributions overall, a new congressional
audit says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office said donations grew from $1.1
million to $5.7 million during a time of rapid gambling expansion
and deepening concern that Congress would further regulate and tax
the industry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In that same six-year period, contributions to federal campaigns
from all sources rose 38 percent, to $851 million, according to
data the General Accounting Office collected from the Center for
Responsive Politics. Thereport on gambling contributions was
requested by Rep. Frank R. Wolf, a Virginia Republican. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very troubling,'' Wolf said. ``You can see they are
trying to heavily influence Congress and both political parties. We
should be concerned when any industry does this.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The head of the leading lobbying group in Washington for
gambling said the industry is drawing unfair attention. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We make no apologies whatsoever for participating in the
political process,'' said Frank Fahrenkopf, president of the
American Gaming Association. ``We are going to do all we can to
make sure our employees and shareholders are heard.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fahrenkopf said the jump in donations is no surprise, because
the industry has grown so rapidly. In 1991, for example, Iowa had
the country's only riverboat casino and now there are dozens in six
states. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fahrenkopf noted that the General Accounting Office report said
the gambling industry ranked 37th among industries giving money to
political campaigns in 1998. The top sources of funds were lawyers,
at $59 million, and real estate companies, at $37 million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The gambling industry is still not going to hold a candle to
real estate, insurance, etc.'' said Elizabeth Schwefler, researcher
for the Center for Responsive Politics. ``But they are climbing the
ladder, bit by bit.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the gambling employees and political action committees
accounted for the highest contribution rate growth _ 83 percent _
among any private industry when compared with 1994, according to
the data. Similar comparisons are not yet available for 1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The contributions in the General Accounting Office report were
made to candidates or political party committees from employees or
political action committees of gambling interests. Of the $5.7
million given for the 1998 election cycle, $3.8 million was
so-called soft money, given to political parties to indirectly
benefit candidates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soft money contributions included almost $1.4 million to
Republican campaign committees at the national level and $850,000
to national committees for the Democrats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's Entertainment accounted for the most money overall from
gambling interests, at $533,090. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some gambling opponents in Missouri and elsewhere said
gambling's greater presence in politics shows that the industry is
concerned about the public putting more pressure on lawmakers to
rein in the industry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We take this as a compliment,'' said Bernie Horn,
communications director of the National Coalition Against Gambling
Expansion. ``It means they are substantially more worried we are
going to be successful in Washington.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Taylor, executive director of Casino Watch Inc. in
Missouri, agreed with Horn and said the report should raise public
concern. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows the growth that is taking place; it's just nice
to see the GAO put some numbers to it,'' Taylor said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State governments are primarily responsible for regulating
casinos, but Wolf and others have suggested Congress consider extra
taxes on gambling revenues, a ban on Internet gambling, a ban on
amateur sports betting and removal of some automated teller
machines from casinos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always watchful (of legislation) but we're no different
than any other industry,'' Fahrenkopf said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Wolf said gambling is different in that it leads to
addiction and can be corrupting because so much money is involved.
In addition, casinos can put restaurants, bowling alleys, theaters
and other ``good companies'' out of business, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the National Gambling Impact Study Commission
released a three-year study recommending a pause in the rapid
growth of gambling, even though it was described as a boon to local
economies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The commission recommended tighter restrictions on
casino-related campaign donations at the state and local level
because that is where casinos are regulated. Horn said that
gambling interests poured much more money into state and local
campaigns last year than into federal campaigns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are state legislatures that really bow down to the
gambling industry,'' Horn said. ``That really is not a problem in
Congress at this time.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said he is not recommending restrictions on gambling
donations to candidates for Congress but said there could be a
dramatic cut in the industry's influence by banning soft-money
donations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bans on soft-money contributions are expected to be a major
topic when campaign finance reform comes up for debate in Congress
later this year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 2300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990801.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2032 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RICKYWILLIAMS-HNS     08-01 1512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RICKYWILLIAMS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LA CROSSE, Wis. _ New Orleans Saints owner Tom Benson stands under
a shade tree trying to get some relief from the hellacious heat and
humidity. Although the temperature pushes the century mark, Benson
smiles like a proud father gazing at his newborn son for the first
time.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Just look at him,'' Benson says, nodding in the direction of
Ricky Williams, the Heisman Trophy-winning running back from the
University of Texas. ``He's already such a great asset for us and
the city of New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   A few yards away, outside the cafeteria on the University of
Wisconsin-La Crosse campus, Williams is signing autographs for fans
of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love him,'' Benson says. ``He's great with kids. The
day he came to us after the draft, he sat in the sun for 1{ hours
signing autographs. He's a superstar, but he's so natural about
everything, so down-to-earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams signs until a member of the Saints' media relations
department pulls him away and almost has to push him through the
cafeteria doors. Benson breaks into a satisfied smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really enjoyed Ricky's company,'' Benson says. ``He's
such a sincere guy. He's almost bashful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think he's very unusual. He thinks things out. He
doesn't make rash decisions. I just know he's going to be
everything we thought he would be.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, unless his name were Jordan, Payton, Ruth or Gretzky,
it might be difficult for any athlete to live up to the Williams
hype in New Orleans. After all, there had never been a team with a
one-player draft until the Saints traded six picks in this year's
draft plus two more in 2000 to swap first-round positions with
Washington this past April.
</P>
<P>
   ``My obligation to the Saints is to play the best football I
can,'' Williams said to about 30 reporters a few minutes later.
``The only ones I want to prove anything to is my team. I want to
prove I'm worthy of what they gave up for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Once coach Mike Ditka and general manager Bill Kuharich made the
decision to go after Williams, it was full speed ahead in trade
negotiations with other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Saints haven't had a marquee name like Ricky since Archie
Manning (drafted in 1971),'' Kuharich said. ``People can make their
judgments now. The facts are we gave up eight for one, but it
depends on what those players do over time and what Ricky gives us
over time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Williams wheel began to spin in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike came to me in January before the college all-star games
and asked who the best player in the draft was,'' Kuharich said.
``I said Ricky Williams. He asked what it would take to get him. I
said probably our whole draft and more. He was very receptive.''
</P>
<P>
   When they pulled the trigger, the Saints received a lot of
criticism around the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think the second-day draft board was as strong as
years past,'' Kuharich said. ``We thought we could supplement the
second day with college free agents in place of rounds four through
seven. In essence, we gave up a No. 1 and a No. 3 and a No. 1 and a
No. 3 to get the most prolific rusher in college history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were coming from the 12th spot. We thought we'd have to
give up a lot of picks to move up seven spots or higher. Precedent
was set last year when San Diego gave up two No. 1s, a No. 2 and
two players (to Arizona) to move up one spot (to select quarterback
Ryan Leaf). We don't think we overpaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Draft picks are still precious, because they give you young
players to develop and low balance in your cap situation, but
there's still another avenue to acquire players (free agency). We
signed 17 or 18 college free agents, which is high for us. And we
got 10 exemptions from NFL Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuharich talked with a number of teams about moving up from the
12th pick in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually offered more to Philadelphia, Cincinnati and
Indianapolis _ much, much more _ another No. 1 (2001) and two
players (cornerback Alex Molden and running back Lamar Smith),''
Kuharich said. ``From what we were willing to give up to Philly to
what we actually gave up to Washington (in the fifth spot), we
didn't give up nearly as much as we were willing to give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a hard thing to do. It never entered my mind that
this is going to be the first time in NFL history that there's been
a one-player draft or the first time you've given up eight picks
for one player.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Saints drafted Williams, they wanted to make sure
they had a good idea they could sign him. He dumped his first agent
and signed with No Limit Sports, the entertainment conglomerate
owned by Percy Miller, the music impresario known as Master P.
Negotiating Williams' contract would be Leland Hardy, the chief
financial officer of No Limit Sports. It would be Hardy's first
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis shied away from Williams and took Miami running
back Edgerrin James because Colts general manager Bill Polian
thought he would be easier to sign. James has still not signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a lot of research on Ricky,'' Kuharich said. ``We
talked to a lot of people who had coached him and been associated
with him. We thought he was a unique individual, that he was going
to call the shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many players say the agent works for them, but it's the other
way around. The agent tells them when to sign. It was clear Ricky's
deal would be up to him. His agent would recommend things, but he
(Williams) would make the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it a risk? Sure. They all are. But signability wasn't as
much of a risk to us as some other clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' contract was heavily criticized by many because so
much of what he will earn over the eight-year deal depends on
incentive bonuses for a variety of statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people saying that are agents,'' Kuharich said. ``They're
worried that this could become another type of contract in the NFL,
and it doesn't work in the agents' favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky's a throwback. He's said many times that he believes
that you get a certain amount of money _ remember, he got the
largest signing bonus in Saints history _ and the rest of it he
should earn. That's a unique approach, but he's atypical of today's
athlete. As long as Ricky's happy, that's all that matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Signing that kind of contract has endeared him to the New
Orleans fans.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that won't endear him to New Orleans fans is fumbling.
He lost two fumbles in his first practice, but one wasn't his
fault. Afterward, he was asked about the fumbles 20 times by
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I count them, too, so it doesn't matter,'' he said about
reporters counting his fumbles. ``I dropped a pen, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to be my toughest critic. I have to ask myself the same
thing (about why he fumbles).''
</P>
<P>
   After his exploits at Texas and his experiences of breaking Tony
Dorsett's Division I-A rushing record and winning the Heisman
Trophy, Williams has been ready for anything the Saints, including
Ditka, throw at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I don't like about him yet,'' Williams said of
Ditka. ``The fact that he shoots from the hip, you'll know where
you stand, like it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Williams knows where he stands _ at the front of the
class. He tries to blend in and just be one of the guys. He has
limited interviews with the media to every other day so he can
``bond with my teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   The only things that set him apart are his dreadlocks and the
crowd of adoring fans who besiege him every chance they get.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not nervous about this,'' he said. ``I didn't know what to
expect before I got here. Now I realize the tempo is full speed
from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a lot of hard work to find out where I need
to be and then to get there. Being in better condition helps my
adjustment. If you're stronger and in better condition, you'll have
more confidence, and you'll be better prepared to do what you want
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of a hazing incident last year that led to a lawsuit
being filed by a former player, Ditka lectured his players and told
them no hazing will be tolerated this year. He said if any rookies
are involved in such incidents, they should fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he won't fight back and resist, then I want him out of
here,'' Ditka said. ``If we'd had guys to stand up last year and
say, `Hey, I don't want any part of this,' that would have ended it
right there. If somebody tried to do that to me, I know one thing:
They might be able to do it, but I'd take some skin with me.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Williams ``would be out of here'' if he didn't
fight back, Ditka said, ``Ricky's part of this team like everyone
else, and he wouldn't want it any other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditka can't say enough good things about Williams, who is the
ideal player because he keeps his mouth shut, does what his coach
tells him and works extremely hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a very good attitude,'' Ditka said. ``He's not hung
up on who he is. He's just a kid trying to prove he's a good
player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 2301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990801.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2137 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCKET-KAN &LR;      08-01 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON KANSAS PRAIRIE, ROCKETEERS GIVE FLIGHT TO THEIR DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARGONIA, Kan. _ About the time most people are clocking in at
work or finishing up the newspaper at home this morning, Bruce Lee
will help escort a rocket he built to a specially made launch pad. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He'll be among the last of at least 300 adults since Thursday
who have made the trek from as far away as Australia to this patch
of Kansas about 30 miles south of Wichita. They came to take part
in a shoot of ``Large and Dangerous Rocket Ships,'' otherwise known
as the annual Tripoli International High-Power Rocket Launch, the
largest and most prestigious annual event of its kind. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And Lee has brought the main event. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the pad, the 47-year-old Omaha, Neb., resident and 10
technicians will prepare to launch the rocket, which, though scaled
down to one-third the size, is an exact reproduction of the Mercury
Redstone that launched Alan B. Shepard Jr. into space in 1961. And
as he prepares, Lee will pause to marvel at what he has made. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His rocket stands 30 feet high. If everything goes as planned,
the engine _ with its fuel supply equal to about 75,000 bottle
rockets _ will ignite properly. Then the exhaust cloud will first
spill across the Kansas prairie, then follow the rocket about a
mile or so skyward. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lee says he will marvel again as it tumbles toward Earth and
parachutes _ on cue _ explode from within and gently land the
craft. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps what he doesn't marvel at is exactly what is most
puzzling to outsiders: This is a hobby, a lark, what he does to
relax. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As they said repeatedly over the loudspeakers this weekend:
``Welcome to the world of high power.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a world where grown men and women spend thousands of
dollars and hundreds of hours fine-tuning big toys. A world where
five days standing outside in hot pasture land was eagerly
anticipated. A world where limitations are set only by
imaginations, and everyone seems to have the imagination of a kid. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday soon, probably this year, one of us is going to send a
rocket into outer space,'' Lee says, speaking about rockets made of
paperboard but powered by some of the same stuff that propels the
space shuttle. ``I mean, we count outer space as 50 miles up, and
we're getting pretty close to figuring out how to get there.
Imagine, being the first nongovernmental body to leave the
atmosphere.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Makes sense. This is a hobby with its roots in the space race of
the late 1950s and '60s, when the orbit of the Soviet Sputnik
satellite scared the dickens out of Americans. Recently, that time
was captured in the movie ``October Sky,'' about four West Virginia
boys who took to making rockets. One of those boys, Quentin Wilson,
was in Argonia this weekend. It's the first such shoot he has
attended. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``For years and years, I didn't have any playmates, so I didn't
shoot rockets. It's no fun by yourself, but this is great,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, this was a hobby for children. They made
little rockets, usually about a foot tall or so, then sneaked out
to a vacant lot and sent them a couple hundred feet into the air
with little engines they lighted by match. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And kids did shoot off rockets like those in Argonia this
weekend. But those involved in the hobby note that much has
changed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the past decade, more adults have gotten involved.
Consequently, backyard liftoffs weren't always enough. Little
rockets weren't always enough. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Dozens of official launch pads were set up for the event. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Launch officials from a central post controlled the remote
electronic ignition of all rockets, meaning rockets were ``lit''
from at least a dozen yards and up to a quarter mile away, and only
when the launch official determined spectators and rocket owners
were in safe positions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Announcers counted down each launch over a loudspeaker system:
``On launch pad 53, ten, nine, eight ....'' Then they described
each flight, ``She's straight,'' ``We've got chute deployment.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Rocketeers spoke in their own jargon: Strippers were rockets
whose speed sheared off their parachutes; streamers fell with
parachutes accidentally twisted into a single string; lawn darts
are those from which the chutes had failed to pop out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Rocket launchers were registered from most states and from
four countries, event officials said. This in a farming community
of 550 people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Emergency crews waited nearby, and official safety officers
added to the notion that Large and Dangerous Rocket Ships were just
what they sound like. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And they were. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ray Bryant came from New York state to launch a rocket he'd
spent more than $1,000 and one year building. Upon ignition, the
engine malfunctioned. Flames shooting out the back sent the rocket
spiraling just high enough to twist the body when it crashed back
to Earth, where it caused a short-lived prairie fire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a monumental disappointment, but it happens,'' he said
stoically, loading the wreckage into a van and preparing to go
home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time and time again, probably more than 1,000 times in all,
usually men but sometimes women would load rockets up to 20 feet
high onto launch rods or pads. After each ignition, hundreds of
spectators craned their necks to watch them race away and then
float back to Earth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As one man noted, shading his eyes from the sun as he watched a
rocket fall: ``Only hobby on Earth where you sunburn the palms of
your hands.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hobby distinguishes itself from most others. Just ask
46-year-old Steve Swagerty of Overland Park, Kan., about who takes
note of his hobby. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For starters, there were the people at the federal Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. He needs two separate licenses from
that agency to store and use the materials needed to send his
rockets screaming into the sky. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the folks at the Federal Communications
Commission. Without their permission, he wouldn't be allowed to
open up the signal that connects him to his toy rocket ship while
it's in flight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Federal Aviation Administration had to approve
all launch times. For this meet, the FAA approved a 25,000-foot
ceiling, though individuals could apply for more space. That's
needed because nobody wants to see these models hit or scare
passing airplanes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And, quite frankly, the regulatory list is just getting started.
At various times, the Secret Service, FBI and CIA have all paid
attention. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So why do it? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To Swagerty, it's obvious. Most days, he's a teacher in the
Shawnee Mission School District, a man who describes a full 51
weeks a year of his life as ``very normal, very predictable.'' But
that 52nd week is given to flying rockets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear, every time one of my rockets lifts off, I'm 12 years
old again,'' he said. ``It's pure magic.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As part of a Kansas City-based group of five that calls itself
the Rocket-Heads, Swagerty spent two years building his rocket.
It's 15 feet tall and contains three computers, a video camera, a
transmitter, a battery pack, an altitude counter and two
parachutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What I love is the process,'' he said. ``You visualize what it
is you want to do, then get your hands dirty in each stage of
actually doing it, and then it flies, and you can see the
results.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rocket partner James Murphy of Kansas City said there were many
challenges in that process. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had to learn or improve in areas from computers to
aeronautics to pyrotechnics to cameras,'' he said. ``We've had to
design our own rockets, then figure out what materials to make them
from. There's always something new to figure out.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fins on their rocket, for example, are made from blue-foam
insulation, then painted with a fiberglass coating. Before they
could cut the foam to their own specifications, they had to make a
special tool. The cutting alone took a month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even these challenges are not always enough. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
