<HEADLINE>
RETIRING FDA INSPECTOR LAMENTS AGENCY'S EASING UP ON AD CLAIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After investing nearly two-thirds of his life
safeguarding foods and drugs for the American public, Roger Lowell
plans to bicycle across the nation, celebrate his successes and
perhaps forget about what still troubles him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing a good job protecting your health and safety, but
we're not protecting your pocketbook anymore,'' Lowell said.
</P>
<P>
   A straight-shooter equally respected within the agency and by
many in the industries he has regulated, the FDA's top local
watchdog retired from his post Friday with a few words of advice
for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't eat raw fish ... and don't expect the FDA to protect you
from false advertising,'' said Lowell, the outgoing director of the
U.S. Food and Drug Administration's region 10 office and
laboratories in Bothell, Wash., north of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of the FDA's mission when Lowell first joined the
agency in 1963 was protecting consumers from fraud. As a food
inspector, he would routinely assess the accuracy of advertising
and packaging claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agency simply doesn't pay any attention to that today,''
Lowell said. Despite an FDA mission statement that still claims
responsibility for assuring ``that the public has access to
truthful and non-misleading product information,'' he says the
agency can no longer give such assurance.
</P>
<P>
   He attributes this to congressional restraints on the agency's
resources that, over time, have forced the FDA to abandon
regulating market claims in many areas and to instead focus its
efforts on public health and safety issues.
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore this point, the main entrance of the Bothell
campus of the FDA features one of the agency's public art projects
_ a crosswalk marking designed to look like a merchandise bar code
with the words ``Caveat Emptor'' (Latin for ``let the buyer
beware'') written on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the staff here hate that because it implies we're not
doing our job,'' Lowell said. ``I think it's OK. It emphasizes that
in some areas, such as in the marketing of products, consumers need
to protect themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic, he said, that people today seem more concerned
about the safety of the food supply than they do about being
cheated. As far as he's concerned, food is much safer than it's
ever been while more people than ever are being defrauded by false
claims and misleading marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are way too paranoid about their food today,'' Lowell
said. There are risks out there _ raw seafood, unpasteurized juices
or other vehicles for foodborne bacterial illness _ but he
considers the food supply exceptionally safe.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA's Bothell branch, which has regulatory responsibility
for Washington, Oregon, Idaho, Montana and Alaska, is the agency's
lead facility for monitoring seafood safety and quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Northwest seafood industry has a close relationship with
the FDA stretching back to the 1920s,'' said Roger DeCamp, director
of the Seattle office of the National Food Processors Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger has continued and improved on that cooperative
relationship by doing his job in a cooperative way, by friendly
persuasion,'' DeCamp said. ``He's very highly respected by industry
for being fair and even-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowell once got fired briefly by the head of the FDA for being
too fair to the industry. In 1993, a hypodermic syringe was found
in a can of Diet Pepsi in Seattle, prompting an alert to the FDA
and local media of possible product tampering. This was on the
heels of the 1991 cyanide-tainted Sudafed tampering case in Tacoma
and Olympia that killed two people.
</P>
<P>
   What the public doesn't know, Lowell said, is that his agency
gets about 100 such product-tampering reports every year and most
turn out to be mistakes or deliberate hoaxes.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1993 Pepsi case, Lowell said his investigators were
fairly certain the syringe came from a diabetic family member of
the elderly couple who reported finding it in their can. The family
member admitted disposing of needles in empty cans but claimed not
to have done it in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this was the case still isn't clear, he said, but it was
clear that all of the other such alleged tamperings prompted by
media attention to this scare were hoaxes or even attempts to
extort money from Pepsi.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell, correctly it turned out, didn't believe this was a
product-tampering case and didn't alert then-FDA commissioner Dr.
David Kessler to the event. When Kessler woke up the next morning
to learn of the episode on television, Lowell said he was promptly
fired by Kessler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fired for about two hours, until later when he had
calmed down and learned what had happened,'' Lowell said with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger's very level-headed and able to manage stressful
situations well,'' said Joe Baca, FDA district director in Dallas
and a former investigator for Lowell in Seattle. ``He's always very
positive and constructive no matter what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowell, 60, is an avid bicyclist who commuted 30 miles on two
wheels every day between work and home and sometimes started his
workday in his biking gear before changing into his slacks and
dress shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Baca, who will join Lowell and others Aug. 18 on their
cross-country cycling trek, said his staff took advantage one day
of his tendency to keep his bike gear on. They sewed the pant legs
of his slacks together.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got a big kick out of that,'' Baca said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
