<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, Aug. 2. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
BURBS (Phoenix) _ Syringes in park sandboxes. Naked men in public
bathrooms. Drunks snoring in the bushes. Residents say they're sick
of it. Thousands of homeless people are migrating to the suburbs
from downtown Phoenix, but few services have followed them. As a
result, the homeless _ especially older, single men _ are gathering
in the streets and parks of Phoenix, Glendale, Mesa, Scottsdale and
Tempe. But doing something about the problem is a lot more
complicated than it sounds, officials say. Coping with the Phoenix
area's migrating homeless is hampered by the clash between every
resident's desire to enjoy his or her neighborhood and every
citizen's right to move freely about public places. By BILL
HERMANN. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOHOKAM (Coolidge, Ariz.) Five hundred years after their
disappearance, the Hohokam Indians are involved in a 20th century
land battle _ this time against economic growth. Construction of a
Wal-Mart store in Coolidge, Ariz., scheduled to begin in May, has
been put on hold while company officials sort out claims by
archaeologists that the land contains valuable Hohokam artifacts.
Wal-Mart's 35-acre plot lies across a highway from the Casa Grande
Ruins National Monument, the oldest archaeological reserve in the
country and the only national monument of the Hohokam Tribe. By
ELIZABETH GREENSPAN. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   NEW&AMP;NOTABLE (undated) Reviews of new books. By ANNE STEPHENSON,
special for the Arizona Republic. Story will move in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
