<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX NIP YANKEES, 5-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Orlando Hernandez complained of a tired arm and took
himself out of a game after six innings last week, and in the days
that followed he grew exasperated whenever reporters asked him
about his arm. Don't make a big deal out of this, he said through
an interpreter. It's not a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   But with Roger Clemens pitching erratically, it is a big deal
when Hernandez, the de facto No. 2 starter, gets hit as hard as the
Red Sox hit him on Sunday night, in his first outing since
mentioning his tired arm.
</P>
<P>
   Boston blistered six extra-base hits over five-plus innings
against Hernandez, beating the Yankees, 5-4. Bret Saberhagen
retired the last 14 batters he faced in his seven innings as the
Red Sox took two of three in this three-game series. Derek Jeter
went 0 for 5, extending his streak of hitless at-bats to 14 when he
grounded out with the bases loaded to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees (62-41) declined to trade Andy Pettitte for minor
leaguers mostly because they did not want to surrender an
experienced and proven pitcher during a pennant race _ and although
the Yankees seemed destined for the playoffs, something of a
pennant race is developing.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto, ignited by the hitting of Shawn Green and bolstered by
the addition of David Segui, swept Detroit in a weekend series to
draw within five games of the Yankees in the American League East,
one game ahead of Boston. The Blue Jays begin a three-game series
in Yankee Stadium on Monday, with David Wells (11-6) pitching
against Pettitte (7-8).
</P>
<P>
   The league has studied and adjusted to Hernandez. When he drops
his arm and throws his sweeping slider from the side, right-handed
batters don't always swing, as they did in 1998. Hernandez likes to
throw curveballs to left-handed batters, a pitch the hitters often
ignored; now there are times when they seem to be looking for it.
The convergence of Hernandez's knee and chin at the beginning of
his delivery is no longer a novelty.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez has adjusted, too, using his fastball more, jamming
hitters. Earlier this season, Hernandez began to ask teammates more
about certain opposing batters; he began checking scouting reports,
something he never really did in 1998, when Hernandez stubbornly
insisted that he need only pitch to his strengths, rather adapt to
the weaknesses of the batters. Like David Cone, Hernandez usually
navigates his way through trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday night, he seemed to have nothing with which he
could combat the Red Sox; it was if he was going through the Amazon
jungle without a compass. Hernandez's breaking pitches did not
appeared fine, and his fastball was mediocre. He was in trouble
constantly; the first Boston batter reached base in every inning _
a five-pitch walk in the first inning, a four-pitch walk in the
second inning, doubles by Damon Buford in the third and fifth, and
a home run and a double by Brian Daubach in the fourth and sixth
innings, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was hanging on, nonetheless, the score 2-2 after five
innings. Bernie Williams tripled home the Yankees' first run,
lining the ball to the warning track in the deepest part of center
field, and in the third inning, Williams' sacrifice fly allowed
Scott Brosius to score. Tino Martinez ended both rallies, however,
by popping out with a runner in scoring position. Martinez is
batting .268 with a respectable 62 runs batted in, but by his own
standards, he is not having a good season. Martinez went into this
game 67 at-bats removed from his last home run; his next home run
will be the 200th of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Everything caved in on Hernandez in the bottom of the sixth.
After Daubach slammed his double into the right field corner, Nomar
Garciaparra laced a run-scoring single to right, and on the very
next pitch, Troy O'Leary slammed a home run to right-center field,
a monster blow; Hernandez stood on the mound, arms folded loosely
across his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Watson began throwing in the bullpen and Mel Stottlemyre,
the Yankees' pitching coach, chose that moment to walk very slowly
to the mound. Hernandez, knowing he was close to being taken out,
moved his hands demonstratively while responding to Stottlemyre,
pleading his case.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Jefferson ripped a double, Hernandez threw a ball high
and outside to Jason Varitek, and Torre moved out of the dugout to
pull Hernandez. Once Hernandez saw Torre, he went to the back of
the mound, classic self-loathing.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen (7-4) threw mostly fastballs, with mixed results
early; the Yankees had the bases loaded with one out in the third
inning, scored on Williams' fly ball _ and would not place another
runner against Saberhagen. Over seven innings, he allowed five
hits, no walks and two runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored two runs in the top of the eighth against
Boston's Tim Wakefield, with Williams tripling again to score one
run. They loaded the bases with two out in the ninth, but Jeter
grounded into a game-ending forceout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
