<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEW OF NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEVENSON  
 c.1999 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stevenson's New &AMP; Notable books:
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside the Oval Office'' &QL; 
By William Doyle (Kodansha, $28) &QL; 
What were they ``thinking,''``'' these powerful men who recorded
conversations that should have been left to our imaginations?
Franklin D. Roosevelt had a microphone hidden in his desk lamp, and
it preserved, among other things, his embarrassing responses to
civil-rights leaders A. Philip Randolph and Walter White, who in
1940 went to the Oval Office to push for integration of the U.S.
military. The tape of the meeting reveals the visitors to be
eloquent and firm, while Roosevelt is condescending and vaguely
racist. At one point, he addresses the issue of putting Black men
aboard Navy ships with this suggestion: ``Another thing (that) I
forgot to mention . . . is this. We are training a certain number
of musicians on board ship. The ship's ``band.'' There's no reason
why we shouldn't have a colored band on some of these ships,
because they're ``darn good at it.'' That's something we should
look into. You know, if it'll increase the ``opportunity,'' that's
what we're after. They may develop a ``leader'' of the band.'' And
consider this exchange as John and Robert Kennedy and their aides
deal with riots after James Meredith's attempts to register as the
first Black student at the University of Mississippi. JFK: ``It's
going to be a long fall in Oxford. I think we oughta get the
National Guard within, you know, shouting distance.'' RFK: ``Yeah.
We have control over the air. If you have gas, you got a pretty
good operation going. They got 500 marshals. You see, they're
sitting there, and they're throwing iron.'' JFK: ``Spikes?'' RFK:
``. . . spikes and they're throwing Coke bottles and they're
throwing rocks.'' JFK: What's Barnett (Mississippi Gov. Ross
Barnett) doing?'' RFK: ``I suppose laughing at us.'' (Laughter in
room.) VOICE: ``This reminds me a little bit of the Bay of Pigs.''
RFK: ``Yech!'' (Laughter in room.) Doyle looks at the bugging
habits of the past 11 presidents. The transcripts are brief but
fascinating, although they are faulty history. Less interesting is
the analysis Doyle offers as he explores the 20th-century tradition
of presidential eavesdropping.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Weight of Dreams''By Jonis Agee (Viking, $24.95) &QL; 
Agee's new novel is so packed with stories that it's not easy to
describe. The central character is Ty Bonte, who has grown up on a
Nebraska ranch with an abusive father and a mother grown distant
after the death of Ty's younger brother, Ronnie. Ty is 17 when the
book begins and about to take part in an event that will govern the
rest of his life: One night, he and his friend, Harney Rivers,
brutally beat two Indians from a nearby reservation, and Tyruns off
before he can be arrested. He ends up in Kansas, where he builds a
life for himself as a horse trader. Now, 20 years have passed, and
although he is haunted by both Ronnie's death and that horrible
night with Harney, he has managed to reinvent himself enough to
begin a comfortable relationship with a woman who has secrets of
her own. It all goes well until Harney reappears and commits acts
so vicious that they make his previous sins seem like child's play.
All of this, astonishingly enough, takes place in the first 100
pages, leaving nearly 300 to resolve everything. This novel offers
violence, romance, ranch life, lots of horses, parental blame,
parental forgiveness, courtroom drama, a hate crime, lots of
remorse and even more redemption. And Agee's fans will be happy to
see Latta Jaboy and Cody Kidwell, characters from her novel,
``Strange Angels,'' who play supporting roles here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go for the Goal''By Mia Hamm (HarperCollins, $20) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She can do anything he can do and better. Even Michael Jordan
must believe it by now. This book was released in April, but its
publisher is sending it around again for those of you who woke up
with the World Cup. Part autobiography, part soccer primer, part
paean to the joys of team play, it is earnest to the point of
stodginess, which just makes Hamm more admirable than she already
was. There are photos of skill and rough play, a glossary of soccer
terms, diagrams of maneuvers and even a page from Hamm's training
log, which we read but did not understand (New &AMP; Notable is not
intense). There are also words of wisdom, as when Hamm talks about
soccer's way of humbling its players. In any match, she says, there
are two opponents _ the other team and soccer itself. Sometimes,
you can outplay the different-color shirts. But you never beat the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Queen Mother's Century''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lacey &QL; 
(Little Brown, $25.95)
</P>
<P>
   She was awfully cute when she was little, and she's awfully cute
now. In between, there was a long succession of bad hats. And bad
jewelry, bad parasols, bad photo opportunities, as when she posed,
smiling sweetly, in a bombed-out London neighborhood after a Nazi
air raid. But if anyone could pull it off, it was the Queen Mother,
who was born in 1900 and whose plump, serene presence is certainly
a hook upon which to hang another century book. Lacey makes a lame
effort to mention news events over the years, but this is really
just an excuse to look at royal photos. Our favorite shows Princess
Margaret, Queen Elizabeth and the Queen Mother dressed in plaid
skirts and standing in a barnyard, frumpy women all. Queen Mum has
a Band-Aid on her shin and is gamely balancing a milk bucket on her
head. It's an improvement over those hats.
</P>
<P>
   You can reach Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net, viae-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
