<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CHIRON CORP. BELIEVES A SLOW AND STEADY PACE WILL WIN THE RACE  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When studying stock charts, investors like to see lines that
rise up and to the right. Judged by this criteria, Chiron Corp. is
a flat-liner.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly three years, regardless of market trends or its
internal rumblings, shares in the Emeryville biotech have lingered
around the low 20s.
</P>
<P>
   The stock stood at $18.63 in January 1997, when Chief Executive
and co-founder Ed Penhoet announced he would resign and return to
academia. The stock rose slightly, to $21.44, over the next 14
months as Chiron searched the world over for a new leader before
appointing British drug industry veteran Sean Lance as Penhoet's
successor.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, with Lance long settled in his post, sitting
comfortably on $1.4 billion in cash earned by selling off bits of
the business, its shares have barely blipped. Chiron did have a
good day Friday (July 30), when it won approval to sell its flu
vaccine in Europe. That sent the stock up 8.4 percent to $25.06.
</P>
<P>
   Friendly analysts, like Jim McCamant of the Medical Technology
Stock Letter in Berkeley, Calif., think Chiron has remain stalled
so long that the momentum players who rule Wall Street have
overlooked the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this is not false optimism, but I have a sense this is
going to change,'' McCamant said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, analyst Alex To of Credit Suisse First Boston has a
``strong buy'' recommendation out on Chiron. He recently issued a
report touting Chiron's new blood-screening system for HIV and
Hepatitis C (see May 31 article in the San Francisco Chronicle) as
a huge potential earnings boost.
</P>
<P>
   But McCamant and To are in a minority. Most analysts have a hold
on Chiron.
</P>
<P>
   The company will have another chance to wake up Wall Street when
it reports its second-quarter earnings after the close of trading
August 3 One consensus estimate predicts quarterly earnings of 14
cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   In an 80-minute briefing last week, Lance and his key managers,
including Chief Financial Officer Jim Sulat, had to steer clear of
talking about finances, while trying to counter the impression that
Chiron is slow, slumbering or darn near dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the outside, nothing appears to be happening, but a hell
of a lot is going on,'' Lance said.
</P>
<P>
   When he came to Chiron, he found a company going off in too many
directions. He has tried to focus on establishing the
blood-screening business, developing a handful of promising new
drugs, and expanding the markets for current drugs, like
cancer-fighting Proleukin, and Betaseron for multiple sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   In word and deed, Lance comes across as a man who takes his
time. Seated at the head of a polished conference table, with
managers arrayed at intervals, Lance explained why Chiron has not
sold the European subsidiary that distributes flu shots and other
vaccines _ something that seemed likely when he addressed biotech
investors at the Hambrecht &AMP; Quist conference in San Francisco in
January. ``I am slowly moving to the belief that if we can manage
and consolidate (the European business), we should keep it,'' Lance
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lance has followed the same tortoise timetable for investing the
cash Chiron earned from the sale of its diagnostics business last
year. With small and mid-size biotech companies enduring the worst
cash crunch in industry history, Chiron has an opportunity to
cherry-pick promising technologies at bargain prices.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked Chiron execs whether they had done any deals, a
moment of silence occurred as heads turned around the table.
Someone recalled a single licensing deal.
</P>
<P>
   If Lance has moved slowly, he gets an understanding nod from
longtime biotech observer Cynthia Robbins-Roth of BioVenture
Consulting in San Mateo, Calif..
</P>
<P>
   ``Chiron has been run since its inception by the same crew of
guys at the top,'' she said. ``It's a tough place to come in to.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lance only consolidated his hold on the company in May,
when he became chairman as well as CEO, replacing co-founder Bill
Rutter, who remained on the board in an advisory capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Lance learned the importance of boardroom chess the hard way
from his former employer, Sir Richard Sykes, imperious chief
executive of Glaxo Wellcome, the British drug giant. Lance had
risen through Glaxo's ranks for 12 years to become second in
command. He had been Sir Richard's anointed successor _ right up
until the latter abruptly dumped Lance in a dispute over merger
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Now undisputed master of Chiron, Lance extols a Churchillian
philosophy. ``We've got to hold our nerve and do what we're doing,
and more of it, and the Street will come around,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street isn't his only audience. Novartis, the Swiss
pharmaceutical firm, holds about 44 percent of Chiron shares and
three of 11 seats on its board. Anytime after January 15, 2000,
Novartis has the right to increase its stake to 55 percent, at
Chiron's market price.
</P>
<P>
   The year after that, Novartis is free to make an offer to buy
all of Chiron. But it must negotiate such a deal with Chiron's
outside board members, who can demand a premium over the stock's
market price before surrendering control of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiron-Novartis situation is reminiscent of the relationship
between Genentech Inc. and Roche Holdings. Roche, which is
headquartered down the street from Novartis in Basel, Switzerland,
recently exercised an option to take over Genentech _ then reissued
about 17 percent of Genentech's stock to give the company a Wall
Street presence.
</P>
<P>
   The parallel isn't lost on Lance, who can only guess what
Novartis will do when the time comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could end up as a subsidiary, with some sort of
Genentech-like independence, that could be something we could live
with,'' Lance said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
