<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMASH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NET SCREENING TOOLS HELP TARGET FUNDS  &HT;     By HARRY DOMASH 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a recent column, I described how to evaluate mutual funds,
but I didn't tell you how to find funds worth analyzing.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; uncx  &LR;  You can find those funds by screening _ a method of
searching through the entire mutual funds universe to find those
that meet certain predetermined criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Many Web sites offer mutual fund screening. My favorite is
Quicken (www.quicken.com) because: 1. Its screening tools are easy
to use, 2. You can screen using Morningstar's Star Ratings and 3.
It's free and doesn't require registration.
</P>
<P>
   From Quicken's home page, click on ``Pick Top Funds'' to display
the Fund Finder. You can use predefined screens or create your own
custom searches.
</P>
<P>
   Start with Quicken's predefined screens by clicking on ``Popular
Searches.'' Quicken has come up with 10 equity fund searches for
five categories: Morningstar's Best, Best of the No-Load, Low
Expense Funds, Best Small Funds, Best of the Market Cap Segments
and Best Getting Started Funds.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite category is Morningstar's Best, which consists of
two searches: rankings by five- and 10-year performances. Both
select funds with Five-Star Morningstar ratings. Five-star funds
have the best combination of historical return and risk ratings,
according to Morningstar. A five-star rating doesn't guarantee that
the fund will do well in the future, but it's a good place to start
your selection process.
</P>
<P>
   I like the five-year performance search. I find five-year
returns as good a predictor of future performance as 10-year
returns _ especially because many funds haven't been around for a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   By clicking on the five-year search, you will bring up a list of
the 25 Morningstar five-star funds with the best five-year average
annual returns, sorted with the best-performing funds at the top.
</P>
<P>
   When I ran the screen last week, the Firsthand Technology Value
fund topped the list, with an astonishing 50.6 percent average
annual return. There were four other funds listed with annual
returns in excess of 40 percent. All of the top 25 funds showed
returns of 32 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   The 25 funds appeared on one screen. All told, 695 five-star
rated funds were listed if one went through all the screens.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the fund name, ticker symbol and star rating, the report
lists the front-load, expense ratio, manager tenure and net assets.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get your search results, you can select other display
options to see returns ranging from three months to 10 years, fees,
valuation ratios and purchase requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The eight additional predefined screens also are powerful. You
can search for the best no-load funds with low expense ratios; the
best large-cap, midcap or small-cap funds; small funds, tiny funds
or funds with low minimum initial-investment requirements. If these
choices don't satisfy you, you can define your own screens.
</P>
<P>
   Quicken gives you two ways to build custom searches: EasyStep
Search and Full Search. EasyStep leads you through the
search-definition process step by step. I find it tedious and more
trouble than it's worth. Full Search is intuitive, versatile and
much faster to use. Here's a rundown of your screening choices
using Full Search. You don't have to use all of them. If you don't
care about a particular characteristic, simply set the drop-down
selection to ``any.''
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar Information.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first of five major sections of the Full Search. You
can limit your search to such Morningstar categories as emerging
markets, high-yield bond, large growth, small value, etc. This is
important to investors who want to allocate their investments
according to asset categories. I don't, so I leave it set to ``All
Categories.''
</P>
<P>
   You also can specify the Star Rating you want in this section
with choices ranging from ``any'' to ``five stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Performance Data.
</P>
<P>
   You can set minimum acceptable returns for periods ranging from
three months to 10 years. Either enter a specific minimum return or
simply require that the funds beat the S&AMP;P 500 index for the
period. (The other drop-down selections, MSCI World and LB
Aggregate, refer to international and bond indices.)
</P>
<P>
   Except for three months and year-to-date, all returns are
expressed as average annual returns. For me, short-term returns
aren't significant and 10 years is too long, so I only specify
three- and five-year returns.
</P>
<P>
   Expenses.
</P>
<P>
   You can select loads, expense ratio and other fees. If you want
a no-load fund, select ``none'' for front-end load and deferred
sales charge. The expense ratio includes the 12b-1 fee, so there is
no point in specifying it separately.
</P>
<P>
   Operations Data.
</P>
<P>
   This includes miscellaneous items such as minimum initial
investment, fund size and manager tenure. Unfortunately, the
maximum choice for initial investment size is ``$2,000 or less.''
That's too small for many funds, so I usually select ``any.''
</P>
<P>
   Return.
</P>
<P>
   This section would more accurately be titled ``risk factors.''
It includes average price/earnings and price/book ratios and the
average size of companies making up the funds' portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   After filling in the values for the five sections in the search,
hit a button called ``show results.''
</P>
<P>
   You will see a list of funds that meet your selection criteria.
You may end with too many or too few funds. If you do, readjust
your screening criteria. If you found too few funds, consider
loosening requirements in these areas first: 10-year total return,
expense ratio, price/earnings and price/book ratios.
</P>
<P>
   Experienced investors consider screening results just the
beginning of the evaluation process.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to look at the details of each fund's
performance records and current portfolio. The best place to find
this information is on Morningstar (www.morningstar.net). If you
missed our columns describing how we evaluate funds, you can find
them in the Basic Training section of our Web site
(www.winninginvesting.com). Look for Mutual Fund Evaluation _ the
Basics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
