<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSTANT-MESSAGING-BATTLE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY TWO TITANS ARE BATTLING OVER INSTANT MESSAGING SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   By TOM STEIN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Instant messaging has made me a happier, more adjusted
person,'' said 33-year-old Randy Weston.
</P>
<P>
   Though there's a slight hint of sarcasm in his voice, he really
means it. After all, when Weston departed San Francisco three years
ago to start a new career as an editor in Boston, he left behind
many close friends and relatives with whom he gradually lost touch.
</P>
<P>
   But then he discovered America Online's instant messaging
software, which can be downloaded for free off the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who slipped off my radar screen are now back on,'' he
said. ``With instant messaging, I can see which of my friends are
online and I can talk with them in real-time as if we were on the
phone. I'm real bad about letter writing and e-mailing, but not
instant messaging.''
</P>
<P>
   Weston is just one of the approximately 100 million rabid users
of instant messaging around the world. For the most part, these
users are glued to their computer screens. Users of America
Online's product alone exchange 750 million messages a day. Those
are the kind of habits big Internet players covet.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of instant messaging is so significant that
Microsoft and America Online are now locked in a bitter war over
what is today a free piece of software.
</P>
<P>
   The two Internet giants are battling over who will control
standards for how the software works _ specifically, how various
messaging products will exchange messages with one another.
</P>
<P>
   AOL is the industry leader, boasting 40 million and 38 million
users, respectively, on its AIM (AOL Instant Messenger) and ICQ
(short for I Seek You) products. Microsoft just entered the fray
with its MSN Messenger, but says 700,000 people downloaded the
software in its first week.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nearly every major company in the high-tech industry is
choosing sides. AOL has recruited the chief technologists and CEOs
from some of Silicon Valley's biggest names _ Sun, Apple, Novell _
to create a standard, while Microsoft is rallying such allies as
Yahoo (which has its own instant-message product), AT&AMP;T and
Infoseek to support a separate standards body.
</P>
<P>
   Instant messaging software typically allows you to create a list
of friends and colleagues _ what AOL calls its ``buddy list'' _ who
use the same flavor of instant messaging you do. It then notifies
you when a person on your list logs onto the Internet. Then you can
type messages back and forth in a little pop-up window on your
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Instant messaging software could provide an ideal platform for
sending targeted advertisements directly to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   AOL, for instance, asks its users to provide demographic
information before downloading the software. Some software is also
able to track the habits and behavioral patterns of users, and take
some actions in response. Yahoo's instant messenger product, for
example, can notify a user when the price of a particular stock
goes up or down.
</P>
<P>
   Demographic information is valuable to advertisers, who will
gladly pay an premium to ensure their ads are directed at the
appropriate audience.
</P>
<P>
   Observers say it's only a matter of time before instant-message
vendors transform some of their prime real estate into virtual
billboards for advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web today is already generating billions of dollars in
advertising revenue,'' said Richard Dym, vice president of
marketing at Tribal Voice Inc., a Scotts Valley maker of instant
messaging software with a user base 5 million strong. ``We will see
a shift of those dollars to our side because ads displayed on our
software will be more targeted.''
</P>
<P>
   Although instant messaging has largely been a social phenomenon
for staying in touch with friends, it has some potential business
applications.
</P>
<P>
   Say you have an urgent question for a co-worker across the
country. You could try the phone or e-mail, but you have no idea if
that person is at her desk and available to respond. With instant
messaging, however, you know who is online and can direct your
question to the person best able to respond the quickest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important story here is the corporate world will move from
e-mail to interactive communication because it works as fast as
businesspeople,'' says Dym.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are a host of drawbacks to instant messaging. The
biggest problem is a lack of common standards and protocols.
</P>
<P>
   None of the existing products can communicate with one another.
This means that if you use Yahoo's software, you can't chat online
with a friend who prefers Microsoft's product. Even users of the
two different AOL offerings cannot exchange chat messages.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers have noted the impracticality of this
arrangement, likening it to a phone system that wouldn't allow
someone who uses Sprint for long-distance to call a friend who uses
AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had a problem with only being able to chat with
friends on AOL, and not with people on other systems,'' said
Weston. ``AOL kind of forced me to become an evangelist for them to
get my friends on the same platform. I was never really comfortable
with that. I don't think there is any way AOL can continue to keep
this proprietary.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and Yahoo agree. In fact, Microsoft tried to force the
issue a little over a week ago when it introduced its entry into
the market, MSN Messenger. Unlike other messaging products, it
boasted interoperability features that allowed users to communicate
with friends on AOL's offering.
</P>
<P>
   But AOL cried foul and said Microsoft was gaining unauthorized
access to its servers by asking people who downloaded MSN Messenger
to first provide their AOL passwords. AOL attempted to block the
connection, but Microsoft continued to one-up AOL by releasing new
versions of its software that circumvent attempts to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has joined forces with Yahoo, Prodigy and others in an
attempt to establish a common standard for instant messaging. These
companies said they are all willing to work with the Internet
Engineering Task Force, an independent standards agency. So far,
AOL has not committed itself to the group.
</P>
<P>
   AOL, for its part, does not like the idea of being pushed around
in a market it now dominates. The company has enlisted the help of
Apple, Sun and Novell to form its own standards group.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Enderle, an analyst with Giga Information Group, expects to
see some kind of standard by the end of next year. ``Whoever
chooses not to adopt a common standard will lose their installed
base,'' he said. ``If I have a communications product that doesn't
communicate with others, then it's not worth very much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
