<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2147 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALM-DEVELOPERS-FEUD &LR;      08-01 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALM-DEVELOPERS-FEUD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRODUCT DEVELOPERS FEUD WITH PALM COMPUTING  &HT;     BY DEBORAH SOLOMON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, Tom Hazzard had a vision while using his Palm
organizer: Why not create a device that functioned as both a
stylus, which could enter data into the handheld electronic device,
and a pen?
</P>
<P>
   The former furniture designer and his wife decided to join the
growing community of developers who craft companion products for
the popular device, and began courting Palm's endorsement of a
``dual-action stylus.''
</P>
<P>
   But instead of becoming the latest must-have gadget for the
Palm, Hazzard's Rhode Island company is on the verge of suing
3Com's Palm Computing division for patent infringement. Ttools
wants the company to stop selling its own Palm-branded dual-action
stylus.
</P>
<P>
   It's a precarious situation for Ttools, &LR;   &LR; which is essentially
biting the hand that feeds it. But the company's concerns are not
unique. Some developers say Palm's treatment of Ttools is
indicative of a larger problem between Palm and the developer
community. Third-party vendors complain that Palm has hurt
developers by keeping information about upcoming products so secret
that companies cannot design products before the latest Palm hits
the market.
</P>
<P>
   Palm officials would not comment on the patent dispute, but
acknowledged that Ttools has a patent on a dual-action stylus
similar to one Palm sells. Gabriel Acosta-Lopez, director of
platform development services for Palm, said there is no friction
with the third-party community and said Palm is trying to come to
an agreement with Ttools.
</P>
<P>
   But Tracy Leigh, president of Ttools, said the two companies
have been in discussions for months and there is no agreement in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   Ttools approached Palm about a year and half ago and showed Palm
officials _ under a nondisclosure agreement _ its dual-action
stylus, whose patent was then pending.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies initially discussed featuring the Ttools
dual-action stylus in Palm's coveted catalog of Palm accessories,
but those talks fell off. Then, Palm approached Ttools about
licensing its technology to develop its own Palm-branded stylus.
Those talks also ended.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1998, four months after Ttools filed its patent
application, Palm filed its own patent request for a dual-action
stylus. Ttools got its patent in June 1999; Palm's application is
still pending.
</P>
<P>
   A few months after their talks collapsed, Leigh saw a
Palm-branded dual action stylus featured in Newsweek magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The product is a complete overlap,'' Leigh said. ``Third-party
developers seem to be completely disrespected by Palm.''
</P>
<P>
   Other developers agree, saying they fear Palm is trying to
cannibalize its development community by giving itself a head start
so its own Palm-branded accessories hit shelves before any
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   While anyone can develop a product for the Palm, only a few
products are Palm-branded and included in the company's accessory
catalog. They include luxury items like leather cases made by Coach
or Dooney and Bourke.
</P>
<P>
   Developers said their experience with the Palm V, which is much
thinner than previous versions, has soured them on Palm. Most
developers said they did not get the specifications of the Palm V
product until it hit the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``My frustration is that they have been very protective of their
pre-launch information,'' said a third-party vendor, who did not
want to be named for fear of ruining the company's relationship
with Palm. The developer, who makes a case for the PalmPilot, said
Palm's failure to release information on the Palm V set his
company's production back months.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh said her company's product was too big for the Palm V
because the PDA had a smaller port for the stylus to rest in. After
the Palm V hit the market, the company raced to make a proper-sized
stylus, but lost out on three months of business. Palm, on the
other hand, was able to offer its pen/stylus products the day the
Palm V was released.
</P>
<P>
   Acosta-Lopez said the complaints of Leigh and other developers
are unfounded. He said Palm works closely with developers to make
sure they get the support they need.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great relationship with our development community,''
he said. ``We're growing at a rate of 500 developers per week.''
</P>
<P>
   There are currently more than 17,000 third-party developers who
make both software and hardware for Palm products.
</P>
<P>
   Acosta-Lopez said Palm does not release advance information
about Palm products to most vendors because specifications can
change before the device is finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't preannounce products,'' he said. ``For certain
developers we do, but it takes us about two months before shipping
until we're final on what the product looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   One developer, who did not want to be identified, said that
policy cost him five months of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were given zero lead time on the Palm V,'' said the
developer, who makes a popular accessory. He also said he's heard
that Palm plans to make a product similar to his.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palm is going to shut out innovation this way because
third-party developers are going to be hesitant to put time into
developing solutions if they feel that 3Com is going to just turn
around and do it themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Palm started cultivating a third-party community about three or
four years ago and has seen an explosion in vendors wanting to
piggyback on the PDA's success.
</P>
<P>
   3Com hosts Palm development conferences each year and has a
resource guide in which third-party vendors can pay to advertise.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Dubinsky, who founded Palm and now heads a Palo Alto
company called Handspring, said there are bound to be a few
disgruntled developers but that, in general, the third-party
community is thriving.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an ecstatic developer community. They're thrilled with
the tools they get and the ability to quickly develop things,''
Dubinsky said. As for the complaints, Dubinsky said, ``There's
always a built-in tension between the platform supplier and
developers. Developers all want to be bundled on every unit and the
platform supplier has to make choices. It's always hard and it
wouldn't surprise me to end up with a couple of unhappy
developers.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, ``I meet with developers pretty regularly and I
have absolutely no sense of broad dissatisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Leigh of Ttools said while some developers may be happy, her
company has lost more than $3 million in potential sales because of
its fight with Palm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we been in their catalog from the start, we would probably
have made $3.8 million,'' Leigh said. ``We haven't even hit $1
million in sales in our first year.'' The Ttools products are for
sale on the company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh said she realizes that taking legal action against Palm
will alienate the company, but said it's her company's only
recourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We conceived of the product first, it's been notarized and
Palm refuses to acknowledge this,'' Leigh said. ``If I didn't think
we had a winning argument, I wouldn't be risking my company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
