<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS: `LET PEOPLE KNOW I'M ENJOYING IT'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pete Sampras, comedian?
</P>
<P>
   Sampras long has been known as unexciting, bland, even ``dull,''
as he called himself Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But the tennis community might be seeing a new Sampras on the
tour, if this week's stop at UCLA and the Mercedes-Benz Cup is any
indication.
</P>
<P>
   In giving chase to a ball in Saturday's semifinal over James
Sekulov, Sampras climbed a backstop to try and get a ball and
appeared to play peek-a-boo with the fans.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, against Andre Agassi, he reached for a shot and ran
up the stairs 10 rows. When the chair umpire asked late-arrivers to
find a seat, Sampras lobbed a tennis ball at the offending fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. brings that out,'' Sampras said. ``I'm to the point where
I've achieved so many goals. Now, it's time to go out and let
people know I'm enjoying it. People want to see me smile. It can
help me out and loosen me up.''
</P>
<P>
   __ And in doubles: Byron Black and Wayne Ferreira beat Brian
MacPhie and Goran Ivanisevic, 6-2, 7-6 (7-4), to win the doubles
title.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tournament discovery: Everyone knew about Sampras and Andre
Agassi. Fewer knew about Andrew Ilie, but they do now.
</P>
<P>
   It started when Ilie ripped his shirts off after winning
hard-fought, three-set matches over Byron Black and Anthony Dupuis.
</P>
<P>
   When Ilie served a 134 mph ace in the first game of Saturday's
semifinal against Agassi, the crowed oohed and aaahed. One man
remarked, ``Oh God! Where does he come from?''
</P>
<P>
   When Ilie won the first game, the man said, ``This is not a
given.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not like Ilie is unknown. The Romanian-born Aussie is
ranked 61st, having reached the semifinals here and in Dubai this
year, as well as the fourth round of the Australian Open and third
round of the French Open.
</P>
<P>
   He also made the crowd laugh when he mimicked the numerous young
girls who were screaming somewhere on the UCLA campus but close
enough for Ilie to hear them.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the shot of the tournament, Ilie running down an
Agassi drop volley, leaping up and hitting the winner through his
legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My eyes went haywire,'' Agassi said. ``All I saw were legs,
and then I was thinking, `Wow! What has to go through your mind to
take a shot like that? You certainly have to lose perspective.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ilie has tried and failed to convert that shot four other times.
``I do it because I enjoy it,'' he explained. ``I don't do it to
entertain the crowd. I'm selfish. I like to entertain myself.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Ranking jump: Sampras moved from 2 to 1 by reaching Sunday's
final. By reaching Saturday's semifinal, Sekulov's ranking leaped
from 236 to the 160s.
</P>
<P>
   __ Attendance: The tournament drew 81,433 fans for the week, a
three-year high. Officials cited several factors, not the least of
which was the quality of the 32-team tournament that included
Agassi and Sampras, who won the French Open and Wimbledon this
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
