<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2149 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOHOKAM-AZR &LR;      08-01 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOHOKAM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANCIENT HO HOKAM HALT WAL-MART PLAN: ARIZONA SITE MAY HOLD RELICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ELIZABETH GREENSPAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOLIDGE, Ariz. _ Five hundred years after their disappearance,
the Hohokam Indians are involved in a 20th century land battle _
this time against economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of a Wal-Mart store in Coolidge, scheduled to begin
in May, has been put on hold while company officials sort out
claims by archaeologists that the land contains valuable Hohokam
artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart's 35-acre plot lies across a highway from the Casa
Grande Ruins National Monument, the oldest archaeological reserve
in the country and the only national monument of the Hohokam Tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an archaeological standpoint, it would be hard to pick a
worse spot to build on in Arizona,'' said Keith Kintigh, an
anthropology professor at Arizona State University who also is
president of the Society for American Archaeology.
</P>
<P>
   The ruins date back to A.D. 1250 and are part of a critical
Hohokam period, Kintigh said.
</P>
<P>
   Bulldozers across the Southwest are hitting historical
roadblocks these days as they make room for highways and housing
complexes.
</P>
<P>
   In Southern California recently, archaeologists discovered an
unprecedented number of ice age animal fossils while building a
reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago in Chandler, archaeologists saved the bones of two
Colombian mammoths found on a housing construction site.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists point out that it is rare to save remains
however. The state does not protect fossils or artifacts on private
land, and high excavations costs often lead developers to build
through ruins.
</P>
<P>
   A little over a year ago in Apache Junction, Ariz., a bulldozer
made quick work of an ancient Hohokam Indian pyramid to clear land
for a housing development.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Howard, curator of anthropology at the Mesa (Ariz.)
Southwest Museum, says that much of our heritage has been lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we destroy it, we're not going to get any Hohokam to do
it again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in Coolidge have a different take. They are upset that
the artifacts issue has held up a store project they say would help
their struggling economy.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Gregory, of Coolidge, now has to drive 25 minutes to Casa
Grande to do most of his shopping, a trip he'd rather not make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather spend money in our town, not someone else's,''
Gregory said from his stool at a local diner.
</P>
<P>
   Spending money in Coolidge isn't easy now.
</P>
<P>
   Vacant, shabby storefronts just about equal the number of
diners, small shops and gas stations lining Coolidge's main road.
</P>
<P>
   Coolidge City Manager John Baudek said the delay in building the
Wal-Mart has hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important piece to our growth as a city,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even more upsetting to Baudek is that city officials believed
they had an OK from archaeologists to build the store.
</P>
<P>
   CONSERVANCY MADE A DEAL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Archaeological Conservancy, a non-profit group
that establishes archaeological preserves across the country, told
Baudek that it would not oppose development on Wal-Mart's site.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the Conservancy's lack of opposition was part
of a deal it had struck with the landowner, Dalton Coles.
</P>
<P>
   In December, before he sold Wal-Mart its site, Coles sold the
Conservancy an adjacent 30-acre plot, with the agreement that the
Conservancy wouldn't oppose development of the Wal-Mart site.
</P>
<P>
   The group figured it was better to preserve a piece of the land
even if that meant agreeing to see the other site developed, said
Jim Walker, Southwest Regional Director of the Conservancy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Conservancy's silence, other archaeological groups
and Native American communities have come forward to stand in
Wal-Mart's way. These other communities, including the Salt-River
Pima-Maricopa Indian Community, Hopi Nation and Tohono O'odham
Nation, want Wal-Mart to build elsewhere in Coolidge.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart put the store project on hold as soon as company
officials learned there might be artifacts on the site, said Daphne
Davis, a spokeswoman for Wal-Mart, which is based in Bentonville,
Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart, which purchased the plot for $285,000, is ``meeting
with involved parties to determine the next step,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to those who oppose building on the site, Wal-Mart
should have known about the contents of the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prehistoric man didn't stop at the road,'' state preservation
officer Jim Garrison said. ``This has been known to be an important
site for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bohnee, spokesman for the Gila River Indian Community, who
claim to be descendents of the Hohokams, said his tribe wants to
make sure Wal-Mart ``protects burial sites, and other traditional
objects potentially there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull stepped into the controversy in May.
</P>
<P>
   She alerted the State Historic Preservation Office of the affair
after Roger Lidman, chairman of the Arizona Archaeology Advisory
Commission, asked for her assistance.
</P>
<P>
   But the preservation office has no power to resolve the issue
because the land is private, Garrison said.
</P>
<P>
   SMALL LEGAL OBSTACLE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only legal obstacle preventing Wal-Mart from building is a
1990 state burial law requiring company officials to return to
local tribes any burial remains they find.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists say it's very likely remains are there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The probability approaches 100 percent for burials on the
site,'' said Lynn Teague, curator of archaeology for the Arizona
State Museum and coordinator of the state repatriation laws.
</P>
<P>
   If Wal-Mart chose to do so, it could dig up the site before
starting construction, pinpointing the burial sites and giving
archaeologists a chance to study other artifacts, Teague said.
</P>
<P>
   That might be less of a hassle for Wal-Mart, since the builders
wouldn't have to stop in the middle of construction each time they
found remains, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At a June 16 meeting between Wal-Mart, Teague and Native
American communities, Wal-Mart said it would hire Northland
Research to make a test dig to sample the extent of the remains,
Teague said.
</P>
<P>
   Teague says she will meet with Wal-Mart after the test, which
she expects to occur in August, to discuss what the company will do
next: completely excavate the site or start construction. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-01-99 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
